U||INTRODUCTION
U||   This volume does not aim to contain all “the best American humorous
U||   short stories”; there are many other stories equally as good, I
U||   suppose, in much the same vein, scattered through the range of American
U||   literature. I have tried to keep a certain unity of aim and impression
U||   in selecting these stories. In the first place I determined that the
U||   pieces of brief fiction which I included must first of all be not
U||   merely good stories, but good short stories. I put myself in the
U||   position of one who was about to select the best short stories in the
U||   whole range of American literature,[2][1] but who, just before he
U||   started to do this, was notified that he must refrain from selecting
U||   any of the best American short stories that did not contain the element
U||   of humor to a marked degree. But I have kept in mind the wide
U||   boundaries of the term humor, and also the fact that the humorous
U||   standard should be kept second—although a close second—to the short
U||   story standard.
U||   In view of the necessary limitations as to the volume’s size, I could
U||   not hope to represent all periods of American literature adequately,
U||   nor was this necessary in order to give examples of the best that has
U||   been done in the short story in a humorous vein in American literature.
U||   Probably all types of the short story of humor are included here, at
U||   any rate. Not only copyright restrictions but in a measure my own
U||   opinion have combined to exclude anything by Joel Chandler Harris—Uncle
U||   Remus—from the collection. Harris is primarily—in his best work—a
U||   humorist, and only secondarily a short story writer. As a humorist he
U||   is of the first rank; as a writer of short stories his place is hardly
U||   so high. His humor is not mere funniness and diversion; he is a
U||   humorist in the fundamental and large sense, as are Cervantes,
U||   Rabelais, and Mark Twain.
U||   No book is duller than a book of jokes, for what is refreshing in small
U||   doses becomes nauseating when perused in large assignments. Humor in
U||   literature is at its best not when served merely by itself but when
U||   presented along with other ingredients of literary force in order to
U||   give a wide representation of life. Therefore “professional literary
U||   humorists,” as they may be called, have not been much considered in
U||   making up this collection. In the history of American humor there are
U||   three names which stand out more prominently than all others before
U||   Mark Twain, who, however, also belongs to a wider classification: “Josh
U||   Billings” (Henry Wheeler Shaw, 1815–1885), “Petroleum V. Nasby” (David
U||   Ross Locke, 1833–1888), and “Artemus Ward” (Charles Farrar Browne,
U||   1834–1867). In the history of American humor these names rank high; in
U||   the field of American literature and the American short story they do
U||   not rank so high. I have found nothing of theirs that was first-class
U||   both as humor and as short story. Perhaps just below these three should
U||   be mentioned George Horatio Derby (1823–1861), author of Phoenixiana
U||   (1855) and the Squibob Papers (1859), who wrote under the name “John
U||   Phoenix.” As has been justly said, “Derby, Shaw, Locke and Browne
U||   carried to an extreme numerous tricks already invented by earlier
U||   American humorists, particularly the tricks of gigantic exaggeration
U||   and calm-faced mendacity, but they are plainly in the main channel of
U||   American humor, which had its origin in the first comments of settlers
U||   upon the conditions of the frontier, long drew its principal
U||   inspiration from the differences between that frontier and the more
U||   settled and compact regions of the country, and reached its highest
U||   development in Mark Twain, in his youth a child of the American
U||   frontier, admirer and imitator of Derby and Browne, and eventually a
U||   man of the world and one of its greatest humorists.”[3][2] Nor have
U||   such later writers who were essentially humorists as “Bill Nye” (Edgar
U||   Wilson Nye, 1850–1896) been considered, because their work does not
U||   attain the literary standard and the short story standard as creditably
U||   as it does the humorous one. When we come to the close of the
U||   nineteenth century the work of such men as “Mr. Dooley” (Finley Peter
U||   Dunne, 1867- ) and George Ade (1866- ) stands out. But while these two
U||   writers successfully conform to the exacting critical requirements of
U||   good humor and—especially the former—of good literature, neither—though
U||   Ade more so—attains to the greatest excellence of the short story. Mr.
U||   Dooley of the Archey Road is essentially a wholesome and wide-poised
U||   humorous philosopher, and the author of Fables in Slang is chiefly a
U||   satirist, whether in fable, play or what not.
U||   This volume might well have started with something by Washington
U||   Irving, I suppose many critics would say. It does not seem to me,
U||   however, that Irving’s best short stories, such as The Legend of Sleepy
U||   Hollow and Rip Van Winkle, are essentially humorous stories, although
U||   they are o’erspread with the genial light of reminiscence. It is the
U||   armchair geniality of the eighteenth century essayists, a constituent
U||   of the author rather than of his material and product. Irving’s best
U||   humorous creations, indeed, are scarcely short stories at all, but
U||   rather essaylike sketches, or sketchlike essays. James Lawson
U||   (1799–1880) in his Tales and Sketches: by a Cosmopolite (1830), notably
U||   in The Dapper Gentleman’s Story, is also plainly a follower of Irving.
U||   We come to a different vein in the work of such writers as William
U||   Tappan Thompson (1812–1882), author of the amusing stories in letter
U||   form, Major Jones’s Courtship (1840); Johnson Jones Hooper (1815–1862),
U||   author of Widow Rugby’s Husband, and Other Tales of Alabama (1851);
U||   Joseph G. Baldwin (1815–1864), who wrote The Flush Times of Alabama and
U||   Mississippi (1853); and Augustus Baldwin Longstreet (1790–1870), whose
U||   Georgia Scenes (1835) are as important in “local color” as they are
U||   racy in humor. Yet none of these writers yield the excellent short
U||   story which is also a good piece of humorous literature. But they
U||   opened the way for the work of later writers who did attain these
U||   combined excellences.
U||   The sentimental vein of the midcentury is seen in the work of Seba
U||   Smith (1792–1868), Eliza Leslie (1787–1858), Frances Miriam Whitcher
U||   (“Widow Bedott,” 1811–1852), Mary W. Janvrin (1830–1870), and Alice
U||   Bradley Haven Neal (1828–1863). The well-known work of Joseph Clay Neal
U||   (1807–1847) is so all pervaded with caricature and humor that it
U||   belongs with the work of the professional humorist school rather than
U||   with the short story writers. To mention his Charcoal Sketches, or
U||   Scenes in a Metropolis (1837–1849) must suffice. The work of Seba Smith
U||   is sufficiently expressed in his title, Way Down East, or Portraitures
U||   of Yankee Life (1854), although his Letters of Major Jack Downing
U||   (1833) is better known. Of his single stories may be mentioned The
U||   General Court and Jane Andrews’ Firkin of Butter (October, 1847,
U||   Graham’s Magazine). The work of Frances Miriam Whitcher (“Widow
U||   Bedott”) is of somewhat finer grain, both as humor and in other
U||   literary qualities. Her stories or sketches, such as Aunt Magwire’s
U||   Account of Parson Scrantum’s Donation Party (March, 1848, Godey’s
U||   Lady’s Book) and Aunt Magwire’s Account of the Mission to Muffletegawmy
U||   (July, 1859, Godey’s), were afterwards collected in The Widow Bedott
U||   Papers (1855-56-80). The scope of the work of Mary B. Haven is
U||   sufficiently suggested by her story, Mrs. Bowen’s Parlor and Spare
U||   Bedroom (February, 1860, Godey’s), while the best stories of Mary W.
U||   Janvrin include The Foreign Count; or, High Art in Tattletown (October,
U||   1860, Godey’s) and City Relations; or, the Newmans’ Summer at
U||   Clovernook (November, 1861, Godey’s). The work of Alice Bradley Haven
U||   Neal is of somewhat similar texture. Her book, The Gossips of
U||   Rivertown, with Sketches in Prose and Verse (1850) indicates her field,
U||   as does the single title, The Third-Class Hotel (December, 1861,
U||   Godey’s). Perhaps the most representative figure of this school is
U||   Eliza Leslie (1787–1858), who as “Miss Leslie” was one of the most
U||   frequent contributors to the magazines of the 1830’s, 1840’s and
U||   1850’s. One of her best stories is The Watkinson Evening (December,
U||   1846, Godey’s Lady’s Book), included in the present volume; others are
U||   The Batson Cottage (November, 1846, Godey’s Lady’s Book) and Juliet
U||   Irwin; or, the Carriage People (June, 1847, Godey’s Lady’s Book). One
U||   of her chief collections of stories is Pencil Sketches (1833–1837).
U||   “Miss Leslie,” wrote Edgar Allan Poe, “is celebrated for the homely
U||   naturalness of her stories and for the broad satire of her comic
U||   style.” She was the editor of The Gift one of the best annuals of the
U||   time, and in that position perhaps exerted her chief influence on
U||   American literature When one has read three or four representative
U||   stories by these seven authors one can grasp them all. Their titles as
U||   a rule strike the keynote. These writers, except “the Widow Bedott,”
U||   are perhaps sentimentalists rather than humorists in intention, but
U||   read in the light of later days their apparent serious delineations of
U||   the frolics and foibles of their time take on a highly humorous aspect.
U||   George Pope Morris (1802–1864) was one of the founders of The New York
U||   Mirror, and for a time its editor. He is best known as the author of
U||   the poem, Woodman, Spare That Tree, and other poems and songs. The
U||   Little Frenchman and His Water Lots (1839), the first story in the
U||   present volume, is selected not because Morris was especially prominent
U||   in the field of the short story or humorous prose but because of this
U||   single story’s representative character. Edgar Allan Poe (1809–1849)
U||   follows with The Angel of the Odd (October, 1844, Columbian Magazine),
U||   perhaps the best of his humorous stories. The System of Dr. Tarr and
U||   Prof. Fether (November, 1845, Graham’s Magazine) may be rated higher,
U||   but it is not essentially a humorous story. Rather it is incisive
U||   satire, with too biting an undercurrent to pass muster in the company
U||   of the genial in literature. Poe’s humorous stories as a whole have
U||   tended to belittle rather than increase his fame, many of them verging
U||   on the inane. There are some, however, which are at least excellent
U||   fooling; few more than that.
U||   Probably this is hardly the place for an extended discussion of Poe,
U||   since the present volume covers neither American literature as a whole
U||   nor the American short story in general, and Poe is not a humorist in
U||   his more notable productions. Let it be said that Poe invented or
U||   perfected—more exactly, perfected his own invention of—the modern short
U||   story; that is his general and supreme achievement. He also stands
U||   superlative for the quality of three varieties of short stories, those
U||   of terror, beauty and ratiocination. In the first class belong A
U||   Descent into the Maelstrom (1841), The Pit and the Pendulum (1842), The
U||   Black Cat (1843), and The Cask of Amontillado (1846). In the realm of
U||   beauty his notable productions are The Assignation (1834), Shadow: a
U||   Parable (1835), Ligeia (1838), The Fall of the House of Usher (1839),
U||   Eleonora (1841), and The Masque of the Red Death (1842). The tales of
U||   ratiocination—what are now generally termed detective stories—include
U||   The Murders in the Rue Morgue (1841) and its sequel, The Mystery of
U||   Marie Rogêt (1842–1843), The Gold-Bug (1843), The Oblong Box (1844),
U||   “Thou Art the Man” (1844), and The Purloined Letter (1844).
U||   Then, too, Poe was a master of style, one of the greatest in English
U||   prose, possibly the greatest since De Quincey, and quite the most
U||   remarkable among American authors. Poe’s influence on the short story
U||   form has been tremendous. Although the effects of structure may be
U||   astounding in their power or unexpectedness, yet the means by which
U||   these effects are brought about are purely mechanical. Any student of
U||   fiction can comprehend them, almost any practitioner of fiction with a
U||   bent toward form can fairly master them. The merit of any short story
U||   production depends on many other elements as well—the value of the
U||   structural element to the production as a whole depends first on the
U||   selection of the particular sort of structural scheme best suited to
U||   the story in hand, and secondly, on the way in which this is combined
U||   with the piece of writing to form a well-balanced whole. Style is more
U||   difficult to imitate than structure, but on the other hand the origin
U||   of structural influence is more difficult to trace than that of style.
U||   So while, in a general way, we feel that Poe’s influence on structure
U||   in the short story has been great, it is difficult rather than obvious
U||   to trace particular instances. It is felt in the advance of the general
U||   level of short story art. There is nothing personal about
U||   structure—there is everything personal about style. Poe’s style is both
U||   too much his own and too superlatively good to be successfully
U||   imitated—whom have we had who, even if he were a master of structural
U||   effects, could be a second Poe? Looking at the matter in another way,
U||   Poe’s style is not his own at all. There is nothing “personal” about it
U||   in the petty sense of that term. Rather we feel that, in the case of
U||   this author, universality has been attained. It was Poe’s good fortune
U||   to be himself in style, as often in content, on a plane of universal
U||   appeal. But in some general characteristics of his style his work can
U||   be, not perhaps imitated, but emulated. Greater vividness, deft
U||   impressionism, brevity that strikes instantly to a telling effect—all
U||   these an author may have without imitating any one’s style but rather
U||   imitating excellence. Poe’s “imitators” who have amounted to anything
U||   have not tried to imitate him but to vie with him. They are striving
U||   after perfectionism. Of course the sort of good style in which Poe
U||   indulged is not the kind of style—or the varieties of style—suited for
U||   all purposes, but for the purposes to which it is adapted it may well
U||   be called supreme.
U||   Then as a poet his work is almost or quite as excellent in a somewhat
U||   more restricted range. In verse he is probably the best artist in
U||   American letters. Here his sole pursuit was beauty, both of form and
U||   thought; he is vivid and apt, intensely lyrical but without much range
U||   of thought. He has deep intuitions but no comprehensive grasp of life.
U||   His criticism is, on the whole, the least important part of his work.
U||   He had a few good and brilliant ideas which came at just the right time
U||   to make a stir in the world, and these his logical mind and telling
U||   style enabled him to present to the best advantage. As a critic he is
U||   neither broad-minded, learned, nor comprehensive. Nor is he, except in
U||   the few ideas referred to, deep. He is, however, limitedly
U||   original—perhaps intensely original within his narrow scope. But the
U||   excellences and limitations of Poe in any one part of his work were his
U||   limitations and excellences in all.
U||   As Poe’s best short stories may be mentioned: Metzengerstein (Jan. 14,
U||   1832, Philadelphia Saturday Courier), Ms. Found in a Bottle (October
U||   19, 1833, Baltimore Saturday Visiter), The Assignation (January, 1834,
U||   Godey’s Lady’s Book), Berenice (March, 1835, Southern Literary
U||   Messenger), Morella (April, 1835, Southern Literary Messenger), The
U||   Unparalleled Adventure of One Hans Pfaall (June, 1835, Southern
U||   Literary Messenger), King Pest: a Tale Containing an Allegory
U||   (September, 1835, Southern Literary Messenger), Shadow: a Parable
U||   (September, 1835, Southern Literary Messenger), Ligeia (September,
U||   1838, American Museum), The Fall of the House of Usher (September,
U||   1839, Burton’s Gentleman’s Magazine), William Wilson (1839: Gift for
U||   1840), The Conversation of Eiros and Charmion (December, 1839, Burton’s
U||   Gentleman’s Magazine), The Murders in the Rue Morgue (April, 1841,
U||   Graham’s Magazine), A Descent into the Maelstrom (May, 1841, Graham’s
U||   Magazine), Eleonora (1841: Gift for 1842), The Masque of the Red Death
U||   (May, 1842, Graham’s Magazine), The Pit and the Pendulum (1842: Gift
U||   for 1843), The Tell-Tale Heart (January, 1843, Pioneer), The Gold-Bug
U||   (June 21 and 28, 1843, Dollar Newspaper), The Black Cat (August 19,
U||   1843, United States Saturday Post), The Oblong Box (September, 1844,
U||   Godey’s Lady’s Book), The Angel of the Odd (October, 1844, Columbian
U||   Magazine), “Thou Art the Man” (November, 1844, Godey’s Lady’s Book),
U||   The Purloined Letter (1844: Gift for 1845), The Imp of the Perverse
U||   (July, 1845, Graham’s Magazine), The System of Dr. Tarr and Prof.
U||   Fether (November, 1845, Graham’s Magazine), The Facts in the Case of M.
U||   Valdemar (December, 1845, American Whig Review), The Cask of
U||   Amontillado (November, 1846, Godey’s Lady’s Book), and Lander’s Cottage
U||   (June 9, 1849, Flag of Our Union). Poe’s chief collections are: Tales
U||   of the Grotesque and Arabesque (1840), Tales (1845), and The Works of
U||   the Late Edgar Allan Poe (1850–56). These titles have been dropped from
U||   recent editions of his works, however, and the stories brought together
U||   under the title Tales, or under subdivisions furnished by his editors,
U||   such as Tales of Ratiocination, etc.
U||   Caroline Matilda Stansbury Kirkland (1801–1864) wrote of the frontier
U||   life of the Middle West in the mid-nineteenth century. Her principal
U||   collection of short stories is Western Clearings (1845), from which The
U||   Schoolmaster’s Progress, first published in The Gift for 1845 (out in
U||   1844), is taken. Other stories republished in that collection are The
U||   Ball at Thram’s Huddle (April, 1840, Knickerbocker Magazine),
U||   Recollections of the Land-Fever (September, 1840, Knickerbocker
U||   Magazine), and The Bee-Tree (The Gift for 1842; out in 1841). Her
U||   description of the country schoolmaster, “a puppet cut out of shingle
U||   and jerked by a string,” and the local color in general of this and
U||   other stories give her a leading place among the writers of her period
U||   who combined fidelity in delineating frontier life with sufficient
U||   fictional interest to make a pleasing whole of permanent value.
U||   George William Curtis (1824–1892) gained his chief fame as an essayist,
U||   and probably became best known from the department which he conducted,
U||   from 1853, as The Editor’s Easy Chair for Harper’s Magazine for many
U||   years. His volume, Prue and I (1856), contains many fictional elements,
U||   and a story from it, Titbottom’s Spectacles, which first appeared in
U||   Putnam’s Monthly for December, 1854, is given in this volume because it
U||   is a good humorous short story rather than because of its author’s
U||   general eminence in this field. Other stories of his worth noting are
U||   The Shrouded Portrait (in The Knickerbocker Gallery, 1855) and The
U||   Millenial Club (November, 1858, Knickerbocker Magazine).
U||   Edward Everett Hale (1822–1909) is chiefly known as the author of the
U||   short story, The Man Without a Country (December, 1863, Atlantic
U||   Monthly), but his venture in the comic vein, My Double; and How He
U||   Undid Me (September, 1859, Atlantic Monthly), is equally worthy of
U||   appreciation. It was his first published story of importance. Other
U||   noteworthy stories of his are: The Brick Moon (October, November and
U||   December, 1869, Atlantic Monthly), Life in the Brick Moon (February,
U||   1870, Atlantic Monthly), and Susan’s Escort (May, 1890, Harper’s
U||   Magazine). His chief volumes of short stories are: The Man Without a
U||   Country, and Other Tales (1868); The Brick Moon, and Other Stories
U||   (1873); Crusoe in New York, and Other Tales (1880); and Susan’s Escort,
U||   and Others (1897). The stories by Hale which have made his fame all
U||   show ability of no mean order; but they are characterized by invention
U||   and ingenuity rather than by suffusing imagination. There is not much
U||   homogeneity about Hale’s work. Almost any two stories of his read as if
U||   they might have been written by different authors. For the time being
U||   perhaps this is an advantage—his stories charm by their novelty and
U||   individuality. In the long run, however, this proves rather a handicap.
U||   True individuality, in literature as in the other arts, consists not in
U||   “being different” on different occasions—in different works—so much as
U||   in being samely different from other writers; in being consistently
U||   one’s self, rather than diffusedly various selves. This does not lessen
U||   the value of particular stories, of course. It merely injures Hale’s
U||   fame as a whole. Perhaps some will chiefly feel not so much that his
U||   stories are different among themselves, but that they are not strongly
U||   anything—anybody’s—in particular, that they lack strong personality.
U||   The pathway to fame is strewn with stray exhibitions of talent. Apart
U||   from his purely literary productions, Hale was one of the large moral
U||   forces of his time, through “uplift” both in speech and the written
U||   word.
U||   Oliver Wendell Holmes (1809–1894), one of the leading wits of American
U||   literature, is not at all well known as a short story writer, nor did
U||   he write many brief pieces of fiction. His fame rests chiefly on his
U||   poems and on the Breakfast-Table books (1858-1860-1872-1890). Old
U||   Ironsides, The Last Leaf, The Chambered Nautilus and Homesick in Heaven
U||   are secure of places in the anthologies of the future, while his
U||   lighter verse has made him one of the leading American writers of
U||   “familiar verse.” Frederick Locker-Lampson in the preface to the first
U||   edition of his Lyra Elegantiarum (1867) declared that Holmes was
U||   “perhaps the best living writer of this species of verse.” His
U||   trenchant attack on Homeopathy and Its Kindred Delusions (1842) makes
U||   us wonder what would have been his attitude toward some of the beliefs
U||   of our own day; Christian Science, for example. He might have “exposed”
U||   it under some such title as The Religio-Medical Masquerade, or brought
U||   the batteries of his humor to bear on it in the manner of Robert Louis
U||   Stevenson’s fable, Something In It: “Perhaps there is not much in it,
U||   as I supposed; but there is something in it after all. Let me be
U||   thankful for that.” In Holmes’ long works of fiction, Elsie Venner
U||   (1861), The Guardian Angel (1867) and A Mortal Antipathy (1885), the
U||   method is still somewhat that of the essayist. I have found a short
U||   piece of fiction by him in the March, 1832, number of The New England
U||   Magazine, called The Début, signed O.W.H. The Story of Iris in The
U||   Professor at the Breakfast Table, which ran in The Atlantic throughout
U||   1859, and A Visit to the Asylum for Aged and Decayed Punsters (January,
U||   1861, Atlantic) are his only other brief fictions of which I am aware.
U||   The last named has been given place in the present selection because it
U||   is characteristic of a certain type and period of American humor,
U||   although its short story qualities are not particularly strong.
U||   Samuel Langhorne Clemens (1835–1910), who achieved fame as “Mark
U||   Twain,” is only incidentally a short story writer, although he wrote
U||   many short pieces of fiction. His humorous quality, I mean, is so
U||   preponderant, that one hardly thinks of the form. Indeed, he is never
U||   very strong in fictional construction, and of the modern short story
U||   art he evidently knew or cared little. He is a humorist in the large
U||   sense, as are Rabelais and Cervantes, although he is also a humorist in
U||   various restricted applications of the word that are wholly American.
U||   The Celebrated Jumping Frog of Calaveras County was his first
U||   publication of importance, and it saw the light in the Nov. 18, 1865,
U||   number of The Saturday Press. It was republished in the collection, The
U||   Celebrated Jumping Frog of Calaveras County, and Other Sketches, in
U||   1867. Others of his best pieces of short fiction are: The Canvasser’s
U||   Tale (December, 1876, Atlantic Monthly), The £1,000,000 Bank Note
U||   (January, 1893, Century Magazine), The Esquimau Maiden’s Romance
U||   (November, 1893, Cosmopolitan), Traveling with a Reformer (December,
U||   1893, Cosmopolitan), The Man That Corrupted Hadleyburg (December, 1899,
U||   Harper’s), A Double-Barrelled Detective Story (January and February,
U||   1902, Harper’s) A Dog’s Tale (December, 1903, Harper’s), and Eve’s
U||   Diary (December, 1905, Harper’s). Among Twain’s chief collections of
U||   short stories are: The Celebrated Jumping Frog of Calaveras County, and
U||   Other Sketches (1867); The Stolen White Elephant (1882), The £1,000,000
U||   Bank Note (1893), and The Man That Corrupted Hadleyburg, and Other
U||   Stories and Sketches (1900).
U||   Harry Stillwell Edwards (1855– ), a native of Georgia, together with
U||   Sarah Barnwell Elliott (? – ) and Will N. Harben (1858–1919) have
U||   continued in the vein of that earlier writer, Augustus Baldwin
U||   Longstreet (1790–1870), author of Georgia Scenes (1835). Edwards’ best
U||   work is to be found in his short stories of black and white life after
U||   the manner of Richard Malcolm Johnston. He has written several novels,
U||   but he is essentially a writer of human-nature sketches. “He is
U||   humorous and picturesque,” says Fred Lewis Pattee, “and often he is for
U||   a moment the master of pathos, but he has added nothing new and nothing
U||   commandingly distinctive.”[4][3] An exception to this might be made in
U||   favor of Elder Brown’s Backslide (August, 1885, Harper’s), a story in
U||   which all the elements are so nicely balanced that the result may well
U||   be called a masterpiece of objective humor and pathos. Others of his
U||   short stories especially worthy of mention are: Two Runaways (July,
U||   1886, Century), Sister Todhunter’s Heart (July, 1887, Century), “De
U||   Valley an’ de Shadder” (January, 1888, Century), An Idyl of “Sinkin’
U||   Mount’in” (October, 1888, Century), The Rival Souls (March, 1889,
U||   Century), The Woodhaven Goat (March, 1899, Century), and The Shadow
U||   (December, 1906, Century). His chief collections are Two Runaways, and
U||   Other Stories (1889) and His Defense, and Other Stories (1898).
U||   The most notable, however, of the group of short story writers of
U||   Georgia life is perhaps Richard Malcolm Johnston (1822–1898). He stands
U||   between Longstreet and the younger writers of Georgia life. His first
U||   book was Georgia Sketches, by an Old Man (1864). The Goose Pond School,
U||   a short story, had been written in 1857; it was not published, however,
U||   till it appeared in the November and December, 1869, numbers of a
U||   Southern magazine, The New Eclectic, over the pseudonym “Philemon
U||   Perch.” His famous Dukesborough Tales (1871–1874) was largely a
U||   republication of the earlier book. Other noteworthy collections of his
U||   are: Mr. Absalom Billingslea and Other Georgia Folk (1888), Mr.
U||   Fortner’s Marital Claims, and Other Stories (1892), and Old Times in
U||   Middle Georgia (1897). Among individual stories stand out: The
U||   Organ-Grinder (July, 1870, New Eclectic), Mr. Neelus Peeler’s
U||   Conditions (June, 1879, Scribner’s Monthly), The Brief Embarrassment of
U||   Mr. Iverson Blount (September, 1884, Century); The Hotel Experience of
U||   Mr. Pink Fluker (June, 1886, Century), republished in the present
U||   collection; The Wimpy Adoptions (February, 1887, Century), The
U||   Experiments of Miss Sally Cash (September, 1888, Century), and Our
U||   Witch (March, 1897, Century). Johnston must be ranked almost with Bret
U||   Harte as a pioneer in “local color” work, although his work had little
U||   recognition until his Dukesborough Tales were republished by Harper &
U||   Brothers in 1883.
U||   Bret Harte (1839–1902) is mentioned here owing to the late date of his
U||   story included in this volume, Colonel Starbottle for the Plaintiff
U||   (March, 1901, Harper’s), although his work as a whole of course belongs
U||   to an earlier period of our literature. It is now well-thumbed literary
U||   history that The Luck of Roaring Camp (August, 1868, Overland) and The
U||   Outcasts of Poker Flat (January, 1869, Overland) brought him a
U||   popularity that, in its suddenness and extent, had no precedent in
U||   American literature save in the case of Mrs. Stowe and Uncle Tom’s
U||   Cabin. According to Harte’s own statement, made in the retrospect of
U||   later years, he set out deliberately to add a new province to American
U||   literature. Although his work has been belittled because he has chosen
U||   exceptional and theatric happenings, yet his real strength came from
U||   his contact with Western life.
U||   Irving and Dickens and other models served only to teach him his art.
U||   “Finally,” says Prof. Pattee, “Harte was the parent of the modern form
U||   of the short story. It was he who started Kipling and Cable and Thomas
U||   Nelson Page. Few indeed have surpassed him in the mechanics of this
U||   most difficult of arts. According to his own belief, the form is an
U||   American product ... Harte has described the genesis of his own art. It
U||   sprang from the Western humor and was developed by the circumstances
U||   that surrounded him. Many of his short stories are models. They contain
U||   not a superfluous word, they handle a single incident with grapic
U||   power, they close without moral or comment. The form came as a natural
U||   evolution from his limitations and powers. With him the story must of
U||   necessity be brief.... Bret Harte was the artist of impulse, the
U||   painter of single burning moments, the flashlight photographer who
U||   caught in lurid detail one dramatic episode in the life of a man or a
U||   community and left the rest in darkness.”[5][4]
U||   Harte’s humor is mostly “Western humor” There is not always uproarious
U||   merriment, but there is a constant background of humor. I know of no
U||   more amusing scene in American literature than that in the courtroom
U||   when the Colonel gives his version of the deacon’s method of signaling
U||   to the widow in Harte’s story included in the present volume, Colonel
U||   Starbottle for the Plaintiff. Here is part of it:
U||   True to the instructions she had received from him, her lips part in
U||   the musical utterance (the Colonel lowered his voice in a faint
U||   falsetto, presumably in fond imitation of his fair client) “Kerree!”
U||   Instantly the night becomes resonant with the impassioned reply (the
U||   Colonel here lifted his voice in stentorian tones), “Kerrow!” Again, as
U||   he passes, rises the soft “Kerree!”; again, as his form is lost in the
U||   distance, comes back the deep “Kerrow!”
U||   While Harte’s stories all have in them a certain element or background
U||   of humor, yet perhaps the majority of them are chiefly romantic or
U||   dramatic even more than they are humorous.
U||   Among the best of his short stories may be mentioned: The Luck of
U||   Roaring Camp (August, 1868, Overland), The Outcasts of Poker Flat
U||   (January, 1869, Overland), Tennessee’s Partner (October, 1869,
U||   Overland), Brown of Calaveras (March, 1870, Overland), Flip: a
U||   California Romance (in Flip, and Other Stories, 1882), Left Out on Lone
U||   Star Mountain (January, 1884, Longman’s), An Ingenue of the Sierras
U||   (July, 1894, McClure’s), The Bell-Ringer of Angel’s (in The Bell-Ringer
U||   of Angel’s, and Other Stories, 1894), Chu Chu (in The Bell-Ringer of
U||   Angel’s, and Other Stories, 1894), The Man and the Mountain (in The
U||   Ancestors of Peter Atherly, and Other Tales, 1897), Salomy Jane’s Kiss
U||   (in Stories in Light and Shadow, 1898), The Youngest Miss Piper
U||   (February, 1900, Leslie’s Monthly), Colonel Starbottle for the
U||   Plaintiff (March, 1901, Harper’s), A Mercury of the Foothills (July,
U||   1901, Cosmopolitan), Lanty Foster’s Mistake (December, 1901, New
U||   England), An Ali Baba of the Sierras (January 4, 1902, Saturday Evening
U||   Post), and Dick Boyle’s Business Card (in Trent’s Trust, and Other
U||   Stories, 1903). Among his notable collections of stories are: The Luck
U||   of Roaring Camp, and Other Sketches (1870), Flip, and Other Stories
U||   (1882), On the Frontier (1884), Colonel Starbottle’s Client, and Some
U||   Other People (1892), A Protégé of Jack Hamlin’s, and Other Stories
U||   (1894), The Bell-Ringer of Angel’s, and Other Stories (1894), The
U||   Ancestors of Peter Atherly, and Other Tales (1897), Openings in the Old
U||   Trail (1902), and Trent’s Trust, and Other Stories (1903). The titles
U||   and makeup of several of his collections were changed when they came to
U||   be arranged in the complete edition of his works.[6][5]
U||   Henry Cuyler Bunner (1855–1896) is one of the humorous geniuses of
U||   American literature. He is equally at home in clever verse or the brief
U||   short story. Prof. Fred Lewis Pattee has summed up his achievement as
U||   follows: “Another [than Stockton] who did much to advance the short
U||   story toward the mechanical perfection it had attained to at the close
U||   of the century was Henry Cuyler Bunner, editor of Puck and creator of
U||   some of the most exquisite vers de société of the period. The title of
U||   one of his collections, Made in France: French Tales Retold with a U.S.
U||   Twist (1893), forms an introduction to his fiction. Not that he was an
U||   imitator; few have been more original or have put more of their own
U||   personality into their work. His genius was Gallic. Like Aldrich, he
U||   approached the short story from the fastidious standpoint of the lyric
U||   poet. With him, as with Aldrich, art was a matter of exquisite touches,
U||   of infinite compression, of almost imperceptible shadings. The lurid
U||   splashes and the heavy emphasis of the local colorists offended his
U||   sensitive taste: he would work with suggestion, with microscopic
U||   focussings, and always with dignity and elegance. He was more American
U||   than Henry James, more even than Aldrich. He chose always distinctively
U||   American subjects—New York City was his favorite theme—and his work had
U||   more depth of soul than Stockton’s or Aldrich’s. The story may be
U||   trivial, a mere expanded anecdote, yet it is sure to be so vitally
U||   treated that, like Maupassant’s work, it grips and remains, and, what
U||   is more, it lifts and chastens or explains. It may be said with
U||   assurance that Short Sixes marks one of the high places which have been
U||   attained by the American short story.”[7][6]
U||   Among Bunner’s best stories are: Love in Old Cloathes (September, 1883,
U||   Century), A Successful Failure (July, 1887, Puck), The Love-Letters of
U||   Smith (July 23, 1890, Puck) The Nice People (July 30, 1890, Puck), The
U||   Nine Cent-Girls (August 13, 1890, Puck), The Two Churches of ’Quawket
U||   (August 27, 1890, Puck), A Round-Up (September 10, 1890, Puck), A
U||   Sisterly Scheme (September 24, 1890, Puck), Our Aromatic Uncle (August,
U||   1895, Scribner’s), The Time-Table Test (in The Suburban Sage, 1896). He
U||   collaborated with Prof. Brander Matthews in several stories, notably in
U||   The Documents in the Case (Sept., 1879, Scribner’s Monthly). His best
U||   collections are: Short Sixes: Stories to be Read While the Candle Burns
U||   (1891), More Short Sixes (1894), and Love in Old Cloathes, and Other
U||   Stories (1896).
U||   After Poe and Hawthorne almost the first author in America to make a
U||   vertiginous impression by his short stories was Bret Harte. The wide
U||   and sudden popularity he attained by the publication of his two short
U||   stories, The Luck of Roaring Camp (1868) and The Outcasts of Poker Flat
U||   (1869), has already been noted.[8][7] But one story just before Harte
U||   that astonished the fiction audience with its power and art was Harriet
U||   Prescott Spofford’s (1835– ) The Amber Gods (January and February,
U||   1860, Atlantic), with its startling ending, “I must have died at ten
U||   minutes past one.” After Harte the next story to make a great sensation
U||   was Thomas Bailey Aldrich’s Marjorie Daw (April, 1873, Atlantic), a
U||   story with a surprise at the end, as had been his A Struggle for Life
U||   (July, 1867, Atlantic), although it was only Marjorie Daw that
U||   attracted much attention at the time. Then came George Washington
U||   Cable’s (1844– ) “Posson Jone’,” (April 1, 1876, Appleton’s Journal)
U||   and a little later Charles Egbert Craddock’s (1850– ) The Dancin’ Party
U||   at Harrison’s Cove (May, 1878, Atlantic) and The Star in the Valley
U||   (November, 1878, Atlantic). But the work of Cable and Craddock, though
U||   of sterling worth, won its way gradually. Even Edward Everett Hale’s
U||   (1822–1909) My Double; and How He Undid Me (September, 1859, Atlantic)
U||   and The Man Without a Country (December, 1863, Atlantic) had fallen
U||   comparatively still-born. The truly astounding short story successes,
U||   after Poe and Hawthorne, then, were Spofford, Bret Harte and Aldrich.
U||   Next came Frank Richard Stockton (1834–1902). “The interest created by
U||   the appearance of Marjorie Daw,” says Prof. Pattee, “was mild compared
U||   with that accorded to Frank R. Stockton’s The Lady or the Tiger?
U||   (1884). Stockton had not the technique of Aldrich nor his naturalness
U||   and ease. Certainly he had not his atmosphere of the beau monde and his
U||   grace of style, but in whimsicality and unexpectedness and in that
U||   subtle art that makes the obviously impossible seem perfectly plausible
U||   and commonplace he surpassed not only him but Edward Everett Hale and
U||   all others. After Stockton and The Lady or the Tiger? it was realized
U||   even by the uncritical that short story writing had become a subtle art
U||   and that the master of its subtleties had his reader at his
U||   mercy.”[9][8] The publication of Stockton’s short stories covers a
U||   period of over forty years, from Mahala’s Drive (November, 1868,
U||   Lippincott’s) to The Trouble She Caused When She Kissed (December,
U||   1911, Ladies’ Home Journal), published nine years after his death.
U||   Among the more notable of his stories may be mentioned: The Transferred
U||   Ghost (May, 1882, Century), The Lady or the Tiger? (November, 1882,
U||   Century), The Reversible Landscape (July, 1884, Century), The
U||   Remarkable Wreck of the “Thomas Hyke” (August, 1884, Century), “His
U||   Wife’s Deceased Sister” (January, 1884, Century), A Tale of Negative
U||   Gravity (December, 1884, Century), The Christmas Wreck (in The
U||   Christmas Wreck, and Other Stories, 1886), Amos Kilbright (in Amos
U||   Kilbright, His Adscititious Experiences, with Other Stories, 1888),
U||   Asaph (May, 1892, Cosmopolitan), My Terminal Moraine (April 26, 1892,
U||   Collier’s Once a Week Library), The Magic Egg (June, 1894, Century),
U||   The Buller-Podington Compact (August, 1897, Scribner’s), and The
U||   Widow’s Cruise (in A Story-Teller’s Pack, 1897). Most of his best work
U||   was gathered into the collections: The Lady or the Tiger?, and Other
U||   Stories (1884), The Bee-Man of Orn, and Other Fanciful Tales (1887),
U||   Amos Kilbright, His Adscititious Experiences, with Other Stories
U||   (1888), The Clocks of Rondaine, and Other Stories (1892), A Chosen Few
U||   (1895), A Story-Teller’s Pack (1897), and The Queen’s Museum, and Other
U||   Fanciful Tales (1906).
U||   After Stockton and Bunner come O. Henry (1862–1910) and Jack London
U||   (1876–1916), apostles of the burly and vigorous in fiction. Beside or
U||   above them stand Henry James (1843–1916)—although he belongs to an
U||   earlier period as well—Edith Wharton (1862– ), Alice Brown (1857– ),
U||   Margaret Wade Deland (1857– ), and Katharine Fullerton Gerould (1879–
U||   ), practitioners in all that O. Henry and London are not, of the finer
U||   fields, the more subtle nuances of modern life. With O. Henry and
U||   London, though perhaps less noteworthy, are to be grouped George
U||   Randolph Chester (1869– ) and Irvin Shrewsbury Cobb (1876– ). Then,
U||   standing rather each by himself, are Melville Davisson Post (1871– ), a
U||   master of psychological mystery stories, and Wilbur Daniel Steele
U||   (1886– ), whose work it is hard to classify. These ten names represent
U||   much that is best in American short story production since the
U||   beginning of the twentieth century (1900). Not all are notable for
U||   humor; but inasmuch as any consideration of the American humorous short
U||   story cannot be wholly dissociated from a consideration of the American
U||   short story in general, it has seemed not amiss to mention these
U||   authors here. Although Sarah Orne Jewett (1849–1909) lived on into the
U||   twentieth century and Mary E. Wilkins Freeman (1862– ) is still with
U||   us, the best and most typical work of these two writers belongs in the
U||   last two decades of the previous century. To an earlier period also
U||   belong Charles Egbert Craddock (1850– ), George Washington Cable (1844–
U||   ), Thomas Nelson Page (1853– ), Constance Fenimore Woolson (1848–1894),
U||   Harriet Prescott Spofford (1835– ), Hamlin Garland (1860– ), Ambrose
U||   Bierce (1842–?), Rose Terry Cooke (1827–1892), and Kate Chopin
U||   (1851–1904).
U||   “O. Henry” was the pen name adopted by William Sydney Porter. He began
U||   his short story career by contributing Whistling Dick’s Christmas
U||   Stocking to McClure’s Magazine in 1899. He followed it with many
U||   stories dealing with Western and South- and Central-American life, and
U||   later came most of his stories of the life of New York City, in which
U||   field lies most of his best work. He contributed more stories to the
U||   New York World than to any other one publication—as if the stories of
U||   the author who later came to be hailed as “the American Maupassant”
U||   were not good enough for the “leading” magazines but fit only for the
U||   sensation-loving public of the Sunday papers! His first published story
U||   that showed distinct strength was perhaps A Blackjack Bargainer
U||   (August, 1901, Munsey’s). He followed this with such masterly stories
U||   as: The Duplicity of Hargraves (February, 1902, Junior Munsey), The
U||   Marionettes (April, 1902, Black Cat), A Retrieved Reformation (April,
U||   1903, Cosmopolitan), The Guardian of the Accolade (May, 1903,
U||   Cosmopolitan), The Enchanted Kiss (February, 1904, Metropolitan), The
U||   Furnished Room (August 14, 1904, New York World), An Unfinished Story
U||   (August, 1905, McClure’s), The Count and the Wedding Guest (October 8,
U||   1905, New York World), The Gift of the Magi (December 10, 1905, New
U||   York World), The Trimmed Lamp (August, 1906, McClure’s), Phoebe
U||   (November, 1907, Everybody’s), The Hiding of Black Bill (October, 1908,
U||   Everybody’s), No Story (June, 1909, Metropolitan), A Municipal Report
U||   (November, 1909, Hampton’s), A Service of Love (in The Four Million,
U||   1909), The Pendulum (in The Trimmed Lamp, 1910), Brickdust Row (in The
U||   Trimmed Lamp, 1910), and The Assessor of Success (in The Trimmed Lamp,
U||   1910). Among O. Henry’s best volumes of short stories are: The Four
U||   Million (1909), Options (1909), Roads of Destiny (1909), The Trimmed
U||   Lamp (1910), Strictly Business: More Stories of the Four Million
U||   (1910), Whirligigs (1910), and Sixes and Sevens (1911).
U||   “Nowhere is there anything just like them. In his best work—and his
U||   tales of the great metropolis are his best—he is unique. The soul of
U||   his art is unexpectedness. Humor at every turn there is, and sentiment
U||   and philosophy and surprise. One never may be sure of himself. The end
U||   is always a sensation. No foresight may predict it, and the sensation
U||   always is genuine. Whatever else O. Henry was, he was an artist, a
U||   master of plot and diction, a genuine humorist, and a philosopher. His
U||   weakness lay in the very nature of his art. He was an entertainer bent
U||   only on amusing and surprising his reader. Everywhere brilliancy, but
U||   too often it is joined to cheapness; art, yet art merging swiftly into
U||   caricature. Like Harte, he cannot be trusted. Both writers on the whole
U||   may be said to have lowered the standards of American literature, since
U||   both worked in the surface of life with theatric intent and always
U||   without moral background, O. Henry moves, but he never lifts. All is
U||   fortissimo; he slaps the reader on the back and laughs loudly as if he
U||   were in a bar-room. His characters, with few exceptions, are extremes,
U||   caricatures. Even his shop girls, in the limning of whom he did his
U||   best work, are not really individuals; rather are they types, symbols.
U||   His work was literary vaudeville, brilliant, highly amusing, and yet
U||   vaudeville.”[10][9] The Duplicity of Hargraves, the story by O. Henry
U||   given in this volume, is free from most of his defects. It has a blend
U||   of humor and pathos that puts it on a plane of universal appeal.
U||   George Randolph Chester (1869– ) gained distinction by creating the
