U||   to the fore so far in America in the twentieth century. The story is no
U||   less delightful in its fidelity to fact and understanding of young
U||   human nature than in its relish of humor. Some of her stories deserving
U||   of special mention are: The Capture of Andy Proudfoot (June, 1904,
U||   Harper’s), In the Strength of the Hills (December, 1905, Metropolitan),
U||   The Machinations of Ocoee Gallantine (April, 1906, Century), A Call
U||   (August, 1906, Harper’s), Scott Bohannon’s Bond (May 4, 1907,
U||   Collier’s), and A Clean Shave (November, 1912, Century). Her best short
