U||   William James Lampton (?–1917), who was known to many of his admirers
U||   as Will Lampton or as W.J.L. merely, was one of the most unique and
U||   interesting characters of literary and Bohemian New York from about
U||   1895 to his death in 1917. I remember walking up Fifth Avenue with him
U||   one Sunday afternoon just after he had shown me a letter from the man
U||   who was then Comptroller of the Currency. The letter was signed so
U||   illegibly that my companion was in doubts as to the sender, so he
U||   suggested that we stop at a well-known hotel at the corner of 59th
U||   Street, and ask the manager who the Comptroller of the Currency then
U||   was, so that he might know whom the letter was from. He said that the
U||   manager of a big hotel like that, where many prominent people stayed,
U||   would be sure to know. When this problem had been solved to our
U||   satisfaction, John Skelton Williams proving to be the man, Lampton
U||   said, “Now you’ve told me who he is, I’ll show you who I am.” So he
U||   asked for a copy of The American Magazine at a newsstand in the hotel
U||   corridor, opened it, and showed the manager a full-page picture of
U||   himself clad in a costume suggestive of the time of Christopher
U||   Columbus, with high ruffs around his neck, that happened to appear in
U||   the magazine the current month. I mention this incident to illustrate
U||   the lack of conventionality and whimsical originality of the man, that
U||   stood out no less forcibly in his writings than in his daily life. He
U||   had little use for “doing the usual thing in the usual sort of way.” He
U||   first gained prominence by his book of verse, Yawps (1900). His poems
U||   were free from convention in technique as well as in spirit, although
U||   their chief innovation was simply that as a rule there was no regular
U||   number of syllables in a line; he let the lines be any length they
U||   wanted to be, to fit the sense or the length of what he had to say. He
U||   once said to me that if anything of his was remembered he thought it
U||   would be his poem, Lo, the Summer Girl. His muse often took the
U||   direction of satire, but it was always good-natured even when it hit
U||   the hardest. He had in his makeup much of the detached philosopher,
U||   like Cervantes and Mark Twain.
U||   There was something cosmic about his attitude to life, and this showed
U||   in much that he did. He was the only American writer of humorous verse
U||   of his day whom I always cared to read, or whose lines I could remember
U||   more than a few weeks. This was perhaps because his work was never
U||   merely humorous, but always had a big sweep of background to it, like
U||   the ruggedness of the Kentucky mountains from which he came. It was
U||   Colonel George Harvey, then editor of Harper’s Weekly, who had started
U||   the boom to make Woodrow Wilson President. Wilson afterwards, at least
U||   seemingly, repudiated his sponsor, probably because of Harvey’s
U||   identification with various moneyed interests. Lampton’s poem on the
U||   subject, with its refrain, “Never again, said Colonel George,” I
U||   remember as one of the most notable of his poems on current topics. But
U||   what always seemed to me the best of his poems dealing with matters of
U||   the hour was one that I suggested he write, which dealt with
U||   gift-giving to the public, at about the time that Andrew Carnegie was
U||   making a big stir with his gifts for libraries, beginning:
U||   Dunno, perhaps
U||   One of the yaps
U||   Like me would make
U||   A holy break
U||   Doing his turn
U||   With money to burn.
U||   Anyhow, I
U||   Wouldn’t shy
U||   Making a try!
U||   and containing, among many effective touches, the pathetic lines,
U||   . . . I’d help
U||   The poor who try to help themselves,
U||   Who have to work so hard for bread
U||   They can’t get very far ahead.
U||   When James Lane Allen’s novel, The Reign of Law, came out (1900), a
U||   little quatrain by Lampton that appeared in The Bookman (September,
U||   1900) swept like wildfire across the country, and was read by a hundred
U||   times as many people as the book itself:
U||   “The Reign of Law”?
U||   Well, Allen, you’re lucky;
U||   It’s the first time it ever
U||   Rained law in Kentucky!
U||   The reader need not be reminded that at that period Kentucky family
U||   feuds were well to the fore. As Lampton had started as a poet, the
U||   editors were bound to keep him pigeon-holed as far as they could, and
U||   his ambition to write short stories was not at first much encouraged by
U||   them. His predicament was something like that of the chief character of
U||   Frank R. Stockton’s story, “His Wife’s Deceased Sister” (January, 1884,
U||   Century), who had written a story so good that whenever he brought the
U||   editors another story they invariably answered in substance, “We’re
U||   afraid it won’t do. Can’t you give us something like ‘His Wife’s
U||   Deceased Sister’?” This was merely Stockton’s turning to account his
U||   own somewhat similar experience with the editors after his story, The
U||   Lady or the Tiger? (November, 1882, Century) appeared. Likewise the
U||   editors didn’t want Lampton’s short stories for a while because they
U||   liked his poems so well.
U||   Do I hear some critics exclaiming that there is nothing remarkable
U||   about How the Widow Won the Deacon, the story by Lampton included in
U||   this volume? It handles an amusing situation lightly and with grace. It
U||   is one of those things that read easily and are often difficult to
U||   achieve. Among his best stories are: The People’s Number of the
U||   Worthyville Watchman (May 12, 1900, Saturday Evening Post), Love’s
U||   Strange Spell (April 27, 1901, Saturday Evening Post), Abimelech
U||   Higgins’ Way (August 24, 1001, Saturday Evening Post), A Cup of Tea
U||   (March, 1902, Metropolitan), Winning His Spurs (May, 1904,
U||   Cosmopolitan), The Perfidy of Major Pulsifer (November, 1909,
U||   Cosmopolitan), How the Widow Won the Deacon (April, 1911, Harper’s
U||   Bazaar), and A Brown Study (December, 1913, Lippincott’s). There is no
U||   collection as yet of his short stories. Although familiarly known as
U||   “Colonel” Lampton, and although of Kentucky, he was not merely a
U||   “Kentucky Colonel,” for he was actually appointed Colonel on the staff
U||   of the governor of Kentucky. At the time of his death he was about to
U||   be made a brigadier-general and was planning to raise a brigade of
U||   Kentucky mountaineers for service in the Great War. As he had just
U||   struck his stride in short story writing, the loss to literature was
U||   even greater than the patriotic loss.
U||   Gideon (April, 1914, Century), by Wells Hastings (1878– ), the story
U||   with which this volume closes, calls to mind the large number of
U||   notable short stories in American literature by writers who have made
U||   no large name for themselves as short story writers, or even otherwise
U||   in letters. American literature has always been strong in its “stray”
U||   short stories of note. In Mr. Hastings’ case, however, I feel that the
U||   fame is sure to come. He graduated from Yale in 1902, collaborated with
U||   Brian Hooker (1880- ) in a novel, The Professor’s Mystery (1911) and
U||   alone wrote another novel, The Man in the Brown Derby (1911). His short
U||   stories include: The New Little Boy (July, 1911, American), That Day
U||   (September, 1911, American), The Pick-Up (December, 1911, Everybody’s),
U||   and Gideon (April, 1914, Century). The last story stands out. It can be
U||   compared without disadvantage to the best work, or all but the very
U||   best work, of Thomas Nelson Page, it seems to me. And from the reader’s
U||   standpoint it has the advantage—is this not also an author’s
U||   advantage?—of a more modern setting and treatment. Mr. Hastings is, I
U||   have been told, a director in over a dozen large corporations. Let us
U||   hope that his business activities will not keep him too much away from
U||   the production of literature—for to rank as a piece of literature,
U||   something of permanent literary value, Gideon is surely entitled.
U||   ALEXANDER JESSUP.
