U||THE LITTLE FRENCHMAN AND HIS WATER LOTS[39][10]
U||   By George Pope Morris (1802–1864)
U||   Look into those they call unfortunate,
U||   And, closer view’d, you’ll find they are unwise.—Young.
U||   Let wealth come in by comely thrift,
U||   And not by any foolish shift:
U||   ’Tis haste
U||   Makes waste:
U||   Who gripes too hard the dry and slippery sand
U||   Holds none at all, or little, in his hand.—Herrick.
U||   Let well alone.—Proverb.
U||   How much real comfort every one might enjoy if he would be contented
U||   with the lot in which heaven has cast him, and how much trouble would
U||   be avoided if people would only “let well alone.” A moderate
U||   independence, quietly and honestly procured, is certainly every way
U||   preferable even to immense possessions achieved by the wear and tear of
U||   mind and body so necessary to procure them. Yet there are very few
U||   individuals, let them be doing ever so well in the world, who are not
U||   always straining every nerve to do better; and this is one of the many
U||   causes why failures in business so frequently occur among us. The
U||   present generation seem unwilling to “realize” by slow and sure
U||   degrees; but choose rather to set their whole hopes upon a single cast,
U||   which either makes or mars them forever!
U||   Gentle reader, do you remember Monsieur Poopoo? He used to keep a small
U||   toy-store in Chatham, near the corner of Pearl Street. You must
U||   recollect him, of course. He lived there for many years, and was one of
U||   the most polite and accommodating of shopkeepers. When a juvenile, you
U||   have bought tops and marbles of him a thousand times. To be sure you
U||   have; and seen his vinegar-visage lighted up with a smile as you flung
U||   him the coppers; and you have laughed at his little straight queue and
U||   his dimity breeches, and all the other oddities that made up the
U||   everyday apparel of my little Frenchman. Ah, I perceive you recollect
U||   him now.
U||   Well, then, there lived Monsieur Poopoo ever since he came from “dear,
U||   delightful Paris,” as he was wont to call the city of his
U||   nativity—there he took in the pennies for his kickshaws—there he laid
U||   aside five thousand dollars against a rainy day—there he was as happy
U||   as a lark—and there, in all human probability, he would have been to
U||   this very day, a respected and substantial citizen, had he been willing
U||   to “let well alone.” But Monsieur Poopoo had heard strange stories
U||   about the prodigious rise in real estate; and, having understood that
U||   most of his neighbors had become suddenly rich by speculating in lots,
U||   he instantly grew dissatisfied with his own lot, forthwith determined
U||   to shut up shop, turn everything into cash, and set about making money
U||   in right-down earnest. No sooner said than done; and our quondam
U||   storekeeper a few days afterward attended an extensive sale of real
U||   estate, at the Merchants’ Exchange.
U||   There was the auctioneer, with his beautiful and inviting lithographic
U||   maps—all the lots as smooth and square and enticingly laid out as
U||   possible—and there were the speculators—and there, in the midst of
U||   them, stood Monsieur Poopoo.
U||   “Here they are, gentlemen,” said he of the hammer, “the most valuable
U||   lots ever offered for sale. Give me a bid for them!”
U||   “One hundred each,” said a bystander.
U||   “One hundred!” said the auctioneer, “scarcely enough to pay for the
U||   maps. One hundred—going—and fifty—gone! Mr. H., they are yours. A noble
U||   purchase. You’ll sell those same lots in less than a fortnight for
U||   fifty thousand dollars profit!”
U||   Monsieur Poopoo pricked up his ears at this, and was lost in
U||   astonishment. This was a much easier way certainly of accumulating
U||   riches than selling toys in Chatham Street, and he determined to buy
U||   and mend his fortune without delay.
U||   The auctioneer proceeded in his sale. Other parcels were offered and
U||   disposed of, and all the purchasers were promised immense advantages
U||   for their enterprise. At last came a more valuable parcel than all the
U||   rest. The company pressed around the stand, and Monsieur Poopoo did the
U||   same.
U||   “I now offer you, gentlemen, these magnificent lots, delightfully
U||   situated on Long Island, with valuable water privileges. Property in
U||   fee—title indisputable—terms of sale, cash—deeds ready for delivery
U||   immediately after the sale. How much for them? Give them a start at
U||   something. How much?” The auctioneer looked around; there were no
U||   bidders. At last he caught the eye of Monsieur Poopoo. “Did you say one
U||   hundred, sir? Beautiful lots—valuable water privileges—shall I say one
U||   hundred for you?”
U||   “Oui, monsieur; I will give you von hundred dollar apiece, for de lot
U||   vid de valuarble vatare privalege; c’est ça.”
U||   “Only one hundred apiece for these sixty valuable lots—only one
U||   hundred—going—going—going—gone!”
U||   Monsieur Poopoo was the fortunate possessor. The auctioneer
U||   congratulated him—the sale closed—and the company dispersed.
U||   “Pardonnez-moi, monsieur,” said Poopoo, as the auctioneer descended his
U||   pedestal, “you shall excusez-moi, if I shall go to votre bureau, your
U||   counting-house, ver quick to make every ting sure wid respec to de lot
U||   vid de valuarble vatare privalege. Von leetle bird in de hand he vorth
U||   two in de tree, c’est vrai—eh?”
U||   “Certainly, sir.”
U||   “Vell den, allons.”
U||   And the gentlemen repaired to the counting-house, where the six
U||   thousand dollars were paid, and the deeds of the property delivered.
U||   Monsieur Poopoo put these carefully in his pocket, and as he was about
U||   taking his leave, the auctioneer made him a present of the lithographic
U||   outline of the lots, which was a very liberal thing on his part,
U||   considering the map was a beautiful specimen of that glorious art.
U||   Poopoo could not admire it sufficiently. There were his sixty lots, as
U||   uniform as possible, and his little gray eyes sparkled like diamonds as
U||   they wandered from one end of the spacious sheet to the other.
U||   Poopoo’s heart was as light as a feather, and he snapped his fingers in
U||   the very wantonness of joy as he repaired to Delmonico’s, and ordered
U||   the first good French dinner that had gladdened his palate since his
U||   arrival in America.
U||   After having discussed his repast, and washed it down with a bottle of
U||   choice old claret, he resolved upon a visit to Long Island to view his
U||   purchase. He consequently immediately hired a horse and gig, crossed
U||   the Brooklyn ferry, and drove along the margin of the river to the
U||   Wallabout, the location in question.
U||   Our friend, however, was not a little perplexed to find his property.
U||   Everything on the map was as fair and even as possible, while all the
U||   grounds about him were as undulated as they could well be imagined, and
U||   there was an elbow of the East River thrusting itself quite into the
U||   ribs of the land, which seemed to have no business there. This puzzled
U||   the Frenchman exceedingly; and, being a stranger in those parts, he
U||   called to a farmer in an adjacent field.
U||   “Mon ami, are you acquaint vid dis part of de country—eh?”
U||   “Yes, I was born here, and know every inch of it.”
U||   “Ah, c’est bien, dat vill do,” and the Frenchman got out of the gig,
U||   tied the horse, and produced his lithographic map.
U||   “Den maybe you vill have de kindness to show me de sixty lot vich I
U||   have bought, vid de valuarble vatare privalege?”
U||   The farmer glanced his eye over the paper.
U||   “Yes, sir, with pleasure; if you will be good enough to get into my
U||   boat, I will row you out to them!”
U||   “Vat dat you say, sure?”
U||   “My friend,” said the farmer, “this section of Long Island has recently
U||   been bought up by the speculators of New York, and laid out for a great
U||   city; but the principal street is only visible at low tide. When this
U||   part of the East River is filled up, it will be just there. Your lots,
U||   as you will perceive, are beyond it; and are now all under water.”
U||   At first the Frenchman was incredulous. He could not believe his
U||   senses. As the facts, however, gradually broke upon him, he shut one
U||   eye, squinted obliquely at the heavens—-the river—the farmer—and then
U||   he turned away and squinted at them all over again! There was his
U||   purchase sure enough; but then it could not be perceived for there was
U||   a river flowing over it! He drew a box from his waistcoat pocket,
U||   opened it, with an emphatic knock upon the lid, took a pinch of snuff
U||   and restored it to his waistcoat pocket as before. Poopoo was evidently
U||   in trouble, having “thoughts which often lie too deep for tears”; and,
U||   as his grief was also too big for words, he untied his horse, jumped
U||   into his gig, and returned to the auctioneer in hot haste.
U||   It was near night when he arrived at the auction-room—his horse in a
U||   foam and himself in a fury. The auctioneer was leaning back in his
U||   chair, with his legs stuck out of a low window, quietly smoking a cigar
U||   after the labors of the day, and humming the music from the last new
U||   opera.
U||   “Monsieur, I have much plaisir to fin’ you, chez vous, at home.”
U||   “Ah, Poopoo! glad to see you. Take a seat, old boy.”
U||   “But I shall not take de seat, sare.”
U||   “No—why, what’s the matter?”
U||   “Oh, beaucoup de matter. I have been to see de gran lot vot you sell me
U||   to-day.”
U||   “Well, sir, I hope you like your purchase?”
U||   “No, monsieur, I no like him.”
U||   “I’m sorry for it; but there is no ground for your complaint.”
U||   “No, sare; dare is no ground at all—de ground is all vatare!”
U||   “You joke!”
U||   “I no joke. I nevare joke; je n’entends pas la raillerie, Sare,
U||   voulez-vous have de kindness to give me back de money vot I pay!”
U||   “Certainly not.”
U||   “Den vill you be so good as to take de East River off de top of my
U||   lot?”
U||   “That’s your business, sir, not mine.”
U||   “Den I make von mauvaise affaire—von gran mistake!”
U||   “I hope not. I don’t think you have thrown your money away in the
U||   land.”
U||   “No, sare; but I tro it avay in de vatare!”
U||   “That’s not my fault.”
U||   “Yes, sare, but it is your fault. You’re von ver gran rascal to swindle
U||   me out of de l’argent.”
U||   “Hello, old Poopoo, you grow personal; and if you can’t keep a civil
U||   tongue in your head, you must go out of my counting-room.”
U||   “Vare shall I go to, eh?”
U||   “To the devil, for aught I care, you foolish old Frenchman!” said the
U||   auctioneer, waxing warm.
U||   “But, sare, I vill not go to de devil to oblige you!” replied the
U||   Frenchman, waxing warmer. “You sheat me out of all de dollar vot I make
U||   in Shatham Street; but I vill not go to de devil for all dat. I vish
U||   you may go to de devil yourself you dem yankee-doo-dell, and I vill go
U||   and drown myself, tout de suite, right avay.”
U||   “You couldn’t make a better use of your water privileges, old boy!”
U||   “Ah, miséricorde! Ah, mon dieu, je suis abîmé. I am ruin! I am done up!
U||   I am break all into ten sousan leetle pieces! I am von lame duck, and I
U||   shall vaddle across de gran ocean for Paris, vish is de only valuarble
U||   vatare privalege dat is left me à present!”
U||   Poor Poopoo was as good as his word. He sailed in the next packet, and
U||   arrived in Paris almost as penniless as the day he left it.
U||   Should any one feel disposed to doubt the veritable circumstances here
U||   recorded, let him cross the East River to the Wallabout, and farmer J——
U||   will row him out to the very place where the poor Frenchman’s lots
U||   still remain under water.
