U||THE ANGEL OF THE ODD[41][11]
U||   By Edgar Allan Poe (1809–1849)
U||   It was a chilly November afternoon. I had just consummated an unusually
U||   hearty dinner, of which the dyspeptic truffe formed not the least
U||   important item, and was sitting alone in the dining-room with my feet
U||   upon the fender and at my elbow a small table which I had rolled up to
U||   the fire, and upon which were some apologies for dessert, with some
U||   miscellaneous bottles of wine, spirit, and liqueur. In the morning I
U||   had been reading Glover’s Leonidas, Wilkie’s Epigoniad, Lamartine’s
U||   Pilgrimage, Barlow’s Columbiad, Tuckerman’s Sicily, and Griswold’s
U||   Curiosities, I am willing to confess, therefore, that I now felt a
U||   little stupid. I made effort to arouse myself by frequent aid of
U||   Lafitte, and all failing, I betook myself to a stray newspaper in
U||   despair. Having carefully perused the column of “Houses to let,” and
U||   the column of “Dogs lost,” and then the columns of “Wives and
U||   apprentices runaway,” I attacked with great resolution the editorial
U||   matter, and reading it from beginning to end without understanding a
U||   syllable, conceived the possibility of its being Chinese, and so
U||   re-read it from the end to the beginning, but with no more satisfactory
U||   result. I was about throwing away in disgust
U||   This folio of four pages, happy work
U||   Which not even critics criticise,
U||   when I felt my attention somewhat aroused by the paragraph which
U||   follows:
U||   “The avenues to death are numerous and strange. A London paper mentions
U||   the decease of a person from a singular cause. He was playing at ‘puff
U||   the dart,’ which is played with a long needle inserted in some worsted,
U||   and blown at a target through a tin tube. He placed the needle at the
U||   wrong end of the tube, and drawing his breath strongly to puff the dart
U||   forward with force, drew the needle into his throat. It entered the
U||   lungs, and in a few days killed him.”
U||   Upon seeing this I fell into a great rage, without exactly knowing why.
U||   “This thing,” I exclaimed, “is a contemptible falsehood—a poor hoax—the
U||   lees of the invention of some pitiable penny-a-liner, of some wretched
U||   concocter of accidents in Cocaigne. These fellows knowing the
U||   extravagant gullibility of the age set their wits to work in the
U||   imagination of improbable possibilities, of odd accidents as they term
U||   them, but to a reflecting intellect (like mine, I added, in
U||   parenthesis, putting my forefinger unconsciously to the side of my
U||   nose), to a contemplative understanding such as I myself possess, it
U||   seems evident at once that the marvelous increase of late in these ‘odd
U||   accidents’ is by far the oddest accident of all. For my own part, I
U||   intend to believe nothing henceforward that has anything of the
U||   ‘singular’ about it.”
U||   “Mein Gott, den, vat a vool you bees for dat!” replied one of the most
U||   remarkable voices I ever heard. At first I took it for a rumbling in my
U||   ears—such as a man sometimes experiences when getting very drunk—but
U||   upon second thought, I considered the sound as more nearly resembling
U||   that which proceeds from an empty barrel beaten with a big stick; and,
U||   in fact, this I should have concluded it to be, but for the
U||   articulation of the syllables and words. I am by no means naturally
U||   nervous, and the very few glasses of Lafitte which I had sipped served
U||   to embolden me a little, so that I felt nothing of trepidation, but
U||   merely uplifted my eyes with a leisurely movement and looked carefully
U||   around the room for the intruder. I could not, however, perceive any
U||   one at all.
U||   “Humph!” resumed the voice as I continued my survey, “you mus pe so
U||   dronk as de pig den for not zee me as I zit here at your zide.”
U||   Hereupon I bethought me of looking immediately before my nose, and
U||   there, sure enough, confronting me at the table sat a personage
U||   nondescript, although not altogether indescribable. His body was a
U||   wine-pipe or a rum puncheon, or something of that character, and had a
U||   truly Falstaffian air. In its nether extremity were inserted two kegs,
U||   which seemed to answer all the purposes of legs. For arms there dangled
U||   from the upper portion of the carcass two tolerably long bottles with
U||   the necks outward for hands. All the head that I saw the monster
U||   possessed of was one of those Hessian canteens which resemble a large
U||   snuff-box with a hole in the middle of the lid. This canteen (with a
U||   funnel on its top like a cavalier cap slouched over the eyes) was set
U||   on edge upon the puncheon, with the hole toward myself; and through
U||   this hole, which seemed puckered up like the mouth of a very precise
U||   old maid, the creature was emitting certain rumbling and grumbling
U||   noises which he evidently intended for intelligible talk.
U||   “I zay,” said he, “you mos pe dronk as de pig, vor zit dare and not zee
U||   me zit ere; and I zay, doo, you mos pe pigger vool as de goose, vor to
U||   dispelief vat iz print in de print. ’Tiz de troof—dat it iz—ebery vord
U||   ob it.”
U||   “Who are you, pray?” said I with much dignity, although somewhat
U||   puzzled; “how did you get here? and what is it you are talking about?”
U||   “As vor ow I com’d ere,” replied the figure, “dat iz none of your
U||   pizziness; and as vor vat I be talking apout, I be talk apout vat I
U||   tink proper; and as vor who I be, vy dat is de very ting I com’d here
U||   for to let you zee for yourself.”
U||   “You are a drunken vagabond,” said I, “and I shall ring the bell and
U||   order my footman to kick you into the street.”
U||   “He! he! he!” said the fellow, “hu! hu! hu! dat you can’t do.”
U||   “Can’t do!” said I, “what do you mean? I can’t do what?”
U||   “Ring de pell,” he replied, attempting a grin with his little
U||   villainous mouth.
U||   Upon this I made an effort to get up in order to put my threat into
U||   execution, but the ruffian just reached across the table very
U||   deliberately, and hitting me a tap on the forehead with the neck of one
U||   of the long bottles, knocked me back into the armchair from which I had
U||   half arisen. I was utterly astounded, and for a moment was quite at a
U||   loss what to do. In the meantime he continued his talk.
U||   “You zee,” said he, “it iz te bess vor zit still; and now you shall
U||   know who I pe. Look at me! zee! I am te Angel ov te Odd.”
U||   “And odd enough, too,” I ventured to reply; “but I was always under the
U||   impression that an angel had wings.”
U||   “Te wing!” he cried, highly incensed, “vat I pe do mit te wing? Mein
U||   Gott! do you take me for a shicken?”
U||   “No—oh, no!” I replied, much alarmed; “you are no chicken—certainly
U||   not.”
U||   “Well, den, zit still and pehabe yourself, or I’ll rap you again mid me
U||   vist. It iz te shicken ab te wing, und te owl ab te wing, und te imp ab
U||   te wing, und te head-teuffel ab te wing. Te angel ab not te wing, and I
U||   am te Angel ov te Odd.”
U||   “And your business with me at present is—is——”
U||   “My pizziness!” ejaculated the thing, “vy vat a low-bred puppy you mos
U||   pe vor to ask a gentleman und an angel apout his pizziness!”
U||   This language was rather more than I could bear, even from an angel;
U||   so, plucking up courage, I seized a salt-cellar which lay within reach,
U||   and hurled it at the head of the intruder. Either he dodged, however,
U||   or my aim was inaccurate; for all I accomplished was the demolition of
U||   the crystal which protected the dial of the clock upon the mantelpiece.
U||   As for the Angel, he evinced his sense of my assault by giving me two
U||   or three hard, consecutive raps upon the forehead as before. These
U||   reduced me at once to submission, and I am almost ashamed to confess
U||   that, either through pain or vexation, there came a few tears into my
U||   eyes.
U||   “Mein Gott!” said the Angel of the Odd, apparently much softened at my
U||   distress; “mein Gott, te man is eder ferry dronk or ferry zorry. You
U||   mos not trink it so strong—you mos put te water in te wine. Here, trink
U||   dis, like a good veller, and don’t gry now—don’t!”
U||   Hereupon the Angel of the Odd replenished my goblet (which was about a
U||   third full of port) with a colorless fluid that he poured from one of
U||   his hand-bottles. I observed that these bottles had labels about their
U||   necks, and that these labels were inscribed “Kirschenwässer.”
U||   The considerate kindness of the Angel mollified me in no little
U||   measure; and, aided by the water with which he diluted my port more
U||   than once, I at length regained sufficient temper to listen to his very
U||   extraordinary discourse. I cannot pretend to recount all that he told
U||   me, but I gleaned from what he said that he was a genius who presided
U||   over the contretemps of mankind, and whose business it was to bring
U||   about the odd accidents which are continually astonishing the skeptic.
U||   Once or twice, upon my venturing to express my total incredulity in
U||   respect to his pretensions, he grew very angry indeed, so that at
U||   length I considered it the wiser policy to say nothing at all, and let
U||   him have his own way. He talked on, therefore, at great length, while I
U||   merely leaned back in my chair with my eyes shut, and amused myself
U||   with munching raisins and filiping the stems about the room. But, by
U||   and by, the Angel suddenly construed this behavior of mine into
U||   contempt. He arose in a terrible passion, slouched his funnel down over
U||   his eyes, swore a vast oath, uttered a threat of some character, which
U||   I did not precisely comprehend, and finally made me a low bow and
U||   departed, wishing me, in the language of the archbishop in “Gil Bias,”
U||   beaucoup de bonheur et un peu plus de bon sens.
U||   His departure afforded me relief. The very few glasses of Lafitte that
U||   I had sipped had the effect of rendering me drowsy, and I felt inclined
U||   to take a nap of some fifteen or twenty minutes, as is my custom after
U||   dinner. At six I had an appointment of consequence, which it was quite
U||   indispensable that I should keep. The policy of insurance for my
U||   dwelling-house had expired the day before; and some dispute having
U||   arisen it was agreed that, at six, I should meet the board of directors
U||   of the company and settle the terms of a renewal. Glancing upward at
U||   the clock on the mantelpiece (for I felt too drowsy to take out my
U||   watch), I had the pleasure to find that I had still twenty-five minutes
U||   to spare. It was half-past five; I could easily walk to the insurance
U||   office in five minutes; and my usual siestas had never been known to
U||   exceed five-and-twenty. I felt sufficiently safe, therefore, and
U||   composed myself to my slumbers forthwith.
U||   Having completed them to my satisfaction, I again looked toward the
U||   timepiece, and was half inclined to believe in the possibility of odd
U||   accidents when I found that, instead of my ordinary fifteen or twenty
U||   minutes, I had been dozing only three; for it still wanted
U||   seven-and-twenty of the appointed hour. I betook myself again to my
U||   nap, and at length a second time awoke, when, to my utter amazement, it
U||   still wanted twenty-seven minutes of six. I jumped up to examine the
U||   clock, and found that it had ceased running. My watch informed me that
U||   it was half-past seven; and, of course, having slept two hours, I was
U||   too late for my appointment. “It will make no difference,” I said: “I
U||   can call at the office in the morning and apologize; in the meantime
U||   what can be the matter with the clock?” Upon examining it I discovered
U||   that one of the raisin stems which I had been filiping about the room
U||   during the discourse of the Angel of the Odd had flown through the
U||   fractured crystal, and lodging, singularly enough, in the keyhole, with
U||   an end projecting outward, had thus arrested the revolution of the
U||   minute hand.
U||   “Ah!” said I, “I see how it is. This thing speaks for itself. A natural
U||   accident, such as will happen now and then!”
U||   I gave the matter no further consideration, and at my usual hour
U||   retired to bed. Here, having placed a candle upon a reading stand at
U||   the bed head, and having made an attempt to peruse some pages of the
U||   Omnipresence of the Deity, I unfortunately fell asleep in less than
U||   twenty seconds, leaving the light burning as it was.
U||   My dreams were terrifically disturbed by visions of the Angel of the
U||   Odd. Methought he stood at the foot of the couch, drew aside the
U||   curtains, and in the hollow, detestable tones of a rum puncheon,
U||   menaced me with the bitterest vengeance for the contempt with which I
U||   had treated him. He concluded a long harangue by taking off his
U||   funnel-cap, inserting the tube into my gullet, and thus deluging me
U||   with an ocean of Kirschenwässer, which he poured in a continuous flood,
U||   from one of the long-necked bottles that stood him instead of an arm.
U||   My agony was at length insufferable, and I awoke just in time to
U||   perceive that a rat had run off with the lighted candle from the stand,
U||   but not in season to prevent his making his escape with it through the
U||   hole, Very soon a strong, suffocating odor assailed my nostrils; the
U||   house, I clearly perceived, was on fire. In a few minutes the blaze
U||   broke forth with violence, and in an incredibly brief period the entire
U||   building was wrapped in flames. All egress from my chamber, except
U||   through a window, was cut off. The crowd, however, quickly procured and
U||   raised a long ladder. By means of this I was descending rapidly, and in
U||   apparent safety, when a huge hog, about whose rotund stomach, and
U||   indeed about whose whole air and physiognomy, there was something which
U||   reminded me of the Angel of the Odd—when this hog, I say, which
U||   hitherto had been quietly slumbering in the mud, took it suddenly into
U||   his head that his left shoulder needed scratching, and could find no
U||   more convenient rubbing-post than that afforded by the foot of the
U||   ladder. In an instant I was precipitated, and had the misfortune to
U||   fracture my arm.
U||   This accident, with the loss of my insurance, and with the more serious
U||   loss of my hair, the whole of which had been singed off by the fire,
U||   predisposed me to serious impressions, so that finally I made up my
U||   mind to take a wife. There was a rich widow disconsolate for the loss
U||   of her seventh husband, and to her wounded spirit I offered the balm of
U||   my vows. She yielded a reluctant consent to my prayers. I knelt at her
U||   feet in gratitude and adoration. She blushed and bowed her luxuriant
U||   tresses into close contact with those supplied me temporarily by
U||   Grandjean. I know not how the entanglement took place but so it was. I
U||   arose with a shining pate, wigless; she in disdain and wrath,
U||   half-buried in alien hair. Thus ended my hopes of the widow by an
U||   accident which could not have been anticipated, to be sure, but which
U||   the natural sequence of events had brought about.
U||   Without despairing, however, I undertook the siege of a less implacable
U||   heart. The fates were again propitious for a brief period, but again a
U||   trivial incident interfered. Meeting my betrothed in an avenue thronged
U||   with the elite of the city, I was hastening to greet her with one of my
U||   best considered bows, when a small particle of some foreign matter
U||   lodging in the corner of my eye rendered me for the moment completely
U||   blind. Before I could recover my sight, the lady of my love had
U||   disappeared—irreparably affronted at what she chose to consider my
U||   premeditated rudeness in passing her by ungreeted. While I stood
U||   bewildered at the suddenness of this accident (which might have
U||   happened, nevertheless, to any one under the sun), and while I still
U||   continued incapable of sight, I was accosted by the Angel of the Odd,
U||   who proffered me his aid with a civility which I had no reason to
U||   expect. He examined my disordered eye with much gentleness and skill,
U||   informed me that I had a drop in it, and (whatever a “drop” was) took
U||   it out, and afforded me relief.
U||   I now considered it high time to die (since fortune had so determined
U||   to persecute me), and accordingly made my way to the nearest river.
U||   Here, divesting myself of my clothes (for there is no reason why we
U||   cannot die as we were born), I threw myself headlong into the current;
U||   the sole witness of my fate being a solitary crow that had been seduced
U||   into the eating of brandy-saturated corn, and so had staggered away
U||   from his fellows. No sooner had I entered the water than this bird took
U||   it into his head to fly away with the most indispensable portion of my
U||   apparel. Postponing, therefore, for the present, my suicidal design, I
U||   just slipped my nether extremities into the sleeves of my coat, and
U||   betook myself to a pursuit of the felon with all the nimbleness which
U||   the case required and its circumstances would admit. But my evil
U||   destiny attended me still. As I ran at full speed, with my nose up in
U||   the atmosphere, and intent only upon the purloiner of my property, I
U||   suddenly perceived that my feet rested no longer upon terra firma; the
U||   fact is, I had thrown myself over a precipice, and should inevitably
U||   have been dashed to pieces but for my good fortune in grasping the end
U||   of a long guide-rope, which depended from a passing balloon.
U||   As soon as I sufficiently recovered my senses to comprehend the
U||   terrific predicament in which I stood, or rather hung, I exerted all
U||   the power of my lungs to make that predicament known to the aeronaut
U||   overhead. But for a long time I exerted myself in vain. Either the fool
U||   could not, or the villain would not perceive me. Meanwhile the machine
U||   rapidly soared, while my strength even more rapidly failed. I was soon
U||   upon the point of resigning myself to my fate, and dropping quietly
U||   into the sea, when my spirits were suddenly revived by hearing a hollow
U||   voice from above, which seemed to be lazily humming an opera air.
U||   Looking up, I perceived the Angel of the Odd. He was leaning, with his
U||   arms folded, over the rim of the car; and with a pipe in his mouth, at
U||   which he puffed leisurely, seemed to be upon excellent terms with
U||   himself and the universe. I was too much exhausted to speak, so I
U||   merely regarded him with an imploring air.
U||   For several minutes, although he looked me full in the face, he said
U||   nothing. At length, removing carefully his meerschaum from the right to
U||   the left corner of his mouth, he condescended to speak.
U||   “Who pe you,” he asked, “und what der teuffel you pe do dare?”
U||   To this piece of impudence, cruelty, and affectation, I could reply
U||   only by ejaculating the monosyllable “Help!”
U||   “Elp!” echoed the ruffian, “not I. Dare iz te pottle—elp yourself, und
U||   pe tam’d!”
U||   With these words he let fall a heavy bottle of Kirschenwässer, which,
U||   dropping precisely upon the crown of my head, caused me to imagine that
U||   my brains were entirely knocked out. Impressed with this idea I was
U||   about to relinquish my hold and give up the ghost with a good grace,
U||   when I was arrested by the cry of the Angel, who bade me hold on.
U||   “’Old on!” he said: “don’t pe in te ’urry—don’t. Will you pe take de
U||   odder pottle, or ’ave you pe got zober yet, and come to your zenzes?”
U||   I made haste, hereupon, to nod my head twice—once in the negative,
U||   meaning thereby that I would prefer not taking the other bottle at
U||   present; and once in the affirmative, intending thus to imply that I
U||   was sober and had positively come to my senses. By these means I
U||   somewhat softened the Angel.
U||   “Und you pelief, ten,” he inquired, “at te last? You pelief, ten, in te
U||   possibility of te odd?”
U||   I again nodded my head in assent.
U||   “Und you ave pelief in me, te Angel of te Odd?”
U||   I nodded again.
U||   “Und you acknowledge tat you pe te blind dronk und te vool?”
U||   I nodded once more.
U||   “Put your right hand into your left preeches pocket, ten, in token ov
U||   your vull zubmizzion unto te Angel ov te Odd.”
U||   This thing, for very obvious reasons, I found it quite impossible to
U||   do. In the first place, my left arm had been broken in my fall from the
U||   ladder, and therefore, had I let go my hold with the right hand I must
U||   have let go altogether. In the second place, I could have no breeches
U||   until I came across the crow. I was therefore obliged, much to my
U||   regret, to shake my head in the negative, intending thus to give the
U||   Angel to understand that I found it inconvenient, just at that moment,
U||   to comply with his very reasonable demand! No sooner, however, had I
U||   ceased shaking my head than—
U||   “Go to der teuffel, ten!” roared the Angel of the Odd.
U||   In pronouncing these words he drew a sharp knife across the guide-rope
U||   by which I was suspended, and as we then happened to be precisely over
U||   my own house (which, during my peregrinations, had been handsomely
U||   rebuilt), it so occurred that I tumbled headlong down the ample chimney
U||   and alit upon the dining-room hearth.
U||   Upon coming to my senses (for the fall had very thoroughly stunned me)
U||   I found it about four o’clock in the morning. I lay outstretched where
U||   I had fallen from the balloon. My head groveled in the ashes of an
U||   extinguished fire, while my feet reposed upon the wreck of a small
U||   table, overthrown, and amid the fragments of a miscellaneous dessert,
U||   intermingled with a newspaper, some broken glasses and shattered
U||   bottles, and an empty jug of the Schiedam Kirschenwässer. Thus revenged
U||   himself the Angel of the Odd.
