U||THE SCHOOLMASTER’S PROGRESS[43][12]
U||   By Caroline M.S. Kirkland (1801–1864)
U||   Master William Horner came to our village to school when he was about
U||   eighteen years old: tall, lank, straight-sided, and straight-haired,
U||   with a mouth of the most puckered and solemn kind. His figure and
U||   movements were those of a puppet cut out of shingle and jerked by a
U||   string; and his address corresponded very well with his appearance.
U||   Never did that prim mouth give way before a laugh. A faint and misty
U||   smile was the widest departure from its propriety, and this
U||   unaccustomed disturbance made wrinkles in the flat, skinny cheeks like
U||   those in the surface of a lake, after the intrusion of a stone. Master
U||   Horner knew well what belonged to the pedagogical character, and that
U||   facial solemnity stood high on the list of indispensable
U||   qualifications. He had made up his mind before he left his father’s
U||   house how he would look during the term. He had not planned any smiles
U||   (knowing that he must “board round”), and it was not for ordinary
U||   occurrences to alter his arrangements; so that when he was betrayed
U||   into a relaxation of the muscles, it was “in such a sort” as if he was
U||   putting his bread and butter in jeopardy.
U||   Truly he had a grave time that first winter. The rod of power was new
U||   to him, and he felt it his “duty” to use it more frequently than might
U||   have been thought necessary by those upon whose sense the privilege had
U||   palled. Tears and sulky faces, and impotent fists doubled fiercely when
U||   his back was turned, were the rewards of his conscientiousness; and the
U||   boys—and girls too—were glad when working time came round again, and
U||   the master went home to help his father on the farm.
U||   But with the autumn came Master Horner again, dropping among us as
U||   quietly as the faded leaves, and awakening at least as much serious
U||   reflection. Would he be as self-sacrificing as before, postponing his
U||   own ease and comfort to the public good, or would he have become more
U||   sedentary, and less fond of circumambulating the school-room with a
U||   switch over his shoulder? Many were fain to hope he might have learned
U||   to smoke during the summer, an accomplishment which would probably have
U||   moderated his energy not a little, and disposed him rather to reverie
U||   than to action. But here he was, and all the broader-chested and
U||   stouter-armed for his labors in the harvest-field.
U||   Let it not be supposed that Master Horner was of a cruel and ogrish
U||   nature—a babe-eater—a Herod—one who delighted in torturing the
U||   helpless. Such souls there may be, among those endowed with the awful
U||   control of the ferule, but they are rare in the fresh and natural
U||   regions we describe. It is, we believe, where young gentlemen are to be
U||   crammed for college, that the process of hardening heart and skin
U||   together goes on most vigorously. Yet among the uneducated there is so
U||   high a respect for bodily strength, that it is necessary for the
U||   schoolmaster to show, first of all, that he possesses this inadmissible
U||   requisite for his place. The rest is more readily taken for granted.
U||   Brains he may have—a strong arm he must have: so he proves the more
U||   important claim first. We must therefore make all due allowance for
U||   Master Horner, who could not be expected to overtop his position so far
U||   as to discern at once the philosophy of teaching.
U||   He was sadly brow-beaten during his first term of service by a great
U||   broad-shouldered lout of some eighteen years or so, who thought he
U||   needed a little more “schooling,” but at the same time felt quite
U||   competent to direct the manner and measure of his attempts.
U||   “You’d ought to begin with large-hand, Joshuay,” said Master Horner to
U||   this youth.
U||   “What should I want coarse-hand for?” said the disciple, with great
U||   contempt; “coarse-hand won’t never do me no good. I want a fine-hand
U||   copy.”
U||   The master looked at the infant giant, and did as he wished, but we say
U||   not with what secret resolutions.
U||   At another time, Master Horner, having had a hint from some one more
U||   knowing than himself, proposed to his elder scholars to write after
U||   dictation, expatiating at the same time quite floridly (the ideas
U||   having been supplied by the knowing friend), upon the advantages likely
U||   to arise from this practice, and saying, among other things,
U||   “It will help you, when you write letters, to spell the words good.”
U||   “Pooh!” said Joshua, “spellin’ ain’t nothin’; let them that finds the
U||   mistakes correct ’em. I’m for every one’s havin’ a way of their own.”
U||   “How dared you be so saucy to the master?” asked one of the little
U||   boys, after school.
U||   “Because I could lick him, easy,” said the hopeful Joshua, who knew
U||   very well why the master did not undertake him on the spot.
U||   Can we wonder that Master Horner determined to make his empire good as
U||   far as it went?
U||   A new examination was required on the entrance into a second term, and,
U||   with whatever secret trepidation, the master was obliged to submit. Our
U||   law prescribes examinations, but forgets to provide for the competency
U||   of the examiners; so that few better farces offer than the course of
U||   question and answer on these occasions. We know not precisely what were
U||   Master Horner’s trials; but we have heard of a sharp dispute between
U||   the inspectors whether a-n-g-e-l spelt angle or angel. Angle had it,
U||   and the school maintained that pronunciation ever after. Master Horner
U||   passed, and he was requested to draw up the certificate for the
U||   inspectors to sign, as one had left his spectacles at home, and the
U||   other had a bad cold, so that it was not convenient for either to write
U||   more than his name. Master Homer’s exhibition of learning on this
U||   occasion did not reach us, but we know that it must have been
U||   considerable, since he stood the ordeal.
U||   “What is orthography?” said an inspector once, in our presence.
U||   The candidate writhed a good deal, studied the beams overhead and the
U||   chickens out of the window, and then replied,
U||   “It is so long since I learnt the first part of the spelling-book, that
U||   I can’t justly answer that question. But if I could just look it over,
U||   I guess I could.”
U||   Our schoolmaster entered upon his second term with new courage and
U||   invigorated authority. Twice certified, who should dare doubt his
U||   competency? Even Joshua was civil, and lesser louts of course
U||   obsequious; though the girls took more liberties, for they feel even at
U||   that early age, that influence is stronger than strength.
U||   Could a young schoolmaster think of feruling a girl with her hair in
U||   ringlets and a gold ring on her finger? Impossible—and the immunity
U||   extended to all the little sisters and cousins; and there were enough
U||   large girls to protect all the feminine part of the school. With the
U||   boys Master Horner still had many a battle, and whether with a view to
U||   this, or as an economical ruse, he never wore his coat in school,
U||   saying it was too warm. Perhaps it was an astute attention to the
U||   prejudices of his employers, who love no man that does not earn his
U||   living by the sweat of his brow. The shirt-sleeves gave the idea of a
U||   manual-labor school in one sense at least. It was evident that the
U||   master worked, and that afforded a probability that the scholars worked
U||   too.
U||   Master Horner’s success was most triumphant that winter. A year’s
U||   growth had improved his outward man exceedingly, filling out the limbs
U||   so that they did not remind you so forcibly of a young colt’s, and
U||   supplying the cheeks with the flesh and blood so necessary where
U||   mustaches were not worn. Experience had given him a degree of
U||   confidence, and confidence gave him power. In short, people said the
U||   master had waked up; and so he had. He actually set about reading for
U||   improvement; and although at the end of the term he could not quite
U||   make out from his historical studies which side Hannibal was on, yet
U||   this is readily explained by the fact that he boarded round, and was
U||   obliged to read generally by firelight, surrounded by ungoverned
U||   children.
U||   After this, Master Horner made his own bargain. When schooltime came
U||   round with the following autumn, and the teacher presented himself for
U||   a third examination, such a test was pronounced no longer necessary;
U||   and the district consented to engage him at the astounding rate of
U||   sixteen dollars a month, with the understanding that he was to have a
U||   fixed home, provided he was willing to allow a dollar a week for it.
U||   Master Horner bethought him of the successive “killing-times,” and
U||   consequent doughnuts of the twenty families in which he had sojourned
U||   the years before, and consented to the exaction.
U||   Behold our friend now as high as district teacher can ever hope to
U||   be—his scholarship established, his home stationary and not revolving,
U||   and the good behavior of the community insured by the fact that he,
U||   being of age, had now a farm to retire upon in case of any disgust.
U||   Master Horner was at once the preëminent beau of the neighborhood,
U||   spite of the prejudice against learning. He brushed his hair straight
U||   up in front, and wore a sky-blue ribbon for a guard to his silver
U||   watch, and walked as if the tall heels of his blunt boots were
U||   egg-shells and not leather. Yet he was far from neglecting the duties
U||   of his place. He was beau only on Sundays and holidays; very
U||   schoolmaster the rest of the time.
U||   It was at a “spelling-school” that Master Horner first met the educated
U||   eyes of Miss Harriet Bangle, a young lady visiting the Engleharts in
U||   our neighborhood. She was from one of the towns in Western New York,
U||   and had brought with her a variety of city airs and graces somewhat
U||   caricatured, set off with year-old French fashions much travestied.
U||   Whether she had been sent out to the new country to try, somewhat late,
U||   a rustic chance for an establishment, or whether her company had been
U||   found rather trying at home, we cannot say. The view which she was at
U||   some pains to make understood was, that her friends had contrived this
U||   method of keeping her out of the way of a desperate lover whose
U||   addresses were not acceptable to them.
U||   If it should seem surprising that so high-bred a visitor should be
U||   sojourning in the wild woods, it must be remembered that more than one
U||   celebrated Englishman and not a few distinguished Americans have farmer
U||   brothers in the western country, no whit less rustic in their exterior
U||   and manner of life than the plainest of their neighbors. When these are
U||   visited by their refined kinsfolk, we of the woods catch glimpses of
U||   the gay world, or think we do.
U||   That great medicine hath
U||   With its tinct gilded—
U||   many a vulgarism to the satisfaction of wiser heads than ours.
U||   Miss Bangle’s manner bespoke for her that high consideration which she
U||   felt to be her due. Yet she condescended to be amused by the rustics
U||   and their awkward attempts at gaiety and elegance; and, to say truth,
U||   few of the village merry-makings escaped her, though she wore always
U||   the air of great superiority.
U||   The spelling-school is one of the ordinary winter amusements in the
U||   country. It occurs once in a fortnight, or so, and has power to draw
U||   out all the young people for miles round, arrayed in their best clothes
U||   and their holiday behavior. When all is ready, umpires are elected, and
U||   after these have taken the distinguished place usually occupied by the
U||   teacher, the young people of the school choose the two best scholars to
U||   head the opposing classes. These leaders choose their followers from
U||   the mass, each calling a name in turn, until all the spellers are
U||   ranked on one side or the other, lining the sides of the room, and all
U||   standing. The schoolmaster, standing too, takes his spelling-book, and
U||   gives a placid yet awe-inspiring look along the ranks, remarking that
U||   he intends to be very impartial, and that he shall give out nothing
U||   that is not in the spelling-book. For the first half hour or so he
U||   chooses common and easy words, that the spirit of the evening may not
U||   be damped by the too early thinning of the classes. When a word is
U||   missed, the blunderer has to sit down, and be a spectator only for the
U||   rest of the evening. At certain intervals, some of the best speakers
U||   mount the platform, and “speak a piece,” which is generally as
U||   declamatory as possible.
U||   The excitement of this scene is equal to that afforded by any city
U||   spectacle whatever; and towards the close of the evening, when
U||   difficult and unusual words are chosen to confound the small number who
U||   still keep the floor, it becomes scarcely less than painful. When
U||   perhaps only one or two remain to be puzzled, the master, weary at last
U||   of his task, though a favorite one, tries by tricks to put down those
U||   whom he cannot overcome in fair fight. If among all the curious,
U||   useless, unheard-of words which may be picked out of the spelling-book,
U||   he cannot find one which the scholars have not noticed, he gets the
U||   last head down by some quip or catch. “Bay” will perhaps be the sound;
U||   one scholar spells it “bey,” another, “bay,” while the master all the
U||   time means “ba,” which comes within the rule, being in the
U||   spelling-book.
U||   It was on one of these occasions, as we have said, that Miss Bangle,
U||   having come to the spelling-school to get materials for a letter to a
U||   female friend, first shone upon Mr. Horner. She was excessively amused
U||   by his solemn air and puckered mouth, and set him down at once as fair
U||   game. Yet she could not help becoming somewhat interested in the
U||   spelling-school, and after it was over found she had not stored up half
U||   as many of the schoolmaster’s points as she intended, for the benefit
U||   of her correspondent.
U||   In the evening’s contest a young girl from some few miles’ distance,
U||   Ellen Kingsbury, the only child of a substantial farmer, had been the
U||   very last to sit down, after a prolonged effort on the part of Mr.
U||   Horner to puzzle her, for the credit of his own school. She blushed,
U||   and smiled, and blushed again, but spelt on, until Mr. Horner’s cheeks
U||   were crimson with excitement and some touch of shame that he should be
U||   baffled at his own weapons. At length, either by accident or design,
U||   Ellen missed a word, and sinking into her seat was numbered with the
U||   slain.
U||   In the laugh and talk which followed (for with the conclusion of the
U||   spelling, all form of a public assembly vanishes), our schoolmaster
U||   said so many gallant things to his fair enemy, and appeared so much
U||   animated by the excitement of the contest, that Miss Bangle began to
U||   look upon him with rather more respect, and to feel somewhat indignant
U||   that a little rustic like Ellen should absorb the entire attention of
U||   the only beau. She put on, therefore, her most gracious aspect, and
U||   mingled in the circle; caused the schoolmaster to be presented to her,
U||   and did her best to fascinate him by certain airs and graces which she
U||   had found successful elsewhere. What game is too small for the
U||   close-woven net of a coquette?
U||   Mr. Horner quitted not the fair Ellen until he had handed her into her
U||   father’s sleigh; and he then wended his way homewards, never thinking
U||   that he ought to have escorted Miss Bangle to her uncle’s, though she
U||   certainly waited a little while for his return.
U||   We must not follow into particulars the subsequent intercourse of our
U||   schoolmaster with the civilized young lady. All that concerns us is the
U||   result of Miss Bangle’s benevolent designs upon his heart. She tried
U||   most sincerely to find its vulnerable spot, meaning no doubt to put Mr.
U||   Homer on his guard for the future; and she was unfeignedly surprised to
U||   discover that her best efforts were of no avail. She concluded he must
U||   have taken a counter-poison, and she was not slow in guessing its
U||   source. She had observed the peculiar fire which lighted up his eyes in
U||   the presence of Ellen Kingsbury, and she bethought her of a plan which
U||   would ensure her some amusement at the expense of these impertinent
U||   rustics, though in a manner different somewhat from her original more
U||   natural idea of simple coquetry.
U||   A letter was written to Master Horner, purporting to come from Ellen
U||   Kingsbury, worded so artfully that the schoolmaster understood at once
U||   that it was intended to be a secret communication, though its
U||   ostensible object was an inquiry about some ordinary affair. This was
U||   laid in Mr. Horner’s desk before he came to school, with an intimation
U||   that he might leave an answer in a certain spot on the following
U||   morning. The bait took at once, for Mr. Horner, honest and true
U||   himself, and much smitten with the fair Ellen, was too happy to be
U||   circumspect. The answer was duly placed, and as duly carried to Miss
U||   Bangle by her accomplice, Joe Englehart, an unlucky pickle who “was
U||   always for ill, never for good,” and who found no difficulty in
U||   obtaining the letter unwatched, since the master was obliged to be in
U||   school at nine, and Joe could always linger a few minutes later. This
U||   answer being opened and laughed at, Miss Bangle had only to contrive a
U||   rejoinder, which being rather more particular in its tone than the
U||   original communication, led on yet again the happy schoolmaster, who
U||   branched out into sentiment, “taffeta phrases, silken terms precise,”
U||   talked of hills and dales and rivulets, and the pleasures of
U||   friendship, and concluded by entreating a continuance of the
U||   correspondence.
U||   Another letter and another, every one more flattering and encouraging
U||   than the last, almost turned the sober head of our poor master, and
U||   warmed up his heart so effectually that he could scarcely attend to his
U||   business. The spelling-schools were remembered, however, and Ellen
U||   Kingsbury made one of the merry company; but the latest letter had not
U||   forgotten to caution Mr. Horner not to betray the intimacy; so that he
U||   was in honor bound to restrict himself to the language of the eyes hard
U||   as it was to forbear the single whisper for which he would have given
U||   his very dictionary. So, their meeting passed off without the
U||   explanation which Miss Bangle began to fear would cut short her
U||   benevolent amusement.
U||   The correspondence was resumed with renewed spirit, and carried on
U||   until Miss Bangle, though not overburdened with sensitiveness, began to
U||   be a little alarmed for the consequences of her malicious pleasantry.
U||   She perceived that she herself had turned schoolmistress, and that
U||   Master Horner, instead of being merely her dupe, had become her pupil
U||   too; for the style of his replies had been constantly improving and the
U||   earnest and manly tone which he assumed promised any thing but the
U||   quiet, sheepish pocketing of injury and insult, upon which she had
U||   counted. In truth, there was something deeper than vanity in the
U||   feelings with which he regarded Ellen Kingsbury. The encouragement
U||   which he supposed himself to have received, threw down the barrier
U||   which his extreme bashfulness would have interposed between himself and
U||   any one who possessed charms enough to attract him; and we must excuse
U||   him if, in such a case, he did not criticise the mode of encouragement,
U||   but rather grasped eagerly the proffered good without a scruple, or one
U||   which he would own to himself, as to the propriety with which it was
U||   tendered. He was as much in love as a man can be, and the seriousness
U||   of real attachment gave both grace and dignity to his once awkward
U||   diction.
U||   The evident determination of Mr. Horner to come to the point of asking
U||   papa brought Miss Bangle to a very awkward pass. She had expected to
U||   return home before matters had proceeded so far, but being obliged to
U||   remain some time longer, she was equally afraid to go on and to leave
U||   off, a dénouement being almost certain to ensue in either case. Things
U||   stood thus when it was time to prepare for the grand exhibition which
U||   was to close the winter’s term.
U||   This is an affair of too much magnitude to be fully described in the
U||   small space yet remaining in which to bring out our veracious history.
U||   It must be “slubber’d o’er in haste”—its important preliminaries left
U||   to the cold imagination of the reader—its fine spirit perhaps
U||   evaporating for want of being embodied in words. We can only say that
U||   our master, whose school-life was to close with the term, labored as
U||   man never before labored in such a cause, resolute to trail a cloud of
U||   glory after him when he left us. Not a candlestick nor a curtain that
U||   was attainable, either by coaxing or bribery, was left in the village;
U||   even the only piano, that frail treasure, was wiled away and placed in
U||   one corner of the rickety stage. The most splendid of all the pieces in
U||   the Columbian Orator, the American Speaker, the——but we must not
U||   enumerate—in a word, the most astounding and pathetic specimens of
U||   eloquence within ken of either teacher or scholars, had been selected
U||   for the occasion; and several young ladies and gentlemen, whose
U||   academical course had been happily concluded at an earlier period,
U||   either at our own institution or at some other, had consented to lend
U||   themselves to the parts, and their choicest decorations for the
U||   properties, of the dramatic portion of the entertainment.
U||   Among these last was pretty Ellen Kingsbury, who had agreed to
U||   personate the Queen of Scots, in the garden scene from Schiller’s
U||   tragedy of Mary Stuart; and this circumstance accidentally afforded
U||   Master Horner the opportunity he had so long desired, of seeing his
U||   fascinating correspondent without the presence of peering eyes. A
U||   dress-rehearsal occupied the afternoon before the day of days, and the
U||   pathetic expostulations of the lovely Mary—
U||   Mine all doth hang—my life—my destiny—
U||   Upon my words—upon the force of tears!—
U||   aided by the long veil, and the emotion which sympathy brought into
U||   Ellen’s countenance, proved too much for the enforced prudence of
U||   Master Horner. When the rehearsal was over, and the heroes and heroines
U||   were to return home, it was found that, by a stroke of witty invention
U||   not new in the country, the harness of Mr. Kingsbury’s horses had been
U||   cut in several places, his whip hidden, his buffalo-skins spread on the
U||   ground, and the sleigh turned bottom upwards on them. This afforded an
U||   excuse for the master’s borrowing a horse and sleigh of somebody, and
U||   claiming the privilege of taking Miss Ellen home, while her father
U||   returned with only Aunt Sally and a great bag of bran from the
U||   mill—companions about equally interesting.
U||   Here, then, was the golden opportunity so long wished for! Here was the
U||   power of ascertaining at once what is never quite certain until we have
U||   heard it from warm, living lips, whose testimony is strengthened by
U||   glances in which the whole soul speaks or—seems to speak. The time was
U||   short, for the sleighing was but too fine; and Father Kingsbury, having
U||   tied up his harness, and collected his scattered equipment, was driving
U||   so close behind that there was no possibility of lingering for a
U||   moment. Yet many moments were lost before Mr. Horner, very much in
U||   earnest, and all unhackneyed in matters of this sort, could find a word
U||   in which to clothe his new-found feelings. The horse seemed to fly—the
U||   distance was half past—and at length, in absolute despair of anything
U||   better, he blurted out at once what he had determined to avoid—a direct
U||   reference to the correspondence.
U||   A game at cross-purposes ensued; exclamations and explanations, and
U||   denials and apologies filled up the time which was to have made Master
U||   Horner so blest. The light from Mr. Kingsbury’s windows shone upon the
U||   path, and the whole result of this conference so longed for, was a
U||   burst of tears from the perplexed and mortified Ellen, who sprang from
U||   Mr. Horner’s attempts to detain her, rushed into the house without
U||   vouchsafing him a word of adieu, and left him standing, no bad
U||   personification of Orpheus, after the last hopeless flitting of his
U||   Eurydice.
U||   “Won’t you ’light, Master?” said Mr. Kingsbury.
U||   “Yes—no—thank you—good evening,” stammered poor Master Horner, so
U||   stupefied that even Aunt Sally called him “a dummy.”
U||   The horse took the sleigh against the fence, going home, and threw out
U||   the master, who scarcely recollected the accident; while to Ellen the
U||   issue of this unfortunate drive was a sleepless night and so high a
U||   fever in the morning that our village doctor was called to Mr.
U||   Kingsbury’s before breakfast.
U||   Poor Master Horner’s distress may hardly be imagined. Disappointed,
U||   bewildered, cut to the quick, yet as much in love as ever, he could
U||   only in bitter silence turn over in his thoughts the issue of his
U||   cherished dream; now persuading himself that Ellen’s denial was the
U||   effect of a sudden bashfulness, now inveighing against the fickleness
U||   of the sex, as all men do when they are angry with any one woman in
U||   particular. But his exhibition must go on in spite of wretchedness; and
U||   he went about mechanically, talking of curtains and candles, and music,
U||   and attitudes, and pauses, and emphasis, looking like a somnambulist
U||   whose “eyes are open but their sense is shut,” and often surprising
U||   those concerned by the utter unfitness of his answers.
U||   It was almost evening when Mr. Kingsbury, having discovered, through
U||   the intervention of the Doctor and Aunt Sally the cause of Ellen’s
U||   distress, made his appearance before the unhappy eyes of Master Horner,
U||   angry, solemn and determined; taking the schoolmaster apart, and
U||   requiring, an explanation of his treatment of his daughter. In vain did
U||   the perplexed lover ask for time to clear himself, declare his respect
U||   for Miss Ellen and his willingness to give every explanation which she
U||   might require; the father was not to be put off; and though excessively
U||   reluctant, Mr. Horner had no resource but to show the letters which
U||   alone could account for his strange discourse to Ellen. He unlocked his
U||   desk, slowly and unwillingly, while the old man’s impatience was such
U||   that he could scarcely forbear thrusting in his own hand to snatch at
U||   the papers which were to explain this vexatious mystery. What could
U||   equal the utter confusion of Master Horner and the contemptuous anger
U||   of the father, when no letters were to be found! Mr. Kingsbury was too
U||   passionate to listen to reason, or to reflect for one moment upon the
U||   irreproachable good name of the schoolmaster. He went away in
U||   inexorable wrath; threatening every practicable visitation of public
U||   and private justice upon the head of the offender, whom he accused of
U||   having attempted to trick his daughter into an entanglement which
U||   should result in his favor.
U||   A doleful exhibition was this last one of our thrice approved and most
U||   worthy teacher! Stern necessity and the power of habit enabled him to
U||   go through with most of his part, but where was the proud fire which
U||   had lighted up his eye on similar occasions before? He sat as one of
U||   three judges before whom the unfortunate Robert Emmet was dragged in
U||   his shirt-sleeves, by two fierce-looking officials; but the chief judge
U||   looked far more like a criminal than did the proper representative. He
U||   ought to have personated Othello, but was obliged to excuse himself
U||   from raving for “the handkerchief! the handkerchief!” on the rather
U||   anomalous plea of a bad cold. Mary Stuart being “i’ the bond,” was
U||   anxiously expected by the impatient crowd, and it was with distress
U||   amounting to agony that the master was obliged to announce, in person,
U||   the necessity of omitting that part of the representation, on account
U||   of the illness of one of the young ladies.
U||   Scarcely had the words been uttered, and the speaker hidden his burning
U||   face behind the curtain, when Mr. Kingsbury started up in his place
U||   amid the throng, to give a public recital of his grievance—no uncommon
U||   resort in the new country. He dashed at once to the point; and before
U||   some friends who saw the utter impropriety of his proceeding could
U||   persuade him to defer his vengeance, he had laid before the
U||   assembly—some three hundred people, perhaps—his own statement of the
U||   case. He was got out at last, half coaxed, half hustled; and the gentle
U||   public only half understanding what had been set forth thus
U||   unexpectedly, made quite a pretty row of it. Some clamored loudly for
U||   the conclusion of the exercises; others gave utterances in no
U||   particularly choice terms to a variety of opinions as to the
U||   schoolmaster’s proceedings, varying the note occasionally by shouting,
U||   “The letters! the letters! why don’t you bring out the letters?”
U||   At length, by means of much rapping on the desk by the president of the
U||   evening, who was fortunately a “popular” character, order was partially
U||   restored; and the favorite scene from Miss More’s dialogue of David and
U||   Goliath was announced as the closing piece. The sight of little David
U||   in a white tunic edged with red tape, with a calico scrip and a very
U||   primitive-looking sling; and a huge Goliath decorated with a militia
U||   belt and sword, and a spear like a weaver’s beam indeed, enchained
U||   everybody’s attention. Even the peccant schoolmaster and his pretended
U||   letters were forgotten, while the sapient Goliath, every time that he
U||   raised the spear, in the energy of his declamation, to thump upon the
U||   stage, picked away fragments of the low ceiling, which fell
U||   conspicuously on his great shock of black hair. At last, with the
U||   crowning threat, up went the spear for an astounding thump, and down
U||   came a large piece of the ceiling, and with it—a shower of letters.
U||   The confusion that ensued beggars all description. A general scramble
U||   took place, and in another moment twenty pairs of eyes, at least, were
U||   feasting on the choice phrases lavished upon Mr. Horner. Miss Bangle
U||   had sat through the whole previous scene, trembling for herself,
U||   although she had, as she supposed, guarded cunningly against exposure.
U||   She had needed no prophet to tell her what must be the result of a
U||   tête-à-tête between Mr. Horner and Ellen; and the moment she saw them
U||   drive off together, she induced her imp to seize the opportunity of
U||   abstracting the whole parcel of letters from Mr. Horner’s desk; which
U||   he did by means of a sort of skill which comes by nature to such
U||   goblins; picking the lock by the aid of a crooked nail, as neatly as if
U||   he had been born within the shadow of the Tombs.
U||   But magicians sometimes suffer severely from the malice with which they
U||   have themselves inspired their familiars. Joe Englehart having been a
U||   convenient tool thus far thought it quite time to torment Miss Bangle a
U||   little; so, having stolen the letters at her bidding, he hid them on
U||   his own account, and no persuasions of hers could induce him to reveal
U||   this important secret, which he chose to reserve as a rod in case she
U||   refused him some intercession with his father, or some other
U||   accommodation, rendered necessary by his mischievous habits.
U||   He had concealed the precious parcels in the unfloored loft above the
U||   school-room, a place accessible only by means of a small trap-door
U||   without staircase or ladder; and here he meant to have kept them while
U||   it suited his purposes, but for the untimely intrusion of the weaver’s
U||   beam.
U||   Miss Bangle had sat through all, as we have said, thinking the letters
U||   safe, yet vowing vengeance against her confederate for not allowing her
U||   to secure them by a satisfactory conflagration; and it was not until
U||   she heard her own name whispered through the crowd, that she was
U||   awakened to her true situation. The sagacity of the low creatures whom
U||   she had despised showed them at once that the letters must be hers,
U||   since her character had been pretty shrewdly guessed, and the
U||   handwriting wore a more practised air than is usual among females in
U||   the country. This was first taken for granted, and then spoken of as an
U||   acknowledged fact.
U||   The assembly moved like the heavings of a troubled sea. Everybody felt
U||   that this was everybody’s business. “Put her out!” was heard from more
U||   than one rough voice near the door, and this was responded to by loud
U||   and angry murmurs from within.
U||   Mr. Englehart, not waiting to inquire into the merits of the case in
U||   this scene of confusion, hastened to get his family out as quietly and
U||   as quickly as possible, but groans and hisses followed his niece as she
U||   hung half-fainting on his arm, quailing completely beneath the
U||   instinctive indignation of the rustic public. As she passed out, a yell
U||   resounded among the rude boys about the door, and she was lifted into a
U||   sleigh, insensible from terror. She disappeared from that evening, and
U||   no one knew the time of her final departure for “the east.”
U||   Mr. Kingsbury, who is a just man when he is not in a passion, made all
U||   the reparation in his power for his harsh and ill-considered attack
U||   upon the master; and we believe that functionary did not show any
U||   traits of implacability of character. At least he was seen, not many
U||   days after, sitting peaceably at tea with Mr. Kingsbury, Aunt Sally,
U||   and Miss Ellen; and he has since gone home to build a house upon his
U||   farm. And people do say, that after a few months more, Ellen will not
U||   need Miss Bangle’s intervention if she should see fit to correspond
U||   with the schoolmaster.
