U||THE WATKINSON EVENING[45][13]
U||   By Eliza Leslie (1787–1858)
U||   Mrs. Morland, a polished and accomplished woman, was the widow of a
U||   distinguished senator from one of the western states, of which, also,
U||   her husband had twice filled the office of governor. Her daughter
U||   having completed her education at the best boarding-school in
U||   Philadelphia, and her son being about to graduate at Princeton, the
U||   mother had planned with her children a tour to Niagara and the lakes,
U||   returning by way of Boston. On leaving Philadelphia, Mrs. Morland and
U||   the delighted Caroline stopped at Princeton to be present at the annual
U||   commencement, and had the happiness of seeing their beloved Edward
U||   receive his diploma as bachelor of arts; after hearing him deliver,
U||   with great applause, an oration on the beauties of the American
U||   character. College youths are very prone to treat on subjects that
U||   imply great experience of the world. But Edward Morland was full of
U||   kind feeling for everything and everybody; and his views of life had
U||   hitherto been tinted with a perpetual rose-color.
U||   Mrs. Morland, not depending altogether upon the celebrity of her late
U||   husband, and wishing that her children should see specimens of the best
U||   society in the northern cities, had left home with numerous letters of
U||   introduction. But when they arrived at New York, she found to her great
U||   regret, that having unpacked and taken out her small traveling desk,
U||   during her short stay in Philadelphia, she had strangely left it behind
U||   in the closet of her room at the hotel. In this desk were deposited all
U||   her letters, except two which had been offered to her by friends in
U||   Philadelphia. The young people, impatient to see the wonders of
U||   Niagara, had entreated her to stay but a day or two in the city of New
U||   York, and thought these two letters would be quite sufficient for the
U||   present. In the meantime she wrote back to the hotel, requesting that
U||   the missing desk should be forwarded to New York as soon as possible.
U||   On the morning after their arrival at the great commercial metropolis
U||   of America, the Morland family took a carriage to ride round through
U||   the principal parts of the city, and to deliver their two letters at
U||   the houses to which they were addressed, and which were both situated
U||   in the region that lies between the upper part of Broadway and the
U||   North River. In one of the most fashionable streets they found the
U||   elegant mansion of Mrs. St. Leonard; but on stopping at the door, were
U||   informed that its mistress was not at home. They then left the
U||   introductory letter (which they had prepared for this mischance, by
U||   enclosing it in an envelope with a card), and proceeding to another
U||   street considerably farther up, they arrived at the dwelling of the
U||   Watkinson family, to the mistress of which the other Philadelphia
U||   letter was directed. It was one of a large block of houses all exactly
U||   alike, and all shut up from top to bottom, according to a custom more
U||   prevalent in New York than in any other city.
U||   Here they were also unsuccessful; the servant who came to the door
U||   telling them that the ladies were particularly engaged and could see no
U||   company. So they left their second letter and card and drove off,
U||   continuing their ride till they reached the Croton water works, which
U||   they quitted the carriage to see and admire. On returning to the hotel,
U||   with the intention after an hour or two of rest to go out again, and
U||   walk till near dinner-time, they found waiting them a note from Mrs.
U||   Watkinson, expressing her regret that she had not been able to see them
U||   when they called; and explaining that her family duties always obliged
U||   her to deny herself the pleasure of receiving morning visitors, and
U||   that her servants had general orders to that effect. But she requested
U||   their company for that evening (naming nine o’clock as the hour), and
U||   particularly desired an immediate answer.
U||   “I suppose,” said Mrs. Morland, “she intends asking some of her friends
U||   to meet us, in case we accept the invitation; and therefore is
U||   naturally desirous of a reply as soon as possible. Of course we will
