U||   As soon as tea was over, Mrs. Morland and her daughter repaired to
U||   their toilettes. Fortunately, fashion as well as good taste, has
U||   decided that, at a summer party, the costume of the ladies should never
U||   go beyond an elegant simplicity. Therefore our two ladies in preparing
U||   for their intended appearance at Mrs. St. Leonard’s, were enabled to
U||   attire themselves in a manner that would not seem out of place in the
U||   smaller company they expected to meet at the Watkinsons. Over an
U||   under-dress of lawn, Caroline Morland put on a white organdy trimmed
U||   with lace, and decorated with bows of pink ribbon. At the back of her
U||   head was a wreath of fresh and beautiful pink flowers, tied with a
U||   similar ribbon. Mrs. Morland wore a black grenadine over a satin, and a
U||   lace cap trimmed with white.
U||   It was but a quarter past nine o’clock when their carriage stopped at
U||   the Watkinson door. The front of the house looked very dark. Not a ray
U||   gleamed through the Venetian shutters, and the glimmer beyond the
U||   fan-light over the door was almost imperceptible. After the coachman
U||   had rung several times, an Irish girl opened the door, cautiously (as
U||   Irish girls always do), and admitted them into the entry, where one
U||   light only was burning in a branch lamp. “Shall we go upstairs?” said
U||   Mrs. Morland. “And what for would ye go upstairs?” said the girl in a
U||   pert tone. “It’s all dark there, and there’s no preparations. Ye can
U||   lave your things here a-hanging on the rack. It is a party ye’re
U||   expecting? Blessed are them what expects nothing.”
U||   The sanguine Edward Morland looked rather blank at this intelligence,
U||   and his sister whispered to him, “We’ll get off to Mrs. St. Leonard’s
U||   as soon as we possibly can. When did you tell the coachman to come for
U||   us?”
U||   “At half past ten,” was the brother’s reply.
U||   “Oh! Edward, Edward!” she exclaimed, “And I dare say he will not be
U||   punctual. He may keep us here till eleven.”
U||   “Courage, mes enfants,” said their mother, “et parlez plus doucement.”
U||   The girl then ushered them into the back parlor, saying, “Here’s the
U||   company.”
U||   The room was large and gloomy. A checquered mat covered the floor, and
U||   all the furniture was encased in striped calico covers, and the lamps,
U||   mirrors, etc. concealed under green gauze. The front parlor was
U||   entirely dark, and in the back apartment was no other light than a
U||   shaded lamp on a large centre table, round which was assembled a circle
