U||   see-sawed on it nearly the whole time. It was a very awkward,
U||   high-legged, crouch-backed rocking-chair, and shamefully unprovided
U||   with anything in the form of a footstool.
U||   “My husband is away, at Boston, on business,” said Mrs. Watkinson. “I
U||   thought at first, ma’am, I should not be able to ask you here this
U||   evening, for it is not our way to have company in his absence; but my
U||   daughter Jane over-persuaded me to send for you.”
U||   “What a pity,” thought Caroline.
U||   “You must take us as you find us, ma’am,” continued Mrs. Watkinson. “We
U||   use no ceremony with anybody; and our rule is never to put ourselves
U||   out of the way. We do not give parties [looking at the dresses of the
U||   ladies]. Our first duty is to our children, and we cannot waste our
U||   substance on fashion and folly. They’ll have cause to thank us for it
