U||   he might want the money for some purpose before he came for us.”
U||   “That was very kind in you, sir,” said Mrs. Watkinson, “but not very
U||   wise. There’s no dependence on any coachman; and perhaps as he may be
U||   sure of business enough this rainy night he may never come at all—being
U||   already paid for bringing you here.”
U||   Now, the truth was that the coachman had come at the appointed time,
U||   but the noise of Jane’s piano had prevented his arrival being heard in
U||   the back parlor. The Irish girl had gone to the door when he rang the
U||   bell, and recognized in him what she called “an ould friend.” Just then
U||   a lady and gentleman who had been caught in the rain came running
U||   along, and seeing a carriage drawing up at a door, the gentleman
U||   inquired of the driver if he could not take them to Rutgers Place. The
U||   driver replied that he had just come for two ladies and a gentleman
U||   whom he had brought from the Astor House.
U||   “Indeed and Patrick,” said the girl who stood at the door, “if I was
U||   you I’d be after making another penny to-night. Miss Jane is pounding
U||   away at one of her long music pieces, and it won’t be over before you
U||   have time to get to Rutgers and back again. And if you do make them
U||   wait awhile, where’s the harm? They’ve a dry roof over their heads, and
U||   I warrant it’s not the first waiting they’ve ever had in their lives;
U||   and it won’t be the last neither.”
U||   “Exactly so,” said the gentleman; and regardless of the propriety of
U||   first sending to consult the persons who had engaged the carriage, he
U||   told his wife to step in, and following her instantly himself, they
U||   drove away to Rutgers Place.
U||   Reader, if you were ever detained in a strange house by the non-arrival
U||   of your carriage, you will easily understand the excessive annoyance of
U||   finding that you are keeping a family out of their beds beyond their
U||   usual hour. And in this case, there was a double grievance; the guests
U||   being all impatience to get off to a better place. The children, all
U||   crying when wakened from their sleep, were finally taken to bed by two
U||   servant maids, and Jane Watkinson, who never came back again. None were
U||   left but Hester, the great French scholar, who, being one of those
U||   young imps that seem to have the faculty of living without sleep, sat
U||   bolt upright with her eyes wide open, watching the uncomfortable
U||   visitors.
U||   The Morlands felt as if they could bear it no longer, and Edward
U||   proposed sending for another carriage to the nearest livery stable.
U||   “We don’t keep a man now,” said Mrs. Watkinson, who sat nodding in the
U||   rocking-chair, attempting now and then a snatch of conversation, and
U||   saying “ma’am” still more frequently than usual. “Men servants are
U||   dreadful trials, ma’am, and we gave them up three years ago. And I
U||   don’t know how Mary or Katy are to go out this stormy night in search
U||   of a livery stable.”
U||   “On no consideration could I allow the women to do so,” replied Edward.
U||   “If you will oblige me by the loan of an umbrella, I will go myself.”
U||   Accordingly he set out on this business, but was unsuccessful at two
U||   livery stables, the carriages being all out. At last he found one, and
U||   was driven in it to Mr. Watkinson’s house, where his mother and sister
U||   were awaiting him, all quite ready, with their calashes and shawls on.
U||   They gladly took their leave; Mrs. Watkinson rousing herself to hope
U||   they had spent a pleasant evening, and that they would come and pass
U||   another with her on their return to New York. In such cases how
U||   difficult it is to reply even with what are called “words of course.”
U||   A kitchen lamp was brought to light them to the door, the entry lamp
U||   having long since been extinguished. Fortunately the rain had ceased;
U||   the stars began to reappear, and the Morlands, when they found
U||   themselves in the carriage and on their way to Mrs. St. Leonard’s, felt
U||   as if they could breathe again. As may be supposed, they freely
U||   discussed the annoyances of the evening; but now those troubles were
U||   over they felt rather inclined to be merry about them.
U||   “Dear mother,” said Edward, “how I pitied you for having to endure Mrs.
U||   Watkinson’s perpetual ‘ma’aming’ and ‘ma’aming’; for I know you dislike
U||   the word.”
U||   “I wish,” said Caroline, “I was not so prone to be taken with
U||   ridiculous recollections. But really to-night I could not get that old
U||   foolish child’s play out of my head—
U||   Here come three knights out of Spain
U||   A-courting of your daughter Jane.”
U||   “I shall certainly never be one of those Spanish knights,” said Edward.
U||   “Her daughter Jane is in no danger of being ruled by any ‘flattering
U||   tongue’ of mine. But what a shame for us to be talking of them in this
U||   manner.”
U||   They drove to Mrs. St. Leonard’s, hoping to be yet in time to pass half
U||   an hour there; though it was now near twelve o’clock and summer parties
U||   never continue to a very late hour. But as they came into the street in
U||   which she lived they were met by a number of coaches on their way home,
U||   and on reaching the door of her brilliantly lighted mansion, they saw
U||   the last of the guests driving off in the last of the carriages, and
U||   several musicians coming down the steps with their instruments in their
U||   hands.
U||   “So there has been a dance, then!” sighed Caroline. “Oh, what we have
U||   missed! It is really too provoking.”
U||   “So it is,” said Edward; “but remember that to-morrow morning we set
U||   off for Niagara.”
U||   “I will leave a note for Mrs. St. Leonard,” said his mother,
U||   “explaining that we were detained at Mrs. Watkinson’s by our coachman
U||   disappointing us. Let us console ourselves with the hope of seeing more
U||   of this lady on our return. And now, dear Caroline, you must draw a
U||   moral from the untoward events of to-day. When you are mistress of a
U||   house, and wish to show civility to strangers, let the invitation be
U||   always accompanied with a frank disclosure of what they are to expect.
U||   And if you cannot conveniently invite company to meet them, tell them
U||   at once that you will not insist on their keeping their engagement with
U||   you if anything offers afterwards that they think they would prefer;
U||   provided only that they apprize you in time of the change in their
U||   plan.”
U||   “Oh, mamma,” replied Caroline, “you may be sure I shall always take
U||   care not to betray my visitors into an engagement which they may have
U||   cause to regret, particularly if they are strangers whose time is
U||   limited. I shall certainly, as you say, tell them not to consider
U||   themselves bound to me if they afterwards receive an invitation which
U||   promises them more enjoyment. It will be a long while before I forget,
U||   the Watkinson evening.”
