U||TITBOTTOM’S SPECTACLES[47][14]
U||   By George William Curtis (1824–1892)
U||   In my mind’s eye, Horatio.
U||   Prue and I do not entertain much; our means forbid it. In truth, other
U||   people entertain for us. We enjoy that hospitality of which no account
U||   is made. We see the show, and hear the music, and smell the flowers of
U||   great festivities, tasting as it were the drippings from rich dishes.
U||   Our own dinner service is remarkably plain, our dinners, even on state
U||   occasions, are strictly in keeping, and almost our only guest is
U||   Titbottom. I buy a handful of roses as I come up from the office,
U||   perhaps, and Prue arranges them so prettily in a glass dish for the
U||   centre of the table that even when I have hurried out to see Aurelia
U||   step into her carriage to go out to dine, I have thought that the
U||   bouquet she carried was not more beautiful because it was more costly.
U||   I grant that it was more harmonious with her superb beauty and her rich
U||   attire. And I have no doubt that if Aurelia knew the old man, whom she
U||   must have seen so often watching her, and his wife, who ornaments her
U||   sex with as much sweetness, although with less splendor, than Aurelia
U||   herself, she would also acknowledge that the nosegay of roses was as
U||   fine and fit upon their table as her own sumptuous bouquet is for
U||   herself. I have that faith in the perception of that lovely lady. It is
U||   at least my habit—I hope I may say, my nature, to believe the best of
U||   people, rather than the worst. If I thought that all this sparkling
U||   setting of beauty—this fine fashion—these blazing jewels and lustrous
U||   silks and airy gauzes, embellished with gold-threaded embroidery and
U||   wrought in a thousand exquisite elaborations, so that I cannot see one
U||   of those lovely girls pass me by without thanking God for the vision—if
U||   I thought that this was all, and that underneath her lace flounces and
U||   diamond bracelets Aurelia was a sullen, selfish woman, then I should
U||   turn sadly homewards, for I should see that her jewels were flashing
U||   scorn upon the object they adorned, and that her laces were of a more
U||   exquisite loveliness than the woman whom they merely touched with a
U||   superficial grace. It would be like a gaily decorated mausoleum—bright
U||   to see, but silent and dark within.
U||   “Great excellences, my dear Prue,” I sometimes allow myself to say,
U||   “lie concealed in the depths of character, like pearls at the bottom of
U||   the sea. Under the laughing, glancing surface, how little they are
U||   suspected! Perhaps love is nothing else than the sight of them by one
U||   person. Hence every man’s mistress is apt to be an enigma to everybody
U||   else. I have no doubt that when Aurelia is engaged, people will say
U||   that she is a most admirable girl, certainly; but they cannot
U||   understand why any man should be in love with her. As if it were at all
U||   necessary that they should! And her lover, like a boy who finds a pearl
U||   in the public street, and wonders as much that others did not see it as
U||   that he did, will tremble until he knows his passion is returned;
U||   feeling, of course, that the whole world must be in love with this
U||   paragon who cannot possibly smile upon anything so unworthy as he.”
U||   “I hope, therefore, my dear Mrs. Prue,” I continue to say to my wife,
U||   who looks up from her work regarding me with pleased pride, as if I
U||   were such an irresistible humorist, “you will allow me to believe that
U||   the depth may be calm although the surface is dancing. If you tell me
U||   that Aurelia is but a giddy girl, I shall believe that you think so.
U||   But I shall know, all the while, what profound dignity, and sweetness,
U||   and peace lie at the foundation of her character.”
U||   I say such things to Titbottom during the dull season at the office.
U||   And I have known him sometimes to reply with a kind of dry, sad humor,
U||   not as if he enjoyed the joke, but as if the joke must be made, that he
U||   saw no reason why I should be dull because the season was so.
U||   “And what do I know of Aurelia or any other girl?” he says to me with
U||   that abstracted air. “I, whose Aurelias were of another century and
U||   another zone.”
U||   Then he falls into a silence which it seems quite profane to interrupt.
U||   But as we sit upon our high stools at the desk opposite each other, I
U||   leaning upon my elbows and looking at him; he, with sidelong face,
U||   glancing out of the window, as if it commanded a boundless landscape,
U||   instead of a dim, dingy office court, I cannot refrain from saying:
U||   “Well!”
U||   He turns slowly, and I go chatting on—a little too loquacious, perhaps,
U||   about those young girls. But I know that Titbottom regards such an
U||   excess as venial, for his sadness is so sweet that you could believe it
U||   the reflection of a smile from long, long years ago.
U||   One day, after I had been talking for a long time, and we had put up
U||   our books, and were preparing to leave, he stood for some time by the
U||   window, gazing with a drooping intentness, as if he really saw
U||   something more than the dark court, and said slowly:
U||   “Perhaps you would have different impressions of things if you saw them
U||   through my spectacles.”
U||   There was no change in his expression. He still looked from the window,
U||   and I said:
U||   “Titbottom, I did not know that you used glasses. I have never seen you
U||   wearing spectacles.”
U||   “No, I don’t often wear them. I am not very fond of looking through
U||   them. But sometimes an irresistible necessity compels me to put them
U||   on, and I cannot help seeing.” Titbottom sighed.
U||   “Is it so grievous a fate, to see?” inquired I.
U||   “Yes; through my spectacles,” he said, turning slowly and looking at me
U||   with wan solemnity.
U||   It grew dark as we stood in the office talking, and taking our hats we
U||   went out together. The narrow street of business was deserted. The
U||   heavy iron shutters were gloomily closed over the windows. From one or
U||   two offices struggled the dim gleam of an early candle, by whose light
U||   some perplexed accountant sat belated, and hunting for his error. A
U||   careless clerk passed, whistling. But the great tide of life had ebbed.
U||   We heard its roar far away, and the sound stole into that silent street
U||   like the murmur of the ocean into an inland dell.
U||   “You will come and dine with us, Titbottom?”
U||   He assented by continuing to walk with me, and I think we were both
U||   glad when we reached the house, and Prue came to meet us, saying:
U||   “Do you know I hoped you would bring Mr. Titbottom to dine?”
U||   Titbottom smiled gently, and answered:
U||   “He might have brought his spectacles with him, and I have been a
U||   happier man for it.”
U||   Prue looked a little puzzled.
U||   “My dear,” I said, “you must know that our friend, Mr. Titbottom, is
U||   the happy possessor of a pair of wonderful spectacles. I have never
U||   seen them, indeed; and, from what he says, I should be rather afraid of
U||   being seen by them. Most short-sighted persons are very glad to have
U||   the help of glasses; but Mr. Titbottom seems to find very little
U||   pleasure in his.”
U||   “It is because they make him too far-sighted, perhaps,” interrupted
U||   Prue quietly, as she took the silver soup-ladle from the sideboard.
U||   We sipped our wine after dinner, and Prue took her work. Can a man be
U||   too far-sighted? I did not ask the question aloud. The very tone in
U||   which Prue had spoken convinced me that he might.
U||   “At least,” I said, “Mr. Titbottom will not refuse to tell us the
U||   history of his mysterious spectacles. I have known plenty of magic in
U||   eyes”—and I glanced at the tender blue eyes of Prue—“but I have not
U||   heard of any enchanted glasses.”
U||   “Yet you must have seen the glass in which your wife looks every
U||   morning, and I take it that glass must be daily enchanted.” said
U||   Titbottom, with a bow of quaint respect to my wife.
U||   I do not think I have seen such a blush upon Prue’s cheek since—well,
U||   since a great many years ago.
U||   “I will gladly tell you the history of my spectacles,” began Titbottom.
U||   “It is very simple; and I am not at all sure that a great many other
U||   people have not a pair of the same kind. I have never, indeed, heard of
U||   them by the gross, like those of our young friend, Moses, the son of
U||   the Vicar of Wakefield. In fact, I think a gross would be quite enough
U||   to supply the world. It is a kind of article for which the demand does
U||   not increase with use. If we should all wear spectacles like mine, we
U||   should never smile any more. Oh—I am not quite sure—we should all be
U||   very happy.”
U||   “A very important difference,” said Prue, counting her stitches.
U||   “You know my grandfather Titbottom was a West Indian. A large
U||   proprietor, and an easy man, he basked in the tropical sun, leading his
U||   quiet, luxurious life. He lived much alone, and was what people call
U||   eccentric, by which I understand that he was very much himself, and,
U||   refusing the influence of other people, they had their little revenges,
U||   and called him names. It is a habit not exclusively tropical. I think I
U||   have seen the same thing even in this city. But he was greatly
U||   beloved—my bland and bountiful grandfather. He was so large-hearted and
U||   open-handed. He was so friendly, and thoughtful, and genial, that even
U||   his jokes had the air of graceful benedictions. He did not seem to grow
U||   old, and he was one of those who never appear to have been very young.
U||   He flourished in a perennial maturity, an immortal middle-age.
U||   “My grandfather lived upon one of the small islands, St. Kit’s,
U||   perhaps, and his domain extended to the sea. His house, a rambling West
U||   Indian mansion, was surrounded with deep, spacious piazzas, covered
U||   with luxurious lounges, among which one capacious chair was his
U||   peculiar seat. They tell me he used sometimes to sit there for the
U||   whole day, his great, soft, brown eyes fastened upon the sea, watching
U||   the specks of sails that flashed upon the horizon, while the evanescent
U||   expressions chased each other over his placid face, as if it reflected
U||   the calm and changing sea before him. His morning costume was an ample
U||   dressing-gown of gorgeously flowered silk, and his morning was very apt
U||   to last all day.
U||   “He rarely read, but he would pace the great piazza for hours, with his
U||   hands sunken in the pockets of his dressing-gown, and an air of sweet
U||   reverie, which any author might be very happy to produce.
U||   “Society, of course, he saw little. There was some slight apprehension
U||   that if he were bidden to social entertainments he might forget his
U||   coat, or arrive without some other essential part of his dress; and
U||   there is a sly tradition in the Titbottom family that, having been
U||   invited to a ball in honor of the new governor of the island, my
U||   grandfather Titbottom sauntered into the hall towards midnight, wrapped
U||   in the gorgeous flowers of his dressing-gown, and with his hands buried
U||   in the pockets, as usual. There was great excitement, and immense
U||   deprecation of gubernatorial ire. But it happened that the governor and
U||   my grandfather were old friends, and there was no offense. But as they
U||   were conversing together, one of the distressed managers cast indignant
U||   glances at the brilliant costume of my grandfather, who summoned him,
U||   and asked courteously:
U||   “‘Did you invite me or my coat?’
U||   “‘You, in a proper coat,’ replied the manager.
U||   “The governor smiled approvingly, and looked at my grandfather.
U||   “‘My friend,” said he to the manager, ‘I beg your pardon, I forgot.’
U||   “The next day my grandfather was seen promenading in full ball dress
U||   along the streets of the little town.
U||   “‘They ought to know,’ said he, ‘that I have a proper coat, and that
U||   not contempt nor poverty, but forgetfulness, sent me to a ball in my
U||   dressing-gown.’
U||   “He did not much frequent social festivals after this failure, but he
U||   always told the story with satisfaction and a quiet smile.
U||   “To a stranger, life upon those little islands is uniform even to
U||   weariness. But the old native dons like my grandfather ripen in the
U||   prolonged sunshine, like the turtle upon the Bahama banks, nor know of
U||   existence more desirable. Life in the tropics I take to be a placid
U||   torpidity. During the long, warm mornings of nearly half a century, my
U||   grandfather Titbottom had sat in his dressing-gown and gazed at the
U||   sea. But one calm June day, as he slowly paced the piazza after
U||   breakfast, his dreamy glance was arrested by a little vessel, evidently
U||   nearing the shore. He called for his spyglass, and surveying the craft,
U||   saw that she came from the neighboring island. She glided smoothly,
U||   slowly, over the summer sea. The warm morning air was sweet with
U||   perfumes, and silent with heat. The sea sparkled languidly, and the
U||   brilliant blue hung cloudlessly over. Scores of little island vessels
U||   had my grandfather seen come over the horizon, and cast anchor in the
U||   port. Hundreds of summer mornings had the white sails flashed and
U||   faded, like vague faces through forgotten dreams. But this time he laid
U||   down the spyglass, and leaned against a column of the piazza, and
U||   watched the vessel with an intentness that he could not explain. She
U||   came nearer and nearer, a graceful spectre in the dazzling morning.
U||   “‘Decidedly I must step down and see about that vessel,’ said my
U||   grandfather Titbottom.
U||   “He gathered his ample dressing-gown about him, and stepped from the
U||   piazza with no other protection from the sun than the little smoking
U||   cap upon his head. His face wore a calm, beaming smile, as if he
U||   approved of all the world. He was not an old man, but there was almost
U||   a patriarchal pathos in his expression as he sauntered along in the
U||   sunshine towards the shore. A group of idle gazers was collected to
U||   watch the arrival. The little vessel furled her sails and drifted
U||   slowly landward, and as she was of very light draft, she came close to
U||   the shelving shore. A long plank was put out from her side, and the
U||   debarkation commenced. My grandfather Titbottom stood looking on to see
U||   the passengers descend. There were but a few of them, and mostly
U||   traders from the neighboring island. But suddenly the face of a young
U||   girl appeared over the side of the vessel, and she stepped upon the
U||   plank to descend. My grandfather Titbottom instantly advanced, and
U||   moving briskly reached the top of the plank at the same moment, and
U||   with the old tassel of his cap flashing in the sun, and one hand in the
U||   pocket of his dressing gown, with the other he handed the young lady
U||   carefully down the plank. That young lady was afterwards my grandmother
U||   Titbottom.
U||   “And so, over the gleaming sea which he had watched so long, and which
U||   seemed thus to reward his patient gaze, came his bride that sunny
U||   morning.
U||   “‘Of course we are happy,’ he used to say: ‘For you are the gift of the
U||   sun I have loved so long and so well.’ And my grandfather Titbottom
U||   would lay his hand so tenderly upon the golden hair of his young bride,
U||   that you could fancy him a devout Parsee caressing sunbeams.
U||   “There were endless festivities upon occasion of the marriage; and my
U||   grandfather did not go to one of them in his dressing-gown. The gentle
U||   sweetness of his wife melted every heart into love and sympathy. He was
U||   much older than she, without doubt. But age, as he used to say with a
U||   smile of immortal youth, is a matter of feeling, not of years. And if,
U||   sometimes, as she sat by his side upon the piazza, her fancy looked
U||   through her eyes upon that summer sea and saw a younger lover, perhaps
U||   some one of those graceful and glowing heroes who occupy the foreground
U||   of all young maidens’ visions by the sea, yet she could not find one
U||   more generous and gracious, nor fancy one more worthy and loving than
U||   my grandfather Titbottom. And if in the moonlit midnight, while he lay
U||   calmly sleeping, she leaned out of the window and sank into vague
U||   reveries of sweet possibility, and watched the gleaming path of the
U||   moonlight upon the water, until the dawn glided over it—it was only
U||   that mood of nameless regret and longing, which underlies all human
U||   happiness,—or it was the vision of that life of society, which she had
U||   never seen, but of which she had often read, and which looked very fair
U||   and alluring across the sea to a girlish imagination which knew that it
U||   should never know that reality.
U||   “These West Indian years were the great days of the family,” said
U||   Titbottom, with an air of majestic and regal regret, pausing and musing
U||   in our little parlor, like a late Stuart in exile, remembering England.
U||   Prue raised her eyes from her work, and looked at him with a subdued
U||   admiration; for I have observed that, like the rest of her sex, she has
U||   a singular sympathy with the representative of a reduced family.
U||   Perhaps it is their finer perception which leads these tender-hearted
U||   women to recognize the divine right of social superiority so much more
U||   readily than we; and yet, much as Titbottom was enhanced in my wife’s
U||   admiration by the discovery that his dusky sadness of nature and
U||   expression was, as it were, the expiring gleam and late twilight of
U||   ancestral splendors, I doubt if Mr. Bourne would have preferred him for
U||   bookkeeper a moment sooner upon that account. In truth, I have
U||   observed, down town, that the fact of your ancestors doing nothing is
U||   not considered good proof that you can do anything. But Prue and her
U||   sex regard sentiment more than action, and I understand easily enough
U||   why she is never tired of hearing me read of Prince Charlie. If
U||   Titbottom had been only a little younger, a little handsomer, a little
U||   more gallantly dressed—in fact, a little more of the Prince Charlie, I
U||   am sure her eyes would not have fallen again upon her work so
U||   tranquilly, as he resumed his story.
U||   “I can remember my grandfather Titbottom, although I was a very young
U||   child, and he was a very old man. My young mother and my young
U||   grandmother are very distinct figures in my memory, ministering to the
U||   old gentleman, wrapped in his dressing-gown, and seated upon the
U||   piazza. I remember his white hair and his calm smile, and how, not long
U||   before he died, he called me to him, and laying his hand upon my head,
U||   said to me:
U||   “My child, the world is not this great sunny piazza, nor life the fairy
U||   stories which the women tell you here as you sit in their laps. I shall
U||   soon be gone, but I want to leave with you some memento of my love for
U||   you, and I know nothing more valuable than these spectacles, which your
U||   grandmother brought from her native island, when she arrived here one
U||   fine summer morning, long ago. I cannot quite tell whether, when you
U||   grow older, you will regard it as a gift of the greatest value or as
U||   something that you had been happier never to have possessed.’
U||   “‘But grandpapa, I am not short-sighted.’
U||   “‘My son, are you not human?’ said the old gentleman; and how shall I
U||   ever forget the thoughtful sadness with which, at the same time he
U||   handed me the spectacles.
U||   “Instinctively I put them on, and looked at my grandfather. But I saw
U||   no grandfather, no piazza, no flowered dressing-gown: I saw only a
U||   luxuriant palm-tree, waving broadly over a tranquil landscape. Pleasant
U||   homes clustered around it. Gardens teeming with fruit and flowers;
U||   flocks quietly feeding; birds wheeling and chirping. I heard children’s
U||   voices, and the low lullaby of happy mothers. The sound of cheerful
U||   singing came wafted from distant fields upon the light breeze. Golden
U||   harvests glistened out of sight, and I caught their rustling whisper of
U||   prosperity. A warm, mellow atmosphere bathed the whole. I have seen
U||   copies of the landscapes of the Italian painter Claude which seemed to
U||   me faint reminiscences of that calm and happy vision. But all this
U||   peace and prosperity seemed to flow from the spreading palm as from a
U||   fountain.
U||   “I do not know how long I looked, but I had, apparently, no power, as I
U||   had no will, to remove the spectacles. What a wonderful island must
U||   Nevis be, thought I, if people carry such pictures in their pockets,
U||   only by buying a pair of spectacles! What wonder that my dear
U||   grandmother Titbottom has lived such a placid life, and has blessed us
U||   all with her sunny temper, when she has lived surrounded by such images
U||   of peace.
U||   “My grandfather died. But still, in the warm morning sunshine upon the
U||   piazza, I felt his placid presence, and as I crawled into his great
U||   chair, and drifted on in reverie through the still, tropical day, it
U||   was as if his soft, dreamy eye had passed into my soul. My grandmother
U||   cherished his memory with tender regret. A violent passion of grief for
U||   his loss was no more possible than for the pensive decay of the year.
U||   We have no portrait of him, but I see always, when I remember him, that
U||   peaceful and luxuriant palm. And I think that to have known one good
U||   old man—one man who, through the chances and rubs of a long life, has
U||   carried his heart in his hand, like a palm branch, waving all discords
U||   into peace, helps our faith in God, in ourselves, and in each other,
U||   more than many sermons. I hardly know whether to be grateful to my
U||   grandfather for the spectacles; and yet when I remember that it is to
U||   them I owe the pleasant image of him which I cherish, I seem to myself
U||   sadly ungrateful.
U||   “Madam,” said Titbottom to Prue, solemnly, “my memory is a long and
U||   gloomy gallery, and only remotely, at its further end, do I see the
U||   glimmer of soft sunshine, and only there are the pleasant pictures
U||   hung. They seem to me very happy along whose gallery the sunlight
U||   streams to their very feet, striking all the pictured walls into
U||   unfading splendor.”
U||   Prue had laid her work in her lap, and as Titbottom paused a moment,
U||   and I turned towards her, I found her mild eyes fastened upon my face,
U||   and glistening with happy tears.
U||   “Misfortunes of many kinds came heavily upon the family after the head
U||   was gone. The great house was relinquished. My parents were both dead,
U||   and my grandmother had entire charge of me. But from the moment that I
U||   received the gift of the spectacles, I could not resist their
U||   fascination, and I withdrew into myself, and became a solitary boy.
U||   There were not many companions for me of my own age, and they gradually
U||   left me, or, at least, had not a hearty sympathy with me; for if they
U||   teased me I pulled out my spectacles and surveyed them so seriously
U||   that they acquired a kind of awe of me, and evidently regarded my
U||   grandfather’s gift as a concealed magical weapon which might be
U||   dangerously drawn upon them at any moment. Whenever, in our games,
U||   there were quarrels and high words, and I began to feel about my dress
U||   and to wear a grave look, they all took the alarm, and shouted, ‘Look
U||   out for Titbottom’s spectacles,’ and scattered like a flock of scared
U||   sheep.
U||   “Nor could I wonder at it. For, at first, before they took the alarm, I
U||   saw strange sights when I looked at them through the glasses. If two
U||   were quarrelling about a marble or a ball, I had only to go behind a
U||   tree where I was concealed and look at them leisurely. Then the scene
U||   changed, and no longer a green meadow with boys playing, but a spot
U||   which I did not recognize, and forms that made me shudder or smile. It
U||   was not a big boy bullying a little one, but a young wolf with
U||   glistening teeth and a lamb cowering before him; or, it was a dog
U||   faithful and famishing—or a star going slowly into eclipse—or a rainbow
U||   fading—or a flower blooming—or a sun rising—or a waning moon. The
U||   revelations of the spectacles determined my feeling for the boys, and
U||   for all whom I saw through them. No shyness, nor awkwardness, nor
U||   silence, could separate me from those who looked lovely as lilies to my
U||   illuminated eyes. If I felt myself warmly drawn to any one I struggled
U||   with the fierce desire of seeing him through the spectacles. I longed
U||   to enjoy the luxury of ignorant feeling, to love without knowing, to
U||   float like a leaf upon the eddies of life, drifted now to a sunny
U||   point, now to a solemn shade—now over glittering ripples, now over
U||   gleaming calms,—and not to determined ports, a trim vessel with an
U||   inexorable rudder.
U||   “But, sometimes, mastered after long struggles, I seized my spectacles
U||   and sauntered into the little town. Putting them to my eyes I peered
U||   into the houses and at the people who passed me. Here sat a family at
U||   breakfast, and I stood at the window looking in. O motley meal!
U||   fantastic vision! The good mother saw her lord sitting opposite, a
U||   grave, respectable being, eating muffins. But I saw only a bank-bill,
U||   more or less crumpled and tattered, marked with a larger or lesser
U||   figure. If a sharp wind blew suddenly, I saw it tremble and flutter; it
U||   was thin, flat, impalpable. I removed my glasses, and looked with my
U||   eyes at the wife. I could have smiled to see the humid tenderness with
U||   which she regarded her strange vis-à-vis. Is life only a game of
U||   blind-man’s-buff? of droll cross-purposes?
U||   “Or I put them on again, and looked at the wife. How many stout trees I
U||   saw,—how many tender flowers,—how many placid pools; yes, and how many
U||   little streams winding out of sight, shrinking before the large, hard,
U||   round eyes opposite, and slipping off into solitude and shade, with a
U||   low, inner song for their own solace. And in many houses I thought to
U||   see angels, nymphs, or at least, women, and could only find
U||   broomsticks, mops, or kettles, hurrying about, rattling, tinkling, in a
U||   state of shrill activity. I made calls upon elegant ladies, and after I
U||   had enjoyed the gloss of silk and the delicacy of lace, and the flash
U||   of jewels, I slipped on my spectacles, and saw a peacock’s feather,
U||   flounced and furbelowed and fluttering; or an iron rod, thin, sharp,
U||   and hard; nor could I possibly mistake the movement of the drapery for
U||   any flexibility of the thing draped,—or, mysteriously chilled, I saw a
U||   statue of perfect form, or flowing movement, it might be alabaster, or
U||   bronze, or marble,—but sadly often it was ice; and I knew that after it
U||   had shone a little, and frozen a few eyes with its despairing
U||   perfection, it could not be put away in the niches of palaces for
U||   ornament and proud family tradition, like the alabaster, or bronze, or
U||   marble statues, but would melt, and shrink, and fall coldly away in
U||   colorless and useless water, be absorbed in the earth and utterly
U||   forgotten.
U||   “But the true sadness was rather in seeing those who, not having the
U||   spectacles, thought that the iron rod was flexible, and the ice statue
U||   warm. I saw many a gallant heart, which seemed to me brave and loyal as
U||   the crusaders sent by genuine and noble faith to Syria and the
U||   sepulchre, pursuing, through days and nights, and a long life of
U||   devotion, the hope of lighting at least a smile in the cold eyes, if
U||   not a fire in the icy heart. I watched the earnest, enthusiastic
U||   sacrifice. I saw the pure resolve, the generous faith, the fine scorn
U||   of doubt, the impatience of suspicion. I watched the grace, the ardor,
U||   the glory of devotion. Through those strange spectacles how often I saw
U||   the noblest heart renouncing all other hope, all other ambition, all
U||   other life, than the possible love of some one of those statues. Ah!
U||   me, it was terrible, but they had not the love to give. The Parian face
U||   was so polished and smooth, because there was no sorrow upon the
U||   heart,—and, drearily often, no heart to be touched. I could not wonder
U||   that the noble heart of devotion was broken, for it had dashed itself
U||   against a stone. I wept, until my spectacles were dimmed for that
U||   hopeless sorrow; but there was a pang beyond tears for those icy
U||   statues.
U||   “Still a boy, I was thus too much a man in knowledge,—I did not
U||   comprehend the sights I was compelled to see. I used to tear my glasses
U||   away from my eyes, and, frightened at myself, run to escape my own
U||   consciousness. Reaching the small house where we then lived, I plunged
U||   into my grandmother’s room and, throwing myself upon the floor, buried
U||   my face in her lap; and sobbed myself to sleep with premature grief.
U||   But when I awakened, and felt her cool hand upon my hot forehead, and
U||   heard the low, sweet song, or the gentle story, or the tenderly told
U||   parable from the Bible, with which she tried to soothe me, I could not
U||   resist the mystic fascination that lured me, as I lay in her lap, to
U||   steal a glance at her through the spectacles.
U||   “Pictures of the Madonna have not her rare and pensive beauty. Upon the
U||   tranquil little islands her life had been eventless, and all the fine
U||   possibilities of her nature were like flowers that never bloomed.
U||   Placid were all her years; yet I have read of no heroine, of no woman
U||   great in sudden crises, that it did not seem to me she might have been.
U||   The wife and widow of a man who loved his own home better than the
U||   homes of others, I have yet heard of no queen, no belle, no imperial
U||   beauty, whom in grace, and brilliancy, and persuasive courtesy, she
U||   might not have surpassed.
U||   “Madam,” said Titbottom to my wife, whose heart hung upon his story;
U||   “your husband’s young friend, Aurelia, wears sometimes a camelia in her
U||   hair, and no diamond in the ball-room seems so costly as that perfect
U||   flower, which women envy, and for whose least and withered petal men
U||   sigh; yet, in the tropical solitudes of Brazil, how many a camelia bud
U||   drops from a bush that no eye has ever seen, which, had it flowered and
U||   been noticed, would have gilded all hearts with its memory.
U||   “When I stole these furtive glances at my grandmother, half fearing
U||   that they were wrong, I saw only a calm lake, whose shores were low,
U||   and over which the sky hung unbroken, so that the least star was
U||   clearly reflected. It had an atmosphere of solemn twilight
U||   tranquillity, and so completely did its unruffled surface blend with
U||   the cloudless, star-studded sky, that, when I looked through my
U||   spectacles at my grandmother, the vision seemed to me all heaven and
U||   stars. Yet, as I gazed and gazed, I felt what stately cities might well
U||   have been built upon those shores, and have flashed prosperity over the
U||   calm, like coruscations of pearls.
U||   “I dreamed of gorgeous fleets, silken sailed and blown by perfumed
U||   winds, drifting over those depthless waters and through those spacious
U||   skies. I gazed upon the twilight, the inscrutable silence, like a
U||   God-fearing discoverer upon a new, and vast, and dim sea, bursting upon
U||   him through forest glooms, and in the fervor of whose impassioned gaze,
U||   a millennial and poetic world arises, and man need no longer die to be
U||   happy.
U||   “My companions naturally deserted me, for I had grown wearily grave and
U||   abstracted: and, unable to resist the allurement of my spectacles, I
U||   was constantly lost in a world, of which those companions were part,
U||   yet of which they knew nothing. I grew cold and hard, almost morose;
U||   people seemed to me blind and unreasonable. They did the wrong thing.
U||   They called green, yellow; and black, white. Young men said of a girl,
U||   ‘What a lovely, simple creature!’ I looked, and there was only a
U||   glistening wisp of straw, dry and hollow. Or they said, ‘What a cold,
U||   proud beauty!’ I looked, and lo! a Madonna, whose heart held the world.
U||   Or they said, ‘What a wild, giddy girl!’ and I saw a glancing, dancing
U||   mountain stream, pure as the virgin snows whence it flowed, singing
U||   through sun and shade, over pearls and gold dust, slipping along
U||   unstained by weed, or rain, or heavy foot of cattle, touching the
U||   flowers with a dewy kiss,—a beam of grace, a happy song, a line of
U||   light, in the dim and troubled landscape.
U||   “My grandmother sent me to school, but I looked at the master, and saw
U||   that he was a smooth, round ferule—or an improper noun—or a vulgar
U||   fraction, and refused to obey him. Or he was a piece of string, a rag,
U||   a willow-wand, and I had a contemptuous pity. But one was a well of
U||   cool, deep water, and looking suddenly in, one day, I saw the stars. He
U||   gave me all my schooling. With him I used to walk by the sea, and, as
U||   we strolled and the waves plunged in long legions before us, I looked
U||   at him through the spectacles, and as his eye dilated with the
U||   boundless view, and his chest heaved with an impossible desire, I saw
U||   Xerxes and his army tossing and glittering, rank upon rank, multitude
U||   upon multitude, out of sight, but ever regularly advancing and with the
U||   confused roar of ceaseless music, prostrating themselves in abject
U||   homage. Or, as with arms outstretched and hair streaming on the wind,
U||   he chanted full lines of the resounding Iliad, I saw Homer pacing the
U||   AEgean sands in the Greek sunsets of forgotten times.
U||   “My grandmother died, and I was thrown into the world without
U||   resources, and with no capital but my spectacles. I tried to find
U||   employment, but men were shy of me. There was a vague suspicion that I
U||   was either a little crazed, or a good deal in league with the Prince of
U||   Darkness. My companions who would persist in calling a piece of painted
U||   muslin a fair and fragrant flower had no difficulty; success waited for
U||   them around every corner, and arrived in every ship. I tried to teach,
U||   for I loved children. But if anything excited my suspicion, and,
U||   putting on my spectacles, I saw that I was fondling a snake, or
U||   smelling at a bud with a worm in it, I sprang up in horror and ran
U||   away; or, if it seemed to me through the glasses that a cherub smiled
U||   upon me, or a rose was blooming in my buttonhole, then I felt myself
U||   imperfect and impure, not fit to be leading and training what was so
U||   essentially superior in quality to myself, and I kissed the children
U||   and left them weeping and wondering.
U||   “In despair I went to a great merchant on the island, and asked him to
U||   employ me.
U||   “‘My young friend,’ said he, ‘I understand that you have some singular
U||   secret, some charm, or spell, or gift, or something, I don’t know what,
U||   of which people are afraid. Now, you know, my dear,’ said the merchant,
U||   swelling up, and apparently prouder of his great stomach than of his
U||   large fortune, ‘I am not of that kind. I am not easily frightened. You
U||   may spare yourself the pain of trying to impose upon me. People who
U||   propose to come to time before I arrive, are accustomed to arise very
U||   early in the morning,’ said he, thrusting his thumbs in the armholes of
U||   his waistcoat, and spreading the fingers, like two fans, upon his
U||   bosom. ‘I think I have heard something of your secret. You have a pair
U||   of spectacles, I believe, that you value very much, because your
U||   grandmother brought them as a marriage portion to your grandfather.
U||   Now, if you think fit to sell me those spectacles, I will pay you the
U||   largest market price for glasses. What do you say?’
U||   “I told him that I had not the slightest idea of selling my spectacles.
U||   “‘My young friend means to eat them, I suppose,’ said he with a
U||   contemptuous smile.
U||   “I made no reply, but was turning to leave the office, when the
U||   merchant called after me—
U||   “‘My young friend, poor people should never suffer themselves to get
U||   into pets. Anger is an expensive luxury, in which only men of a certain
U||   income can indulge. A pair of spectacles and a hot temper are not the
U||   most promising capital for success in life, Master Titbottom.’
U||   “I said nothing, but put my hand upon the door to go out, when the
U||   merchant said more respectfully,—
U||   “‘Well, you foolish boy, if you will not sell your spectacles, perhaps
U||   you will agree to sell the use of them to me. That is, you shall only
U||   put them on when I direct you, and for my purposes. Hallo! you little
U||   fool!’ cried he impatiently, as he saw that I intended to make no
U||   reply.
U||   “But I had pulled out my spectacles, and put them on for my own
U||   purpose, and against his direction and desire. I looked at him, and saw
U||   a huge bald-headed wild boar, with gross chops and a leering eye—only
U||   the more ridiculous for the high-arched, gold-bowed spectacles, that
U||   straddled his nose. One of his fore hoofs was thrust into the safe,
U||   where his bills payable were hived, and the other into his pocket,
U||   among the loose change and bills there. His ears were pricked forward
U||   with a brisk, sensitive smartness. In a world where prize pork was the
U||   best excellence, he would have carried off all the premiums.
U||   “I stepped into the next office in the street, and a mild-faced, genial
U||   man, also a large and opulent merchant, asked me my business in such a
U||   tone, that I instantly looked through my spectacles, and saw a land
U||   flowing with milk and honey. There I pitched my tent, and stayed till
U||   the good man died, and his business was discontinued.
U||   “But while there,” said Titbottom, and his voice trembled away into a
U||   sigh, “I first saw Preciosa. Spite of the spectacles, I saw Preciosa.
U||   For days, for weeks, for months, I did not take my spectacles with me.
U||   I ran away from them, I threw them up on high shelves, I tried to make
U||   up my mind to throw them into the sea, or down the well. I could not, I
U||   would not, I dared not look at Preciosa through the spectacles. It was
U||   not possible for me deliberately to destroy them; but I awoke in the
U||   night, and could almost have cursed my dear old grandfather for his
U||   gift. I escaped from the office, and sat for whole days with Preciosa.
U||   I told her the strange things I had seen with my mystic glasses. The
U||   hours were not enough for the wild romances which I raved in her ear.
U||   She listened, astonished and appalled. Her blue eyes turned upon me
U||   with a sweet deprecation. She clung to me, and then withdrew, and fled
U||   fearfully from the room. But she could not stay away. She could not
U||   resist my voice, in whose tones burned all the love that filled my
U||   heart and brain. The very effort to resist the desire of seeing her as
U||   I saw everybody else, gave a frenzy and an unnatural tension to my
U||   feeling and my manner. I sat by her side, looking into her eyes,
U||   smoothing her hair, folding her to my heart, which was sunken and
U||   deep—why not forever?—in that dream of peace. I ran from her presence,
U||   and shouted, and leaped with joy, and sat the whole night through,
U||   thrilled into happiness by the thought of her love and loveliness, like
U||   a wind-harp, tightly strung, and answering the airiest sigh of the
U||   breeze with music. Then came calmer days—the conviction of deep love
U||   settled upon our lives—as after the hurrying, heaving days of spring,
U||   comes the bland and benignant summer.
U||   “‘It is no dream, then, after all, and we are happy,’ I said to her,
U||   one day; and there came no answer, for happiness is speechless.
U||   “We are happy then,” I said to myself, “there is no excitement now. How
U||   glad I am that I can now look at her through my spectacles.”
U||   “I feared lest some instinct should warn me to beware. I escaped from
U||   her arms, and ran home and seized the glasses and bounded back again to
U||   Preciosa. As I entered the room I was heated, my head was swimming with
U||   confused apprehension, my eyes must have glared. Preciosa was
U||   frightened, and rising from her seat, stood with an inquiring glance of
U||   surprise in her eyes. But I was bent with frenzy upon my purpose. I was
U||   merely aware that she was in the room. I saw nothing else. I heard
U||   nothing. I cared for nothing, but to see her through that magic glass,
U||   and feel at once, all the fulness of blissful perfection which that
U||   would reveal. Preciosa stood before the mirror, but alarmed at my wild
U||   and eager movements, unable to distinguish what I had in my hands, and
U||   seeing me raise them suddenly to my face, she shrieked with terror, and
U||   fell fainting upon the floor, at the very moment that I placed the
U||   glasses before my eyes, and beheld—myself, reflected in the mirror,
U||   before which she had been standing.
U||   “Dear madam,” cried Titbottom, to my wife, springing up and falling
U||   back again in his chair, pale and trembling, while Prue ran to him and
U||   took his hand, and I poured out a glass of water—“I saw myself.”
U||   There was silence for many minutes. Prue laid her hand gently upon the
U||   head of our guest, whose eyes were closed, and who breathed softly,
U||   like an infant in sleeping. Perhaps, in all the long years of anguish
U||   since that hour, no tender hand had touched his brow, nor wiped away
U||   the damps of a bitter sorrow. Perhaps the tender, maternal fingers of
U||   my wife soothed his weary head with the conviction that he felt the
U||   hand of his mother playing with the long hair of her boy in the soft
U||   West Indian morning. Perhaps it was only the natural relief of
U||   expressing a pent-up sorrow. When he spoke again, it was with the old,
U||   subdued tone, and the air of quaint solemnity.
U||   “These things were matters of long, long ago, and I came to this
U||   country soon after. I brought with me, premature age, a past of
U||   melancholy memories, and the magic spectacles. I had become their
U||   slave. I had nothing more to fear. Having seen myself, I was compelled
U||   to see others, properly to understand my relations to them. The lights
U||   that cheer the future of other men had gone out for me. My eyes were
U||   those of an exile turned backwards upon the receding shore, and not
U||   forwards with hope upon the ocean. I mingled with men, but with little
U||   pleasure. There are but many varieties of a few types. I did not find
U||   those I came to clearer sighted than those I had left behind. I heard
U||   men called shrewd and wise, and report said they were highly
U||   intelligent and successful. But when I looked at them through my
U||   glasses, I found no halo of real manliness. My finest sense detected no
U||   aroma of purity and principle; but I saw only a fungus that had
U||   fattened and spread in a night. They all went to the theater to see
U||   actors upon the stage. I went to see actors in the boxes, so
U||   consummately cunning, that the others did not know they were acting,
U||   and they did not suspect it themselves.
U||   “Perhaps you wonder it did not make me misanthropical. My dear friends,
U||   do not forget that I had seen myself. It made me compassionate, not
U||   cynical. Of course I could not value highly the ordinary standards of
U||   success and excellence. When I went to church and saw a thin, blue,
U||   artificial flower, or a great sleepy cushion expounding the beauty of
U||   holiness to pews full of eagles, half-eagles, and threepences, however
U||   adroitly concealed in broadcloth and boots: or saw an onion in an
U||   Easter bonnet weeping over the sins of Magdalen, I did not feel as they
U||   felt who saw in all this, not only propriety, but piety. Or when at
U||   public meetings an eel stood up on end, and wriggled and squirmed
U||   lithely in every direction, and declared that, for his part, he went in
U||   for rainbows and hot water—how could I help seeing that he was still
U||   black and loved a slimy pool?
U||   “I could not grow misanthropical when I saw in the eyes of so many who
U||   were called old, the gushing fountains of eternal youth, and the light
U||   of an immortal dawn, or when I saw those who were esteemed unsuccessful
U||   and aimless, ruling a fair realm of peace and plenty, either in
U||   themselves, or more perfectly in another—a realm and princely
U||   possession for which they had well renounced a hopeless search and a
U||   belated triumph. I knew one man who had been for years a by-word for
U||   having sought the philosopher’s stone. But I looked at him through the
U||   spectacles and saw a satisfaction in concentrated energies, and a
U||   tenacity arising from devotion to a noble dream, which was not apparent
U||   in the youths who pitied him in the aimless effeminacy of clubs, nor in
U||   the clever gentlemen who cracked their thin jokes upon him over a
U||   gossiping dinner.
U||   “And there was your neighbor over the way, who passes for a woman who
U||   has failed in her career, because she is an old maid. People wag solemn
U||   heads of pity, and say that she made so great a mistake in not marrying
U||   the brilliant and famous man who was for long years her suitor. It is
U||   clear that no orange flower will ever bloom for her. The young people
U||   make tender romances about her as they watch her, and think of her
U||   solitary hours of bitter regret, and wasting longing, never to be
U||   satisfied. When I first came to town I shared this sympathy, and
U||   pleased my imagination with fancying her hard struggle with the
U||   conviction that she had lost all that made life beautiful. I supposed
U||   that if I looked at her through my spectacles, I should see that it was
U||   only her radiant temper which so illuminated her dress, that we did not
U||   see it to be heavy sables. But when, one day, I did raise my glasses
U||   and glanced at her, I did not see the old maid whom we all pitied for a
U||   secret sorrow, but a woman whose nature was a tropic, in which the sun
U||   shone, and birds sang, and flowers bloomed forever. There were no
U||   regrets, no doubts and half wishes, but a calm sweetness, a transparent
U||   peace. I saw her blush when that old lover passed by, or paused to
U||   speak to her, but it was only the sign of delicate feminine
U||   consciousness. She knew his love, and honored it, although she could
U||   not understand it nor return it. I looked closely at her, and I saw
U||   that although all the world had exclaimed at her indifference to such
U||   homage, and had declared it was astonishing she should lose so fine a
U||   match, she would only say simply and quietly—
U||   “‘If Shakespeare loved me and I did not love him, how could I marry
U||   him?’
U||   “Could I be misanthropical when I saw such fidelity, and dignity, and
U||   simplicity?
U||   “You may believe that I was especially curious to look at that old
U||   lover of hers, through my glasses. He was no longer young, you know,
U||   when I came, and his fame and fortune were secure. Certainly I have
U||   heard of few men more beloved, and of none more worthy to be loved. He
U||   had the easy manner of a man of the world, the sensitive grace of a
U||   poet, and the charitable judgment of a wide traveller. He was accounted
U||   the most successful and most unspoiled of men. Handsome, brilliant,
U||   wise, tender, graceful, accomplished, rich, and famous, I looked at
U||   him, without the spectacles, in surprise, and admiration, and wondered
U||   how your neighbor over the way had been so entirely untouched by his
U||   homage. I watched their intercourse in society, I saw her gay smile,
U||   her cordial greeting; I marked his frank address, his lofty courtesy.
U||   Their manner told no tales. The eager world was balked, and I pulled
U||   out my spectacles.
U||   “I had seen her, already, and now I saw him. He lived only in memory,
U||   and his memory was a spacious and stately palace. But he did not
U||   oftenest frequent the banqueting hall, where were endless hospitality
U||   and feasting—nor did he loiter much in reception rooms, where a throng
U||   of new visitors was forever swarming—nor did he feed his vanity by
U||   haunting the apartment in which were stored the trophies of his varied
U||   triumphs—nor dream much in the great gallery hung with pictures of his
U||   travels. But from all these lofty halls of memory he constantly escaped
U||   to a remote and solitary chamber, into which no one had ever
U||   penetrated. But my fatal eyes, behind the glasses, followed and entered
U||   with him, and saw that the chamber was a chapel. It was dim, and
U||   silent, and sweet with perpetual incense that burned upon an altar
U||   before a picture forever veiled. There, whenever I chanced to look, I
U||   saw him kneel and pray; and there, by day and by night, a funeral hymn
U||   was chanted.
U||   “I do not believe you will be surprised that I have been content to
U||   remain deputy bookkeeper. My spectacles regulated my ambition, and I
U||   early learned that there were better gods than Plutus. The glasses have
U||   lost much of their fascination now, and I do not often use them.
U||   Sometimes the desire is irresistible. Whenever I am greatly interested,
U||   I am compelled to take them out and see what it is that I admire.
U||   “And yet—and yet,” said Titbottom, after a pause, “I am not sure that I
U||   thank my grandfather.”
U||   Prue had long since laid away her work, and had heard every word of the
U||   story. I saw that the dear woman had yet one question to ask, and had
U||   been earnestly hoping to hear something that would spare her the
U||   necessity of asking. But Titbottom had resumed his usual tone, after
U||   the momentary excitement, and made no further allusion to himself. We
U||   all sat silently; Titbottom’s eyes fastened musingly upon the carpet:
U||   Prue looking wistfully at him, and I regarding both.
U||   It was past midnight, and our guest arose to go. He shook hands
U||   quietly, made his grave Spanish bow to Prue, and taking his hat, went
U||   towards the front door. Prue and I accompanied him. I saw in her eyes
U||   that she would ask her question. And as Titbottom opened the door, I
U||   heard the low words:
U||   “And Preciosa?”
U||   Titbottom paused. He had just opened the door and the moonlight
U||   streamed over him as he stood, turning back to us.
U||   “I have seen her but once since. It was in church, and she was kneeling
U||   with her eyes closed, so that she did not see me. But I rubbed the
U||   glasses well, and looked at her, and saw a white lily, whose stem was
U||   broken, but which was fresh; and luminous, and fragrant, still.”
U||   “That was a miracle,” interrupted Prue.
U||   “Madam, it was a miracle,” replied Titbottom, “and for that one sight I
U||   am devoutly grateful for my grandfather’s gift. I saw, that although a
U||   flower may have lost its hold upon earthly moisture, it may still bloom
U||   as sweetly, fed by the dews of heaven.”
U||   The door closed, and he was gone. But as Prue put her arm in mine and
U||   we went upstairs together, she whispered in my ear:
U||   “How glad I am that you don’t wear spectacles.”
