U||MY DOUBLE; AND HOW HE UNDID ME[49][15]
U||   By Edward Everett Hale (1822–1909)
U||   It is not often that I trouble the readers of The Atlantic Monthly. I
U||   should not trouble them now, but for the importunities of my wife, who
U||   “feels to insist” that a duty to society is unfulfilled, till I have
U||   told why I had to have a double, and how he undid me. She is sure, she
U||   says, that intelligent persons cannot understand that pressure upon
U||   public servants which alone drives any man into the employment of a
U||   double. And while I fear she thinks, at the bottom of her heart, that
U||   my fortunes will never be re-made, she has a faint hope, that, as
U||   another Rasselas, I may teach a lesson to future publics, from which
U||   they may profit, though we die. Owing to the behavior of my double, or,
U||   if you please, to that public pressure which compelled me to employ
U||   him, I have plenty of leisure to write this communication.
U||   I am, or rather was, a minister, of the Sandemanian connection. I was
U||   settled in the active, wide-awake town of Naguadavick, on one of the
U||   finest water-powers in Maine. We used to call it a Western town in the
U||   heart of the civilization of New England. A charming place it was and
U||   is. A spirited, brave young parish had I; and it seemed as if we might
U||   have all “the joy of eventful living” to our hearts’ content.
U||   Alas! how little we knew on the day of my ordination, and in those
U||   halcyon moments of our first housekeeping! To be the confidential
U||   friend in a hundred families in the town—cutting the social trifle, as
U||   my friend Haliburton says, “from the top of the whipped-syllabub to the
U||   bottom of the sponge-cake, which is the foundation”—to keep abreast of
U||   the thought of the age in one’s study, and to do one’s best on Sunday
U||   to interweave that thought with the active life of an active town, and
U||   to inspirit both and make both infinite by glimpses of the Eternal
U||   Glory, seemed such an exquisite forelook into one’s life! Enough to do,
U||   and all so real and so grand! If this vision could only have lasted.
U||   The truth is, that this vision was not in itself a delusion, nor,
U||   indeed, half bright enough. If one could only have been left to do his
U||   own business, the vision would have accomplished itself and brought out
U||   new paraheliacal visions, each as bright as the original. The misery
U||   was and is, as we found out, I and Polly, before long, that, besides
U||   the vision, and besides the usual human and finite failures in life
U||   (such as breaking the old pitcher that came over in the Mayflower, and
U||   putting into the fire the alpenstock with which her father climbed Mont
U||   Blanc)—besides, these, I say (imitating the style of Robinson Crusoe),
U||   there were pitchforked in on us a great rowen-heap of humbugs, handed
U||   down from some unknown seed-time, in which we were expected, and I
U||   chiefly, to fulfil certain public functions before the community, of
U||   the character of those fulfilled by the third row of supernumeraries
U||   who stand behind the Sepoys in the spectacle of the Cataract of the
U||   Ganges. They were the duties, in a word, which one performs as member
U||   of one or another social class or subdivision, wholly distinct from
U||   what one does as A. by himself A. What invisible power put these
U||   functions on me, it would be very hard to tell. But such power there
U||   was and is. And I had not been at work a year before I found I was
U||   living two lives, one real and one merely functional—for two sets of
U||   people, one my parish, whom I loved, and the other a vague public, for
U||   whom I did not care two straws. All this was in a vague notion, which
U||   everybody had and has, that this second life would eventually bring out
U||   some great results, unknown at present, to somebody somewhere.
U||   Crazed by this duality of life, I first read Dr. Wigan on the Duality
U||   of the Brain, hoping that I could train one side of my head to do these
U||   outside jobs, and the other to do my intimate and real duties. For
U||   Richard Greenough once told me that, in studying for the statue of
U||   Franklin, he found that the left side of the great man’s face was
U||   philosophic and reflective, and the right side funny and smiling. If
U||   you will go and look at the bronze statue, you will find he has
U||   repeated this observation there for posterity. The eastern profile is
U||   the portrait of the statesman Franklin, the western of Poor Richard.
U||   But Dr. Wigan does not go into these niceties of this subject, and I
U||   failed. It was then that, on my wife’s suggestion, I resolved to look
U||   out for a Double.
U||   I was, at first, singularly successful. We happened to be recreating at
U||   Stafford Springs that summer. We rode out one day, for one of the
U||   relaxations of that watering-place, to the great Monsonpon House. We
U||   were passing through one of the large halls, when my destiny was
U||   fulfilled! I saw my man!
U||   He was not shaven. He had on no spectacles. He was dressed in a green
U||   baize roundabout and faded blue overalls, worn sadly at the knee. But I
U||   saw at once that he was of my height, five feet four and a half. He had
U||   black hair, worn off by his hat. So have and have not I. He stooped in
U||   walking. So do I. His hands were large, and mine. And—choicest gift of
U||   Fate in all—he had, not “a strawberry-mark on his left arm,” but a cut
U||   from a juvenile brickbat over his right eye, slightly affecting the
U||   play of that eyebrow. Reader, so have I!—My fate was sealed!
U||   A word with Mr. Holley, one of the inspectors, settled the whole thing.
U||   It proved that this Dennis Shea was a harmless, amiable fellow, of the
U||   class known as shiftless, who had sealed his fate by marrying a dumb
U||   wife, who was at that moment ironing in the laundry. Before I left
U||   Stafford, I had hired both for five years. We had applied to Judge
U||   Pynchon, then the probate judge at Springfield, to change the name of
U||   Dennis Shea to Frederic Ingham. We had explained to the Judge, what was
U||   the precise truth, that an eccentric gentleman wished to adopt Dennis
U||   under this new name into his family. It never occurred to him that
U||   Dennis might be more than fourteen years old. And thus, to shorten this
U||   preface, when we returned at night to my parsonage at Naguadavick,
U||   there entered Mrs. Ingham, her new dumb laundress, myself, who am Mr.
U||   Frederic Ingham, and my double, who was Mr. Frederic Ingham by as good
U||   right as I.
U||   Oh, the fun we had the next morning in shaving his beard to my pattern,
U||   cutting his hair to match mine, and teaching him how to wear and how to
U||   take off gold-bowed spectacles! Really, they were electroplate, and the
U||   glass was plain (for the poor fellow’s eyes were excellent). Then in
U||   four successive afternoons I taught him four speeches. I had found
U||   these would be quite enough for the supernumerary-Sepoy line of life,
U||   and it was well for me they were. For though he was good-natured, he
U||   was very shiftless, and it was, as our national proverb says, “like
U||   pulling teeth” to teach him. But at the end of the next week he could
U||   say, with quite my easy and frisky air:
U||   1. “Very well, thank you. And you?” This for an answer to casual
U||   salutations.
U||   2. “I am very glad you liked it.”
U||   3. “There has been so much said, and, on the whole, so well said, that
U||   I will not occupy the time.”
U||   4. “I agree, in general, with my friend on the other side of the room.”
U||   At first I had a feeling that I was going to be at great cost for
U||   clothing him. But it proved, of course, at once, that, whenever he was
U||   out, I should be at home. And I went, during the bright period of his
U||   success, to so few of those awful pageants which require a black
U||   dress-coat and what the ungodly call, after Mr. Dickens, a white
U||   choker, that in the happy retreat of my own dressing-gowns and jackets
U||   my days went by as happily and cheaply as those of another Thalaba. And
U||   Polly declares there was never a year when the tailoring cost so
U||   little. He lived (Dennis, not Thalaba) in his wife’s room over the
U||   kitchen. He had orders never to show himself at that window. When he
U||   appeared in the front of the house, I retired to my sanctissimum and my
U||   dressing-gown. In short, the Dutchman and, his wife, in the old
U||   weather-box, had not less to do with, each other than he and I. He made
U||   the furnace-fire and split the wood before daylight; then he went to
U||   sleep again, and slept late; then came for orders, with a red silk
U||   bandanna tied round his head, with his overalls on, and his dress-coat
U||   and spectacles off. If we happened to be interrupted, no one guessed
U||   that he was Frederic Ingham as well as I; and, in the neighborhood,
U||   there grew up an impression that the minister’s Irishman worked
U||   day-times in the factory village at New Coventry. After I had given him
U||   his orders, I never saw him till the next day.
U||   I launched him by sending him to a meeting of the Enlightenment Board.
U||   The Enlightenment Board consists of seventy-four members, of whom
U||   sixty-seven are necessary to form a quorum. One becomes a member under
U||   the regulations laid down in old Judge Dudley’s will. I became one by
U||   being ordained pastor of a church in Naguadavick. You see you cannot
U||   help yourself, if you would. At this particular time we had had four
U||   successive meetings, averaging four hours each—wholly occupied in
U||   whipping in a quorum. At the first only eleven men were present; at the
U||   next, by force of three circulars, twenty-seven; at the third, thanks
U||   to two days’ canvassing by Auchmuty and myself, begging men to come, we
U||   had sixty. Half the others were in Europe. But without a quorum we
U||   could do nothing. All the rest of us waited grimly for our four hours,
U||   and adjourned without any action. At the fourth meeting we had flagged,
U||   and only got fifty-nine together. But on the first appearance of my
U||   double—whom I sent on this fatal Monday to the fifth meeting—he was the
U||   sixty-seventh man who entered the room. He was greeted with a storm of
U||   applause! The poor fellow had missed his way—read the street signs ill
U||   through his spectacles (very ill, in fact, without them)—and had not
U||   dared to inquire. He entered the room—finding the president and
U||   secretary holding to their chairs two judges of the Supreme Court, who
U||   were also members ex officio, and were begging leave to go away. On his
U||   entrance all was changed. Presto, the by-laws were amended, and the
U||   Western property was given away. Nobody stopped to converse with him.
U||   He voted, as I had charged him to do, in every instance, with the
U||   minority. I won new laurels as a man of sense, though a little
U||   unpunctual—and Dennis, alias Ingham, returned to the parsonage,
U||   astonished to see with how little wisdom the world is governed. He cut
U||   a few of my parishioners in the street; but he had his glasses off, and
U||   I am known to be nearsighted. Eventually he recognized them more
U||   readily than I.
U||   I “set him again” at the exhibition of the New Coventry Academy; and
U||   here he undertook a “speaking part”—as, in my boyish, worldly days, I
U||   remember the bills used to say of Mlle. Celeste. We are all trustees of
U||   the New Coventry Academy; and there has lately been “a good deal of
U||   feeling” because the Sandemanian trustees did not regularly attend the
U||   exhibitions. It has been intimated, indeed, that the Sandemanians are
U||   leaning towards Free-Will, and that we have, therefore, neglected these
U||   semi-annual exhibitions, while there is no doubt that Auchmuty last
U||   year went to Commencement at Waterville. Now the head master at New
U||   Coventry is a real good fellow, who knows a Sanskrit root when he sees
U||   it, and often cracks etymologies with me—so that, in strictness, I
U||   ought to go to their exhibitions. But think, reader, of sitting through
U||   three long July days in that Academy chapel, following the program from
U||   Tuesday Morning. English Composition. Sunshine. Miss Jones,
U||   round to
U||   Trio on Three Pianos. Duel from opera of Midshipman Easy. Marryatt.
U||   coming in at nine, Thursday evening! Think of this, reader, for men who
U||   know the world is trying to go backward, and who would give their lives
U||   if they could help it on! Well! The double had succeeded so well at the
U||   Board, that I sent him to the Academy. (Shade of Plato, pardon!) He
U||   arrived early on Tuesday, when, indeed, few but mothers and clergymen
U||   are generally expected, and returned in the evening to us, covered with
U||   honors. He had dined at the right hand of the chairman, and he spoke in
U||   high terms of the repast. The chairman had expressed his interest in
U||   the French conversation. “I am very glad you liked it,” said Dennis;
U||   and the poor chairman, abashed, supposed the accent had been wrong. At
U||   the end of the day, the gentlemen present had been called upon for
U||   speeches—the Rev. Frederic Ingham first, as it happened; upon which
U||   Dennis had risen, and had said, “There has been so much said, and, on
U||   the whole, so well said, that I will not occupy the time.” The girls
U||   were delighted, because Dr. Dabney, the year before, had given them at
U||   this occasion a scolding on impropriety of behavior at lyceum lectures.
U||   They all declared Mr. Ingham was a love—and so handsome! (Dennis is
U||   good-looking.) Three of them, with arms behind the others’ waists,
U||   followed him up to the wagon he rode home in; and a little girl with a
U||   blue sash had been sent to give him a rosebud. After this debut in
U||   speaking, he went to the exhibition for two days more, to the mutual
U||   satisfaction of all concerned. Indeed, Polly reported that he had
U||   pronounced the trustees’ dinners of a higher grade than those of the
U||   parsonage. When the next term began, I found six of the Academy girls
U||   had obtained permission to come across the river and attend our church.
U||   But this arrangement did not long continue.
U||   After this he went to several Commencements for me, and ate the dinners
U||   provided; he sat through three of our Quarterly Conventions for
U||   me—always voting judiciously, by the simple rule mentioned above, of
U||   siding with the minority. And I, meanwhile, who had before been losing
U||   caste among my friends, as holding myself aloof from the associations
U||   of the body, began to rise in everybody’s favor. “Ingham’s a good
U||   fellow—always on hand”; “never talks much—but does the right thing at
U||   the right time”; “is not as unpunctual as he used to be—he comes early,
U||   and sits through to the end.” “He has got over his old talkative habit,
U||   too. I spoke to a friend of his about it once; and I think Ingham took
U||   it kindly,” etc., etc.
U||   This voting power of Dennis was particularly valuable at the quarterly
U||   meetings of the Proprietors of the Naguadavick Ferry. My wife inherited
U||   from her father some shares in that enterprise, which is not yet fully
U||   developed, though it doubtless will become a very valuable property.
U||   The law of Maine then forbade stockholders to appear by proxy at such
U||   meetings. Polly disliked to go, not being, in fact, a “hens’-rights
U||   hen,” and transferred her stock to me. I, after going once, disliked it
U||   more than she. But Dennis went to the next meeting, and liked it very
U||   much. He said the armchairs were good, the collation good, and the free
U||   rides to stockholders pleasant. He was a little frightened when they
U||   first took him upon one of the ferry-boats, but after two or three
U||   quarterly meetings he became quite brave.
U||   Thus far I never had any difficulty with him. Indeed, being of that
U||   type which is called shiftless, he was only too happy to be told daily
U||   what to do, and to be charged not to be forthputting or in any way
U||   original in his discharge of that duty. He learned, however, to
U||   discriminate between the lines of his life, and very much preferred
U||   these stockholders’ meetings and trustees’ dinners and commencement
U||   collations to another set of occasions, from which he used to beg off
U||   most piteously. Our excellent brother, Dr. Fillmore, had taken a notion
U||   at this time that our Sandemanian churches needed more expression of
U||   mutual sympathy. He insisted upon it that we were remiss. He said,
U||   that, if the Bishop came to preach at Naguadavick, all the Episcopal
U||   clergy of the neighborhood were present; if Dr. Pond came, all the
