U||   more. Now this really meant that I had not been to hear one of Dr.
U||   Fillmore’s lectures on the Ethnology of Religion. He forgot that he did
U||   not hear one of my course on the Sandemanianism of Anselm. But I felt
U||   badly when he said it; and afterwards I always made Dennis go to hear
U||   all the brethren preach, when I was not preaching myself. This was what
U||   he took exceptions to—the only thing, as I said, which he ever did
U||   except to. Now came the advantage of his long morning-nap, and of the
U||   green tea with which Polly supplied the kitchen. But he would plead, so
U||   humbly, to be let off, only from one or two! I never excepted him,
U||   however. I knew the lectures were of value, and I thought it best he
U||   should be able to keep the connection.
U||   Polly is more rash than I am, as the reader has observed in the outset
U||   of this memoir. She risked Dennis one night under the eyes of her own
U||   sex. Governor Gorges had always been very kind to us; and when he gave
