U||   the hall, he was scarcely understood by any but Polly, as he said,
U||   “There has been so much said, and, on the whole, so well said, that I
U||   will not occupy the time.”
U||   His great resource the rest of the evening was standing in the library,
U||   carrying on animated conversations with one and another in much the
U||   same way. Polly had initiated him in the mysteries of a discovery of
U||   mine, that it is not necessary to finish your sentence in a crowd, but
U||   by a sort of mumble, omitting sibilants and dentals. This, indeed, if
U||   your words fail you, answers even in public extempore speech—but better
U||   where other talking is going on. Thus: “We missed you at the Natural
U||   History Society, Ingham.” Ingham replies: “I am very gligloglum, that
U||   is, that you were m-m-m-m-m.” By gradually dropping the voice, the
U||   interlocutor is compelled to supply the answer. “Mrs. Ingham, I hope
U||   your friend Augusta is better.” Augusta has not been ill. Polly cannot
U||   think of explaining, however, and answers: “Thank you, ma’am; she is
U||   very rearason wewahwewob,” in lower and lower tones. And Mrs.
U||   Throckmorton, who forgot the subject of which she spoke, as soon as she
U||   asked the question, is quite satisfied. Dennis could see into the
U||   card-room, and came to Polly to ask if he might not go and play
U||   all-fours. But, of course, she sternly refused. At midnight they came
U||   home delightedly: Polly, as I said, wild to tell me the story of
U||   victory; only both the pretty Walton girls said: “Cousin Frederic, you
U||   did not come near me all the evening.”
U||   We always called him Dennis at home, for convenience, though his real
U||   name was Frederic Ingham, as I have explained. When the election day
U||   came round, however, I found that by some accident there was only one
U||   Frederic Ingham’s name on the voting-list; and, as I was quite busy
U||   that day in writing some foreign letters to Halle, I thought I would
U||   forego my privilege of suffrage, and stay quietly at home, telling
U||   Dennis that he might use the record on the voting-list and vote. I gave
U||   him a ticket, which I told him he might use, if he liked to. That was
U||   that very sharp election in Maine which the readers of The Atlantic so
U||   well remember, and it had been intimated in public that the ministers
U||   would do well not to appear at the polls. Of course, after that, we had
U||   to appear by self or proxy. Still, Naguadavick was not then a city, and
U||   this standing in a double queue at townmeeting several hours to vote
U||   was a bore of the first water; and so, when I found that there was but
U||   one Frederic Ingham on the list, and that one of us must give up, I
U||   stayed at home and finished the letters (which, indeed, procured for
U||   Fothergill his coveted appointment of Professor of Astronomy at
U||   Leavenworth), and I gave Dennis, as we called him, the chance.
U||   Something in the matter gave a good deal of popularity to the Frederic
U||   Ingham name; and at the adjourned election, next week, Frederic Ingham
U||   was chosen to the legislature. Whether this was I or Dennis, I never
U||   really knew. My friends seemed to think it was I; but I felt, that, as
U||   Dennis had done the popular thing, he was entitled to the honor; so I
U||   sent him to Augusta when the time came, and he took the oaths. And a
U||   very valuable member he made. They appointed him on the Committee on
U||   Parishes; but I wrote a letter for him, resigning, on the ground that
U||   he took an interest in our claim to the stumpage in the minister’s
U||   sixteenths of Gore A, next No. 7, in the 10th Range. He never made any
U||   speeches, and always voted with the minority, which was what he was
U||   sent to do. He made me and himself a great many good friends, some of
U||   whom I did not afterwards recognize as quickly as Dennis did my
U||   parishioners. On one or two occasions, when there was wood to saw at
U||   home, I kept him at home; but I took those occasions to go to Augusta
U||   myself. Finding myself often in his vacant seat at these times, I
U||   watched the proceedings with a good deal of care; and once was so much
U||   excited that I delivered my somewhat celebrated speech on the Central
U||   School District question, a speech of which the State of Maine printed
U||   some extra copies. I believe there is no formal rule permitting
U||   strangers to speak; but no one objected.
U||   Dennis himself, as I said, never spoke at all. But our experience this
U||   session led me to think, that if, by some such “general understanding”
U||   as the reports speak of in legislation daily, every member of Congress
U||   might leave a double to sit through those deadly sessions and answer to
U||   roll-calls and do the legitimate party-voting, which appears
U||   stereotyped in the regular list of Ashe, Bocock, Black, etc., we should
U||   gain decidedly in working power. As things stand, the saddest state
U||   prison I ever visit is that Representatives’ Chamber in Washington. If
U||   a man leaves for an hour, twenty “correspondents” may be howling,
U||   “Where was Mr. Prendergast when the Oregon bill passed?” And if poor
U||   Prendergast stays there! Certainly, the worst use you can make of a man
U||   is to put him in prison!
U||   I know, indeed, that public men of the highest rank have resorted to
U||   this expedient long ago. Dumas’s novel of The Iron Mask turns on the
U||   brutal imprisonment of Louis the Fourteenth’s double. There seems
U||   little doubt, in our own history, that it was the real General Pierce
U||   who shed tears when the delegate from Lawrence explained to him the
U||   sufferings of the people there—and only General Pierce’s double who had
U||   given the orders for the assault on that town, which was invaded the
U||   next day. My charming friend, George Withers, has, I am almost sure, a
U||   double, who preaches his afternoon sermons for him. This is the reason
U||   that the theology often varies so from that of the forenoon. But that
U||   double is almost as charming as the original. Some of the most
U||   well-defined men, who stand out most prominently on the background of
U||   history, are in this way stereoscopic men; who owe their distinct
U||   relief to the slight differences between the doubles. All this I know.
U||   My present suggestion is simply the great extension of the system, so
U||   that all public machine-work may be done by it.
U||   But I see I loiter on my story, which is rushing to the plunge. Let me
U||   stop an instant more, however, to recall, were it only to myself, that
U||   charming year while all was yet well. After the double had become a
U||   matter of course, for nearly twelve months before he undid me, what a
U||   year it was! Full of active life, full of happy love, of the hardest
U||   work, of the sweetest sleep, and the fulfilment of so many of the fresh
U||   aspirations and dreams of boyhood! Dennis went to every
U||   school-committee meeting, and sat through all those late wranglings
U||   which used to keep me up till midnight and awake till morning. He
U||   attended all the lectures to which foreign exiles sent me tickets
U||   begging me to come for the love of Heaven and of Bohemia. He accepted
U||   and used all the tickets for charity concerts which were sent to me. He
U||   appeared everywhere where it was specially desirable that “our
U||   denomination,” or “our party,” or “our class,” or “our family,” or “our
U||   street,” or “our town,” or “our country,” or “our state,” should be
U||   fully represented. And I fell back to that charming life which in
U||   boyhood one dreams of, when he supposes he shall do his own duty and
U||   make his own sacrifices, without being tied up with those of other
U||   people. My rusty Sanskrit, Arabic, Hebrew, Greek, Latin, French,
U||   Italian, Spanish, German and English began to take polish. Heavens! how
U||   little I had done with them while I attended to my public duties! My
U||   calls on my parishioners became the friendly, frequent, homelike
U||   sociabilities they were meant to be, instead of the hard work of a man
U||   goaded to desperation by the sight of his lists of arrears. And
U||   preaching! what a luxury preaching was when I had on Sunday the whole
U||   result of an individual, personal week, from which to speak to a people
U||   whom all that week I had been meeting as hand-to-hand friend! I never
U||   tired on Sunday, and was in condition to leave the sermon at home, if I
U||   chose, and preach it extempore, as all men should do always. Indeed, I
U||   wonder, when I think that a sensible people like ours—really more
U||   attached to their clergy than they were in the lost days, when the
U||   Mathers and Nortons were noblemen—should choose to neutralize so much
U||   of their ministers’ lives, and destroy so much of their early training,
U||   by this undefined passion for seeing them in public. It springs from
U||   our balancing of sects. If a spirited Episcopalian takes an interest in
U||   the almshouse, and is put on the Poor Board, every other denomination
U||   must have a minister there, lest the poorhouse be changed into St.
U||   Paul’s Cathedral. If a Sandemanian is chosen president of the Young
U||   Men’s Library, there must be a Methodist vice-president and a Baptist
U||   secretary. And if a Universalist Sunday-School Convention collects five
U||   hundred delegates, the next Congregationalist Sabbath-School Conference
U||   must be as large, “lest ‘they’—whoever they may be—should think
U||   ‘we’—whoever we may be—are going down.”
U||   Freed from these necessities, that happy year, I began to know my wife
U||   by sight. We saw each other sometimes. In those long mornings, when
U||   Dennis was in the study explaining to map-peddlers that I had eleven
U||   maps of Jerusalem already, and to school-book agents that I would see
U||   them hanged before I would be bribed to introduce their textbooks into
U||   the schools—she and I were at work together, as in those old dreamy
U||   days—and in these of our log-cabin again. But all this could not
U||   last—and at length poor Dennis, my double, overtasked in turn, undid
U||   me.
U||   It was thus it happened. There is an excellent fellow—once a minister—I
U||   will call him Isaacs—who deserves well of the world till he dies, and
U||   after—because he once, in a real exigency, did the right thing, in the
U||   right way, at the right time, as no other man could do it. In the
U||   world’s great football match, the ball by chance found him loitering on
U||   the outside of the field; he closed with it, “camped” it, charged, it
U||   home—yes, right through the other side—not disturbed, not frightened by
U||   his own success—and breathless found himself a great man—as the Great
U||   Delta rang applause. But he did not find himself a rich man; and the
U||   football has never come in his way again. From that moment to this
U||   moment he has been of no use, that one can see, at all. Still, for that
U||   great act we speak of Isaacs gratefully and remember him kindly; and he
U||   forges on, hoping to meet the football somewhere again. In that vague
U||   hope, he had arranged a “movement” for a general organization of the
U||   human family into Debating Clubs, County Societies, State Unions, etc.,
U||   etc., with a view of inducing all children to take hold of the handles
U||   of their knives and forks, instead of the metal. Children have bad
U||   habits in that way. The movement, of course, was absurd; but we all did
U||   our best to forward, not it, but him. It came time for the annual
U||   county-meeting on this subject to be held at Naguadavick. Isaacs came
U||   round, good fellow! to arrange for it—got the townhall, got the
U||   Governor to preside (the saint!—he ought to have triplet doubles
U||   provided him by law), and then came to get me to speak. “No,” I said,
U||   “I would not speak, if ten Governors presided. I do not believe in the
U||   enterprise. If I spoke, it should be to say children should take hold
U||   of the prongs of the forks and the blades of the knives. I would
U||   subscribe ten dollars, but I would not speak a mill.” So poor Isaacs
U||   went his way, sadly, to coax Auchmuty to speak, and Delafield. I went
U||   out. Not long after, he came back, and told Polly that they had
U||   promised to speak—the Governor would speak—and he himself would close
U||   with the quarterly report, and some interesting anecdotes regarding.
U||   Miss Biffin’s way of handling her knife and Mr. Nellis’s way of footing
U||   his fork. “Now if Mr. Ingham will only come and sit on the platform, he
U||   need not say one word; but it will show well in the paper—it will show
U||   that the Sandemanians take as much interest in the movement as the
U||   Armenians or the Mesopotamians, and will be a great favor to me.”
U||   Polly, good soul! was tempted, and she promised. She knew Mrs. Isaacs
U||   was starving, and the babies—she knew Dennis was at home—and she
U||   promised! Night came, and I returned. I heard her story. I was sorry. I
U||   doubted. But Polly had promised to beg me, and I dared all! I told
U||   Dennis to hold his peace, under all circumstances, and sent him down.
U||   It was not half an hour more before he returned, wild with
U||   excitement—in a perfect Irish fury—which it was long before I
U||   understood. But I knew at once that he had undone me!
U||   What happened was this: The audience got together, attracted by
U||   Governor Gorges’s name. There were a thousand people. Poor Gorges was
U||   late from Augusta. They became impatient. He came in direct from the
U||   train at last, really ignorant of the object of the meeting. He opened
U||   it in the fewest possible words, and said other gentlemen were present
U||   who would entertain them better than he. The audience were
U||   disappointed, but waited. The Governor, prompted by Isaacs, said, “The
U||   Honorable Mr. Delafield will address you.” Delafield had forgotten the
U||   knives and forks, and was playing the Ruy Lopez opening at the chess
U||   club. “The Rev. Mr. Auchmuty will address you.” Auchmuty had promised
U||   to speak late, and was at the school committee. “I see Dr. Stearns in
U||   the hall; perhaps he will say a word.” Dr. Stearns said he had come to
U||   listen and not to speak. The Governor and Isaacs whispered. The
U||   Governor looked at Dennis, who was resplendent on the platform; but
U||   Isaacs, to give him his due, shook his head. But the look was enough. A
U||   miserable lad, ill-bred, who had once been in Boston, thought it would
U||   sound well to call for me, and peeped out, “Ingham!” A few more
U||   wretches cried, “Ingham! Ingham!” Still Isaacs was firm; but the
U||   Governor, anxious, indeed, to prevent a row, knew I would say
U||   something, and said, “Our friend Mr. Ingham is always prepared—and
U||   though we had not relied upon him, he will say a word, perhaps.”
U||   Applause followed, which turned Dennis’s head. He rose, flattered, and
U||   tried No. 3: “There has been so much said, and, on the whole, so well
U||   said, that I will not longer occupy the time!” and sat down, looking
U||   for his hat; for things seemed squally. But the people cried, “Go on!
U||   go on!” and some applauded. Dennis, still confused, but flattered by
U||   the applause, to which neither he nor I are used, rose again, and this
U||   time tried No. 2: “I am very glad you liked it!” in a sonorous, clear
U||   delivery. My best friends stared. All the people who did not know me
U||   personally yelled with delight at the aspect of the evening; the
U||   Governor was beside himself, and poor Isaacs thought he was undone!
U||   Alas, it was I! A boy in the gallery cried in a loud tone, “It’s all an
U||   infernal humbug,” just as Dennis, waving his hand, commanded silence,
U||   and tried No. 4: “I agree, in general, with my friend the other side of
U||   the room.” The poor Governor doubted his senses, and crossed to stop
U||   him—not in time, however. The same gallery-boy shouted, “How’s your
U||   mother?”—and Dennis, now completely lost, tried, as his last shot, No.
U||   1, vainly: “Very well, thank you; and you?”
U||   I think I must have been undone already. But Dennis, like another
U||   Lockhard chose “to make sicker.” The audience rose in a whirl of
U||   amazement, rage, and sorrow. Some other impertinence, aimed at Dennis,
U||   broke all restraint, and, in pure Irish, he delivered himself of an
U||   address to the gallery, inviting any person who wished to fight to come
U||   down and do so—stating, that they were all dogs and cowards—that he
U||   would take any five of them single-handed, “Shure, I have said all his
U||   Riverence and the Misthress bade me say,” cried he, in defiance; and,
U||   seizing the Governor’s cane from his hand, brandished it, quarter-staff
U||   fashion, above his head. He was, indeed, got from the hall only with
U||   the greatest difficulty by the Governor, the City Marshal, who had been
U||   called in, and the Superintendent of my Sunday School.
U||   The universal impression, of course, was, that the Rev. Frederic Ingham
U||   had lost all command of himself in some of those haunts of intoxication
U||   which for fifteen years I have been laboring to destroy. Till this
U||   moment, indeed, that is the impression in Naguadavick. This number of
U||   The Atlantic will relieve from it a hundred friends of mine who have
U||   been sadly wounded by that notion now for years—but I shall not be
U||   likely ever to show my head there again.
U||   No! My double has undone me.
U||   We left town at seven the next morning. I came to No. 9, in the Third
U||   Range, and settled on the Minister’s Lot, In the new towns in Maine,
U||   the first settled minister has a gift of a hundred acres of land. I am
U||   the first settled minister in No. 9. My wife and little Paulina are my
U||   parish. We raise corn enough to live on in summer. We kill bear’s meat
U||   enough to carbonize it in winter. I work on steadily on my Traces of
U||   Sandemanianism in the Sixth and Seventh Centuries, which I hope to
U||   persuade Phillips, Sampson & Co. to publish next year. We are very
U||   happy, but the world thinks we are undone.
