U||A VISIT TO THE ASYLUM FOR AGED AND DECAYED PUNSTERS[53][17]
U||   By Oliver Wendell Holmes (1809–1894)
U||   Having just returned from a visit to this admirable Institution in
U||   company with a friend who is one of the Directors, we propose giving a
U||   short account of what we saw and heard. The great success of the Asylum
U||   for Idiots and Feeble-minded Youth, several of the scholars from which
U||   have reached considerable distinction, one of them being connected with
U||   a leading Daily Paper in this city, and others having served in the
U||   State and National Legislatures, was the motive which led to the
U||   foundation of this excellent charity. Our late distinguished townsman,
U||   Noah Dow, Esquire, as is well known, bequeathed a large portion of his
U||   fortune to this establishment— “being thereto moved,” as his will
U||   expressed it, “by the desire of N. Dowing some public Institution for
U||   the benefit of Mankind.” Being consulted as to the Rules of the
U||   Institution and the selection of a Superintendent, he replied, that
U||   “all Boards must construct their own Platforms of operation. Let them
U||   select anyhow and he should be pleased.” N.E. Howe, Esq., was chosen in
U||   compliance with this delicate suggestion.
U||   The Charter provides for the support of “One hundred aged and decayed
U||   Gentlemen-Punsters.” On inquiry if there way no provision for females,
U||   my friend called my attention to this remarkable psychological fact,
U||   namely:
U||   There is no such thing as a female Punster.
U||   This remark struck me forcibly, and on reflection I found that I never
U||   knew nor heard of one, though I have once or twice heard a woman make a
U||   single detached pun, as I have known a hen to crow.
U||   On arriving at the south gate of the Asylum grounds, I was about to
U||   ring, but my friend held my arm and begged me to rap with my stick,
U||   which I did. An old man with a very comical face presently opened the
U||   gate and put out his head.
U||   “So you prefer Cane to A bell, do you?” he said—and began chuckling and
U||   coughing at a great rate.
U||   My friend winked at me.
U||   “You’re here still, Old Joe, I see,” he said to the old man.
U||   “Yes, yes—and it’s very odd, considering how often I’ve bolted,
U||   nights.”
U||   He then threw open the double gates for us to ride through.
U||   “Now,” said the old man, as he pulled the gates after us, “you’ve had a
U||   long journey.”
U||   “Why, how is that, Old Joe?” said my friend.
U||   “Don’t you see?” he answered; “there’s the East hinges on the one side
U||   of the gate, and there’s the West hinges on t’other side—haw! haw!
U||   haw!”
U||   We had no sooner got into the yard than a feeble little gentleman, with
U||   a remarkably bright eye, came up to us, looking very serious, as if
U||   something had happened.
U||   “The town has entered a complaint against the Asylum as a gambling
U||   establishment,” he said to my friend, the Director.
U||   “What do you mean?” said my friend.
U||   “Why, they complain that there’s a lot o’ rye on the premises,” he
U||   answered, pointing to a field of that grain—and hobbled away, his
U||   shoulders shaking with laughter, as he went.
U||   On entering the main building, we saw the Rules and Regulations for the
U||   Asylum conspicuously posted up. I made a few extracts which may be
U||   interesting:
U||   Sect. I. Of Verbal Exercises.
U||   5. Each Inmate shall be permitted to make Puns freely from eight in the
U||   morning until ten at night, except during Service in the Chapel and
U||   Grace before Meals.
U||   6. At ten o’clock the gas will be turned off, and no further Puns,
U||   Conundrums, or other play on words will be allowed to be uttered, or to
U||   be uttered aloud.
U||   9. Inmates who have lost their faculties and cannot any longer make
U||   Puns shall be permitted to repeat such as may be selected for them by
U||   the Chaplain out of the work of Mr. Joseph Miller.
U||   10. Violent and unmanageable Punsters, who interrupt others when
U||   engaged in conversation, with Puns or attempts at the same, shall be
U||   deprived of their Joseph Millers, and, if necessary, placed in solitary
U||   confinement.
U||   Sect. III. Of Deportment at Meals.
U||   4. No Inmate shall make any Pun, or attempt at the same, until the
U||   Blessing has been asked and the company are decently seated.
U||   7. Certain Puns having been placed on the Index Expurgatorius of the
U||   Institution, no Inmate shall be allowed to utter them, on pain of being
U||   debarred the perusal of Punch and Vanity Fair, and, if repeated,
U||   deprived of his Joseph Miller.
U||   Among these are the following:
U||   Allusions to Attic salt, when asked to pass the salt-cellar.
U||   Remarks on the Inmates being mustered, etc., etc.
U||   Associating baked beans with the bene-factors of the Institution.
U||   Saying that beef-eating is befitting, etc., etc.
U||   The following are also prohibited, excepting to such Inmates as may
U||   have lost their faculties and cannot any longer make Puns of their own:
U||   “——your own hair or a wig”; “it will be long enough,” etc., etc.;
U||   “little of its age,” etc., etc.; also, playing upon the following
U||   words: hospital; mayor; pun; pitied; bread; sauce, etc., etc., etc. See
U||   INDEX EXPURGATORIUS, printed for use of Inmates.
U||   The subjoined Conundrum is not allowed: Why is Hasty Pudding like the
U||   Prince? Because it comes attended by its sweet; nor this variation to
U||   it, to wit: Because the ’lasses runs after it.
U||   The Superintendent, who went round with us, had been a noted punster in
U||   his time, and well known in the business world, but lost his customers
U||   by making too free with their names—as in the famous story he set
U||   afloat in ’29 of four Jerries attaching to the names of a noted Judge,
U||   an eminent Lawyer, the Secretary of the Board of Foreign Missions, and
U||   the well-known Landlord at Springfield. One of the four Jerries, he
U||   added, was of gigantic magnitude. The play on words was brought out by
U||   an accidental remark of Solomons, the well-known Banker. “Capital
U||   punishment!” the Jew was overheard saying, with reference to the guilty
U||   parties. He was understood, as saying, A capital pun is meant, which
U||   led to an investigation and the relief of the greatly excited public
U||   mind.
U||   The Superintendent showed some of his old tendencies, as he went round
U||   with us.
U||   “Do you know”—he broke out all at once—“why they don’t take steppes in
U||   Tartary for establishing Insane Hospitals?”
U||   We both confessed ignorance.
U||   “Because there are nomad people to be found there,” he said, with a
U||   dignified smile.
U||   He proceeded to introduce us to different Inmates. The first was a
U||   middle-aged, scholarly man, who was seated at a table with a Webster’s
U||   Dictionary and a sheet of paper before him.
U||   “Well, what luck to-day, Mr. Mowzer?” said the Superintendent.
U||   “Three or four only,” said Mr. Mowzer. “Will you hear ’em now—now I’m
U||   here?”
U||   We all nodded.
U||   “Don’t you see Webster ers in the words center and theater?
U||   “If he spells leather lether, and feather fether, isn’t there danger
U||   that he’ll give us a bad spell of weather?
U||   “Besides, Webster is a resurrectionist; he does not allow u to rest
U||   quietly in the mould.
U||   “And again, because Mr. Worcester inserts an illustration in his text,
U||   is that any reason why Mr. Webster’s publishers should hitch one on in
U||   their appendix? It’s what I call a Connect-a-cut trick.
U||   “Why is his way of spelling like the floor of an oven? Because it is
U||   under bread.”
U||   “Mowzer!” said the Superintendent, “that word is on the Index!”
U||   “I forgot,” said Mr. Mowzer; “please don’t deprive me of Vanity Fair
U||   this one time, sir.”
U||   “These are all, this morning. Good day, gentlemen.” Then to the
U||   Superintendent: “Add you, sir!”
U||   The next Inmate was a semi-idiotic-looking old man. He had a heap of
U||   block-letters before him, and, as we came up, he pointed, without
U||   saying a word, to the arrangements he had made with them on the table.
U||   They were evidently anagrams, and had the merit of transposing the
U||   letters of the words employed without addition or subtraction. Here are
U||   a few of them:
U||   Times.      Smite!
U||   Post.         Stop!
U||   Tribune.       True nib.
