U||   Advertiser. { Res veri dat.
U||                      { Is true. Read!
U||   Allopathy.   All o’ th’ Pay.
U||   Homœopathy.   O, the ——! O! O, my! Pah!
U||   The mention of several New York papers led to two or three questions.
U||   Thus: Whether the Editor of The Tribune was H.G. really? If the
U||   complexion of his politics were not accounted for by his being an eager
U||   person himself? Whether Wendell Fillips were not a reduced copy of John
U||   Knocks? Whether a New York Feuilletoniste is not the same thing as a
U||   Fellow down East?
U||   At this time a plausible-looking, bald-headed man joined us, evidently
U||   waiting to take a part in the conversation.
U||   “Good morning, Mr. Riggles,” said the Superintendent, “Anything fresh
U||   this morning? Any Conundrum?”
U||   “I haven’t looked at the cattle,” he answered, dryly.
U||   “Cattle? Why cattle?”
U||   “Why, to see if there’s any corn under ’em!” he said; and immediately
U||   asked, “Why is Douglas like the earth?”
U||   We tried, but couldn’t guess.
U||   “Because he was flattened out at the polls!” said Mr. Riggles.
U||   “A famous politician, formerly,” said the Superintendent. “His
U||   grandfather was a seize-Hessian-ist in the Revolutionary War. By the
U||   way, I hear the freeze-oil doctrines don’t go down at New Bedford.”
U||   The next Inmate looked as if he might have been a sailor formerly.
U||   “Ask him what his calling was,” said the Superintendent.
U||   “Followed the sea,” he replied to the question put by one of us. “Went
U||   as mate in a fishing-schooner.”
U||   “Why did you give it up?”
U||   “Because I didn’t like working for two mast-ers,” he replied.
U||   Presently we came upon a group of elderly persons, gathered about a
U||   venerable gentleman with flowing locks, who was propounding questions
U||   to a row of Inmates.
U||   “Can any Inmate give me a motto for M. Berger?” he said.
U||   Nobody responded for two or three minutes. At last one old man, whom I
U||   at once recognized as a Graduate of our University (Anno 1800) held up
U||   his hand.
U||   “Rem a cue tetigit.”
U||   “Go to the head of the class, Josselyn,” said the venerable patriarch.
U||   The successful Inmate did as he was told, but in a very rough way,
U||   pushing against two or three of the Class.
U||   “How is this?” said the Patriarch.
U||   “You told me to go up jostlin’,” he replied.
U||   The old gentlemen who had been shoved about enjoyed the pun too much to
U||   be angry.
U||   Presently the Patriarch asked again:
U||   “Why was M. Berger authorized to go to the dances given to the Prince?”
U||   The Class had to give up this, and he answered it himself:
U||   “Because every one of his carroms was a tick-it to the ball.”
U||   “Who collects the money to defray the expenses of the last campaign in
U||   Italy?” asked the Patriarch.
U||   Here again the Class failed.
U||   “The war-cloud’s rolling Dun,” he answered.
U||   “And what is mulled wine made with?”
U||   Three or four voices exclaimed at once:
U||   “Sizzle-y Madeira!”
U||   Here a servant entered, and said, “Luncheon-time.” The old gentlemen,
U||   who have excellent appetites, dispersed at once, one of them politely
U||   asking us if we would not stop and have a bit of bread and a little
U||   mite of cheese.
U||   “There is one thing I have forgotten to show you,” said the
U||   Superintendent, “the cell for the confinement of violent and
U||   unmanageable Punsters.”
U||   We were very curious to see it, particularly with reference to the
U||   alleged absence of every object upon which a play of words could
U||   possibly be made.
U||   The Superintendent led us up some dark stairs to a corridor, then along
U||   a narrow passage, then down a broad flight of steps into another
U||   passageway, and opened a large door which looked out on the main
U||   entrance.
U||   “We have not seen the cell for the confinement of ‘violent and
U||   unmanageable’ Punsters,” we both exclaimed.
U||   “This is the sell!” he exclaimed, pointing to the outside prospect.
U||   My friend, the Director, looked me in the face so good-naturedly that I
U||   had to laugh.
U||   “We like to humor the Inmates,” he said. “It has a bad effect, we find,
U||   on their health and spirits to disappoint them of their little
U||   pleasantries. Some of the jests to which we have listened are not new
U||   to me, though I dare say you may not have heard them often before. The
U||   same thing happens in general society, with this additional
U||   disadvantage, that there is no punishment provided for ‘violent and
U||   unmanageable’ Punsters, as in our Institution.”
U||   We made our bow to the Superintendent and walked to the place where our
U||   carriage was waiting for us. On our way, an exceedingly decrepit old
U||   man moved slowly toward us, with a perfectly blank look on his face,
U||   but still appearing as if he wished to speak.
U||   “Look!” said the Director—“that is our Centenarian.”
U||   The ancient man crawled toward us, cocked one eye, with which he seemed
U||   to see a little, up at us, and said:
U||   “Sarvant, young Gentlemen. Why is a—a—a—like a—a—a—? Give it up?
U||   Because it’s a—a—a—a—.”
U||   He smiled a pleasant smile, as if it were all plain enough.
U||   “One hundred and seven last Christmas,” said the Director. “Of late
U||   years he puts his whole Conundrums in blank—but they please him just as
U||   well.”
U||   We took our departure, much gratified and instructed by our visit,
U||   hoping to have some future opportunity of inspecting the Records of
U||   this excellent Charity and making extracts for the benefit of our
U||   Readers.
