U||THE CELEBRATED JUMPING FROG OF CALAVERAS COUNTY[55][18]
U||   By Mark Twain (1835–1910)
U||   In compliance with the request of a friend of mine, who wrote me from
U||   the East, I called on good-natured, garrulous old Simon Wheeler, and
U||   inquired after my friend’s friend, Leonidas W. Smiley, as requested to
U||   do, and I hereunto append the result. I have a lurking suspicion that
U||   Leonidas W. Smiley is a myth; and that my friend never knew such a
U||   personage; and that he only conjectured that if I asked old Wheeler
U||   about him, it would remind him of his infamous Jim Smiley, and he would
U||   go to work and bore me to death with some exasperating reminiscence of
U||   him as long and as tedious as it should be useless to me. If that was
U||   the design, it succeeded.
U||   I found Simon Wheeler dozing comfortably by the bar-room stove of the
U||   dilapidated tavern in the decayed mining camp of Angel’s, and I noticed
U||   that he was fat and bald-headed, and had an expression of winning
U||   gentleness and simplicity upon his tranquil countenance. He roused up,
U||   and gave me good-day. I told him a friend had commissioned me to make
U||   some inquiries about a cherished companion of his boyhood named
U||   Leonidas W. Smiley—Rev. Leonidas W. Smiley, a young minister of the
U||   Gospel, who he had heard was at one time a resident of Angel’s Camp. I
U||   added that if Mr. Wheeler could tell me anything about this Rev.
U||   Leonidas W. Smiley, I would feel under many obligations to him.
U||   Simon Wheeler backed me into a corner and blockaded me there with his
U||   chair, and then sat down and reeled off the monotonous narrative which
U||   follows this paragraph. He never smiled, he never frowned, he never
U||   changed his voice from the gentle-flowing key to which he tuned his
U||   initial sentence, he never betrayed the slightest suspicion of
U||   enthusiasm; but all through the interminable narrative there ran a vein
U||   of impressive earnestness and sincerity, which showed me plainly that,
U||   so far from his imagining that there was anything ridiculous or funny
U||   about his story, he regarded it as a really important matter, and
U||   admired its two heroes as men of transcendent genius in finesse. I let
U||   him go on in his own way, and never interrupted him once.
U||   “Rev. Leonidas W. H’m, Reverend Le—well, there was a feller here once
U||   by the name of Jim Smiley, in the winter of ’49—or may be it was the
U||   spring of ’50—I don’t recollect exactly, somehow, though what makes me
U||   think it was one or the other is because I remember the big flume
U||   warn’t finished when he first came to the camp; but any way, he was the
U||   curiousest man about always betting on anything that turned up you ever
U||   see, if he could get anybody to bet on the other side; and if he
U||   couldn’t he’d change sides. Any way that suited the other man would
U||   suit him—any way just so’s he got a bet, he was satisfied. But still he
U||   was lucky, uncommon lucky; he most always come out winner. He was
U||   always ready and laying for a chance; there couldn’t be no solit’ry
U||   thing mentioned but that feller’d offer to bet on it, and take any side
U||   you please, as I was just telling you. If there was a horse-race, you’d
U||   find him flush or you’d find him busted at the end of it; if there was
U||   a dog-fight, he’d bet on it; if there was a cat-fight, he’d bet on it;
U||   if there was a chicken-fight, he’d bet on it; why, if there was two
U||   birds setting on a fence, he would bet you which one would fly first;
U||   or if there was a camp-meeting, he would be there reg’lar to bet on
U||   Parson Walker, which he judged to be the best exhorter about here, and
U||   he was, too, and a good man. If he even see a straddle-bug start to go
U||   anywheres, he would bet you how long it would take him to get to—to
U||   wherever he was going to, and if you took him up, he would foller that
U||   straddle-bug to Mexico but what he would find out where he was bound
U||   for and how long he was on the road. Lots of the boys here has seen
U||   that Smiley and can tell you about him. Why, it never made no
U||   difference to him—he’d bet on any thing—the dangest feller. Parson
U||   Walker’s wife laid very sick once, for a good while, and it seemed as
U||   if they warn’t going to save her; but one morning he come in, and
U||   Smiley up and asked him how she was, and he said she was considerable
U||   better—thank the Lord for his inf’nit’ mercy—and coming on so smart
U||   that with the blessing of Prov’dence she’d get well yet; and Smiley,
U||   before he thought, says, Well, I’ll risk two-and-a-half she don’t
U||   anyway.’”
U||   Thish-yer Smiley had a mare—the boys called her the fifteen-minute nag,
U||   but that was only in fun, you know, because, of course, she was faster
U||   than that—and he used to win money on that horse, for all she was so
U||   slow and always had the asthma, or the distemper, or the consumption,
U||   or something of that kind. They used to give her two or three hundred
U||   yards start, and then pass her under way; but always at the fag-end of
U||   the race she’d get excited and desperate-like, and come cavorting and
U||   straddling up, and scattering her legs around limber, sometimes in the
U||   air, and sometimes out to one side amongst the fences, and kicking up
U||   m-o-r-e dust and raising m-o-r-e racket with her coughing and sneezing
U||   and blowing her nose—and always fetch up at the stand just about a neck
U||   ahead, as near as you could cipher it down.
U||   And he had a little small bull-pup, that to look at him you’d think he
U||   warn’t worth a cent but to set around and look ornery and lay for a
U||   chance to steal something. But as soon as money was up on him he was a
U||   different dog; his under-jaw’d begin to stick out like the fo’-castle
U||   of a steamboat, and his teeth would uncover and shine like the
U||   furnaces. And a dog might tackle him and bully-rag him, and bite him,
U||   and throw him over his shoulder two or three times, and Andrew
U||   Jackson—which was the name of the pup—Andrew Jackson would never let on
U||   but what he was satisfied, and hadn’t expected nothing else—and the
U||   bets being doubled and doubled on the other side all the time, till the
U||   money was all up; and then all of a sudden he would grab that other dog
U||   jest by the j’int of his hind leg and freeze to it—not chaw, you
U||   understand, but only just grip and hang on till they throwed up the
U||   sponge, if it was a year. Smiley always come out winner on that pup,
U||   till he harnessed a dog once that didn’t have no hind legs, because
U||   they’d been sawed off in a circular saw, and when the thing had gone
U||   along far enough, and the money was all up, and he come to make a
U||   snatch for his pet holt, he see in a minute how he’d been imposed on,
U||   and how the other dog had him in the door, so to speak, and he ’peared
U||   surprised, and then he looked sorter discouraged-like, and didn’t try
U||   no more to win the fight, and so he got shucked out bad. He gave Smiley
U||   a look, as much as to say his heart was broke, and it was his fault,
U||   for putting up a dog that hadn’t no hind legs for him to take holt of,
U||   which was his main dependence in a fight, and then he limped off a
U||   piece and laid down and died. It was a good pup, was that Andrew
U||   Jackson, and would have made a name for hisself if he’d lived, for the
U||   stuff was in him and he had genius—I know it, because he hadn’t no
U||   opportunities to speak of, and it don’t stand to reason that a dog
U||   could make such a fight as he could under them circumstances if he
U||   hadn’t no talent. It always makes me feel sorry when I think of that
U||   last fight of his’n, and the way it turned out.
U||   Well, thish-yer Smiley had rat-tarriers, and chicken cocks, and
U||   tom-cats and all of them kind of things, till you couldn’t rest, and
U||   you couldn’t fetch nothing for him to bet on but he’d match you. He
U||   ketched a frog one day, and took him home, and said he cal’lated to
U||   educate him; and so he never done nothing for three months but set in
U||   his back yard and learn that frog to jump. And you bet you he did learn
U||   him, too. He’d give him a little punch behind, and the next minute
U||   you’d see that frog whirling in the air like a doughnut—see him turn
U||   one summerset, or may be a couple, if he got a good start, and come
U||   down flat-footed and all right, like a cat. He got him up so in the
U||   matter of ketching flies, and kep’ him in practice so constant, that
U||   he’d nail a fly every time as fur as he could see him. Smiley said all
U||   a frog wanted was education, and he could do ’most anything—and I
U||   believe him. Why, I’ve seen him set Dan’l Webster down here on this
U||   floor—Dan’l Webster was the name of the frog—and sing out, “Flies,
U||   Dan’l, flies!” and quicker’n you could wink he’d spring straight up and
U||   snake a fly off’n the counter there, and flop down on the floor ag’in
U||   as solid as a gob of mud, and fall to scratching the side of his head
U||   with his hind foot as indifferent as if he hadn’t no idea he’d been
U||   doin’ any more’n any frog might do. You never see a frog so modest and
U||   straightfor’ard as he was, for all he was so gifted. And when it come
U||   to fair and square jumping on a dead level, he could get over more
U||   ground at one straddle than any animal of his breed you ever see.
U||   Jumping on a dead level was his strong suit, you understand; and when
U||   it come to that, Smiley would ante up money on him as long as he had a
U||   red. Smiley was monstrous proud of his frog, and well he might be, for
U||   fellers that had traveled and been everywheres, all said he laid over
U||   any frog that ever they see.
U||   Well, Smiley kep’ the beast in a little lattice box, and he used to
U||   fetch him downtown sometimes and lay for a bet. One day a feller—a
U||   stranger in the camp, he was—come acrost him with his box, and says:
U||   “What might be that you’ve got in the box?”
U||   And Smiley says, sorter indifferent-like, “It might be a parrot, or it
U||   might be a canary, maybe, but it ain’t—it’s only just a frog.”
U||   And the feller took it, and looked at it careful, and turned it round
U||   this way and that, and says, “H’m—so ’tis. Well, what’s he good for?”
U||   “Well,” Smiley says, easy and careless, “he’s good enough for one
U||   thing, I should judge—he can outjump any frog in Calaveras county.”
U||   The feller took the box again, and took another long, particular look,
U||   and give it back to Smiley, and says, very deliberate, “Well,” he says,
U||   “I don’t see no p’ints about that frog that’s any better’n any other
U||   frog.”
U||   “Maybe you don’t,” Smiley says. “Maybe you understand frogs and maybe
U||   you don’t understand ’em; maybe you’ve had experience, and maybe you
U||   ain’t only a amature, as it were. Anyways, I’ve got my opinion and I’ll
U||   risk forty dollars that he can outjump any frog in Calaveras County.”
U||   And the feller studied a minute, and then says, kinder sad like, “Well,
U||   I’m only a stranger here, and I ain’t got no frog; but if I had a frog,
U||   I’d bet you.”
U||   And then Smiley says, “That’s all right—that’s all right—if you’ll hold
U||   my box a minute, I’ll go and get you a frog.” And so the feller took
U||   the box, and put up his forty dollars along with Smiley’s, and set down
U||   to wait.
U||   So he set there a good while thinking and thinking to hisself, and then
U||   he got the frog out and prized his mouth open and took a teaspoon and
U||   filled him full of quail shot—filled! him pretty near up to his
U||   chin—and set him on the floor. Smiley he went to the swamp and slopped
U||   around in the mud for a long time, and finally he ketched a frog, and
U||   fetched him in, and give him to this feller, and says:
U||   “Now, if you’re ready, set him alongside of Dan’l, with his forepaws
U||   just even with Dan’l’s, and I’ll give the word.” Then he says,
U||   “One—two—three—git!” and him and the feller touched up the frogs from
U||   behind, and the new frog hopped off lively, but Dan’l give a heave, and
U||   hysted up his shoulders—so—like a Frenchman, but it warn’t no use—he
U||   couldn’t budge; he was planted as solid as a church, and he couldn’t no
U||   more stir than if he was anchored out. Smiley was a good deal
U||   surprised, and he was disgusted too, but he didn’t have no idea what
U||   the matter was, of course.
U||   The feller took the money and started away; and when he was going out
U||   at the door, he sorter jerked his thumb over his shoulder—so—at Dan’l,
U||   and says again, very deliberate, “Well,” he says, “I don’t see no
U||   p’ints about that frog that’s any better’n any other frog.”
U||   Smiley he stood scratching his head and looking down at Dan’l a long
U||   time, and at last says, “I do wonder what in the nation that frog
U||   throwed off for—I wonder if there ain’t something the matter with
U||   him—he ’pears to look mighty baggy, somehow.” And he ketched Dan’l up
U||   by the nap of the neck, and hefted him, and says, “Why blame my cats if
U||   he don’t weigh five pounds!” and turned him upside down and he belched
U||   out a double handful of shot. And then he see how it was, and he was
U||   the maddest man—he set the frog down and took out after that feller,
U||   but he never ketched him. And——
U||   (Here Simon Wheeler heard his name called from the front yard, and got
U||   up to see what was wanted.) And turning to me as he moved away, he
U||   said: “Just set where you are, stranger, and rest easy—I ain’t going to
U||   be gone a second.”
U||   But, by your leave, I did not think that a continuation of the history
U||   of the enterprising vagabond Jim Smiley would be likely to afford me
U||   much information concerning the Rev. Leonidas W. Smiley, and so I
U||   started away.
U||   At the door I met the sociable Wheeler returning, and he buttonholed me
U||   and recommenced:
U||   “Well, thish-yer Smiley had a yaller, one-eyed cow that didn’t have no
U||   tail, only jest a short stump like a bannanner, and——”
U||   However, lacking both time and inclination, I did not wait to hear
U||   about the afflicted cow, but took my leave.
