U||ELDER BROWN’S BACKSLIDE[57][19]
U||   By Harry Stillwell Edwards (1855- )
U||  I
U||   Elder Brown told his wife good-by at the farmhouse door as mechanically
U||   as though his proposed trip to Macon, ten miles away, was an everyday
U||   affair, while, as a matter of fact, many years had elapsed since
U||   unaccompanied he set foot in the city. He did not kiss her. Many very
U||   good men never kiss their wives. But small blame attaches to the elder
U||   for his omission on this occasion, since his wife had long ago
U||   discouraged all amorous demonstrations on the part of her liege lord,
U||   and at this particular moment was filling the parting moments with a
U||   rattling list of directions concerning thread, buttons, hooks, needles,
U||   and all the many etceteras of an industrious housewife’s basket. The
U||   elder was laboriously assorting these postscript commissions in his
U||   memory, well knowing that to return with any one of them neglected
U||   would cause trouble in the family circle.
U||   Elder Brown mounted his patient steed that stood sleepily motionless in
U||   the warm sunlight, with his great pointed ears displayed to the right
U||   and left, as though their owner had grown tired of the life burden
U||   their weight inflicted upon him, and was, old soldier fashion, ready to
U||   forego the once rigid alertness of early training for the pleasures of
U||   frequent rest on arms.
U||   “And, elder, don’t you forgit them caliker scraps, or you’ll be wantin’
U||   kiver soon an’ no kiver will be a-comin’.”
U||   Elder Brown did not turn his head, but merely let the whip hand, which
U||   had been checked in its backward motion, fall as he answered
U||   mechanically. The beast he bestrode responded with a rapid whisking of
U||   its tail and a great show of effort, as it ambled off down the sandy
U||   road, the rider’s long legs seeming now and then to touch the ground.
U||   But as the zigzag panels of the rail fence crept behind him, and he
U||   felt the freedom of the morning beginning to act upon his well-trained
U||   blood, the mechanical manner of the old man’s mind gave place to a mild
U||   exuberance. A weight seemed to be lifting from it ounce by ounce as the
U||   fence panels, the weedy corners, the persimmon sprouts and sassafras
U||   bushes crept away behind him, so that by the time a mile lay between
U||   him and the life partner of his joys and sorrows he was in a reasonably
U||   contented frame of mind, and still improving.
U||   It was a queer figure that crept along the road that cheery May
U||   morning. It was tall and gaunt, and had been for thirty years or more.
U||   The long head, bald on top, covered behind with iron-gray hair, and in
U||   front with a short tangled growth that curled and kinked in every
U||   direction, was surmounted by an old-fashioned stove-pipe hat, worn and
U||   stained, but eminently impressive. An old-fashioned Henry Clay cloth
U||   coat, stained and threadbare, divided itself impartially over the
U||   donkey’s back and dangled on his sides. This was all that remained of
U||   the elder’s wedding suit of forty years ago. Only constant care, and
U||   use of late years limited to extra occasions, had preserved it so long.
U||   The trousers had soon parted company with their friends. The
U||   substitutes were red jeans, which, while they did not well match his
U||   court costume, were better able to withstand the old man’s abuse, for
U||   if, in addition to his frequent religious excursions astride his beast,
U||   there ever was a man who was fond of sitting down with his feet higher
U||   than his head, it was this selfsame Elder Brown.
U||   The morning expanded, and the old man expanded with it; for while a
U||   vigorous leader in his church, the elder at home was, it must be
U||   admitted, an uncomplaining slave. To the intense astonishment of the
U||   beast he rode, there came new vigor into the whacks which fell upon his
U||   flanks; and the beast allowed astonishment to surprise him into real
U||   life and decided motion. Somewhere in the elder’s expanding soul a tune
U||   had begun to ring. Possibly he took up the far, faint tune that came
U||   from the straggling gang of negroes away off in the field, as they
U||   slowly chopped amid the threadlike rows of cotton plants which lined
U||   the level ground, for the melody he hummed softly and then sang
U||   strongly, in the quavering, catchy tones of a good old country
U||   churchman, was “I’m glad salvation’s free.”
U||   It was during the singing of this hymn that Elder Brown’s regular
U||   motion-inspiring strokes were for the first time varied. He began to
U||   hold his hickory up at certain pauses in the melody, and beat the
U||   changes upon the sides of his astonished steed. The chorus under this
U||   arrangement was:
U||   I’m glad salvation’s free,
U||   I’m glad salvation’s free,
U||   I’m glad salvation’s free for all,
U||   I’m glad salvation’s free.
U||   Wherever there is an italic, the hickory descended. It fell about as
U||   regularly and after the fashion of the stick beating upon the bass drum
U||   during a funeral march. But the beast, although convinced that
U||   something serious was impending, did not consider a funeral march
U||   appropriate for the occasion. He protested, at first, with vigorous
U||   whiskings of his tail and a rapid shifting of his ears. Finding these
U||   demonstrations unavailing, and convinced that some urgent cause for
U||   hurry had suddenly invaded the elder’s serenity, as it had his own, he
U||   began to cover the ground with frantic leaps that would have surprised
U||   his owner could he have realized what was going on. But Elder Brown’s
U||   eyes were half closed, and he was singing at the top of his voice. Lost
U||   in a trance of divine exaltation, for he felt the effects of the
U||   invigorating motion, bent only on making the air ring with the lines
U||   which he dimly imagined were drawing upon him the eyes of the whole
U||   female congregation, he was supremely unconscious that his beast was
U||   hurrying.
U||   And thus the excursion proceeded, until suddenly a shote, surprised in
U||   his calm search for roots in a fence corner, darted into the road, and
U||   stood for an instant gazing upon the newcomers with that idiotic stare
U||   which only a pig can imitate. The sudden appearance of this
U||   unlooked-for apparition acted strongly upon the donkey. With one
U||   supreme effort he collected himself into a motionless mass of matter,
U||   bracing his front legs wide apart; that is to say, he stopped short.
U||   There he stood, returning the pig’s idiotic stare with an interest
U||   which must have led to the presumption that never before in all his
U||   varied life had he seen such a singular little creature. End over end
U||   went the man of prayer, finally bringing up full length in the sand,
U||   striking just as he should have shouted “free” for the fourth time in
U||   his glorious chorus.
U||   Fully convinced that his alarm had been well founded, the shote sped
U||   out from under the gigantic missile hurled at him by the donkey, and
U||   scampered down the road, turning first one ear and then the other to
U||   detect any sounds of pursuit. The donkey, also convinced that the
U||   object before which he had halted was supernatural, started back
U||   violently upon seeing it apparently turn to a man. But seeing that it
U||   had turned to nothing but a man, he wandered up into the deserted fence
U||   corner, and began to nibble refreshment from a scrub oak.
U||   For a moment the elder gazed up into the sky, half impressed with the
U||   idea that the camp-meeting platform had given way. But the truth forced
U||   its way to the front in his disordered understanding at last, and with
U||   painful dignity he staggered into an upright position, and regained his
U||   beaver. He was shocked again. Never before in all the long years it had
U||   served him had he seen it in such shape. The truth is, Elder Brown had
U||   never before tried to stand on his head in it. As calmly as possible he
U||   began to straighten it out, caring but little for the dust upon his
U||   garments. The beaver was his special crown of dignity. To lose it was
U||   to be reduced to a level with the common woolhat herd. He did his best,
U||   pulling, pressing, and pushing, but the hat did not look natural when
U||   he had finished. It seemed to have been laid off into counties,
U||   sections, and town lots. Like a well-cut jewel, it had a face for him,
U||   view it from whatever point he chose, a quality which so impressed him
U||   that a lump gathered in his throat, and his eyes winked vigorously.
U||   Elder Brown was not, however, a man for tears. He was a man of action.
U||   The sudden vision which met his wandering gaze, the donkey calmly
U||   chewing scrub buds, with the green juice already oozing from the
U||   corners of his frothy mouth, acted upon him like magic. He was, after
U||   all, only human, and when he got hands upon a piece of brush he
U||   thrashed the poor beast until it seemed as though even its already
U||   half-tanned hide would be eternally ruined. Thoroughly exhausted at
U||   last, he wearily straddled his saddle, and with his chin upon his
U||   breast resumed the early morning tenor of his way.
U||  II
U||   “Good-mornin’, sir.”
U||   Elder Brown leaned over the little pine picket which divided the
U||   bookkeepers’ department of a Macon warehouse from the room in general,
U||   and surveyed the well-dressed back of a gentleman who was busily
U||   figuring at a desk within. The apartment was carpetless, and the dust
U||   of a decade lay deep on the old books, shelves, and the familiar
U||   advertisements of guano and fertilizers which decorated the room. An
U||   old stove, rusty with the nicotine contributed by farmers during the
U||   previous season while waiting by its glowing sides for their cotton to
U||   be sold, stood straight up in a bed of sand, and festoons of cobwebs
U||   clung to the upper sashes of the murky windows. The lower sash of one
U||   window had been raised, and in the yard without, nearly an acre in
U||   extent, lay a few bales of cotton, with jagged holes in their ends,
U||   just as the sampler had left them. Elder Brown had time to notice all
U||   these familiar points, for the figure at the desk kept serenely at its
U||   task, and deigned no reply.
U||   “Good-mornin’, sir,” said Elder Brown again, in his most dignified
U||   tones. “Is Mr. Thomas in?”
U||   “Good-morning, sir,” said the figure. “I’ll wait on you in a minute.”
U||   The minute passed, and four more joined it. Then the desk man turned.
U||   “Well, sir, what can I do for you?”
U||   The elder was not in the best of humor when he arrived, and his state
U||   of mind had not improved. He waited full a minute as he surveyed the
U||   man of business.
U||   “I thought I mout be able to make some arrangements with you to git
U||   some money, but I reckon I was mistaken.” The warehouse man came
U||   nearer.
U||   “This is Mr. Brown, I believe. I did not recognize you at once. You are
U||   not in often to see us.”
U||   “No; my wife usually ’tends to the town bizness, while I run the church
U||   and farm. Got a fall from my donkey this morning,” he said, noticing a
U||   quizzical, interrogating look upon the face before him, “and fell
U||   squar’ on the hat.” He made a pretense of smoothing it. The man of
U||   business had already lost interest.
U||   “How much money will you want, Mr. Brown?”
U||   “Well, about seven hundred dollars,” said the elder, replacing his hat,
U||   and turning a furtive look upon the warehouse man. The other was
U||   tapping with his pencil upon the little shelf lying across the rail.
U||   “I can get you five hundred.”
U||   “But I oughter have seven.”
U||   “Can’t arrange for that amount. Wait till later in the season, and come
U||   again. Money is very tight now. How much cotton will you raise?”
U||   “Well, I count on a hundr’d bales. An’ you can’t git the sev’n hundr’d
U||   dollars?”
U||   “Like to oblige you, but can’t right now; will fix it for you later
U||   on.”
U||   “Well,” said the elder, slowly, “fix up the papers for five, an’ I’ll
U||   make it go as far as possible.”
U||   The papers were drawn. A note was made out for $552.50, for the
U||   interest was at one and a half per cent. for seven months, and a
U||   mortgage on ten mules belonging to the elder was drawn and signed. The
U||   elder then promised to send his cotton to the warehouse to be sold in
U||   the fall, and with a curt “Anything else?” and a “Thankee, that’s all,”
U||   the two parted.
U||   Elder Brown now made an effort to recall the supplemental commissions
U||   shouted to him upon his departure, intending to execute them first, and
U||   then take his written list item by item. His mental resolves had just
U||   reached this point when a new thought made itself known. Passersby were
U||   puzzled to see the old man suddenly snatch his headpiece off and peer
U||   with an intent and awestruck air into its irregular caverns. Some of
U||   them were shocked when he suddenly and vigorously ejaculated:
U||   “Hannah-Maria-Jemimy! goldarn an’ blue blazes!”
U||   He had suddenly remembered having placed his memoranda in that hat, and
U||   as he studied its empty depths his mind pictured the important scrap
U||   fluttering along the sandy scene of his early-morning tumble. It was
U||   this that caused him to graze an oath with less margin that he had
U||   allowed himself in twenty years. What would the old lady say?
U||   Alas! Elder Brown knew too well. What she would not say was what
U||   puzzled him. But as he stood bareheaded in the sunlight a sense of
U||   utter desolation came and dwelt with him. His eye rested upon sleeping
U||   Balaam anchored to a post in the street, and so as he recalled the
U||   treachery that lay at the base of all his affliction, gloom was added
U||   to the desolation.
U||   To turn back and search for the lost paper would have been worse than
U||   useless. Only one course was open to him, and at it went the leader of
U||   his people. He called at the grocery; he invaded the recesses of the
U||   dry-goods establishments; he ransacked the hardware stores; and
U||   wherever he went he made life a burden for the clerks, overhauling
U||   show-cases and pulling down whole shelves of stock. Occasionally an
U||   item of his memoranda would come to light, and thrusting his hand into
U||   his capacious pocket, where lay the proceeds of his check, he would pay
U||   for it upon the spot, and insist upon having it rolled up. To the
U||   suggestion of the slave whom he had in charge for the time being that
U||   the articles be laid aside until he had finished, he would not listen.
U||   “Now you look here, sonny,” he said, in the dry-goods store, “I’m
U||   conducting this revival, an’ I don’t need no help in my line. Just you
U||   tie them stockin’s up an’ lemme have ’em. Then I know I’ve got ’em.” As
U||   each purchase was promptly paid for, and change had to be secured, the
U||   clerk earned his salary for that day at least.
U||   So it was when, near the heat of the day, the good man arrived at the
U||   drugstore, the last and only unvisited division of trade, he made his
U||   appearance equipped with half a hundred packages, which nestled in his
U||   arms and bulged out about the sections of his clothing that boasted of
U||   pockets. As he deposited his deck-load upon the counter, great drops of
U||   perspiration rolled down his face and over his waterlogged collar to
U||   the floor.
U||   There was something exquisitely refreshing in the great glasses of
U||   foaming soda that a spruce young man was drawing from a marble
U||   fountain, above which half a dozen polar bears in an ambitious print
U||   were disporting themselves. There came a break in the run of customers,
U||   and the spruce young man, having swept the foam from the marble,
U||   dexterously lifted a glass from the revolving rack which had rinsed it
U||   with a fierce little stream of water, and asked mechanically, as he
U||   caught the intense look of the perspiring elder, “What syrup, sir?”
U||   Now it had not occurred to the elder to drink soda, but the suggestion,
U||   coming as it did in his exhausted state, was overpowering. He drew near
U||   awkwardly, put on his glasses, and examined the list of syrups with
U||   great care. The young man, being for the moment at leisure, surveyed
U||   critically the gaunt figure, the faded bandanna, the antique clawhammer
U||   coat, and the battered stove-pipe hat, with a gradually relaxing
U||   countenance. He even called the prescription clerk’s attention by a
U||   cough and a quick jerk of the thumb. The prescription clerk smiled
U||   freely, and continued his assaults upon a piece of blue mass.
U||   “I reckon,” said the elder, resting his hands upon his knees and
U||   bending down to the list, “you may gimme sassprilla an’ a little
U||   strawberry. Sassprilla’s good for the blood this time er year, an’
U||   strawberry’s good any time.”
U||   The spruce young man let the syrup stream into the glass as he smiled
U||   affably. Thinking, perhaps, to draw out the odd character, he ventured
U||   upon a jest himself, repeating a pun invented by the man who made the
U||   first soda fountain. With a sweep of his arm he cleared away the swarm
U||   of insects as he remarked, “People who like a fly in theirs are easily
U||   accommodated.”
U||   It was from sheer good-nature only that Elder Brown replied, with his
U||   usual broad, social smile, “Well, a fly now an’ then don’t hurt
U||   nobody.”
U||   Now if there is anybody in the world who prides himself on knowing a
U||   thing or two, it is the spruce young man who presides over a soda
U||   fountain. This particular young gentleman did not even deem a reply
U||   necessary. He vanished an instant, and when he returned a close
U||   observer might have seen that the mixture in the glass he bore had
U||   slightly changed color and increased in quantity. But the elder saw
U||   only the whizzing stream of water dart into its center, and the rosy
U||   foam rise and tremble on the glass’s rim. The next instant he was
U||   holding his breath and sipping the cooling drink.
U||   As Elder Brown paid his small score he was at peace with the world. I
U||   firmly believe that when he had finished his trading, and the little
U||   blue-stringed packages had been stored away, could the poor donkey have
U||   made his appearance at the door, and gazed with his meek, fawnlike eyes
U||   into his master’s, he would have obtained full and free forgiveness.
U||   Elder Brown paused at the door as he was about to leave. A rosy-cheeked
U||   schoolgirl was just lifting a creamy mixture to her lips before the
U||   fountain. It was a pretty picture, and he turned back, resolved to
U||   indulge in one more glass of the delightful beverage before beginning
U||   his long ride homeward.
U||   “Fix it up again, sonny,” he said, renewing his broad, confiding smile,
U||   as the spruce young man poised a glass inquiringly. The living
U||   automaton went through the same motions as before, and again Elder
U||   Brown quaffed the fatal mixture.
U||   What a singular power is habit! Up to this time Elder Brown had been
U||   entirely innocent of transgression, but with the old alcoholic fire in
U||   his veins, twenty years dropped from his shoulders, and a feeling came
U||   over him familiar to every man who has been “in his cups.” As a matter
U||   of fact, the elder would have been a confirmed drunkard twenty years
U||   before had his wife been less strong-minded. She took the reins into
U||   her own hands when she found that his business and strong drink did not
U||   mix well, worked him into the church, sustained his resolutions by
U||   making it difficult and dangerous for him to get to his toddy. She
U||   became the business head of the family, and he the spiritual. Only at
U||   rare intervals did he ever “backslide” during the twenty years of the
U||   new era, and Mrs. Brown herself used to say that the “sugar in his’n
U||   turned to gall before the backslide ended.” People who knew her never
U||   doubted it.
U||   But Elder Brown’s sin during the remainder of the day contained an
U||   element of responsibility. As he moved majestically down toward where
U||   Balaam slept in the sunlight, he felt no fatigue. There was a glow upon
U||   his cheek-bones, and a faint tinge upon his prominent nose. He nodded
U||   familiarly to people as he met them, and saw not the look of amusement
U||   which succeeded astonishment upon the various faces. When he reached
U||   the neighborhood of Balaam it suddenly occurred to him that he might
U||   have forgotten some one of his numerous commissions, and he paused to
U||   think. Then a brilliant idea rose in his mind. He would forestall blame
U||   and disarm anger with kindness—he would purchase Hannah a bonnet.
U||   What woman’s heart ever failed to soften at sight of a new bonnet?
U||   As I have stated, the elder was a man of action. He entered a store
U||   near at hand.
U||   “Good-morning,” said an affable gentleman with a Hebrew countenance,
U||   approaching.
U||   “Good-mornin’, good-mornin’,” said the elder, piling his bundles on the
U||   counter. “I hope you are well?” Elder Brown extended his hand fervidly.
U||   “Quite well, I thank you. What—”
U||   “And the little wife?” said Elder Brown, affectionately retaining the
U||   Jew’s hand.
U||   “Quite well, sir.”
U||   “And the little ones—quite well, I hope, too?”
U||   “Yes, sir; all well, thank you. Something I can do for you?”
U||   The affable merchant was trying to recall his customer’s name.
U||   “Not now, not now, thankee. If you please to let my bundles stay untell
U||   I come back—”
U||   “Can’t I show you something? Hat, coat—”
U||   “Not now. Be back bimeby.”
U||   Was it chance or fate that brought Elder Brown in front of a bar? The
U||   glasses shone bright upon the shelves as the swinging door flapped back
U||   to let out a coatless clerk, who passed him with a rush, chewing upon a
U||   farewell mouthful of brown bread and bologna. Elder Brown beheld for an
U||   instant the familiar scene within. The screws of his resolution had
U||   been loosened. At sight of the glistening bar the whole moral structure
U||   of twenty years came tumbling down. Mechanically he entered the saloon,
U||   and laid a silver quarter upon the bar as he said:
U||   “A little whiskey an’ sugar.” The arms of the bartender worked like a
U||   faker’s in a side show as he set out the glass with its little quota of
U||   “short sweetening” and a cut-glass decanter, and sent a half-tumbler of
U||   water spinning along from the upper end of the bar with a dime in
U||   change.
U||   “Whiskey is higher’n used to be,” said Elder Brown; but the bartender
U||   was taking another order, and did not hear him. Elder Brown stirred
U||   away the sugar, and let a steady stream of red liquid flow into the
U||   glass. He swallowed the drink as unconcernedly as though his morning
U||   tod had never been suspended, and pocketed the change. “But it ain’t
U||   any better than it was,” he concluded, as he passed out. He did not
U||   even seem to realize that he had done anything extraordinary.
U||   There was a millinery store up the street, and thither with uncertain
U||   step he wended his way, feeling a little more elate, and altogether
U||   sociable. A pretty, black-eyed girl, struggling to keep down her mirth,
U||   came forward and faced him behind the counter. Elder Brown lifted his
U||   faded hat with the politeness, if not the grace, of a Castilian, and
U||   made a sweeping bow. Again he was in his element. But he did not speak.
U||   A shower of odds and ends, small packages, thread, needles, and
U||   buttons, released from their prison, rattled down about him.
U||   The girl laughed. She could not help it. And the elder, leaning his
U||   hand on the counter, laughed, too, until several other girls came
U||   half-way to the front. Then they, hiding behind counters and suspended
U||   cloaks, laughed and snickered until they reconvulsed the elder’s
U||   vis-à-vis, who had been making desperate efforts to resume her demure
U||   appearance.
U||   “Let me help you, sir,” she said, coming from behind the counter, upon
U||   seeing Elder Brown beginning to adjust his spectacles for a search. He
U||   waved her back majestically. “No, my dear, no; can’t allow it. You mout
U||   sile them purty fingers. No, ma’am. No gen’l’man’ll ’low er lady to do
U||   such a thing.” The elder was gently forcing the girl back to her place.
U||   “Leave it to me. I’ve picked up bigger things ’n them. Picked myself up
U||   this mornin’. Balaam—you don’t know Balaam; he’s my donkey—he tumbled
U||   me over his head in the sand this mornin’.” And Elder Brown had to
U||   resume an upright position until his paroxysm of laughter had passed.
U||   “You see this old hat?” extending it, half full of packages; “I fell
U||   clear inter it; jes’ as clean inter it as them things thar fell out’n
U||   it.” He laughed again, and so did the girls. “But, my dear, I whaled
U||   half the hide off’n him for it.”
U||   “Oh, sir! how could you? Indeed, sir. I think you did wrong. The poor
U||   brute did not know what he was doing, I dare say, and probably he has
U||   been a faithful friend.” The girl cast her mischievous eyes towards her
U||   companions, who snickered again. The old man was not conscious of the
U||   sarcasm. He only saw reproach. His face straightened, and he regarded
U||   the girl soberly.
U||   “Mebbe you’re right, my dear; mebbe I oughtn’t.”
U||   “I am sure of it,” said the girl. “But now don’t you want to buy a
U||   bonnet or a cloak to carry home to your wife?”
U||   “Well, you’re whistlin’ now, birdie; that’s my intention; set ’em all
U||   out.” Again the elder’s face shone with delight. “An’ I don’t want no
U||   one-hoss bonnet neither.”
U||   “Of course not. Now here is one; pink silk, with delicate pale blue
U||   feathers. Just the thing for the season. We have nothing more elegant
U||   in stock.” Elder Brown held it out, upside down, at arm’s-length.
U||   “Well, now, that’s suthin’ like. Will it soot a sorter redheaded
U||   ’ooman?”
U||   A perfectly sober man would have said the girl’s corsets must have
U||   undergone a terrible strain, but the elder did not notice her dumb
U||   convulsion. She answered, heroically:
U||   “Perfectly, sir. It is an exquisite match.”
U||   “I think you’re whistlin’ again. Nancy’s head’s red, red as a
U||   woodpeck’s. Sorrel’s only half-way to the color of her top-knot, an’ it
U||   do seem like red oughter to soot red. Nancy’s red an’ the hat’s red;
U||   like goes with like, an’ birds of a feather flock together.” The old
U||   man laughed until his cheeks were wet.
U||   The girl, beginning to feel a little uneasy, and seeing a customer
U||   entering, rapidly fixed up the bonnet, took fifteen dollars out of a
U||   twenty-dollar bill, and calmly asked the elder if he wanted anything
U||   else. He thrust his change somewhere into his clothes, and beat a
U||   retreat. It had occurred to him that he was nearly drunk.
U||   Elder Brown’s step began to lose its buoyancy. He found himself utterly
U||   unable to walk straight. There was an uncertain straddle in his gait
U||   that carried him from one side of the walk to the other, and caused
U||   people whom he met to cheerfully yield him plenty of room.
U||   Balaam saw him coming. Poor Balaam. He had made an early start that
U||   day, and for hours he stood in the sun awaiting relief. When he opened
U||   his sleepy eyes and raised his expressive ears to a position of
U||   attention, the old familiar coat and battered hat of the elder were
U||   before him. He lifted up his honest voice and cried aloud for joy.
U||   The effect was electrical for one instant. Elder Brown surveyed the
U||   beast with horror, but again in his understanding there rang out the
U||   trumpet words.
U||   “Drunk, drunk, drunk, drer-unc, -er-unc, -unc, -unc.”
U||   He stooped instinctively for a missile with which to smite his accuser,
U||   but brought up suddenly with a jerk and a handful of sand.
U||   Straightening himself up with a majestic dignity, he extended his right
U||   hand impressively.
U||   “You’re a goldarn liar, Balaam, and, blast your old buttons, you kin
U||   walk home by yourself, for I’m danged if you sh’ll ride me er step.”
U||   Surely Coriolanus never turned his back upon Rome with a grander
U||   dignity than sat upon the old man’s form as he faced about and left the
U||   brute to survey with anxious eyes the new departure of his master.
U||   He saw the elder zigzag along the street, and beheld him about to turn
U||   a friendly corner. Once more he lifted up his mighty voice:
U||   “Drunk, drunk, drunk, drer-unc, drer-unc, -erunc, -unc, -unc.”
U||   Once more the elder turned with lifted hand and shouted back:
U||   “You’re a liar, Balaam, goldarn you! You’re er iffamous liar.” Then he
U||   passed from view.
U||  III
U||   Mrs. Brown stood upon the steps anxiously awaiting the return of her
U||   liege lord. She knew he had with him a large sum of money, or should
U||   have, and she knew also that he was a man without business methods. She
U||   had long since repented of the decision which sent him to town. When
U||   the old battered hat and flour-covered coat loomed up in the gloaming
U||   and confronted her, she stared with terror. The next instant she had
U||   seized him.
U||   “For the Lord sakes, Elder Brown, what ails you? As I live, if the man
U||   ain’t drunk! Elder Brown! Elder Brown! for the life of me can’t I make
U||   you hear? You crazy old hypocrite! you desavin’ old sinner! you
U||   black-hearted wretch! where have you ben?”
U||   The elder made an effort to wave her off.
U||   “Woman,” he said, with grand dignity, “you forgit yus-sef; shu know
U||   ware I’ve ben ’swell’s I do. Ben to town, wife, an’ see yer wat I’ve
U||   brought—the fines’ hat, ole woman, I could git. Look’t the color. Like
U||   goes ’ith like; it’s red an’ you’re red, an’ it’s a dead match. What
U||   yer mean? Hey! hole on! ole woman!—you! Hannah!—you.” She literally
U||   shook him into silence.
U||   “You miserable wretch! you low-down drunken sot! what do you mean by
U||   coming home and insulting your wife?” Hannah ceased shaking him from
U||   pure exhaustion.
U||   “Where is it, I say? where is it?”
U||   By this time she was turning his pockets wrong side out. From one she
U||   got pills, from another change, from another packages.
U||   “The Lord be praised, and this is better luck than I hoped! Oh, elder!
U||   elder! elder! what did you do it for? Why, man, where is Balaam?”
U||   Thought of the beast choked off the threatened hysterics.
U||   “Balaam? Balaam?” said the elder, groggily. “He’s in town. The infernal
U||   ole fool ’sulted me, an’ I lef’ him to walk home.”
U||   His wife surveyed him. Really at that moment she did think his mind was
U||   gone; but the leer upon the old man’s face enraged her beyond
U||   endurance.
U||   “You did, did you? Well, now, I reckon you’ll laugh for some cause, you
U||   will. Back you go, sir—straight back; an’ don’t you come home ’thout
U||   that donkey, or you’ll rue it, sure as my name is Hannah Brown.
U||   Aleck!—you Aleck-k-k!”
U||   A black boy darted round the corner, from behind which, with several
U||   others, he had beheld the brief but stirring scene.
U||   “Put a saddle on er mule. The elder’s gwine back to town. And don’t you
U||   be long about it neither.”
U||   “Yessum.” Aleck’s ivories gleamed in the darkness as he disappeared.
U||   Elder Brown was soberer at that moment than he had been for hours.
U||   “Hannah, you don’t mean it?”
U||   “Yes, sir, I do. Back you go to town as sure as my name is Hannah
U||   Brown.”
U||   The elder was silent. He had never known his wife to relent on any
U||   occasion after she had affirmed her intention, supplemented with “as
U||   sure as my name is Hannah Brown.” It was her way of swearing. No
U||   affidavit would have had half the claim upon her as that simple
U||   enunciation.
U||   So back to town went Elder Brown, not in the order of the early morn,
U||   but silently, moodily, despairingly, surrounded by mental and actual
U||   gloom.
U||   The old man had turned a last appealing glance upon the angry woman, as
U||   he mounted with Aleck’s assistance, and sat in the light that streamed
U||   from out the kitchen window. She met the glance without a waver.
U||   “She means it, as sure as my name is Elder Brown,” he said, thickly.
U||   Then he rode on.
U||  IV
U||   To say that Elder Brown suffered on this long journey back to Macon
U||   would only mildly outline his experience. His early morning’s fall had
U||   begun to make itself felt. He was sore and uncomfortable. Besides, his
U||   stomach was empty, and called for two meals it had missed for the first
U||   time in years.
U||   When, sore and weary, the elder entered the city, the electric lights
U||   shone above it like jewels in a crown. The city slept; that is, the
U||   better portion of it did. Here and there, however, the lower lights
U||   flashed out into the night. Moodily the elder pursued his journey, and
U||   as he rode, far off in the night there rose and quivered a plaintive
U||   cry. Elder Brown smiled wearily: it was Balaam’s appeal, and he
U||   recognized it. The animal he rode also recognized it, and replied,
U||   until the silence of the city was destroyed. The odd clamor and
U||   confusion drew from a saloon near by a group of noisy youngsters, who
U||   had been making a night of it. They surrounded Elder Brown as he began
U||   to transfer himself to the hungry beast to whose motion he was more
U||   accustomed, and in the “hail fellow well met” style of the day began to
U||   bandy jests upon his appearance. Now Elder Brown was not in a jesting
U||   humor. Positively he was in the worst humor possible. The result was
U||   that before many minutes passed the old man was swinging several of the
U||   crowd by their collars, and breaking the peace of the city. A policeman
U||   approached, and but for the good-humored party, upon whom the elder’s
U||   pluck had made a favorable impression, would have run the old man into
U||   the barracks. The crowd, however, drew him laughingly into the saloon
U||   and to the bar. The reaction was too much for his half-rallied senses.
U||   He yielded again. The reviving liquor passed his lips. Gloom vanished.
U||   He became one of the boys.
U||   The company into which Elder Brown had fallen was what is known as
U||   “first-class.” To such nothing is so captivating as an adventure out of
U||   the common run of accidents. The gaunt countryman, with his battered
U||   hat and clawhammer coat, was a prize of an extraordinary nature. They
U||   drew him into a rear room, whose gilded frames and polished tables
U||   betrayed the character and purpose of the place, and plied him with
U||   wine until ten thousand lights danced about him. The fun increased. One
U||   youngster made a political speech from the top of the table; another
U||   impersonated Hamlet; and finally Elder Brown was lifted into a chair,
U||   and sang a camp-meeting song. This was rendered by him with startling
U||   effect. He stood upright, with his hat jauntily knocked to one side,
U||   and his coat tails ornamented with a couple of show-bills, kindly
U||   pinned on by his admirers. In his left hand he waved the stub of a
U||   cigar, and on his back was an admirable representation of Balaam’s
U||   head, executed by some artist with billiard chalk.
U||   As the elder sang his favorite hymn, “I’m glad salvation’s free,” his
U||   stentorian voice awoke the echoes. Most of the company rolled upon the
U||   floor in convulsions of laughter.
U||   The exhibition came to a close by the chair overturning. Again Elder
U||   Brown fell into his beloved hat. He arose and shouted: “Whoa, Balaam!”
U||   Again he seized the nearest weapon, and sought satisfaction. The young
U||   gentleman with political sentiments was knocked under the table, and
U||   Hamlet only escaped injury by beating the infuriated elder into the
U||   street.
U||   What next? Well, I hardly know. How the elder found Balaam is a mystery
U||   yet: not that Balaam was hard to find, but that the old man was in no
U||   condition to find anything. Still he did, and climbing laboriously into
U||   the saddle, he held on stupidly while the hungry beast struck out for
U||   home.
U||  V
U||   Hannah Brown did not sleep that night. Sleep would not come. Hour after
U||   hour passed, and her wrath refused to be quelled. She tried every
U||   conceivable method, but time hung heavily. It was not quite peep of
U||   day, however, when she laid her well-worn family Bible aside. It had
U||   been her mother’s, and amid all the anxieties and tribulations incident
U||   to the life of a woman who had free negroes and a miserable husband to
U||   manage, it had been her mainstay and comfort. She had frequently read
U||   it in anger, page after page, without knowing what was contained in the
U||   lines. But eventually the words became intelligible and took meaning.
U||   She wrested consolation from it by mere force of will.
U||   And so on this occasion when she closed the book the fierce anger was
U||   gone.
U||   She was not a hard woman naturally. Fate had brought her conditions
U||   which covered up the woman heart within her, but though it lay deep, it
U||   was there still. As she sat with folded hands her eyes fell upon—what?
U||   The pink bonnet with the blue plume!
U||   It may appear strange to those who do not understand such natures, but
U||   to me her next action was perfectly natural. She burst into a
U||   convulsive laugh; then, seizing the queer object, bent her face upon it
U||   and sobbed hysterically. When the storm was over, very tenderly she
U||   laid the gift aside, and bareheaded passed out into the night.
U||   For a half-hour she stood at the end of the lane, and then hungry
U||   Balaam and his master hove in sight. Reaching out her hand, she checked
U||   the beast.
U||   “William,” said she, very gently, “where is the mule?”
U||   The elder had been asleep. He woke and gazed upon her blankly.
U||   “What mule, Hannah?”
U||   “The mule you rode to town.”
U||   For one full minute the elder studied her face. Then it burst from his
U||   lips:
U||   “Well, bless me! if I didn’t bring Balaam and forgit the mule!”
U||   The woman laughed till her eyes ran water.
U||   “William,” said she, “you’re drunk.”
U||   “Hannah,” said he, meekly, “I know it. The truth is, Hannah, I—”
U||   “Never mind, now, William,” she said, gently. “You are tired and
U||   hungry. Come into the house, husband.”
U||   Leading Balaam, she disappeared down the lane; and when, a few minutes
U||   later, Hannah Brown and her husband entered through the light that
U||   streamed out of the open door her arms were around him, and her face
U||   upturned to his.
