U||THE HOTEL EXPERIENCE OF MR. PINK FLUKER[59][20]
U||   By Richard Malcolm Johnston (1822–1898)
U||  I
U||   Mr. Peterson Fluker, generally called Pink, for his fondness for as
U||   stylish dressing as he could afford, was one of that sort of men who
U||   habitually seem busy and efficient when they are not. He had the
U||   bustling activity often noticeable in men of his size, and in one way
U||   and another had made up, as he believed, for being so much smaller than
U||   most of his adult acquaintance of the male sex. Prominent among his
U||   achievements on that line was getting married to a woman who, among
U||   other excellent gifts, had that of being twice as big as her husband.
U||   “Fool who?” on the day after his marriage he had asked, with a look at
U||   those who had often said that he was too little to have a wife.
U||   They had a little property to begin with, a couple of hundreds of
U||   acres, and two or three negroes apiece. Yet, except in the natural
U||   increase of the latter, the accretions of worldly estate had been
U||   inconsiderable till now, when their oldest child, Marann, was some
U||   fifteen years old. These accretions had been saved and taken care of by
U||   Mrs. Fluker, who was as staid and silent as he was mobile and voluble.
U||   Mr. Fluker often said that it puzzled him how it was that he made
U||   smaller crops than most of his neighbors, when, if not always
U||   convincing, he could generally put every one of them to silence in
U||   discussions upon agricultural topics. This puzzle had led him to not
U||   unfrequent ruminations in his mind as to whether or not his vocation
U||   might lie in something higher than the mere tilling of the ground.
U||   These ruminations had lately taken a definite direction, and it was
U||   after several conversations which he had held with his friend Matt
U||   Pike.
U||   Mr. Matt Pike was a bachelor of some thirty summers, a foretime clerk
U||   consecutively in each of the two stores of the village, but latterly a
U||   trader on a limited scale in horses, wagons, cows, and similar objects
U||   of commerce, and at all times a politician. His hopes of holding office
U||   had been continually disappointed until Mr. John Sanks became sheriff,
U||   and rewarded with a deputyship some important special service rendered
U||   by him in the late very close canvass. Now was a chance to rise, Mr.
U||   Pike thought. All he wanted, he had often said, was a start. Politics,
U||   I would remark, however, had been regarded by Mr. Pike as a means
U||   rather than an end. It is doubtful if he hoped to become governor of
U||   the state, at least before an advanced period in his career. His main
U||   object now was to get money, and he believed that official position
U||   would promote him in the line of his ambition faster than was possible
U||   to any private station, by leading him into more extensive acquaintance
U||   with mankind, their needs, their desires, and their caprices. A deputy
U||   sheriff, provided that lawyers were not too indulgent in allowing
U||   acknowledgment of service of court processes, in postponing levies and
U||   sales, and in settlement of litigated cases, might pick up three
U||   hundred dollars, a good sum for those times, a fact which Mr. Pike had
U||   known and pondered long.
U||   It happened just about then that the arrears of rent for the village
U||   hotel had so accumulated on Mr. Spouter, the last occupant, that the
U||   owner, an indulgent man, finally had said, what he had been expected
U||   for years and years to say, that he could not wait on Mr. Spouter
U||   forever and eternally. It was at this very nick, so to speak, that Mr.
U||   Pike made to Mr. Fluker the suggestion to quit a business so far
U||   beneath his powers, sell out, or rent out, or tenant out, or do
U||   something else with his farm, march into town, plant himself upon the
U||   ruins of Jacob Spouter, and begin his upward soar.
U||   Now Mr. Fluker had many and many a time acknowledged that he had
U||   ambition; so one night he said to his wife:
U||   “You see how it is here, Nervy. Farmin’ somehow don’t suit my talons. I
U||   need to be flung more ’mong people to fetch out what’s in me. Then
U||   thar’s Marann, which is gittin’ to be nigh on to a growd-up woman; an’
U||   the child need the s’iety which you ’bleeged to acknowledge is sca’ce
U||   about here, six mile from town. Your brer Sam can stay here an’ raise
U||   butter, chickens, eggs, pigs, an’—an’—an’ so forth. Matt Pike say he
U||   jes’ know they’s money in it, an’ special with a housekeeper keerful
U||   an’ equinomical like you.”
U||   It is always curious the extent of influence that some men have upon
U||   wives who are their superiors. Mrs. Fluker, in spite of accidents, had
U||   ever set upon her husband a value that was not recognized outside of
U||   his family. In this respect there seems a surprising compensation in
U||   human life. But this remark I make only in passing. Mrs. Fluker,
U||   admitting in her heart that farming was not her husband’s forte, hoped,
U||   like a true wife, that it might be found in the new field to which he
U||   aspired. Besides, she did not forget that her brother Sam had said to
U||   her several times privately that if his brer Pink wouldn’t have so many
U||   notions and would let him alone in his management, they would all do
U||   better. She reflected for a day or two, and then said:
U||   “Maybe it’s best, Mr. Fluker. I’m willin’ to try it for a year, anyhow.
U||   We can’t lose much by that. As for Matt Pike, I hain’t the confidence
U||   in him you has. Still, he bein’ a boarder and deputy sheriff, he might
U||   accidentally do us some good. I’ll try it for a year providin’ you’ll
U||   fetch me the money as it’s paid in, for you know I know how to manage
U||   that better’n you do, and you know I’ll try to manage it and all the
U||   rest of the business for the best.”
U||   To this provision Mr. Fluker gave consent, qualified by the claim that
U||   he was to retain a small margin for indispensable personal exigencies.
U||   For he contended, perhaps with justice, that no man in the responsible
U||   position he was about to take ought to be expected to go about, or sit
U||   about, or even lounge about, without even a continental red in his
U||   pocket.
U||   The new house—I say new because tongue could not tell the amount of
U||   scouring, scalding, and whitewashing that that excellent housekeeper
U||   had done before a single stick of her furniture went into it—the new
U||   house, I repeat, opened with six eating boarders at ten dollars a month
U||   apiece, and two eating and sleeping at eleven, besides Mr. Pike, who
U||   made a special contract. Transient custom was hoped to hold its own,
U||   and that of the county people under the deputy’s patronage and
U||   influence to be considerably enlarged.
U||   In words and other encouragement Mr. Pike was pronounced. He could
U||   commend honestly, and he did so cordially.
U||   “The thing to do, Pink, is to have your prices reg’lar, and make people
U||   pay up reg’lar. Ten dollars for eatin’, jes’ so; eleb’n for eatin’ an’
U||   sleepin’; half a dollar for dinner, jes’ so; quarter apiece for
U||   breakfast, supper, and bed, is what I call reason’ble bo’d. As for me,
U||   I sca’cely know how to rig’late, because, you know, I’m a’ officer now,
U||   an’ in course I natchel has to be away sometimes an’ on expenses at
U||   ’tother places, an’ it seem like some ’lowance ought by good rights to
U||   be made for that; don’t you think so?”
U||   “Why, matter o’ course, Matt; what you think? I ain’t so powerful good
U||   at figgers. Nervy is. S’posen you speak to her ’bout it.”
U||   “Oh, that’s perfec’ unuseless, Pink. I’m a’ officer o’ the law, Pink,
U||   an’ the law consider women—well, I may say the law, she deal ’ith men,
U||   not women, an’ she expect her officers to understan’ figgers, an’ if I
U||   hadn’t o’ understood figgers Mr. Sanks wouldn’t or darsnt’ to ’p’int me
U||   his dep’ty. Me ’n’ you can fix them terms. Now see here, reg’lar
U||   bo’d—eatin’ bo’d, I mean—is ten dollars, an’ sleepin’ and singuil meals
U||   is ’cordin’ to the figgers you’ve sot for ’em. Ain’t that so? Jes’ so.
U||   Now, Pink, you an’ me’ll keep a runnin’ account, you a-chargin’ for
U||   reg’lar bo’d, an’ I a’lowin’ to myself credics for my absentees,
U||   accordin’ to transion customers an’ singuil mealers an’ sleepers. Is
U||   that fa’r, er is it not fa’r?”
U||   Mr. Fluker turned his head, and after making or thinking he had made a
U||   calculation, answered:
U||   “That’s—that seem fa’r, Matt.”
U||   “Cert’nly ’tis, Pink; I knowed you’d say so, an’ you know I’d never
U||   wish to be nothin’ but fa’r ’ith people I like, like I do you an’ your
U||   wife. Let that be the understandin’, then, betwix’ us. An’ Pink, let
U||   the understandin’ be jes’ betwix’ us, for I’ve saw enough o’ this world
U||   to find out that a man never makes nothin’ by makin’ a blowin’ horn o’
U||   his business. You make the t’others pay up spuntial, monthly. You ’n’
U||   me can settle whensomever it’s convenant, say three months from to-day.
U||   In course I shall talk up for the house whensomever and wharsomever I
U||   go or stay. You know that. An’ as for my bed,” said Mr. Pike finally,
U||   “whensomever I ain’t here by bed-time, you welcome to put any transion
U||   person in it, an’ also an’ likewise, when transion custom is pressin’,
U||   and you cramped for beddin’, I’m willin’ to give it up for the time
U||   bein’; an’ rather’n you should be cramped too bad, I’ll take my chances
U||   somewhars else, even if I has to take a pallet at the head o’ the
U||   sta’r-steps.”
U||   “Nervy,” said Mr. Fluker to his wife afterwards, “Matt Pike’s a
U||   sensibler an’ a friendlier an’ a ’commodatiner feller’n I thought.”
U||   Then, without giving details of the contract, he mentioned merely the
U||   willingness of their boarder to resign his bed on occasions of pressing
U||   emergency.
U||   “He’s talked mighty fine to me and Marann,” answered Mrs. Fluker.
U||   “We’ll see how he holds out. One thing I do not like of his doin’, an’
U||   that’s the talkin’ ’bout Sim Marchman to Marann, an’ makin’ game o’ his
U||   country ways, as he call ’em. Sech as that ain’t right.”
U||   It may be as well to explain just here that Simeon Marchman, the person
U||   just named by Mrs. Fluker, a stout, industrious young farmer, residing
U||   with his parents in the country near by where the Flukers had dwelt
U||   before removing to town, had been eying Marann for a year or two, and
U||   waiting upon her fast-ripening womanhood with intentions that, he
U||   believed to be hidden in his own breast, though he had taken less pains
U||   to conceal them from Marann than from the rest of his acquaintance. Not
U||   that he had ever told her of them in so many words, but—Oh, I need not
U||   stop here in the midst of this narration to explain how such intentions
U||   become known, or at least strongly suspected by girls, even those less
U||   bright than Marann Fluker. Simeon had not cordially indorsed the
U||   movement into town, though, of course, knowing it was none of his
U||   business, he had never so much as hinted opposition. I would not be
U||   surprised, also, if he reflected that there might be some selfishness
U||   in his hostility, or at least that it was heightened by apprehensions
U||   personal to himself.
U||   Considering the want of experience in the new tenants, matters went on
U||   remarkably well. Mrs. Fluker, accustomed to rise from her couch long
U||   before the lark, managed to the satisfaction of all,—regular boarders,
U||   single-meal takers, and transient people. Marann went to the village
U||   school, her mother dressing her, though with prudent economy, as neatly
U||   and almost as tastefully as any of her schoolmates; while, as to study,
U||   deportment, and general progress, there was not a girl in the whole
U||   school to beat her, I don’t care who she was.
U||  II
U||   During a not inconsiderable period Mr. Fluker indulged the honorable
U||   conviction that at last he had found the vein in which his best talents
U||   lay, and he was happy in foresight of the prosperity and felicity which
U||   that discovery promised to himself and his family. His native activity
U||   found many more objects for its exertion than before. He rode out to
U||   the farm, not often, but sometimes, as a matter of duty, and was forced
U||   to acknowledge that Sam was managing better than could have been
U||   expected in the absence of his own continuous guidance. In town he
U||   walked about the hotel, entertained the guests, carved at the meals,
U||   hovered about the stores, the doctors’ offices, the wagon and
U||   blacksmith shops, discussed mercantile, medical, mechanical questions
U||   with specialists in all these departments, throwing into them all more
U||   and more of politics as the intimacy between him and his patron and
U||   chief boarder increased.
U||   Now as to that patron and chief boarder. The need of extending his
U||   acquaintance seemed to press upon Mr. Pike with ever-increasing weight.
U||   He was here and there, all over the county; at the county-seat, at the
U||   county villages, at justices’ courts, at executors’ and administrators’
U||   sales, at quarterly and protracted religious meetings, at barbecues of
U||   every dimension, on hunting excursions and fishing frolics, at social
U||   parties in all neighborhoods. It got to be said of Mr. Pike that a
U||   freer acceptor of hospitable invitations, or a better appreciator of
U||   hospitable intentions, was not and needed not to be found possibly in
U||   the whole state. Nor was this admirable deportment confined to the
U||   county in which he held so high official position. He attended, among
U||   other occasions less public, the spring sessions of the supreme and
U||   county courts in the four adjoining counties: the guest of acquaintance
U||   old and new over there. When starting upon such travels, he would
U||   sometimes breakfast with his traveling companion in the village, and,
U||   if somewhat belated in the return, sup with him also.
U||   Yet, when at Flukers’, no man could have been a more cheerful and
U||   otherwise satisfactory boarder than Mr. Matt Pike. He praised every
U||   dish set before him, bragged to their very faces of his host and
U||   hostess, and in spite of his absences was the oftenest to sit and chat
U||   with Marann when her mother would let her go into the parlor. Here and
U||   everywhere about the house, in the dining-room, in the passage, at the
U||   foot of the stairs, he would joke with Marann about her country beau,
U||   as he styled poor Sim Marchman, and he would talk as though he was
U||   rather ashamed of Sim, and wanted Marann to string her bow for higher
U||   game.
U||   Brer Sam did manage well, not only the fields, but the yard. Every
U||   Saturday of the world he sent in something or other to his sister. I
U||   don’t know whether I ought to tell it or not, but for the sake of what
U||   is due to pure veracity I will. On as many as three different occasions
U||   Sim Marchman, as if he had lost all self-respect, or had not a particle
U||   of tact, brought in himself, instead of sending by a negro, a bucket of
U||   butter and a coop of spring chickens as a free gift to Mrs. Fluker. I
U||   do think, on my soul, that Mr. Matt Pike was much amused by such
U||   degradation—however, he must say that they were all first-rate. As for
U||   Marann, she was very sorry for Sim, and wished he had not brought these
U||   good things at all.
U||   Nobody knew how it came about; but when the Flukers had been in town
U||   somewhere between two and three months, Sim Marchman, who (to use his
U||   own words) had never bothered her a great deal with his visits, began
U||   to suspect that what few he made were received by Marann lately with
U||   less cordiality than before; and so one day, knowing no better, in his
U||   awkward, straightforward country manners, he wanted to know the reason
U||   why. Then Marann grew distant, and asked Sim the following question:
U||   “You know where Mr. Pike’s gone, Mr. Marchman?”
U||   Now the fact was, and she knew it, that Marann Fluker had never before,
U||   not since she was born, addressed that boy as Mister.
U||   The visitor’s face reddened and reddened.
U||   “No,” he faltered in answer; “no—no—ma’am, I should say. I—I don’t know
U||   where Mr. Pike’s gone.”
U||   Then he looked around for his hat, discovered it in time, took it into
U||   his hands, turned it around two or three times, then, bidding good-bye
U||   without shaking hands, took himself off.
U||   Mrs. Fluker liked all the Marchmans, and she was troubled somewhat when
U||   she heard of the quickness and manner of Sim’s departure; for he had
U||   been fully expected by her to stay to dinner.
U||   “Say he didn’t even shake hands, Marann? What for? What you do to him?”
U||   “Not one blessed thing, ma; only he wanted to know why I wasn’t gladder
U||   to see him.” Then Marann looked indignant.
U||   “Say them words, Marann?”
U||   “No, but he hinted ’em.”
U||   “What did you say then?”
U||   “I just asked, a-meaning nothing in the wide world, ma—I asked him if
U||   he knew where Mr. Pike had gone.”
U||   “And that were answer enough to hurt his feelin’s. What you want to
U||   know where Matt Pike’s gone for, Marann?”
U||   “I didn’t care about knowing, ma, but I didn’t like the way Sim
U||   talked.”
U||   “Look here, Marann. Look straight at me. You’ll be mighty fur off your
U||   feet if you let Matt Pike put things in your head that hain’t no
U||   business a-bein’ there, and special if you find yourself a-wantin’ to
U||   know where he’s a-perambulatin’ in his everlastin’ meanderin’s. Not a
U||   cent has he paid for his board, and which your pa say he have a’
U||   understandin’ with him about allowin’ for his absentees, which is all
U||   right enough, but which it’s now goin’ on to three mont’s, and what is
U||   comin’ to us I need and I want. He ought, your pa ought to let me
U||   bargain with Matt Pike, because he know he don’t understan’ figgers
U||   like Matt Pike. He don’t know exactly what the bargain were; for I’ve
U||   asked him, and he always begins with a multiplyin’ of words and never
U||   answers me.”
U||   On his next return from his travels Mr. Pike noticed a coldness in Mrs.
U||   Fluker’s manner, and this enhanced his praise of the house. The last
U||   week of the third month came. Mr. Pike was often noticed, before and
U||   after meals, standing at the desk in the hotel office (called in those
U||   times the bar-room) engaged in making calculations. The day before the
U||   contract expired Mrs. Fluker, who had not indulged herself with a
U||   single holiday since they had been in town, left Marann in charge of
U||   the house, and rode forth, spending part of the day with Mrs. Marchman,
U||   Sim’s mother. All were glad to see her, of course, and she returned
U||   smartly, freshened by the visit. That night she had a talk with Marann,
U||   and oh, how Marann did cry!
U||   The very last day came. Like insurance policies, the contract was to
U||   expire at a certain hour. Sim Marchman came just before dinner, to
U||   which he was sent for by Mrs. Fluker, who had seen him as he rode into
U||   town.
U||   “Hello, Sim,” said Mr. Pike as he took his seat opposite him. “You
U||   here? What’s the news in the country? How’s your health? How’s crops?”
U||   “Jest mod’rate, Mr. Pike. Got little business with you after dinner, ef
U||   you can spare time.”
U||   “All right. Got a little matter with Pink here first. ’Twon’t take
U||   long. See you arfter amejiant, Sim.”
U||   Never had the deputy been more gracious and witty. He talked and
U||   talked, outtalking even Mr. Fluker; he was the only man in town who
U||   could do that. He winked at Marann as he put questions to Sim, some of
U||   the words employed in which Sim had never heard before. Yet Sim held up
U||   as well as he could, and after dinner followed Marann with some little
U||   dignity into the parlor. They had not been there more than ten minutes
U||   when Mrs. Fluker was heard to walk rapidly along the passage leading
U||   from the dining-room, to enter her own chamber for only a moment, then
U||   to come out and rush to the parlor door with the gig-whip in her hand.
U||   Such uncommon conduct in a woman like Mrs. Pink Fluker of course needs
U||   explanation.
U||   When all the other boarders had left the house, the deputy and Mr.
U||   Fluker having repaired to the bar-room, the former said:
U||   “Now, Pink, for our settlement, as you say your wife think we better
U||   have one. I’d ’a’ been willin’ to let accounts keep on a-runnin’,
U||   knowin’ what a straightforrards sort o’ man you was. Your count, ef I
U||   ain’t mistakened, is jes’ thirty-three dollars, even money. Is that so,
U||   or is it not?”
U||   “That’s it, to a dollar, Matt. Three times eleben make thirty-three,
U||   don’t it?”
U||   “It do, Pink, or eleben times three, jes’ which you please. Now here’s
U||   my count, on which you’ll see, Pink, that not nary cent have I charged
U||   for infloonce. I has infloonced a consider’ble custom to this house, as
U||   you know, bo’din’ and transion. But I done that out o’ my respects of
U||   you an’ Missis Fluker, an’ your keepin’ of a fa’r—I’ll say, as I’ve
U||   said freckwent, a very fa’r house. I let them infloonces go to
U||   friendship, ef you’ll take it so. Will you, Pink Fluker?”
U||   “Cert’nly, Matt, an’ I’m a thousand times obleeged to you, an’—”
U||   “Say no more, Pink, on that p’int o’ view. Ef I like a man, I know how
U||   to treat him. Now as to the p’ints o’ absentees, my business as dep’ty
U||   sheriff has took me away from this inconsider’ble town freckwent,
U||   hain’t it?”
U||   “It have, Matt, er somethin’ else, more’n I were a expectin’, an’—”
U||   “Jes’ so. But a public officer, Pink, when jooty call on him to go, he
U||   got to go; in fack he got to goth, as the Scripture say, ain’t that
U||   so?”
U||   “I s’pose so, Matt, by good rights, a—a official speakin’.”
U||   Mr. Fluker felt that he was becoming a little confused.
U||   “Jes’ so. Now, Pink, I were to have credics for my absentees ’cordin’
U||   to transion an’ single-meal bo’ders an’ sleepers; ain’t that so?”
U||   “I—I—somethin’ o’ that sort, Matt,” he answered vaguely.
U||   “Jes’ so. Now look here,” drawing from his pocket a paper. “Itom one.
U||   Twenty-eight dinners at half a dollar makes fourteen dollars, don’t it?
U||   Jes’ so. Twenty-five breakfasts at a quarter makes six an’ a quarter,
U||   which make dinners an’ breakfasts twenty an’ a quarter. Foller me up,
U||   as I go up, Pink. Twenty-five suppers at a quarter makes six an’ a
U||   quarter, an’ which them added to the twenty an’ a quarter makes them
U||   twenty-six an’ a half. Foller, Pink, an’ if you ketch me in any
U||   mistakes in the kyarin’ an’ addin’, p’int it out. Twenty-two an’ a half
U||   beds—an’ I say half, Pink, because you ’member one night when them
U||   A’gusty lawyers got here ’bout midnight on their way to co’t, rather’n
U||   have you too bad cramped, I ris to make way for two of ’em; yit as I
U||   had one good nap, I didn’t think I ought to put that down but for half.
U||   Them makes five dollars half an’ seb’n pence, an’ which kyar’d on to
U||   the t’other twenty-six an’ a half, fetches the whole cabool to jes’
U||   thirty-two dollars an’ seb’n pence. But I made up my mind I’d fling out
U||   that seb’n pence, an’ jes’ call it a dollar even money, an’ which
U||   here’s the solid silver.”
U||   In spite of the rapidity with which this enumeration of counter-charges
U||   was made, Mr. Fluker commenced perspiring at the first item, and when
U||   the balance was announced his face was covered with huge drops.
U||   It was at this juncture that Mrs. Fluker, who, well knowing her
U||   husband’s unfamiliarity with complicated accounts, had felt her duty to
U||   be listening near the bar-room door, left, and quickly afterwards
U||   appeared before Marann and Sim as I have represented.
U||   “You think Matt Pike ain’t tryin’ to settle with your pa with a dollar?
U||   I’m goin’ to make him keep his dollar, an’ I’m goin’ to give him
U||   somethin’ to go ’long with it.”
U||   “The good Lord have mercy upon us!” exclaimed Marann, springing up and
U||   catching hold of her mother’s skirts, as she began her advance towards
U||   the bar-room. “Oh, ma! for the Lord’s sake!—Sim, Sim, Sim, if you care
U||   anything for me in this wide world, don’t let ma go into that room!”
U||   “Missis Fluker,” said Sim, rising instantly, “wait jest two minutes
U||   till I see Mr. Pike on some pressin’ business; I won’t keep you over
U||   two minutes a-waitin’.”
U||   He took her, set her down in a chair trembling, looked at her a moment
U||   as she began to weep, then, going out and closing the door, strode
U||   rapidly to the bar-room.
U||   “Let me help you settle your board-bill, Mr. Pike, by payin’ you a
U||   little one I owe you.”
U||   Doubling his fist, he struck out with a blow that felled the deputy to
U||   the floor. Then catching him by his heels, he dragged him out of the
U||   house into the street. Lifting his foot above his face, he said:
U||   “You stir till I tell you, an’ I’ll stomp your nose down even with the
U||   balance of your mean face. ’Tain’t exactly my business how you cheated
U||   Mr. Fluker, though, ’pon my soul, I never knowed a trifliner, lowdowner
U||   trick. But I owed you myself for your talkin’ ’bout and your lyin’
U||   ’bout me, and now I’ve paid you; an’ ef you only knowed it, I’ve saved
U||   you from a gig-whippin’. Now you may git up.”
U||   “Here’s his dollar, Sim,” said Mr. Fluker, throwing it out of the
U||   window. “Nervy say make him take it.”
U||   The vanquished, not daring to refuse, pocketed the coin, and slunk away
U||   amid the jeers of a score of villagers who had been drawn to the scene.
U||   In all human probability the late omission of the shaking of Sim’s and
U||   Marann’s hands was compensated at their parting that afternoon. I am
U||   more confident on this point because at the end of the year those hands
U||   were joined inseparably by the preacher. But this was when they had all
U||   gone back to their old home; for if Mr. Fluker did not become fully
U||   convinced that his mathematical education was not advanced quite enough
U||   for all the exigencies of hotel-keeping, his wife declared that she had
U||   had enough of it, and that she and Marann were going home. Mr. Fluker
U||   may be said, therefore, to have followed, rather than led, his family
U||   on the return.
U||   As for the deputy, finding that if he did not leave it voluntarily he
U||   would be drummed out of the village, he departed, whither I do not
U||   remember if anybody ever knew.
