U||THE NICE PEOPLE[61][21]
U||   By Henry Cuyler Bunner (1855–1896)
U||   “They certainly are nice people,” I assented to my wife’s observation,
U||   using the colloquial phrase with a consciousness that it was anything
U||   but “nice” English, “and I’ll bet that their three children are better
U||   brought up than most of——”
U||   “Two children,” corrected my wife.
U||   “Three, he told me.”
U||   “My dear, she said there were two.”
U||   “He said three.”
U||   “You’ve simply forgotten. I’m sure she told me they had only two—a boy
U||   and a girl.”
U||   “Well, I didn’t enter into particulars.”
U||   “No, dear, and you couldn’t have understood him. Two children.”
U||   “All right,” I said; but I did not think it was all right. As a
U||   nearsighted man learns by enforced observation to recognize persons at
U||   a distance when the face is not visible to the normal eye, so the man
U||   with a bad memory learns, almost unconsciously, to listen carefully and
U||   report accurately. My memory is bad; but I had not had time to forget
U||   that Mr. Brewster Brede had told me that afternoon that he had three
U||   children, at present left in the care of his mother-in-law, while he
U||   and Mrs. Brede took their summer vacation.
U||   “Two children,” repeated my wife; “and they are staying with his aunt
U||   Jenny.”
U||   “He told me with his mother-in-law,” I put in. My wife looked at me
U||   with a serious expression. Men may not remember much of what they are
U||   told about children; but any man knows the difference between an aunt
U||   and a mother-in-law.
U||   “But don’t you think they’re nice people?” asked my wife.
U||   “Oh, certainly,” I replied. “Only they seem to be a little mixed up
U||   about their children.”
U||   “That isn’t a nice thing to say,” returned my wife. I could not deny
U||   it.
U||     __________________________________________________________________
U||   And yet, the next morning, when the Bredes came down and seated
U||   themselves opposite us at table, beaming and smiling in their natural,
U||   pleasant, well-bred fashion, I knew, to a social certainty, that they
U||   were “nice” people. He was a fine-looking fellow in his neat
U||   tennis-flannels, slim, graceful, twenty-eight or thirty years old, with
U||   a Frenchy pointed beard. She was “nice” in all her pretty clothes, and
U||   she herself was pretty with that type of prettiness which outwears most
U||   other types—the prettiness that lies in a rounded figure, a dusky skin,
U||   plump, rosy cheeks, white teeth and black eyes. She might have been
U||   twenty-five; you guessed that she was prettier than she was at twenty,
U||   and that she would be prettier still at forty.
U||   And nice people were all we wanted to make us happy in Mr. Jacobus’s
U||   summer boarding-house on top of Orange Mountain. For a week we had come
U||   down to breakfast each morning, wondering why we wasted the precious
U||   days of idleness with the company gathered around the Jacobus board.
U||   What joy of human companionship was to be had out of Mrs. Tabb and Miss
U||   Hoogencamp, the two middle-aged gossips from Scranton, Pa.—out of Mr.
U||   and Mrs. Biggle, an indurated head-bookkeeper and his prim and
U||   censorious wife—out of old Major Halkit, a retired business man, who,
U||   having once sold a few shares on commission, wrote for circulars of
U||   every stock company that was started, and tried to induce every one to
U||   invest who would listen to him? We looked around at those dull faces,
U||   the truthful indices of mean and barren minds, and decided that we
U||   would leave that morning. Then we ate Mrs. Jacobus’s biscuit, light as
U||   Aurora’s cloudlets, drank her honest coffee, inhaled the perfume of the
U||   late azaleas with which she decked her table, and decided to postpone
U||   our departure one more day. And then we wandered out to take our
U||   morning glance at what we called “our view”; and it seemed to us as if
U||   Tabb and Hoogencamp and Halkit and the Biggleses could not drive us
U||   away in a year.
U||   I was not surprised when, after breakfast, my wife invited the Bredes
U||   to walk with us to “our view.” The Hoogencamp-Biggle-Tabb-Halkit
U||   contingent never stirred off Jacobus’s veranda; but we both felt that
U||   the Bredes would not profane that sacred scene. We strolled slowly
U||   across the fields, passed through the little belt of woods and, as I
U||   heard Mrs. Brede’s little cry of startled rapture, I motioned to Brede
U||   to look up.
U||   “By Jove!” he cried, “heavenly!”
U||   We looked off from the brow of the mountain over fifteen miles of
U||   billowing green, to where, far across a far stretch of pale blue lay a
U||   dim purple line that we knew was Staten Island. Towns and villages lay
U||   before us and under us; there were ridges and hills, uplands and
U||   lowlands, woods and plains, all massed and mingled in that great silent
U||   sea of sunlit green. For silent it was to us, standing in the silence
U||   of a high place—silent with a Sunday stillness that made us listen,
U||   without taking thought, for the sound of bells coming up from the
U||   spires that rose above the tree-tops—the tree-tops that lay as far
U||   beneath us as the light clouds were above us that dropped great shadows
U||   upon our heads and faint specks of shade upon the broad sweep of land
U||   at the mountain’s foot.
U||   “And so that is your view?” asked Mrs. Brede, after a moment; “you are
U||   very generous to make it ours, too.”
U||   Then we lay down on the grass, and Brede began to talk, in a gentle
U||   voice, as if he felt the influence of the place. He had paddled a
U||   canoe, in his earlier days, he said, and he knew every river and creek
U||   in that vast stretch of landscape. He found his landmarks, and pointed
U||   out to us where the Passaic and the Hackensack flowed, invisible to us,
U||   hidden behind great ridges that in our sight were but combings of the
U||   green waves upon which we looked down. And yet, on the further side of
U||   those broad ridges and rises were scores of villages—a little world of
U||   country life, lying unseen under our eyes.
U||   “A good deal like looking at humanity,” he said; “there is such a thing
U||   as getting so far above our fellow men that we see only one side of
U||   them.”
U||   Ah, how much better was this sort of talk than the chatter and gossip
U||   of the Tabb and the Hoogencamp—than the Major’s dissertations upon his
U||   everlasting circulars! My wife and I exchanged glances.
U||   “Now, when I went up the Matterhorn” Mr. Brede began.
U||   “Why, dear,” interrupted his wife, “I didn’t know you ever went up the
U||   Matterhorn.”
U||   “It—it was five years ago,” said Mr. Brede, hurriedly. “I—I didn’t tell
U||   you—when I was on the other side, you know—it was rather
U||   dangerous—well, as I was saying—it looked—oh, it didn’t look at all
U||   like this.”
U||   A cloud floated overhead, throwing its great shadow over the field
U||   where we lay. The shadow passed over the mountain’s brow and reappeared
U||   far below, a rapidly decreasing blot, flying eastward over the golden
U||   green. My wife and I exchanged glances once more.
U||   Somehow, the shadow lingered over us all. As we went home, the Bredes
U||   went side by side along the narrow path, and my wife and I walked
U||   together.
U||   “Should you think,” she asked me, “that a man would climb the
U||   Matterhorn the very first year he was married?”
U||   “I don’t know, my dear,” I answered, evasively; “this isn’t the first
U||   year I have been married, not by a good many, and I wouldn’t climb
U||   it—for a farm.”
U||   “You know what I mean,” she said.
U||   I did.
U||     __________________________________________________________________
U||   When we reached the boarding-house, Mr. Jacobus took me aside.
U||   “You know,” he began his discourse, “my wife she uset to live in N’
U||   York!”
U||   I didn’t know, but I said “Yes.”
U||   “She says the numbers on the streets runs criss-cross-like.
U||   Thirty-four’s on one side o’ the street an’ thirty-five on t’other.
U||   How’s that?”
U||   “That is the invariable rule, I believe.”
U||   “Then—I say—these here new folk that you ’n’ your wife seem so mighty
U||   taken up with—d’ye know anything about ’em?”
U||   “I know nothing about the character of your boarders, Mr. Jacobus,” I
U||   replied, conscious of some irritability. “If I choose to associate with
U||   any of them——”
U||   “Jess so—jess so!” broke in Jacobus. “I hain’t nothin’ to say ag’inst
U||   yer sosherbil’ty. But do ye know them?”
U||   “Why, certainly not,” I replied.
U||   “Well—that was all I wuz askin’ ye. Ye see, when he come here to take
U||   the rooms—you wasn’t here then—he told my wife that he lived at number
U||   thirty-four in his street. An’ yistiddy she told her that they lived at
U||   number thirty-five. He said he lived in an apartment-house. Now there
U||   can’t be no apartment-house on two sides of the same street, kin they?”
U||   “What street was it?” I inquired, wearily.
U||   “Hundred ’n’ twenty-first street.”
U||   “May be,” I replied, still more wearily. “That’s Harlem. Nobody knows
U||   what people will do in Harlem.”
U||   I went up to my wife’s room.
U||   “Don’t you think it’s queer?” she asked me.
U||   “I think I’ll have a talk with that young man to-night,” I said, “and
U||   see if he can give some account of himself.”
U||   “But, my dear,” my wife said, gravely, “she doesn’t know whether
U||   they’ve had the measles or not.”
U||   “Why, Great Scott!” I exclaimed, “they must have had them when they
U||   were children.”
U||   “Please don’t be stupid,” said my wife. “I meant their children.”
U||   After dinner that night—or rather, after supper, for we had dinner in
U||   the middle of the day at Jacobus’s—I walked down the long verandah to
U||   ask Brede, who was placidly smoking at the other end, to accompany me
U||   on a twilight stroll. Half way down I met Major Halkit.
U||   “That friend of yours,” he said, indicating the unconscious figure at
U||   the further end of the house, “seems to be a queer sort of a Dick. He
U||   told me that he was out of business, and just looking round for a
U||   chance to invest his capital. And I’ve been telling him what an
U||   everlasting big show he had to take stock in the Capitoline Trust
U||   Company—starts next month—four million capital—I told you all about it.
U||   ‘Oh, well,’ he says, ‘let’s wait and think about it.’ ‘Wait!’ says I,
U||   ‘the Capitoline Trust Company won’t wait for you, my boy. This is
U||   letting you in on the ground floor,’ says I, ‘and it’s now or never.’
U||   ‘Oh, let it wait,’ says he. I don’t know what’s in-to the man.”
U||   “I don’t know how well he knows his own business, Major,” I said as I
U||   started again for Brede’s end of the veranda. But I was troubled none
U||   the less. The Major could not have influenced the sale of one share of
U||   stock in the Capitoline Company. But that stock was a great investment;
U||   a rare chance for a purchaser with a few thousand dollars. Perhaps it
U||   was no more remarkable that Brede should not invest than that I should
U||   not—and yet, it seemed to add one circumstance more to the other
U||   suspicious circumstances.
U||     __________________________________________________________________
U||   When I went upstairs that evening, I found my wife putting her hair to
U||   bed—I don’t know how I can better describe an operation familiar to
U||   every married man. I waited until the last tress was coiled up, and
U||   then I spoke:
U||   “I’ve talked with Brede,” I said, “and I didn’t have to catechize him.
U||   He seemed to feel that some sort of explanation was looked for, and he
U||   was very outspoken. You were right about the children—that is, I must
U||   have misunderstood him. There are only two. But the Matterhorn episode
U||   was simple enough. He didn’t realize how dangerous it was until he had
U||   got so far into it that he couldn’t back out; and he didn’t tell her,
U||   because he’d left her here, you see, and under the circumstances——”
U||   “Left her here!” cried my wife. “I’ve been sitting with her the whole
U||   afternoon, sewing, and she told me that he left her at Geneva, and came
U||   back and took her to Basle, and the baby was born there—now I’m sure,
U||   dear, because I asked her.”
U||   “Perhaps I was mistaken when I thought he said she was on this side of
U||   the water,” I suggested, with bitter, biting irony.
U||   “You poor dear, did I abuse you?” said my wife. “But, do you know, Mrs.
U||   Tabb said that she didn’t know how many lumps of sugar he took in his
U||   coffee. Now that seems queer, doesn’t it?”
U||   It did. It was a small thing. But it looked queer, Very queer.
U||     __________________________________________________________________
U||   The next morning, it was clear that war was declared against the
U||   Bredes. They came down to breakfast somewhat late, and, as soon as they
U||   arrived, the Biggleses swooped up the last fragments that remained on
U||   their plates, and made a stately march out of the dining-room, Then
U||   Miss Hoogencamp arose and departed, leaving a whole fish-ball on her
U||   plate. Even as Atalanta might have dropped an apple behind her to tempt
U||   her pursuer to check his speed, so Miss Hoogencamp left that fish-ball
U||   behind her, and between her maiden self and contamination.
U||   We had finished our breakfast, my wife and I, before the Bredes
U||   appeared. We talked it over, and agreed that we were glad that we had
U||   not been obliged to take sides upon such insufficient testimony.
U||   After breakfast, it was the custom of the male half of the Jacobus
U||   household to go around the corner of the building and smoke their pipes
U||   and cigars where they would not annoy the ladies. We sat under a
U||   trellis covered with a grapevine that had borne no grapes in the memory
U||   of man. This vine, however, bore leaves, and these, on that pleasant
U||   summer morning, shielded from us two persons who were in earnest
U||   conversation in the straggling, half-dead flower-garden at the side of
U||   the house.
U||   “I don’t want,” we heard Mr. Jacobus say, “to enter in no man’s
U||   pry-vacy; but I do want to know who it may be, like, that I hev in my
U||   house. Now what I ask of you, and I don’t want you to take it as in no
U||   ways personal, is—hev you your merridge-license with you?”
U||   “No,” we heard the voice of Mr. Brede reply. “Have you yours?”
U||   I think it was a chance shot; but it told all the same. The Major (he
U||   was a widower) and Mr. Biggle and I looked at each other; and Mr.
U||   Jacobus, on the other side of the grape-trellis, looked at—I don’t know
U||   what—and was as silent as we were.
U||   Where is your marriage-license, married reader? Do you know? Four men,
U||   not including Mr. Brede, stood or sat on one side or the other of that
U||   grape-trellis, and not one of them knew where his marriage-license was.
U||   Each of us had had one—the Major had had three. But where were they?
U||   Where is yours? Tucked in your best-man’s pocket; deposited in his
U||   desk—or washed to a pulp in his white waistcoat (if white waistcoats be
U||   the fashion of the hour), washed out of existence—can you tell where it
U||   is? Can you—unless you are one of those people who frame that
U||   interesting document and hang it upon their drawing-room walls?
U||   Mr. Brede’s voice arose, after an awful stillness of what seemed like
U||   five minutes, and was, probably, thirty seconds:
U||   “Mr. Jacobus, will you make out your bill at once, and let me pay it? I
U||   shall leave by the six o’clock train. And will you also send the wagon
U||   for my trunks?”
U||   “I hain’t said I wanted to hev ye leave——” began Mr. Jacobus; but Brede
U||   cut him short.
U||   “Bring me your bill.”
U||   “But,” remonstrated Jacobus, “ef ye ain’t——”
U||   “Bring me your bill!” said Mr. Brede.
U||     __________________________________________________________________
U||   My wife and I went out for our morning’s walk. But it seemed to us,
U||   when we looked at “our view,” as if we could only see those invisible
U||   villages of which Brede had told us—that other side of the ridges and
U||   rises of which we catch no glimpse from lofty hills or from the heights
U||   of human self-esteem. We meant to stay out until the Bredes had taken
U||   their departure; but we returned just in time to see Pete, the Jacobus
U||   darkey, the blacker of boots, the brasher of coats, the general
U||   handy-man of the house, loading the Brede trunks on the Jacobus wagon.
U||   And, as we stepped upon the verandah, down came Mrs. Brede, leaning on
U||   Mr. Brede’s arm, as though she were ill; and it was clear that she had
U||   been crying. There were heavy rings about her pretty black eyes.
U||   My wife took a step toward her.
U||   “Look at that dress, dear,” she whispered; “she never thought anything
U||   like this was going to happen when she put that on.”
U||   It was a pretty, delicate, dainty dress, a graceful, narrow-striped
U||   affair. Her hat was trimmed with a narrow-striped silk of the same
U||   colors—maroon and white—and in her hand she held a parasol that matched
U||   her dress.
U||   “She’s had a new dress on twice a day,” said my wife, “but that’s the
U||   prettiest yet. Oh, somehow—I’m awfully sorry they’re going!”
U||   But going they were. They moved toward the steps. Mrs. Brede looked
U||   toward my wife, and my wife moved toward Mrs. Brede. But the ostracized
U||   woman, as though she felt the deep humiliation of her position, turned
U||   sharply away, and opened her parasol to shield her eyes from the sun. A
U||   shower of rice—a half-pound shower of rice—fell down over her pretty
U||   hat and her pretty dress, and fell in a spattering circle on the floor,
U||   outlining her skirts—and there it lay in a broad, uneven band, bright
U||   in the morning sun.
U||   Mrs. Brede was in my wife’s arms, sobbing as if her young heart would
U||   break.
U||   “Oh, you poor, dear, silly children!” my wife cried, as Mrs. Brede
U||   sobbed on her shoulder, “why didn’t you tell us?”
U||   “W-W-W-We didn’t want to be t-t-taken for a b-b-b-b-bridal couple,”
U||   sobbed Mrs. Brede; “and we d-d-didn’t dream what awful lies we’d have
U||   to tell, and all the aw-awful mixed-up-ness of it. Oh, dear, dear,
U||   dear!”
U||     __________________________________________________________________
U||   “Pete!” commanded Mr. Jacobus, “put back them trunks. These folks stays
U||   here’s long’s they wants ter. Mr. Brede”—he held out a large, hard
U||   hand—“I’d orter’ve known better,” he said. And my last doubt of Mr.
U||   Brede vanished as he shook that grimy hand in manly fashion.
U||   The two women were walking off toward “our view,” each with an arm
U||   about the other’s waist—touched by a sudden sisterhood of sympathy.
U||   “Gentlemen,” said Mr. Brede, addressing Jacobus, Biggle, the Major and
U||   me, “there is a hostelry down the street where they sell honest New
U||   Jersey beer. I recognize the obligations of the situation.”
U||   We five men filed down the street. The two women went toward the
U||   pleasant slope where the sunlight gilded the forehead of the great
U||   hill. On Mr. Jacobus’s veranda lay a spattered circle of shining grains
U||   of rice. Two of Mr. Jacobus’s pigeons flew down and picked up the
U||   shining grains, making grateful noises far down in their throats.
