U||THE BULLER-PODINGTON COMPACT[63][22]
U||   By Frank Richard Stockton (1834–1902)
U||   “I tell you, William,” said Thomas Buller to his friend Mr. Podington,
U||   “I am truly sorry about it, but I cannot arrange for it this year. Now,
U||   as to my invitation—that is very different.”
U||   “Of course it is different,” was the reply, “but I am obliged to say,
U||   as I said before, that I really cannot accept it.”
U||   Remarks similar to these had been made by Thomas Buller and William
U||   Podington at least once a year for some five years. They were old
U||   friends; they had been schoolboys together and had been associated in
U||   business since they were young men. They had now reached a vigorous
U||   middle age; they were each married, and each had a house in the country
U||   in which he resided for a part of the year. They were warmly attached
U||   to each other, and each was the best friend which the other had in this
U||   world. But during all these years neither of them had visited the other
U||   in his country home.
U||   The reason for this avoidance of each other at their respective rural
U||   residences may be briefly stated. Mr. Buller’s country house was
U||   situated by the sea, and he was very fond of the water. He had a good
U||   cat-boat, which he sailed himself with much judgment and skill, and it
U||   was his greatest pleasure to take his friends and visitors upon little
U||   excursions on the bay. But Mr. Podington was desperately afraid of the
U||   water, and he was particularly afraid of any craft sailed by an
U||   amateur. If his friend Buller would have employed a professional
U||   mariner, of years and experience, to steer and manage his boat,
U||   Podington might have been willing to take an occasional sail; but as
U||   Buller always insisted upon sailing his own boat, and took it ill if
U||   any of his visitors doubted his ability to do so properly, Podington
U||   did not wish to wound the self-love of his friend, and he did not wish
U||   to be drowned. Consequently he could not bring himself to consent to go
U||   to Buller’s house by the sea.
U||   To receive his good friend Buller at his own house in the beautiful
U||   upland region in which he lived would have been a great joy to Mr.
U||   Podington; but Buller could not be induced to visit him. Podington was
U||   very fond of horses and always drove himself, while Buller was more
U||   afraid of horses than he was of elephants or lions. To one or more
U||   horses driven by a coachman of years and experience he did not always
U||   object, but to a horse driven by Podington, who had much experience and
U||   knowledge regarding mercantile affairs, but was merely an amateur
U||   horseman, he most decidedly and strongly objected. He did not wish to
U||   hurt his friend’s feelings by refusing to go out to drive with him, but
U||   he would not rack his own nervous system by accompanying him. Therefore
U||   it was that he had not yet visited the beautiful upland country
U||   residence of Mr. Podington.
U||   At last this state of things grew awkward. Mrs. Buller and Mrs.
U||   Podington, often with their families, visited each other at their
U||   country houses, but the fact that on these occasions they were never
U||   accompanied by their husbands caused more and more gossip among their
U||   neighbors both in the upland country and by the sea.
U||   One day in spring as the two sat in their city office, where Mr.
U||   Podington had just repeated his annual invitation, his friend replied
U||   to him thus:
U||   “William, if I come to see you this summer, will you visit me? The
U||   thing is beginning to look a little ridiculous, and people are talking
U||   about it.”
U||   Mr. Podington put his hand to his brow and for a few moments closed his
U||   eyes. In his mind he saw a cat-boat upon its side, the sails spread out
U||   over the water, and two men, almost entirely immersed in the waves,
U||   making efforts to reach the side of the boat. One of these was getting
U||   on very well—that was Buller. The other seemed about to sink, his arms
U||   were uselessly waving in the air—that was himself. But he opened his
U||   eyes and looked bravely out of the window; it was time to conquer all
U||   this; it was indeed growing ridiculous. Buller had been sailing many
U||   years and had never been upset.
U||   “Yes,” said he; “I will do it; I am ready any time you name.”
U||   Mr. Buller rose and stretched out his hand.
U||   “Good!” said he; “it is a compact!”
U||   Buller was the first to make the promised country visit. He had not
U||   mentioned the subject of horses to his friend, but he knew through Mrs.
U||   Buller that Podington still continued to be his own driver. She had
U||   informed him, however, that at present he was accustomed to drive a big
U||   black horse which, in her opinion, was as gentle and reliable as these
U||   animals ever became, and she could not imagine how anybody could be
U||   afraid of him. So when, the next morning after his arrival, Mr. Buller
U||   was asked by his host if he would like to take a drive, he suppressed a
U||   certain rising emotion and said that it would please him very much.
U||   When the good black horse had jogged along a pleasant road for half an
U||   hour Mr. Buller began to feel that, perhaps, for all these years he had
U||   been laboring under a misconception. It seemed to be possible that
U||   there were some horses to which surrounding circumstances in the shape
U||   of sights and sounds were so irrelevant that they were to a certain
U||   degree entirely safe, even when guided and controlled by an amateur
U||   hand. As they passed some meadow-land, somebody behind a hedge fired a
U||   gun; Mr. Buller was frightened, but the horse was not.
U||   “William,” said Buller, looking cheerfully around him,
U||   “I had no idea that you lived in such a pretty country. In fact, I
U||   might almost call it beautiful. You have not any wide stretch of water,
U||   such as I like so much, but here is a pretty river, those rolling hills
U||   are very charming, and, beyond, you have the blue of the mountains.”
U||   “It is lovely,” said his friend; “I never get tired of driving through
U||   this country. Of course the seaside is very fine, but here we have such
U||   a variety of scenery.”
U||   Mr. Buller could not help thinking that sometimes the seaside was a
U||   little monotonous, and that he had lost a great deal of pleasure by not
U||   varying his summers by going up to spend a week or two with Podington.
U||   “William,” said he, “how long have you had this horse?”
U||   “About two years,” said Mr. Podington; “before I got him, I used to
U||   drive a pair.”
U||   “Heavens!” thought Buller, “how lucky I was not to come two years ago!”
U||   And his regrets for not sooner visiting his friend greatly decreased.
U||   Now they came to a place where the stream, by which the road ran, had
U||   been dammed for a mill and had widened into a beautiful pond.
U||   “There now!” cried Mr. Buller. “That’s what I like. William, you seem
U||   to have everything! This is really a very pretty sheet of water, and
U||   the reflections of the trees over there make a charming picture; you
U||   can’t get that at the seaside, you know.”
U||   Mr. Podington was delighted; his face glowed; he was rejoiced at the
U||   pleasure of his friend. “I tell you, Thomas,” said he, “that——”
U||   “William!” exclaimed Buller, with a sudden squirm in his seat, “what is
U||   that I hear? Is that a train?”
U||   “Yes,” said Mr. Podington, “that is the ten-forty, up.”
U||   “Does it come near here?” asked Mr. Buller, nervously. “Does it go over
U||   that bridge?”
U||   “Yes,” said Podington, “but it can’t hurt us, for our road goes under
U||   the bridge; we are perfectly safe; there is no risk of accident.”
U||   “But your horse! Your horse!” exclaimed Buller, as the train came
U||   nearer and nearer. “What will he do?”
U||   “Do?” said Podington; “he’ll do what he is doing now; he doesn’t mind
U||   trains.”
U||   “But look here, William,” exclaimed Buller, “it will get there just as
U||   we do; no horse could stand a roaring up in the air like that!”
U||   Podington laughed. “He would not mind it in the least,” said he.
U||   “Come, come now,” cried Buller. “Really, I can’t stand this! Just stop
U||   a minute, William, and let me get out. It sets all my nerves
U||   quivering.”
U||   Mr. Podington smiled with a superior smile. “Oh, you needn’t get out,”
U||   said he; “there’s not the least danger in the world. But I don’t want
U||   to make you nervous, and I will turn around and drive the other way.”
U||   “But you can’t!” screamed Buller. “This road is not wide enough, and
U||   that train is nearly here. Please stop!”
U||   The imputation that the road was not wide enough for him to turn was
U||   too much for Mr. Podington to bear. He was very proud of his ability to
U||   turn a vehicle in a narrow place.
U||   “Turn!” said he; “that’s the easiest thing in the world. See; a little
U||   to the right, then a back, then a sweep to the left and we will be
U||   going the other way.” And instantly he began the maneuver in which he
U||   was such an adept.
U||   “Oh, Thomas!” cried Buller, half rising in his seat, “that train is
U||   almost here!”
U||   “And we are almost——” Mr. Podington was about to say “turned around,”
U||   but he stopped. Mr. Buller’s exclamations had made him a little
U||   nervous, and, in his anxiety to turn quickly, he had pulled upon his
U||   horse’s bit with more energy than was actually necessary, and his
U||   nervousness being communicated to the horse, that animal backed with
U||   such extraordinary vigor that the hind wheels of the wagon went over a
U||   bit of grass by the road and into the water. The sudden jolt gave a new
U||   impetus to Mr. Buller’s fears.
U||   “You’ll upset!” he cried, and not thinking of what he was about, he
U||   laid hold of his friend’s arm. The horse, startled by this sudden jerk
U||   upon his bit, which, combined with the thundering of the train, which
U||   was now on the bridge, made him think that something extraordinary was
U||   about to happen, gave a sudden and forcible start backward, so that not
U||   only the hind wheels of the light wagon, but the fore wheels and his
U||   own hind legs went into the water. As the bank at this spot sloped
U||   steeply, the wagon continued to go backward, despite the efforts of the
U||   agitated horse to find a footing on the crumbling edge of the bank.
U||   “Whoa!” cried Mr. Buller.
U||   “Get up!” exclaimed Mr. Podington, applying his whip upon the plunging
U||   beast.
U||   But exclamations and castigations had no effect upon the horse. The
U||   original bed of the stream ran close to the road, and the bank was so
U||   steep and the earth so soft that it was impossible for the horse to
U||   advance or even maintain his footing. Back, back he went, until the
U||   whole equipage was in the water and the wagon was afloat.
U||   This vehicle was a road wagon, without a top, and the joints of its
U||   box-body were tight enough to prevent the water from immediately
U||   entering it; so, somewhat deeply sunken, it rested upon the water.
U||   There was a current in this part of the pond and it turned the wagon
U||   downstream. The horse was now entirely immersed in the water, with the
U||   exception of his head and the upper part of his neck, and, unable to
U||   reach the bottom with his feet, he made vigorous efforts to swim.
U||   Mr. Podington, the reins and whip in his hands, sat horrified and pale;
U||   the accident was so sudden, he was so startled and so frightened that,
U||   for a moment, he could not speak a word. Mr. Buller, on the other hand,
U||   was now lively and alert. The wagon had no sooner floated away from the
U||   shore than he felt himself at home. He was upon his favorite element;
U||   water had no fears for him. He saw that his friend was nearly
U||   frightened out of his wits, and that, figuratively speaking, he must
U||   step to the helm and take charge of the vessel. He stood up and gazed
U||   about him.
U||   “Put her across stream!” he shouted; “she can’t make headway against
U||   this current. Head her to that clump of trees on the other side; the
U||   bank is lower there, and we can beach her. Move a little the other way,
U||   we must trim boat. Now then, pull on your starboard rein.”
U||   Podington obeyed, and the horse slightly changed his direction.
U||   “You see,” said Buller, “it won’t do to sail straight across, because
U||   the current would carry us down and land us below that spot.”
U||   Mr. Podington said not a word; he expected every moment to see the
U||   horse sink into a watery grave.
U||   “It isn’t so bad after all, is it, Podington? If we had a rudder and a
U||   bit of a sail it would be a great help to the horse. This wagon is not
U||   a bad boat.”
U||   The despairing Podington looked at his feet. “It’s coming in,” he said
U||   in a husky voice. “Thomas, the water is over my shoes!”
U||   “That is so,” said Buller. “I am so used to water I didn’t notice it.
U||   She leaks. Do you carry anything to bail her out with?”
U||   “Bail!” cried Podington, now finding his voice. “Oh, Thomas, we are
U||   sinking!”
U||   “That’s so,” said Buller; “she leaks like a sieve.”
U||   The weight of the running-gear and of the two men was entirely too much
U||   for the buoyancy of the wagon body. The water rapidly rose toward the
U||   top of its sides.
U||   “We are going to drown!” cried Podington, suddenly rising.
U||   “Lick him! Lick him!” exclaimed Buller. “Make him swim faster!”
U||   “There’s nothing to lick,” cried Podington, vainly lashing at the
U||   water, for he could not reach the horse’s head. The poor man was
U||   dreadfully frightened; he had never even imagined it possible that he
U||   should be drowned in his own wagon.
U||   “Whoop!” cried Buller, as the water rose over the sides. “Steady
U||   yourself, old boy, or you’ll go overboard!” And the next moment the
U||   wagon body sunk out of sight.
U||   But it did not go down very far. The deepest part of the channel of the
U||   stream had been passed, and with a bump the wheels struck the bottom.
U||   “Heavens!” exclaimed Buller, “we are aground.”
U||   “Aground!” exclaimed Podington, “Heaven be praised!”
U||   As the two men stood up in the submerged wagon the water was above
U||   their knees, and when Podington looked out over the surface of the
U||   pond, now so near his face, it seemed like a sheet of water he had
U||   never seen before. It was something horrible, threatening to rise and
U||   envelop him. He trembled so that he could scarcely keep his footing.
U||   “William,” said his companion, “you must sit down; if you don’t, you’ll
U||   tumble overboard and be drowned. There is nothing for you to hold to.”
U||   “Sit down,” said Podington, gazing blankly at the water around him, “I
U||   can’t do that!”
U||   At this moment the horse made a slight movement. Having touched bottom
U||   after his efforts in swimming across the main bed of the stream, with a
U||   floating wagon in tow, he had stood for a few moments, his head and
U||   neck well above water, and his back barely visible beneath the surface.
U||   Having recovered his breath, he now thought it was time to move on.
U||   At the first step of the horse Mr. Podington began to totter.
U||   Instinctively he clutched Buller.
U||   “Sit down!” cried the latter, “or you’ll have us both overboard.” There
U||   was no help for it; down sat Mr. Podington; and, as with a great splash
U||   he came heavily upon the seat, the water rose to his waist.
U||   “Ough!” said he. “Thomas, shout for help.”
U||   “No use doing that,” replied Buller, still standing on his nautical
U||   legs; “I don’t see anybody, and I don’t see any boat. We’ll get out all
U||   right. Just you stick tight to the thwart.”
U||   “The what?” feebly asked the other.
U||   “Oh, the seat, I mean. We can get to the shore all right if you steer
U||   the horse straight. Head him more across the pond.”
U||   “I can’t head him,” cried Podington. “I have dropped the reins!”
U||   “Good gracious!” cried Mr. Buller, “that’s bad. Can’t you steer him by
U||   shouting ‘Gee’ and ‘Haw’?”
U||   “No,” said Podington, “he isn’t an ox; but perhaps I can stop him.” And
U||   with as much voice as he could summon, he called out: “Whoa!” and the
U||   horse stopped.
U||   “If you can’t steer him any other way,” said Buller, “we must get the
U||   reins. Lend me your whip.”
U||   “I have dropped that too,” said Podington; “there it floats.”
U||   “Oh, dear,” said Buller, “I guess I’ll have to dive for them; if he
U||   were to run away, we should be in an awful fix.”
U||   “Don’t get out! Don’t get out!” exclaimed Podington. “You can reach
U||   over the dashboard.”
U||   “As that’s under water,” said Buller, “it will be the same thing as
U||   diving; but it’s got to be done, and I’ll try it. Don’t you move now; I
U||   am more used to water than you are.”
U||   Mr. Buller took off his hat and asked his friend to hold it. He thought
U||   of his watch and other contents of his pockets, but there was no place
U||   to put them, so he gave them no more consideration. Then bravely
U||   getting on his knees in the water, he leaned over the dashboard, almost
U||   disappearing from sight. With his disengaged hand Mr. Podington grasped
U||   the submerged coat-tails of his friend.
U||   In a few seconds the upper part of Mr. Buller rose from the water. He
U||   was dripping and puffing, and Mr. Podington could not but think what a
U||   difference it made in the appearance of his friend to have his hair
U||   plastered close to his head.
U||   “I got hold of one of them,” said the sputtering Buller, “but it was
U||   fast to something and I couldn’t get it loose.”
U||   “Was it thick and wide?” asked Podington.
U||   “Yes,” was the answer; “it did seem so.”
U||   “Oh, that was a trace,” said Podington; “I don’t want that; the reins
U||   are thinner and lighter.”
U||   “Now I remember they are,” said Buller. “I’ll go down again.”
U||   Again Mr. Buller leaned over the dashboard, and this time he remained
U||   down longer, and when he came up he puffed and sputtered more than
U||   before.
U||   “Is this it?” said he, holding up a strip of wet leather.
U||   “Yes,” said Podington, “you’ve got the reins.”
U||   “Well, take them, and steer. I would have found them sooner if his tail
U||   had not got into my eyes. That long tail’s floating down there and
U||   spreading itself out like a fan; it tangled itself all around my head.
U||   It would have been much easier if he had been a bob-tailed horse.”
U||   “Now then,” said Podington, “take your hat, Thomas, and I’ll try to
U||   drive.”
U||   Mr. Buller put on his hat, which was the only dry thing about him, and
U||   the nervous Podington started the horse so suddenly that even the
U||   sea-legs of Buller were surprised, and he came very near going backward
U||   into the water; but recovering himself, he sat down.
U||   “I don’t wonder you did not like to do this, William,” said he. “Wet as
U||   I am, it’s ghastly!”
U||   Encouraged by his master’s voice, and by the feeling of the familiar
U||   hand upon his bit, the horse moved bravely on.
U||   But the bottom was very rough and uneven. Sometimes the wheels struck a
U||   large stone, terrifying Mr. Buller, who thought they were going to
U||   upset; and sometimes they sank into soft mud, horrifying Mr. Podington,
U||   who thought they were going to drown.
U||   Thus proceeding, they presented a strange sight. At first Mr. Podington
U||   held his hands above the water as he drove, but he soon found this
U||   awkward, and dropped them to their usual position, so that nothing was
U||   visible above the water but the head and neck of a horse and the heads
U||   and shoulders of two men.
U||   Now the submarine equipage came to a low place in the bottom, and even
U||   Mr. Buller shuddered as the water rose to his chin. Podington gave a
U||   howl of horror, and the horse, with high, uplifted head, was obliged to
U||   swim. At this moment a boy with a gun came strolling along the road,
U||   and hearing Mr. Podington’s cry, he cast his eyes over the water.
U||   Instinctively he raised his weapon to his shoulder, and then, in an
U||   instant, perceiving that the objects he beheld were not aquatic birds,
U||   he dropped his gun and ran yelling down the road toward the mill.
U||   But the hollow in the bottom was a narrow one, and when it was passed
U||   the depth of the water gradually decreased. The back of the horse came
U||   into view, the dashboard became visible, and the bodies and the spirits
U||   of the two men rapidly rose. Now there was vigorous splashing and
U||   tugging, and then a jet black horse, shining as if he had been newly
U||   varnished, pulled a dripping wagon containing two well-soaked men upon
U||   a shelving shore.
U||   “Oh, I am chilled to the bones!” said Podington.
U||   “I should think so,” replied his friend; “if you have got to be wet, it
U||   is a great deal pleasanter under the water.”
U||   There was a field-road on this side of the pond which Podington well
U||   knew, and proceeding along this they came to the bridge and got into
U||   the main road.
U||   “Now we must get home as fast as we can,” cried Podington, “or we shall
U||   both take cold. I wish I hadn’t lost my whip. Hi now! Get along!”
U||   Podington was now full of life and energy, his wheels were on the hard
U||   road, and he was himself again.
U||   When he found his head was turned toward his home, the horse set off at
U||   a great rate.
U||   “Hi there!” cried Podington. “I am so sorry I lost my whip.”
U||   “Whip!” said Buller, holding fast to the side of the seat; “surely you
U||   don’t want him to go any faster than this. And look here, William,” he
U||   added, “it seems to me we are much more likely to take cold in our wet
U||   clothes if we rush through the air in this way. Really, it seems to me
U||   that horse is running away.”
U||   “Not a bit of it,” cried Podington. “He wants to get home, and he wants
U||   his dinner. Isn’t he a fine horse? Look how he steps out!”
U||   “Steps out!” said Buller, “I think I’d like to step out myself. Don’t
U||   you think it would be wiser for me to walk home, William? That will
U||   warm me up.”
U||   “It will take you an hour,” said his friend. “Stay where you are, and
U||   I’ll have you in a dry suit of clothes in less than fifteen minutes.”
U||   “I tell you, William,” said Mr. Buller, as the two sat smoking after
U||   dinner, “what you ought to do; you should never go out driving without
U||   a life-preserver and a pair of oars; I always take them. It would make
U||   you feel safer.”
U||   Mr. Buller went home the next day, because Mr. Podington’s clothes did
U||   not fit him, and his own outdoor suit was so shrunken as to be
U||   uncomfortable. Besides, there was another reason, connected with the
U||   desire of horses to reach their homes, which prompted his return. But
U||   he had not forgotten his compact with his friend, and in the course of
U||   a week he wrote to Podington, inviting him to spend some days with him.
U||   Mr. Podington was a man of honor, and in spite of his recent
U||   unfortunate water experience he would not break his word. He went to
U||   Mr. Buller’s seaside home at the time appointed.
U||   Early on the morning after his arrival, before the family were up, Mr.
U||   Podington went out and strolled down to the edge of the bay. He went to
U||   look at Buller’s boat. He was well aware that he would be asked to take
U||   a sail, and as Buller had driven with him, it would be impossible for
U||   him to decline sailing with Buller; but he must see the boat. There was
U||   a train for his home at a quarter past seven; if he were not on the
U||   premises he could not be asked to sail. If Buller’s boat were a little,
U||   flimsy thing, he would take that train—but he would wait and see.
U||   There was only one small boat anchored near the beach, and a
U||   man—apparently a fisherman—informed Mr. Podington that it belonged to
U||   Mr. Buller. Podington looked at it eagerly; it was not very small and
U||   not flimsy.
U||   “Do you consider that a safe boat?” he asked the fisherman.
U||   “Safe?” replied the man. “You could not upset her if you tried. Look at
U||   her breadth of beam! You could go anywhere in that boat! Are you
U||   thinking of buying her?”
U||   The idea that he would think of buying a boat made Mr. Podington laugh.
U||   The information that it would be impossible to upset the little vessel
U||   had greatly cheered him, and he could laugh.
U||   Shortly after breakfast Mr. Buller, like a nurse with a dose of
U||   medicine, came to Mr. Podington with the expected invitation to take a
U||   sail.
U||   “Now, William,” said his host, “I understand perfectly your feeling
U||   about boats, and what I wish to prove to you is that it is a feeling
U||   without any foundation. I don’t want to shock you or make you nervous,
U||   so I am not going to take you out to-day on the bay in my boat. You are
U||   as safe on the bay as you would be on land—a little safer, perhaps,
U||   under certain circumstances, to which we will not allude—but still it
U||   is sometimes a little rough, and this, at first, might cause you some
U||   uneasiness, and so I am going to let you begin your education in the
U||   sailing line on perfectly smooth water. About three miles back of us
U||   there is a very pretty lake several miles long. It is part of the canal
U||   system which connects the town with the railroad. I have sent my boat
U||   to the town, and we can walk up there and go by the canal to the lake;
U||   it is only about three miles.”
U||   If he had to sail at all, this kind of sailing suited Mr. Podington. A
U||   canal, a quiet lake, and a boat which could not be upset. When they
U||   reached the town the boat was in the canal, ready for them.
U||   “Now,” said Mr. Buller, “you get in and make yourself comfortable. My
U||   idea is to hitch on to a canal-boat and be towed to the lake. The boats
U||   generally start about this time in the morning, and I will go and see
U||   about it.”
U||   Mr. Podington, under the direction of his friend, took a seat in the
U||   stern of the sailboat, and then he remarked:
U||   “Thomas, have you a life-preserver on board? You know I am not used to
U||   any kind of vessel, and I am clumsy. Nothing might happen to the boat,
U||   but I might trip and fall overboard, and I can’t swim.”
U||   “All right,” said Buller; “here’s a life-preserver, and you can put it
U||   on. I want you to feel perfectly safe. Now I will go and see about the
U||   tow.”
U||   But Mr. Buller found that the canal-boats would not start at their
U||   usual time; the loading of one of them was not finished, and he was
U||   informed that he might have to wait for an hour or more. This did not
U||   suit Mr. Buller at all, and he did not hesitate to show his annoyance.
U||   “I tell you, sir, what you can do,” said one of the men in charge of
U||   the boats; “if you don’t want to wait till we are ready to start, we’ll
U||   let you have a boy and a horse to tow you up to the lake. That won’t
U||   cost you much, and they’ll be back before we want ’em.”
U||   The bargain was made, and Mr. Buller joyfully returned to his boat with
U||   the intelligence that they were not to wait for the canal-boats. A long
U||   rope, with a horse attached to the other end of it, was speedily made
U||   fast to the boat, and with a boy at the head of the horse, they started
U||   up the canal.
U||   “Now this is the kind of sailing I like,” said Mr. Podington. “If I
U||   lived near a canal I believe I would buy a boat and train my horse to
U||   tow. I could have a long pair of rope-lines and drive him myself; then
U||   when the roads were rough and bad the canal would always be smooth.”
U||   “This is all very nice,” replied Mr. Buller, who sat by the tiller to
U||   keep the boat away from the bank, “and I am glad to see you in a boat
U||   under any circumstances. Do you know, William, that although I did not
U||   plan it, there could not have been a better way to begin your sailing
U||   education. Here we glide along, slowly and gently, with no possible
U||   thought of danger, for if the boat should suddenly spring a leak, as if
U||   it were the body of a wagon, all we would have to do would be to step
U||   on shore, and by the time you get to the end of the canal you will like
U||   this gentle motion so much that you will be perfectly ready to begin
U||   the second stage of your nautical education.”
U||   “Yes,” said Mr. Podington. “How long did you say this canal is?”
U||   “About three miles,” answered his friend. “Then we will go into the
U||   lock and in a few minutes we shall be on the lake.”
U||   “So far as I am concerned,” said Mr. Podington, “I wish the canal were
U||   twelve miles long. I cannot imagine anything pleasanter than this. If I
U||   lived anywhere near a canal—a long canal, I mean, this one is too
U||   short—I’d—”
U||   “Come, come now,” interrupted Buller. “Don’t be content to stay in the
U||   primary school just because it is easy. When we get on the lake I will
U||   show you that in a boat, with a gentle breeze, such as we are likely to
U||   have to-day, you will find the motion quite as pleasing, and ever so
U||   much more inspiriting. I should not be a bit surprised, William, if
U||   after you have been two or three times on the lake you will ask me—yes,
U||   positively ask me—to take you out on the bay!”
U||   Mr. Podington smiled, and leaning backward, he looked up at the
U||   beautiful blue sky.
U||   “You can’t give me anything better than this, Thomas,” said he; “but
U||   you needn’t think I am weakening; you drove with me, and I will sail
U||   with you.”
U||   The thought came into Buller’s mind that he had done both of these
U||   things with Podington, but he did not wish to call up unpleasant
U||   memories, and said nothing.
U||   About half a mile from the town there stood a small cottage where
U||   house-cleaning was going on, and on a fence, not far from the canal,
U||   there hung a carpet gaily adorned with stripes and spots of red and
U||   yellow.
U||   When the drowsy tow-horse came abreast of the house, and the carpet
U||   caught his eye, he suddenly stopped and gave a start toward the canal.
U||   Then, impressed with a horror of the glaring apparition, he gathered
U||   himself up, and with a bound dashed along the tow-path. The astounded
U||   boy gave a shout, but was speedily left behind. The boat of Mr. Buller
U||   shot forward as if she had been struck by a squall.
U||   The terrified horse sped on as if a red and yellow demon were after
U||   him. The boat bounded, and plunged, and frequently struck the grassy
U||   bank of the canal, as if it would break itself to pieces. Mr. Podington
U||   clutched the boom to keep himself from being thrown out, while Mr.
U||   Buller, both hands upon the tiller, frantically endeavored to keep the
U||   boat from the bank.
U||   “William!” he screamed, “he is running away with us; we shall be dashed
U||   to pieces! Can’t you get forward and cast off that line?”
U||   “What do you mean?” cried Podington, as the boom gave a great jerk as
U||   if it would break its fastenings and drag him overboard.
U||   “I mean untie the tow-line. We’ll be smashed if you don’t! I can’t
U||   leave this tiller. Don’t try to stand up; hold on to the boom and creep
U||   forward. Steady now, or you’ll be overboard!”
U||   Mr. Podington stumbled to the bow of the boat, his efforts greatly
U||   impeded by the big cork life-preserver tied under his arms, and the
U||   motion of the boat was so violent and erratic that he was obliged to
U||   hold on to the mast with one arm and to try to loosen the knot with the
U||   other; but there was a great strain on the rope, and he could do
U||   nothing with one hand.
U||   “Cut it! Cut it!” cried Mr. Buller.
U||   “I haven’t a knife,” replied Podington.
U||   Mr. Buller was terribly frightened; his boat was cutting through the
U||   water as never vessel of her class had sped since sail-boats were
U||   invented, and bumping against the bank as if she were a billiard-ball
U||   rebounding from the edge of a table. He forgot he was in a boat; he
U||   only knew that for the first time in his life he was in a runaway. He
U||   let go the tiller. It was of no use to him.
U||   “William,” he cried, “let us jump out the next time we are near enough
U||   to shore!”
U||   “Don’t do that! Don’t do that!” replied Podington. “Don’t jump out in a
U||   runaway; that is the way to get hurt. Stick to your seat, my boy; he
U||   can’t keep this up much longer. He’ll lose his wind!”
U||   Mr. Podington was greatly excited, but he was not frightened, as Buller
U||   was. He had been in a runaway before, and he could not help thinking
U||   how much better a wagon was than a boat in such a case.
U||   “If he were hitched up shorter and I had a snaffle-bit and a stout pair
U||   of reins,” thought he, “I could soon bring him up.”
U||   But Mr. Buller was rapidly losing his wits. The horse seemed to be
U||   going faster than ever. The boat bumped harder against the bank, and at
U||   one time Buller thought they could turn over.
U||   Suddenly a thought struck him.
U||   “William,” he shouted, “tip that anchor over the side! Throw it in, any
U||   way!”
U||   Mr. Podington looked about him, and, almost under his feet, saw the
U||   anchor. He did not instantly comprehend why Buller wanted it thrown
U||   overboard, but this was not a time to ask questions. The difficulties
U||   imposed by the life-preserver, and the necessity of holding on with one
U||   hand, interfered very much with his getting at the anchor and throwing
U||   it over the side, but at last he succeeded, and just as the boat threw
U||   up her bow as if she were about to jump on shore, the anchor went out
U||   and its line shot after it. There was an irregular trembling of the
U||   boat as the anchor struggled along the bottom of the canal; then there
U||   was a great shock; the boat ran into the bank and stopped; the tow-line
U||   was tightened like a guitar-string, and the horse, jerked back with
U||   great violence, came tumbling in a heap upon the ground.
U||   Instantly Mr. Podington was on the shore and running at the top of his
U||   speed toward the horse. The astounded animal had scarcely begun to
U||   struggle to his feet when Podington rushed upon him, pressed his head
U||   back to the ground, and sat upon it.
U||   “Hurrah!” he cried, waving his hat above his head. “Get out, Buller; he
U||   is all right now!”
U||   Presently Mr. Buller approached, very much shaken up.
U||   “All right?” he said. “I don’t call a horse flat in a road with a man
U||   on his head all right; but hold him down till we get him loose from my
U||   boat. That is the thing to do. William, cast him loose from the boat
U||   before you let him up! What will he do when he gets up?”
U||   “Oh. he’ll be quiet enough when he gets up,” said Podington. “But if
U||   you’ve got a knife you can cut his traces—-I mean that rope—but no, you
U||   needn’t. Here comes the boy. We’ll settle this business in very short
U||   order now.”
U||   When the horse was on his feet, and all connection between the animal
U||   and the boat had been severed, Mr. Podington looked at his friend.
U||   “Thomas,” said he, “you seem to have had a hard time of it. You have
U||   lost your hat and you look as if you had been in a wrestling-match.”
U||   “I have,” replied the other; “I wrestled with that tiller and I wonder
U||   it didn’t throw me out.”
U||   Now approached the boy. “Shall I hitch him on again, sir?” said he.
U||   “He’s quiet enough now.”
U||   “No,” cried Mr. Buller; “I want no more sailing after a horse, and,
U||   besides, we can’t go on the lake with that boat; she has been battered
U||   about so much that she must have opened a dozen seams. The best thing
U||   we can do is to walk home.”
U||   Mr. Podington agreed with his friend that walking home was the best
U||   thing they could do. The boat was examined and found to be leaking, but
U||   not very badly, and when her mast had been unshipped and everything had
U||   been made tight and right on board, she was pulled out of the way of
U||   tow-lines and boats, and made fast until she could be sent for from the
U||   town.
U||   Mr. Buller and Mr. Podington walked back toward the town. They had not
U||   gone very far when they met a party of boys, who, upon seeing them,
U||   burst into unseemly laughter.
U||   “Mister,” cried one of them, “you needn’t be afraid of tumbling into
U||   the canal. Why don’t you take off your life-preserver and let that
U||   other man put it on his head?”
U||   The two friends looked at each other and could not help joining in the
U||   laughter of the boys.
U||   “By George! I forgot all about this,” said Podington, as he unfastened
U||   the cork jacket. “It does look a little super-timid to wear a
U||   life-preserver just because one happens to be walking by the side of a
U||   canal.”
U||   Mr. Buller tied a handkerchief on his head, and Mr. Podington rolled up
U||   his life-preserver and carried it under his arm. Thus they reached the
U||   town, where Buller bought a hat, Podington dispensed with his bundle,
U||   and arrangements were made to bring back the boat.
U||   “Runaway in a sailboat!” exclaimed one of the canal boatmen when he had
U||   heard about the accident. “Upon my word! That beats anything that could
U||   happen to a man!”
U||   “No, it doesn’t,” replied Mr. Buller, quietly. “I have gone to the
U||   bottom in a foundered road-wagon.”
U||   The man looked at him fixedly.
U||   “Was you ever struck in the mud in a balloon?” he asked.
U||   “Not yet,” replied Mr. Buller.
U||   It required ten days to put Mr. Buller’s sailboat into proper
U||   condition, and for ten days Mr. Podington stayed with his friend, and
U||   enjoyed his visit very much. They strolled on the beach, they took long
U||   walks in the back country, they fished from the end of a pier, they
U||   smoked, they talked, and were happy and content.
U||   “Thomas,” said Mr. Podington, on the last evening of his stay, “I have
U||   enjoyed myself very much since I have been down here, and now, Thomas,
U||   if I were to come down again next summer, would you mind—would you
U||   mind, not——”
U||   “I would not mind it a bit,” replied Buller, promptly. “I’ll never so
U||   much as mention it; so you can come along without a thought of it. And
U||   since you have alluded to the subject, William,” he continued, “I’d
U||   like very much to come and see you again; you know my visit was a very
U||   short one this year. That is a beautiful country you live in. Such a
U||   variety of scenery, such an opportunity for walks and rambles! But,
U||   William, if you could only make up your mind not to——”
U||   “Oh, that is all right!” exclaimed Podington. “I do not need to make up
U||   my mind. You come to my house and you will never so much as hear of it.
U||   Here’s my hand upon it!”
U||   “And here’s mine!” said Mr. Buller.
U||   And they shook hands over a new compact.
