U||COLONEL STARBOTTLE FOR THE PLAINTIFF[65][23]
U||   By Bret Harte (1839–1902)
U||   It had been a day of triumph for Colonel Starbottle. First, for his
U||   personality, as it would have been difficult to separate the Colonel’s
U||   achievements from his individuality; second, for his oratorical
U||   abilities as a sympathetic pleader; and third, for his functions as the
U||   leading counsel for the Eureka Ditch Company versus the State of
U||   California. On his strictly legal performances in this issue I prefer
U||   not to speak; there were those who denied them, although the jury had
U||   accepted them in the face of the ruling of the half-amused,
U||   half-cynical Judge himself. For an hour they had laughed with the
U||   Colonel, wept with him, been stirred to personal indignation or
U||   patriotic exaltation by his passionate and lofty periods—what else
U||   could they do than give him their verdict? If it was alleged by some
U||   that the American eagle, Thomas Jefferson, and the Resolutions of ’98
U||   had nothing whatever to do with the contest of a ditch company over a
U||   doubtfully worded legislative document; that wholesale abuse of the
U||   State Attorney and his political motives had not the slightest
U||   connection with the legal question raised—it was, nevertheless,
U||   generally accepted that the losing party would have been only too glad
U||   to have the Colonel on their side. And Colonel Starbottle knew this,
U||   as, perspiring, florid, and panting, he rebuttoned the lower buttons of
U||   his blue frock-coat, which had become loosed in an oratorical spasm,
U||   and readjusted his old-fashioned, spotless shirt frill above it as he
U||   strutted from the courtroom amidst the hand-shakings and acclamations
U||   of his friends.
U||   And here an unprecedented thing occurred. The Colonel absolutely
U||   declined spirituous refreshment at the neighboring Palmetto Saloon, and
U||   declared his intention of proceeding directly to his office in the
U||   adjoining square. Nevertheless the Colonel quitted the building alone,
U||   and apparently unarmed except for his faithful gold-headed stick, which
U||   hung as usual from his forearm. The crowd gazed after him with
U||   undisguised admiration of this new evidence of his pluck. It was
U||   remembered also that a mysterious note had been handed to him at the
U||   conclusion of his speech—evidently a challenge from the State Attorney.
U||   It was quite plain that the Colonel—a practised duellist—was hastening
U||   home to answer it.
U||   But herein they were wrong. The note was in a female hand, and simply
U||   requested the Colonel to accord an interview with the writer at the
U||   Colonel’s office as soon as he left the court. But it was an engagement
U||   that the Colonel—as devoted to the fair sex as he was to the “code”—was
U||   no less prompt in accepting. He flicked away the dust from his spotless
U||   white trousers and varnished boots with his handkerchief, and settled
U||   his black cravat under his Byron collar as he neared his office. He was
U||   surprised, however, on opening the door of his private office to find
U||   his visitor already there; he was still more startled to find her
U||   somewhat past middle age and plainly attired. But the Colonel was
U||   brought up in a school of Southern politeness, already antique in the
U||   republic, and his bow of courtesy belonged to the epoch of his shirt
U||   frill and strapped trousers. No one could have detected his
U||   disappointment in his manner, albeit his sentences were short and
U||   incomplete. But the Colonel’s colloquial speech was apt to be
U||   fragmentary incoherencies of his larger oratorical utterances.
U||   “A thousand pardons—for—er—having kept a lady waiting—er!
U||   But—er—congratulations of friends—and—er—courtesy due to
U||   them—er—interfered with—though perhaps only heightened—by
U||   procrastination—pleasure of—ha!” And the Colonel completed his sentence
U||   with a gallant wave of his fat but white and well-kept hand.
U||   “Yes! I came to see you along o’ that speech of yours. I was in court.
U||   When I heard you gettin’ it off on that jury, I says to myself that’s
U||   the kind o’ lawyer I want. A man that’s flowery and convincin’! Just
U||   the man to take up our case.”
U||   “Ah! It’s a matter of business, I see,” said the Colonel, inwardly
U||   relieved, but externally careless. “And—er—may I ask the nature of the
U||   case?”
U||   “Well! it’s a breach-o’-promise suit,” said the visitor, calmly.
U||   If the Colonel had been surprised before, he was now really startled,
U||   and with an added horror that required all his politeness to conceal.
U||   Breach-of-promise cases were his peculiar aversion. He had always held
U||   them to be a kind of litigation which could have been obviated by the
U||   prompt killing of the masculine offender—in which case he would have
U||   gladly defended the killer. But a suit for damages!—damages!—with the
U||   reading of love-letters before a hilarious jury and court, was against
U||   all his instincts. His chivalry was outraged; his sense of humor was
U||   small—and in the course of his career he had lost one or two important
U||   cases through an unexpected development of this quality in a jury.
U||   The woman had evidently noticed his hesitation, but mistook its cause.
U||   “It ain’t me—but my darter.”
U||   The Colonel recovered his politeness. “Ah! I am relieved, my dear
U||   madam! I could hardly conceive a man ignorant enough to—er—er—throw
U||   away such evident good fortune—or base enough to deceive the
U||   trustfulness of womanhood—matured and experienced only in the chivalry
U||   of our sex, ha!”
U||   The woman smiled grimly. “Yes!—it’s my darter, Zaidee Hooker—so ye
U||   might spare some of them pretty speeches for her—before the jury.”
U||   The Colonel winced slightly before this doubtful prospect, but smiled.
U||   “Ha! Yes!—certainly—the jury. But—er—my dear lady, need we go as far as
U||   that? Cannot this affair be settled—er—out of court? Could not
U||   this—er—individual—be admonished—told that he must give
U||   satisfaction—personal satisfaction—for his dastardly conduct—to
U||   —er—near relative—or even valued personal friend? The—er—arrangements
U||   necessary for that purpose I myself would undertake.”
U||   He was quite sincere; indeed, his small black eyes shone with that fire
U||   which a pretty woman or an “affair of honor” could alone kindle. The
U||   visitor stared vacantly at him, and said, slowly:
U||   “And what good is that goin’ to do us?”
U||   “Compel him to—er—perform his promise,” said the Colonel, leaning back
U||   in his chair.
U||   “Ketch him doin’ it!” said the woman, scornfully. “No—that ain’t wot
U||   we’re after. We must make him pay! Damages—and nothin’ short o’ that.”
U||   The Colonel bit his lip. “I suppose,” he said, gloomily, “you have
U||   documentary evidence—written promises and protestations—er—er—
U||   love-letters, in fact?”
U||   “No—nary a letter! Ye see, that’s jest it—and that’s where you come in.
U||   You’ve got to convince that jury yourself. You’ve got to show what it
U||   is—tell the whole story your own way. Lord! to a man like you that’s
U||   nothin’.”
U||   Startling as this admission might have been to any other lawyer,
U||   Starbottle was absolutely relieved by it. The absence of any
U||   mirth-provoking correspondence, and the appeal solely to his own powers
U||   of persuasion, actually struck his fancy. He lightly put aside the
U||   compliment with a wave of his white hand.
U||   “Of course,” said the Colonel, confidently, “there is strongly
U||   presumptive and corroborative evidence? Perhaps you can give me—er—a
U||   brief outline of the affair?”
U||   “Zaidee kin do that straight enough, I reckon,” said the woman; “what I
U||   want to know first is, kin you take the case?”
U||   The Colonel did not hesitate; his curiosity was piqued. “I certainly
U||   can. I have no doubt your daughter will put me in possession of
U||   sufficient facts and details—to constitute what we call—er—a brief.”
U||   “She kin be brief enough—or long enough—for the matter of that,” said
U||   the woman, rising. The Colonel accepted this implied witticism with a
U||   smile.
U||   “And when may I have the pleasure of seeing her?” he asked, politely.
U||   “Well, I reckon as soon as I can trot out and call her. She’s just
U||   outside, meanderin’ in the road—kinder shy, ye know, at first.”
U||   She walked to the door. The astounded Colonel nevertheless gallantly
U||   accompanied her as she stepped out into the street and called, shrilly,
U||   “You Zaidee!”
U||   A young girl here apparently detached herself from a tree and the
U||   ostentatious perusal of an old election poster, and sauntered down
U||   towards the office door. Like her mother, she was plainly dressed;
U||   unlike her, she had a pale, rather refined face, with a demure mouth
U||   and downcast eyes. This was all the Colonel saw as he bowed profoundly
U||   and led the way into his office, for she accepted his salutations
U||   without lifting her head. He helped her gallantly to a chair, on which
U||   she seated herself sideways, somewhat ceremoniously, with her eyes
U||   following the point of her parasol as she traced a pattern on the
U||   carpet. A second chair offered to the mother that lady, however,
U||   declined. “I reckon to leave you and Zaidee together to talk it out,”
U||   she said; turning to her daughter, she added, “Jest you tell him all,
U||   Zaidee,” and before the Colonel could rise again, disappeared from the
U||   room. In spite of his professional experience, Starbottle was for a
U||   moment embarrassed. The young girl, however, broke the silence without
U||   looking up.
U||   “Adoniram K. Hotchkiss,” she began, in a monotonous voice, as if it
U||   were a recitation addressed to the public, “first began to take notice
U||   of me a year ago. Arter that—off and on——”
U||   “One moment,” interrupted the astounded Colonel; “do you mean Hotchkiss
U||   the President of the Ditch Company?” He had recognized the name of a
U||   prominent citizen—a rigid ascetic, taciturn, middle-aged man—a
U||   deacon—and more than that, the head of the company he had just
U||   defended. It seemed inconceivable.
U||   “That’s him,” she continued, with eyes still fixed on the parasol and
U||   without changing her monotonous tone—“off and on ever since. Most of
U||   the time at the Free-Will Baptist church—at morning service,
U||   prayer-meetings, and such. And at home—outside—er—in the road.”
U||   “Is it this gentleman—Mr. Adoniram K. Hotchkiss—who—er—promised
U||   marriage?” stammered the Colonel.
U||   “Yes.”
U||   The Colonel shifted uneasily in his chair. “Most extraordinary! for—you
U||   see—my dear young lady—this becomes—a—er—most delicate affair.”
U||   “That’s what maw said,” returned the young woman, simply, yet with the
U||   faintest smile playing around her demure lips and downcast cheek.
U||   “I mean,” said the Colonel, with a pained yet courteous smile, “that
U||   this—er—gentleman—is in fact—er—one of my clients.”
U||   “That’s what maw said, too, and of course your knowing him will make it
U||   all the easier for you,” said the young woman.
U||   A slight flush crossed the Colonel’s cheek as he returned quickly and a
U||   little stiffly, “On the contrary—er—it may make it impossible for me
U||   to—er—act in this matter.”
U||   The girl lifted her eyes. The Colonel held his breath as the long
U||   lashes were raised to his level. Even to an ordinary observer that
U||   sudden revelation of her eyes seemed to transform her face with subtle
U||   witchery. They were large, brown, and soft, yet filled with an
U||   extraordinary penetration and prescience. They were the eyes of an
U||   experienced woman of thirty fixed in the face of a child. What else the
U||   Colonel saw there Heaven only knows! He felt his inmost secrets plucked
U||   from him—his whole soul laid bare—his vanity, belligerency,
