U||   impertinent and irrelevant to the issue.”
U||   The Judge cast an inquiring look at Colonel Starbottle.
U||   “May it please the Court,” returned Colonel Starbottle with dignity,
U||   ignoring the counsel, “the defendant’s counsel will observe that he is
U||   already furnished with the matter—which I regret to say he has
U||   treated—in the presence of the Court—and of his client, a deacon of the
U||   church—with—er—-great superciliousness. When I state to your Honor that
U||   the books in question are hymn-books and copies of the Holy Scriptures,
U||   and that they are for the instruction of the jury, to whom I shall have
U||   to refer them in the course of my opening, I believe I am within my
U||   rights.”
U||   “The act is certainly unprecedented,” said the Judge, dryly, “but
U||   unless the counsel for the plaintiff expects the jury to sing from
U||   these hymn-books, their introduction is not improper, and I cannot
U||   admit the objection. As defendant’s counsel are furnished with copies
U||   also, they cannot plead ‘surprise,’ as in the introduction of new
U||   matter, and as plaintiff’s counsel relies evidently upon the jury’s
U||   attention to his opening, he would not be the first person to distract
U||   it.” After a pause he added, addressing the Colonel, who remained
U||   standing, “The Court is with you, sir; proceed.”
U||   But the Colonel remained motionless and statuesque, with folded arms.
U||   “I have overruled the objection,” repeated the Judge; “you may go on.”
U||   “I am waiting, your Honor, for the—er—withdrawal by the defendant’s
U||   counsel of the word ‘tampering,’ as refers to myself, and of
U||   ‘impertinent,’ as refers to the sacred volumes.”
U||   “The request is a proper one, and I have no doubt will be acceded to,”
U||   returned the Judge, quietly. The defendant’s counsel rose and mumbled a
U||   few words of apology, and the incident closed. There was, however, a
U||   general feeling that the Colonel had in some way “scored,” and if his
U||   object had been to excite the greatest curiosity about the books, he
U||   had made his point.
U||   But impassive of his victory, he inflated his chest, with his right
U||   hand in the breast of his buttoned coat, and began. His usual high
U||   color had paled slightly, but the small pupils of his prominent eyes
U||   glittered like steel. The young girl leaned forward in her chair with
U||   an attention so breathless, a sympathy so quick, and an admiration so
U||   artless and unconscious that in an instant she divided with the speaker
U||   the attention of the whole assemblage. It was very hot; the court was
U||   crowded to suffocation; even the open windows revealed a crowd of faces
U||   outside the building, eagerly following the Colonel’s words.
U||   He would remind the jury that only a few weeks ago he stood there as
U||   the advocate of a powerful company, then represented by the present
U||   defendant. He spoke then as the champion of strict justice against
U||   legal oppression; no less should he to-day champion the cause of the
U||   unprotected and the comparatively defenseless—save for that paramount
U||   power which surrounds beauty and innocence—even though the plaintiff of
U||   yesterday was the defendant of to-day. As he approached the court a
U||   moment ago he had raised his eyes and beheld the starry flag flying
U||   from its dome—and he knew that glorious banner was a symbol of the
U||   perfect equality, under the Constitution, of the rich and the poor, the
U||   strong and the weak—an equality which made the simple citizen taken
U||   from the plough in the veld, the pick in the gulch, or from behind the
U||   counter in the mining town, who served on that jury, the equal arbiters
U||   of justice with that highest legal luminary whom they were proud to
U||   welcome on the bench to-day. The Colonel paused, with a stately bow to
U||   the impassive Judge. It was this, he continued, which lifted his heart
U||   as he approached the building. And yet—he had entered it with an
U||   uncertain—he might almost say—a timid step. And why? He knew,
U||   gentlemen, he was about to confront a profound—aye! a sacred
U||   responsibility! Those hymn-books and holy writings handed to the jury
U||   were not, as his Honor surmised, for the purpose of enabling the jury
U||   to indulge in—er—preliminary choral exercise! He might, indeed, say
U||   “alas not!” They were the damning, incontrovertible proofs of the
U||   perfidy of the defendant. And they would prove as terrible a warning to
U||   him as the fatal characters upon Belshazzar’s wall. There was a strong
U||   sensation. Hotchkiss turned a sallow green. His lawyers assumed a
U||   careless smile.
U||   It was his duty to tell them that this was not one of those ordinary
U||   “breach-of-promise” cases which were too often the occasion of ruthless
U||   mirth and indecent levity in the courtroom. The jury would find nothing
U||   of that here, There were no love-letters with the epithets of
U||   endearment, nor those mystic crosses and ciphers which, he had been
U||   credibly informed, chastely hid the exchange of those mutual caresses
U||   known as “kisses.” There was no cruel tearing of the veil from those
U||   sacred privacies of the human affection—there was no forensic shouting
U||   out of those fond confidences meant only for one. But there was, he was
U||   shocked to say, a new sacrilegious intrusion. The weak pipings of Cupid
U||   were mingled with the chorus of the saints—the sanctity of the temple
U||   known as the “meeting-house” was desecrated by proceedings more in
U||   keeping with the shrine of Venus—and the inspired writings themselves
U||   were used as the medium of amatory and wanton flirtation by the
U||   defendant in his sacred capacity as Deacon.
U||   The Colonel artistically paused after this thunderous denunciation. The
U||   jury turned eagerly to the leaves of the hymn-books, but the larger
U||   gaze of the audience remained fixed upon the speaker and the girl, who
U||   sat in rapt admiration of his periods. After the hush, the Colonel
U||   continued in a lower and sadder voice: “There are, perhaps, few of us
U||   here, gentlemen—with the exception of the defendant—who can arrogate to
U||   themselves the title of regular churchgoers, or to whom these humbler
U||   functions of the prayer-meeting, the Sunday-school, and the Bible class
U||   are habitually familiar. Yet”—more solemnly—“down in your hearts is the
U||   deep conviction of our short-comings and failings, and a laudable
U||   desire that others at least should profit by the teachings we neglect.
U||   Perhaps,” he continued, closing his eyes dreamily, “there is not a man
U||   here who does not recall the happy days of his boyhood, the rustic
U||   village spire, the lessons shared with some artless village maiden,
U||   with whom he later sauntered, hand in hand, through the woods, as the
U||   simple rhyme rose upon their lips,
U||   Always make it a point to have it a rule
U||   Never to be late at the Sabbath-school.
U||   He would recall the strawberry feasts, the welcome annual picnic,
U||   redolent with hunks of gingerbread and sarsaparilla. How would they
U||   feel to know that these sacred recollections were now forever profaned
U||   in their memory by the knowledge that the defendant was capable of
