U||   these disks may be bought for five cents a dozen—or at considerably
U||   less than one half-cent for the single lozenge. Yes, gentlemen, the
U||   words ‘I love you!‘—the oldest legend of all; the refrain, ‘when the
U||   morning stars sang together’—were presented to the plaintiff by a
U||   medium so insignificant that there is, happily, no coin in the republic
U||   low enough to represent its value.
U||   “I shall prove to you, gentlemen of the jury,” said the Colonel,
U||   solemnly, drawing a Bible from his coat-tail pocket, “that the
U||   defendant, for the last twelve months, conducted an amatory
U||   correspondence with the plaintiff by means of underlined words of
U||   sacred writ and church psalmody, such as ‘beloved,’ ‘precious,’ and
U||   ‘dearest,’ occasionally appropriating whole passages which seemed
U||   apposite to his tender passion. I shall call your attention to one of
U||   them. The defendant, while professing to be a total abstainer—a man
U||   who, in my own knowledge, has refused spirituous refreshment as an
U||   inordinate weakness of the flesh, with shameless hypocrisy underscores
U||   with his pencil the following passage and presents it to the plaintiff.
U||   The gentlemen of the jury will find it in the Song of Solomon, page
U||   548, chapter II, verse 5.” After a pause, in which the rapid rustling
U||   of leaves was heard in the jury-box, Colonel Starbottle declaimed in a
U||   pleading, stentorian voice, “‘Stay me with —er—flagons, comfort me
U||   with—er—apples—for I am—er—sick of love.’ Yes, gentlemen!—yes, you may
U||   well turn from those accusing pages and look at the double-faced
U||   defendant. He desires—to—er—be —‘stayed with flagons’! I am not aware,
U||   at present, what kind of liquor is habitually dispensed at these
U||   meetings, and for which the defendant so urgently clamored; but it will
U||   be my duty before this trial is over to discover it, if I have to
U||   summon every barkeeper in this district. For the moment, I will simply
U||   call your attention to the quantity. It is not a single drink that the
U||   defendant asks for—not a glass of light and generous wine, to be shared
U||   with his inamorata—but a number of flagons or vessels, each possibly
U||   holding a pint measure—for himself!”
U||   The smile of the audience had become a laugh. The Judge looked up
U||   warningly, when his eye caught the fact that the Colonel had again
U||   winced at this mirth. He regarded him seriously. Mr. Hotchkiss’s
U||   counsel had joined in the laugh affectedly, but Hotchkiss himself was
U||   ashy pale. There was also a commotion in the jury-box, a hurried
U||   turning over of leaves, and an excited discussion.
U||   “The gentlemen of the jury,” said the Judge, with official gravity,
U||   “will please keep order and attend only to the speeches of counsel. Any
U||   discussion here is irregular and premature—and must be reserved for the
U||   jury-room—after they have retired.”
U||   The foreman of the jury struggled to his feet. He was a powerful man,
U||   with a good-humored face, and, in spite of his unfelicitous nickname of
U||   “The Bone-Breaker,” had a kindly, simple, but somewhat emotional
U||   nature. Nevertheless, it appeared as if he were laboring under some
U||   powerful indignation.
U||   “Can we ask a question, Judge?” he said, respectfully, although his
U||   voice had the unmistakable Western-American ring in it, as of one who
U||   was unconscious that he could be addressing any but his peers.
U||   “Yes,” said the Judge, good-humoredly.
U||   “We’re finding in this yere piece, out of which the Kernel hes just bin
U||   a-quotin’, some language that me and my pardners allow hadn’t orter to
U||   be read out afore a young lady in court—and we want to know of you—ez a
U||   fair-minded and impartial man—ef this is the reg’lar kind o’ book given
U||   to gals and babies down at the meetin’-house.”
U||   “The jury will please follow the counsel’s speech, without comment,”
U||   said the Judge, briefly, fully aware that the defendant’s counsel would
U||   spring to his feet, as he did promptly. “The Court will allow us to
U||   explain to the gentlemen that the language they seem to object to has
U||   been accepted by the best theologians for the last thousand years as
U||   being purely mystic. As I will explain later, those are merely symbols
U||   of the Church—”
U||   “Of wot?” interrupted the foreman, in deep scorn.
U||   “Of the Church!”
U||   “We ain’t askin’ any questions o’ you—and we ain’t takin’ any answers,”
U||   said the foreman, sitting down promptly.
U||   “I must insist,” said the Judge, sternly, “that the plaintiff’s counsel
U||   be allowed to continue his opening without interruption. You” (to
U||   defendant’s counsel) “will have your opportunity to reply later.”
U||   The counsel sank down in his seat with the bitter conviction that the
U||   jury was manifestly against him, and the case as good as lost. But his
U||   face was scarcely as disturbed as his client’s, who, in great
U||   agitation, had begun to argue with him wildly, and was apparently
U||   pressing some point against the lawyer’s vehement opposal. The
U||   Colonel’s murky eyes brightened as he still stood erect with his hand
U||   thrust in his breast.
U||   “It will be put to you, gentlemen, when the counsel on the other side
U||   refrains from mere interruption and confines himself to reply, that my
U||   unfortunate client has no action—no remedy at law—because there were no
U||   spoken words of endearment. But, gentlemen, it will depend upon you to
U||   say what are and what are not articulate expressions of love. We all
U||   know that among the lower animals, with whom you may possibly be called
U||   upon to classify the defendant, there are certain signals more or less
U||   harmonious, as the case may be. The ass brays, the horse neighs, the
U||   sheep bleats—the feathered denizens of the grove call to their mates in
U||   more musical roundelays. These are recognized facts, gentlemen, which
U||   you yourselves, as dwellers among nature in this beautiful land, are
U||   all cognizant of. They are facts that no one would deny—and we should
U||   have a poor opinion of the ass who, at—er—such a supreme moment, would
U||   attempt to suggest that his call was unthinking and without
U||   significance. But, gentlemen, I shall prove to you that such was the
U||   foolish, self-convicting custom of the defendant. With the greatest
U||   reluctance, and the—er—greatest pain, I succeeded in wresting from the
U||   maidenly modesty of my fair client the innocent confession that the
U||   defendant had induced her to correspond with him in these methods.
U||   Picture to yourself, gentlemen, the lonely moonlight road beside the
U||   widow’s humble cottage. It is a beautiful night, sanctified to the
U||   affections, and the innocent girl is leaning from her casement.
U||   Presently there appears upon the road a slinking, stealthy figure—the
U||   defendant, on his way to church. True to the instruction she has
U||   received from him, her lips part in the musical utterance” (the Colonel
U||   lowered his voice in a faint falsetto, presumably in fond imitation of
U||   his fair client),“‘Kerree!’ Instantly the night became resonant with
U||   the impassioned reply” (the Colonel here lifted his voice in stentorian
U||   tones), “‘Kerrow.’ Again, as he passes, rises the soft ‘Kerree’; again,
U||   as his form is lost in the distance, comes back the deep ‘Kerrow.’”
U||   A burst of laughter, long, loud, and irrepressible, struck the whole
U||   courtroom, and before the Judge could lift his half-composed face and
U||   take his handkerchief from his mouth, a faint “Kerree” from some
U||   unrecognized obscurity of the courtroom was followed by a loud “Kerrow”
U||   from some opposite locality. “The sheriff will clear the court,” said
U||   the Judge, sternly; but alas, as the embarrassed and choking officials
U||   rushed hither and thither, a soft “Kerree” from the spectators at the
U||   window, outside the courthouse, was answered by a loud chorus of
U||   “Kerrows” from the opposite windows, filled with onlookers. Again the
U||   laughter arose everywhere—even the fair plaintiff herself sat convulsed
U||   behind her handkerchief.
