U||   And then the Judge, looking up, saw what no one else in the court had
U||   seen—that the Colonel was sincere and in earnest; that what he had
U||   conceived to be the pleader’s most perfect acting, and most elaborate
U||   irony, were the deep, serious, mirthless convictions of a man without
U||   the least sense of humor. There was a touch of this respect in the
U||   Judge’s voice as he said to him, gently, “You may proceed, Colonel
U||   Starbottle.”
U||   “I thank your Honor,” said the Colonel, slowly, “for recognizing and
U||   doing all in your power to prevent an interruption that, during my
U||   thirty years’ experience at the bar, I have never yet been subjected to
U||   without the privilege of holding the instigators thereof
U||   responsible—personally responsible. It is possibly my fault that I have
U||   failed, oratorically, to convey to the gentlemen of the jury the full
U||   force and significance of the defendant’s signals. I am aware that my
U||   voice is singularly deficient in producing either the dulcet tones of
U||   my fair client or the impassioned vehemence of the defendant’s repose.
U||   I will,” continued the Colonel, with a fatigued but blind fatuity that
U||   ignored the hurriedly knit brows and warning eyes of the Judge, “try
U||   again. The note uttered by my client” (lowering his voice to the
U||   faintest of falsettos) “was ‘Kerree’; the response was ‘Kerrow’”—and
U||   the Colonel’s voice fairly shook the dome above him.
U||   Another uproar of laughter followed this apparently audacious
U||   repetition, but was interrupted by an unlooked-for incident. The
U||   defendant rose abruptly, and tearing himself away from the withholding
U||   hand and pleading protestations of his counsel, absolutely fled from
U||   the courtroom, his appearance outside being recognized by a prolonged
U||   “Kerrow” from the bystanders, which again and again followed him in the
U||   distance. In the momentary silence which followed, the Colonel’s voice
