U||THE DUPLICITY OF HARGRAVES[67][24]
U||   By O. Henry (1862–1910)
U||   When Major Pendleton Talbot, of Mobile, sir, and his daughter, Miss
U||   Lydia Talbot, came to Washington to reside, they selected for a
U||   boarding place a house that stood fifty yards back from one of the
U||   quietest avenues. It was an old-fashioned brick building, with a
U||   portico upheld by tall white pillars. The yard was shaded by stately
U||   locusts and elms, and a catalpa tree in season rained its pink and
U||   white blossoms upon the grass. Rows of high box bushes lined the fence
U||   and walks. It was the Southern style and aspect of the place that
U||   pleased the eyes of the Talbots.
U||   In this pleasant private boarding house they engaged rooms, including a
U||   study for Major Talbot, who was adding the finishing chapters to his
U||   book, Anecdotes and Reminiscences of the Alabama Army, Bench, and Bar.
U||   Major Talbot was of the old, old South. The present day had little
U||   interest or excellence in his eyes. His mind lived in that period
U||   before the Civil War when the Talbots owned thousands of acres of fine
U||   cotton land and the slaves to till them; when the family mansion was
U||   the scene of princely hospitality, and drew its guests from the
U||   aristocracy of the South. Out of that period he had brought all its old
U||   pride and scruples of honor, an antiquated and punctilious politeness,
U||   and (you would think) its wardrobe.
U||   Such clothes were surely never made within fifty years. The Major was
U||   tall, but whenever he made that wonderful, archaic genuflexion he
U||   called a bow, the corners of his frock coat swept the floor. That
U||   garment was a surprise even to Washington, which has long ago ceased to
U||   shy at the frocks and broad-brimmed hats of Southern Congressmen. One
U||   of the boarders christened it a “Father Hubbard,” and it certainly was
U||   high in the waist and full in the skirt.
U||   But the Major, with all his queer clothes, his immense area of plaited,
U||   raveling shirt bosom, and the little black string tie with the bow
U||   always slipping on one side, both was smiled at and liked in Mrs.
U||   Vardeman’s select boarding house. Some of the young department clerks
U||   would often “string him,” as they called it, getting him started upon
U||   the subject dearest to him—the traditions and history of his beloved
U||   Southland. During his talks he would quote freely from the Anecdotes
U||   and Reminiscences. But they were very careful not to let him see their
U||   designs, for in spite of his sixty-eight years he could make the
U||   boldest of them uncomfortable under the steady regard of his piercing
U||   gray eyes.
U||   Miss Lydia was a plump, little old maid of thirty-five, with smoothly
U||   drawn, tightly twisted hair that made her look still older.
U||   Old-fashioned, too, she was; but antebellum glory did not radiate from
U||   her as it did from the Major. She possessed a thrifty common sense, and
U||   it was she who handled the finances of the family, and met all comers
U||   when there were bills to pay. The Major regarded board bills and wash
U||   bills as contemptible nuisances. They kept coming in so persistently
U||   and so often. Why, the Major wanted to know, could they not be filed
U||   and paid in a lump sum at some convenient period—say when the Anecdotes
U||   and Reminiscences had been published and paid for? Miss Lydia would
U||   calmly go on with her sewing and say, “We’ll pay as we go as long as
U||   the money lasts, and then perhaps they’ll have to lump it.”
U||   Most of Mrs. Vardeman’s boarders were away during the day, being nearly
U||   all department clerks and business men; but there was one of them who
U||   was about the house a great deal from morning to night. This was a
U||   young man named Henry Hopkins Hargraves—every one in the house
U||   addressed him by his full name—who was engaged at one of the popular
U||   vaudeville theaters. Vaudeville has risen to such a respectable plane
U||   in the last few years, and Mr. Hargraves was such a modest and
U||   well-mannered person, that Mrs. Vardeman could find no objection to
U||   enrolling him upon her list of boarders.
U||   At the theater Hargraves was known as an all-round dialect comedian,
U||   having a large repertoire of German, Irish, Swede, and black-face
U||   specialties. But Mr. Hargraves was ambitious, and often spoke of his
U||   great desire to succeed in legitimate comedy.
U||   This young man appeared to conceive a strong fancy for Major Talbot.
U||   Whenever that gentleman would begin his Southern reminiscences, or
U||   repeat some of the liveliest of the anecdotes, Hargraves could always
U||   be found, the most attentive among his listeners.
U||   For a time the Major showed an inclination to discourage the advances
U||   of the “play actor,” as he privately termed him; but soon the young
U||   man’s agreeable manner and indubitable appreciation of the old
U||   gentleman’s stories completely won him over.
U||   It was not long before the two were like old chums. The Major set apart
U||   each afternoon to read to him the manuscript of his book. During the
U||   anecdotes Hargraves never failed to laugh at exactly the right point.
U||   The Major was moved to declare to Miss Lydia one day that young
U||   Hargraves possessed remarkable perception and a gratifying respect for
U||   the old régime. And when it came to talking of those old days—if Major
U||   Talbot liked to talk, Mr. Hargraves was entranced to listen.
U||   Like almost all old people who talk of the past, the Major loved to
U||   linger over details. In describing the splendid, almost royal, days of
U||   the old planters, he would hesitate until he had recalled the name of
U||   the negro who held his horse, or the exact date of certain minor
U||   happenings, or the number of bales of cotton raised in such a year; but
U||   Hargraves never grew impatient or lost interest. On the contrary, he
U||   would advance questions on a variety of subjects connected with the
U||   life of that time, and he never failed to extract ready replies.
U||   The fox hunts, the ’possum suppers, the hoe-downs and jubilees in the
U||   negro quarters, the banquets in the plantation-house hall, when
U||   invitations went for fifty miles around; the occasional feuds with the
U||   neighboring gentry; the Major’s duel with Rathbone Culbertson about
U||   Kitty Chalmers, who afterward married a Thwaite of South Carolina; and
U||   private yacht races for fabulous sums on Mobile Bay; the quaint
U||   beliefs, improvident habits, and loyal virtues of the old slaves—all
U||   these were subjects that held both the Major and Hargraves absorbed for
U||   hours at a time.
U||   Sometimes, at night, when the young man would be coming upstairs to his
U||   room after his turn at the theater was over, the Major would appear at
U||   the door of his study and beckon archly to him. Going in, Hargraves
U||   would find a little table set with a decanter, sugar bowl, fruit, and a
U||   big bunch of fresh green mint.
U||   “It occurred to me,” the Major would begin—he was always
U||   ceremonious—“that perhaps you might have found your duties at the—at
U||   your place of occupation—sufficiently arduous to enable you, Mr.
U||   Hargraves, to appreciate what the poet might well have had in his mind
U||   when he wrote, ‘tired Nature’s sweet restorer’—one of our Southern
U||   juleps.”
U||   It was a fascination to Hargraves to watch him make it. He took rank
U||   among artists when he began, and he never varied the process. With what
U||   delicacy he bruised the mint; with what exquisite nicety he estimated
U||   the ingredients; with what solicitous care he capped the compound with
U||   the scarlet fruit glowing against the dark green fringe! And then the
U||   hospitality and grace with which he offered it, after the selected oat
U||   straws had been plunged into its tinkling depths!
U||   After about four months in Washington, Miss Lydia discovered one
U||   morning that they were almost without money. The Anecdotes and
U||   Reminiscences was completed, but publishers had not jumped at the
U||   collected gems of Alabama sense and wit. The rental of a small house
U||   which they still owned in Mobile was two months in arrears. Their board
U||   money for the month would be due in three days. Miss Lydia called her
U||   father to a consultation.
U||   “No money?” said he with a surprised look. “It is quite annoying to be
U||   called on so frequently for these petty sums, Really, I—”
U||   The Major searched his pockets. He found only a two-dollar bill, which
U||   he returned to his vest pocket.
U||   “I must attend to this at once, Lydia,” he said. “Kindly get me my
U||   umbrella and I will go downtown immediately. The congressman from our
U||   district, General Fulghum, assured me some days ago that he would use
U||   his influence to get my book published at an early date. I will go to
U||   his hotel at once and see what arrangement has been made.”
U||   With a sad little smile Miss Lydia watched him button his “Father
U||   Hubbard” and depart, pausing at the door, as he always did, to bow
U||   profoundly.
U||   That evening, at dark, he returned. It seemed that Congressman Fulghum
U||   had seen the publisher who had the Major’s manuscript for reading. That
U||   person had said that if the anecdotes, etc., were carefully pruned down
U||   about one-half, in order to eliminate the sectional and class prejudice
U||   with which the book was dyed from end to end, he might consider its
U||   publication.
U||   The Major was in a white heat of anger, but regained his equanimity,
U||   according to his code of manners, as soon as he was in Miss Lydia’s
U||   presence.
U||   “We must have money,” said Miss Lydia, with a little wrinkle above her
U||   nose. “Give me the two dollars, and I will telegraph to Uncle Ralph for
U||   some to-night.”
U||   The Major drew a small envelope from his upper vest pocket and tossed
U||   it on the table.
U||   “Perhaps it was injudicious,” he said mildly, “but the sum was so
U||   merely nominal that I bought tickets to the theater to-night. It’s a
U||   new war drama, Lydia. I thought you would be pleased to witness its
U||   first production in Washington. I am told that the South has very fair
U||   treatment in the play. I confess I should like to see the performance
U||   myself.”
U||   Miss Lydia threw up her hands in silent despair.
U||   Still, as the tickets were bought, they might as well be used. So that
U||   evening, as they sat in the theater listening to the lively overture,
U||   even Miss Lydia was minded to relegate their troubles, for the hour, to
U||   second place. The Major, in spotless linen, with his extraordinary coat
U||   showing only where it was closely buttoned, and his white hair smoothly
U||   roached, looked really fine and distinguished. The curtain went up on
U||   the first act of A Magnolia Flower, revealing a typical Southern
U||   plantation scene. Major Talbot betrayed some interest.
U||   “Oh, see!” exclaimed Miss Lydia, nudging his arm, and pointing to her
U||   program.
U||   The Major put on his glasses and read the line in the cast of
U||   characters that her fingers indicated.
U||   Col. Webster Calhoun .... Mr. Hopkins Hargraves.
U||   “It’s our Mr. Hargraves,” said Miss Lydia. “It must be his first
U||   appearance in what he calls ‘the legitimate.’ I’m so glad for him.”
U||   Not until the second act did Col. Webster Calhoun appear upon the
U||   stage. When he made his entry Major Talbot gave an audible sniff,
U||   glared at him, and seemed to freeze solid. Miss Lydia uttered a little,
U||   ambiguous squeak and crumpled her program in her hand. For Colonel
U||   Calhoun was made up as nearly resembling Major Talbot as one pea does
U||   another. The long, thin white hair, curly at the ends, the aristocratic
U||   beak of a nose, the crumpled, wide, raveling shirt front, the string
U||   tie, with the bow nearly under one ear, were almost exactly duplicated.
U||   And then, to clinch the imitation, he wore the twin to the Major’s
U||   supposed to be unparalleled coat. High-collared, baggy, empire-waisted,
U||   ample-skirted, hanging a foot lower in front than behind, the garment
U||   could have been designed from no other pattern. From then on, the Major
U||   and Miss Lydia sat bewitched, and saw the counterfeit presentment of a
U||   haughty Talbot “dragged,” as the Major afterward expressed it, “through
U||   the slanderous mire of a corrupt stage.”
U||   Mr. Hargraves had used his opportunities well. He had caught the
U||   Major’s little idiosyncrasies of speech, accent, and intonation and his
U||   pompous courtliness to perfection—exaggerating all to the purpose of
U||   the stage. When he performed that marvelous bow that the Major fondly
U||   imagined to be the pink of all salutations, the audience sent forth a
U||   sudden round of hearty applause.
U||   Miss Lydia sat immovable, not daring to glance toward her father.
U||   Sometimes her hand next to him would be laid against her cheek, as if
U||   to conceal the smile which, in spite of her disapproval, she could not
U||   entirely suppress.
U||   The culmination of Hargraves audacious imitation took place in the
U||   third act. The scene is where Colonel Calhoun entertains a few of the
U||   neighboring planters in his “den.”
U||   Standing at a table in the center of the stage, with his friends
U||   grouped about him, he delivers that inimitable, rambling character
U||   monologue so famous in A Magnolia Flower, at the same time that he
U||   deftly makes juleps for the party.
U||   Major Talbot, sitting quietly, but white with indignation, heard his
U||   best stories retold, his pet theories and hobbies advanced and
U||   expanded, and the dream of the Anecdotes and Reminiscences served,
U||   exaggerated and garbled. His favorite narrative—that of his duel with
U||   Rathbone Culbertson—was not omitted, and it was delivered with more
U||   fire, egotism, and gusto than the Major himself put into it.
U||   The monologue concluded with a quaint, delicious, witty little lecture
U||   on the art of concocting a julep, illustrated by the act. Here Major
U||   Talbot’s delicate but showy science was reproduced to a hair’s
U||   breadth—from his dainty handling of the fragrant weed—“the
U||   one-thousandth part of a grain too much pressure, gentlemen, and you
U||   extract the bitterness, instead of the aroma, of this heaven-bestowed
U||   plant”—to his solicitous selection of the oaten straws.
U||   At the close of the scene the audience raised a tumultuous roar of
U||   appreciation. The portrayal of the type was so exact, so sure and
U||   thorough, that the leading characters in the play were forgotten. After
U||   repeated calls, Hargraves came before the curtain and bowed, his rather
U||   boyish face bright and flushed with the knowledge of success.
U||   At last Miss Lydia turned and looked at the Major. His thin nostrils
U||   were working like the gills of a fish. He laid both shaking hands upon
U||   the arms of his chair to rise.
U||   “We will go, Lydia,” he said chokingly. “This is an
U||   abominable—desecration.”
U||   Before he could rise, she pulled him back into his seat.
U||   “We will stay it out,” she declared. “Do you want to advertise the copy
U||   by exhibiting the original coat?” So they remained to the end.
U||   Hargraves’s success must have kept him up late that night, for neither
U||   at the breakfast nor at the dinner table did he appear.
U||   About three in the afternoon he tapped at the door of Major Talbot’s
U||   study. The Major opened it, and Hargraves walked in with his hands full
U||   of the morning papers—too full of his triumph to notice anything
U||   unusual in the Major’s demeanor.
U||   “I put it all over ’em last night, Major,” he began exultantly. “I had
U||   my inning, and, I think, scored. Here’s what The Post says:
U||   “‘His conception and portrayal of the old-time Southern colonel, with
U||   his absurd grandiloquence, his eccentric garb, his quaint idioms and
U||   phrases, his motheaten pride of family, and his really kind heart,
U||   fastidious sense of honor, and lovable simplicity, is the best
U||   delineation of a character role on the boards to-day. The coat worn by
U||   Colonel Calhoun is itself nothing less than an evolution of genius. Mr.
U||   Hargraves has captured his public.’
U||   “How does that sound, Major, for a first-nighter?”
U||   “I had the honor”—the Major’s voice sounded ominously frigid—“of
U||   witnessing your very remarkable performance, sir, last night.”
U||   Hargraves looked disconcerted.
U||   “You were there? I didn’t know you ever—I didn’t know you cared for the
U||   theater. Oh, I say, Major Talbot,” he exclaimed frankly, “don’t you be
U||   offended. I admit I did get a lot of pointers from you that helped out
U||   wonderfully in the part. But it’s a type, you know—not individual. The
U||   way the audience caught on shows that. Half the patrons of that theater
U||   are Southerners. They recognized it.”
U||   “Mr. Hargraves,” said the Major, who had remained standing, “you have
U||   put upon me an unpardonable insult. You have burlesqued my person,
U||   grossly betrayed my confidence, and misused my hospitality. If I
U||   thought you possessed the faintest conception of what is the sign
U||   manual of a gentleman, or what is due one, I would call you out, sir,
U||   old as I am. I will ask you to leave the room, sir.”
U||   The actor appeared to be slightly bewildered, and seemed hardly to take
U||   in the full meaning of the old gentleman’s words.
U||   “I am truly sorry you took offense,” he said regretfully. “Up here we
U||   don’t look at things just as you people do. I know men who would buy
U||   out half the house to have their personality put on the stage so the
U||   public would recognize it.”
U||   “They are not from Alabama, sir,” said the Major haughtily.
U||   “Perhaps not. I have a pretty good memory, Major; let me quote a few
U||   lines from your book. In response to a toast at a banquet given
U||   in—Milledgeville, I believe—you uttered, and intend to have printed,
U||   these words:
U||   “‘The Northern man is utterly without sentiment or warmth except in so
U||   far as the feelings may be turned to his own commercial profit. He will
U||   suffer without resentment any imputation cast upon the honor of himself
U||   or his loved ones that does not bear with it the consequence of
U||   pecuniary loss. In his charity, he gives with a liberal hand; but it
U||   must be heralded with the trumpet and chronicled in brass.’
U||   “Do you think that picture is fairer than the one you saw of Colonel
U||   Calhoun last night?”
U||   “The description,” said the Major, frowning, “is—not without grounds.
U||   Some exag—latitude must be allowed in public speaking.”
U||   “And in public acting,” replied Hargraves.
U||   “That is not the point,” persisted the Major, unrelenting. “It was a
U||   personal caricature. I positively decline to overlook it, sir.”
U||   “Major Talbot,” said Hargraves, with a winning smile, “I wish you would
U||   understand me. I want you to know that I never dreamed of insulting
U||   you. In my profession, all life belongs to me. I take what I want, and
U||   what I can, and return it over the footlights. Now, if you will, let’s
U||   let it go at that. I came in to see you about something else. We’ve
U||   been pretty good friends for some months, and I’m going to take the
U||   risk of offending you again. I know you are hard up for money—never
U||   mind how I found out, a boarding house is no place to keep such matters
U||   secret—and I want you to let me help you out of the pinch. I’ve been
U||   there often enough myself. I’ve been getting a fair salary all the
U||   season, and I’ve saved some money. You’re welcome to a couple
U||   hundred—or even more—until you get——”
U||   “Stop!” commanded the Major, with his arm outstretched. “It seems that
U||   my book didn’t lie, after all. You think your money salve will heal all
U||   the hurts of honor. Under no circumstances would I accept a loan from a
U||   casual acquaintance; and as to you, sir, I would starve before I would
U||   consider your insulting offer of a financial adjustment of the
U||   circumstances we have discussed. I beg to repeat my request relative to
U||   your quitting the apartment.”
U||   Hargraves took his departure without another word. He also left the
U||   house the same day, moving, as Mrs. Vardeman explained at the supper
U||   table, nearer the vicinity of the downtown theater, where A Magnolia
U||   Flower was booked for a week’s run.
U||   Critical was the situation with Major Talbot and Miss Lydia. There was
U||   no one in Washington to whom the Major’s scruples allowed him to apply
U||   for a loan. Miss Lydia wrote a letter to Uncle Ralph, but it was
U||   doubtful whether that relative’s constricted affairs would permit him
U||   to furnish help. The Major was forced to make an apologetic address to
U||   Mrs. Vardeman regarding the delayed payment for board, referring to
U||   “delinquent rentals” and “delayed remittances” in a rather confused
U||   strain.
U||   Deliverance came from an entirely unexpected source.
U||   Late one afternoon the door maid came up and announced an old colored
U||   man who wanted to see Major Talbot. The Major asked that he be sent up
U||   to his study. Soon an old darkey appeared in the doorway, with his hat
U||   in hand, bowing, and scraping with one clumsy foot. He was quite
U||   decently dressed in a baggy suit of black. His big, coarse shoes shone
U||   with a metallic luster suggestive of stove polish. His bushy wool was
U||   gray—almost white. After middle life, it is difficult to estimate the
U||   age of a negro. This one might have seen as many years as had Major
U||   Talbot.
U||   “I be bound you don’t know me, Mars’ Pendleton,” were his first words.
U||   The Major rose and came forward at the old, familiar style of address.
U||   It was one of the old plantation darkeys without a doubt; but they had
U||   been widely scattered, and he could not recall the voice or face.
U||   “I don’t believe I do,” he said kindly—“unless you will assist my
U||   memory.”
U||   “Don’t you ’member Cindy’s Mose, Mars’ Pendleton, what ’migrated
U||   ’mediately after de war?”
U||   “Wait a moment,” said the Major, rubbing his forehead with the tips of
U||   his fingers. He loved to recall everything connected with those beloved
U||   days. “Cindy’s Mose,” he reflected. “You worked among the
U||   horses—breaking the colts. Yes, I remember now. After the surrender,
U||   you took the name of—don’t prompt me—Mitchell, and went to the West—to
U||   Nebraska.”
U||   “Yassir, yassir,”—the old man’s face stretched with a delighted
U||   grin—“dat’s him, dat’s it. Newbraska. Dat’s me—Mose Mitchell. Old Uncle
U||   Mose Mitchell, dey calls me now. Old mars’, your pa, gimme a pah of dem
U||   mule colts when I lef’ fur to staht me goin’ with. You ’member dem
U||   colts, Mars’ Pendleton?”
U||   “I don’t seem to recall the colts,” said the Major. “You know. I was
U||   married the first year of the war and living at the old Follinsbee
U||   place. But sit down, sit down, Uncle Mose. I’m glad to see you. I hope
U||   you have prospered.”
U||   Uncle Mose took a chair and laid his hat carefully on the floor beside
U||   it.
U||   “Yessir; of late I done mouty famous. When I first got to Newbraska,
U||   dey folks come all roun’ me to see dem mule colts. Dey ain’t see no
U||   mules like dem in Newbraska. I sold dem mules for three hundred
U||   dollars. Yessir—three hundred.
U||   “Den I open a blacksmith shop, suh, and made some money and bought some
U||   lan’. Me and my old ’oman done raised up seb’m chillun, and all doin’
U||   well ’cept two of ’em what died. Fo’ year ago a railroad come along and
U||   staht a town slam ag’inst my lan’, and, suh, Mars’ Pendleton, Uncle
U||   Mose am worth leb’m thousand dollars in money, property, and lan’.”
U||   “I’m glad to hear it,” said the Major heartily. “Glad to hear it.”
U||   “And dat little baby of yo’n, Mars’ Pendleton—one what you name Miss
U||   Lyddy—I be bound dat little tad done growed up tell nobody wouldn’t
U||   know her.”
U||   The Major stepped to the door and called: “Lydie, dear, will you come?”
U||   Miss Lydia, looking quite grown up and a little worried, came in from
U||   her room.
U||   “Dar, now! What’d I tell you? I knowed dat baby done be plum growed up.
U||   You don’t ’member Uncle Mose, child?”
U||   “This is Aunt Cindy’s Mose, Lydia,” explained the Major. “He left
U||   Sunnymead for the West when you were two years old.”
U||   “Well,” said Miss Lydia, “I can hardly be expected to remember you,
U||   Uncle Mose, at that age. And, as you say, I’m ’plum growed up,’ and was
U||   a blessed long time ago. But I’m glad to see you, even if I can’t
U||   remember you.”
U||   And she was. And so was the Major. Something alive and tangible had
U||   come to link them with the happy past. The three sat and talked over
U||   the olden times, the Major and Uncle Mose correcting or prompting each
U||   other as they reviewed the plantation scenes and days.
U||   The Major inquired what the old man was doing so far from his home.
U||   “Uncle Mose am a delicate,” he explained, “to de grand Baptis’
U||   convention in dis city. I never preached none, but bein’ a residin’
U||   elder in de church, and able fur to pay my own expenses, dey sent me
U||   along.”
U||   “And how did you know we were in Washington?” inquired Miss Lydia.
U||   “Dey’s a cullud man works in de hotel whar I stops, what comes from
U||   Mobile. He told me he seen Mars’ Pendleton comin’ outen dish here house
U||   one mawnin’.
U||   “What I come fur,” continued Uncle Mose, reaching into his
U||   pocket—“besides de sight of home folks—was to pay Mars’ Pendleton what
U||   I owes him.
U||   “Yessir—three hundred dollars.” He handed the Major a roll of bills.
U||   “When I lef’ old mars’ says: ‘‘Take dem mule colts, Mose, and, if it be
U||   so you gits able, pay fur ’em.’ Yessir—dem was his words. De war had
