U||   “Take it, honey,” said Uncle Mose. “Hit belongs to you. Hit’s Talbot
U||   money.”
U||   After Uncle Mose had gone, Miss Lydia had a good cry—-for joy; and the
U||   Major turned his face to a corner, and smoked his clay pipe
U||   volcanically.
U||   The succeeding days saw the Talbots restored to peace and ease. Miss
U||   Lydia’s face lost its worried look. The major appeared in a new frock
U||   coat, in which he looked like a wax figure personifying the memory of
U||   his golden age. Another publisher who read the manuscript of the
U||   Anecdotes and Reminiscences thought that, with a little retouching and
U||   toning down of the high lights, he could make a really bright and
U||   salable volume of it. Altogether, the situation was comfortable, and
U||   not without the touch of hope that is often sweeter than arrived
U||   blessings.
U||   One day, about a week after their piece of good luck, a maid brought a
U||   letter for Miss Lydia to her room. The postmark showed that it was from
U||   New York. Not knowing any one there, Miss Lydia, in a mild flutter of
U||   wonder, sat down by her table and opened the letter with her scissors.
U||   This was what she read:
U||   Dear Miss Talbot:
U||   I thought you might be glad to learn of my good fortune. I have
U||   received and accepted an offer of two hundred dollars per week by a New
U||   York stock company to play Colonel Calhoun in A Magnolia Flower.
U||   There is something else I wanted you to know. I guess you’d better not
