U||   By George Randolph Chester (1869- )
U||  I
U||   Just as the stage rumbled over the rickety old bridge, creaking and
U||   groaning, the sun came from behind the clouds that had frowned all the
U||   way, and the passengers cheered up a bit. The two richly dressed
U||   matrons who had been so utterly and unnecessarily oblivious to the
U||   presence of each other now suspended hostilities for the moment by
U||   mutual and unspoken consent, and viewed with relief the little,
U||   golden-tinted valley and the tree-clad road just beyond. The respective
U||   husbands of these two ladies exchanged a mere glance, no more, of
U||   comfort. They, too, were relieved, though more by the momentary truce
U||   than by anything else. They regretted very much to be compelled to hate
U||   each other, for each had reckoned up his vis-à-vis as a rather proper
U||   sort of fellow, probably a man of some achievement, used to good living
U||   and good company.
U||   Extreme iciness was unavoidable between them, however. When one
U||   stranger has a splendidly preserved blonde wife and the other a
U||   splendidly preserved brunette wife, both of whom have won social
U||   prominence by years of hard fighting and aloofness, there remains
U||   nothing for the two men but to follow the lead, especially when
U||   directly under the eyes of the leaders.
U||   The son of the blonde matron smiled cheerfully as the welcome light
U||   flooded the coach.
U||   He was a nice-looking young man, of about twenty-two, one might judge,
U||   and he did his smiling, though in a perfectly impersonal and correct
U||   sort of manner, at the pretty daughter of the brunette matron. The
U||   pretty daughter also smiled, but her smile was demurely directed at the
U||   trees outside, clad as they were in all the flaming glory of their
U||   autumn tints, glistening with the recent rain and dripping with gems
U||   that sparkled and flashed in the noonday sun as they fell.
U||   It is marvelous how much one can see out of the corner of the eye,
U||   while seeming to view mere scenery.
U||   The driver looked down, as he drove safely off the bridge, and shook
U||   his head at the swirl of water that rushed and eddied, dark and muddy,
U||   close up under the rotten planking; then he cracked his whip, and the
U||   horses sturdily attacked the little hill.
U||   Thick, overhanging trees on either side now dimmed the light again, and
U||   the two plump matrons once more glared past the opposite shoulders,
U||   profoundly unaware of each other. The husbands took on the politely
U||   surly look required of them. The blonde son’s eyes still sought the
U||   brunette daughter, but it was furtively done and quite unsuccessfully,
U||   for the daughter was now doing a little glaring on her own account. The
U||   blonde matron had just swept her eyes across the daughter’s skirt,
U||   estimating the fit and material of it with contempt so artistically
U||   veiled that it could almost be understood in the dark.
U||  II
U||   The big bays swung to the brow of the hill with ease, and dashed into a
U||   small circular clearing, where a quaint little two-story building, with
U||   a mossy watering-trough out in front, nestled under the shade of
U||   majestic old trees that reared their brown and scarlet crowns proudly
U||   into the sky. A long, low porch ran across the front of the structure,
U||   and a complaining sign hung out announcing, in dim, weather-flecked
U||   letters on a cracked board, that this was the “Tutt House.” A
U||   gray-headed man, in brown overalls and faded blue jumper, stood on the
U||   porch and shook his fist at the stage as it whirled by.
U||   “What a delightfully old-fashioned inn!” exclaimed the pretty daughter.
U||   “How I should like to stop there over night!”
U||   “You would probably wish yourself away before morning, Evelyn,” replied
U||   her mother indifferently. “No doubt it would be a mere siege of
U||   discomfort.”
U||   The blonde matron turned to her husband. The pretty daughter had been
U||   looking at the picturesque “inn” between the heads of this lady and her
U||   son.
U||   “Edward, please pull down the shade behind me,” she directed. “There is
U||   quite a draught from that broken window.”
U||   The pretty daughter bit her lip. The brunette matron continued to stare
U||   at the shade in the exact spot upon which her gaze had been before
U||   directed, and she never quivered an eyelash. The young man seemed very
U||   uncomfortable, and he tried to look his apologies to the pretty
U||   daughter, but she could not see him now, not even if her eyes had been
U||   all corners.
U||   They were bowling along through another avenue of trees when the driver
U||   suddenly shouted, “Whoa there!”
U||   The horses were brought up with a jerk that was well nigh fatal to the
U||   assortment of dignity inside the coach. A loud roaring could be heard,
U||   both ahead and in the rear, a sharp splitting like a fusillade of
U||   pistol shots, then a creaking and tearing of timbers. The driver bent
U||   suddenly forward.
U||   “Gid ap!” he cried, and the horses sprang forward with a lurch. He
U||   swung them around a sharp bend with a skillful hand and poised his
U||   weight above the brake as they plunged at terrific speed down a steep
U||   grade. The roaring was louder than ever now, and it became deafening as
U||   they suddenly emerged from the thick underbrush at the bottom of the
U||   declivity.
U||   “Caught, by gravy!” ejaculated the driver, and, for the second time, he
U||   brought the coach to an abrupt stop.
U||   “Do see what is the matter, Ralph,” said the blonde matron impatiently.
U||   Thus commanded, the young man swung out and asked the driver about it.
U||   “Paintsville dam’s busted,” he was informed. “I been a-lookin’ fer it
U||   this many a year, an’ this here freshet done it. You see the holler
U||   there? Well, they’s ten foot o’ water in it, an’ it had ort to be stone
U||   dry. The bridge is tore out behind us, an’ we’re stuck here till that
U||   water runs out. We can’t git away till to-morry, anyways.”
U||   He pointed out the peculiar topography of the place, and Ralph got back
U||   in the coach.
U||   “We’re practically on a flood-made island,” he exclaimed, with one eye
U||   on the pretty daughter, “and we shall have to stop over night at that
U||   quaint, old-fashioned inn we passed a few moments ago.”
U||   The pretty daughter’s eyes twinkled, and he thought he caught a swift,
U||   direct gleam from under the long lashes—but he was not sure.
U||   “Dear me, how annoying,” said the blonde matron, but the brunette
U||   matron still stared, without the slightest trace of interest in
U||   anything else, at the infinitesimal spot she had selected on the
U||   affronting window-shade.
U||   The two men gave sighs of resignation, and cast carefully concealed
U||   glances at each other, speculating on the possibility of a cigar and a
U||   glass, and maybe a good story or two, or possibly even a game of poker
U||   after the evening meal. Who could tell what might or might not happen?
U||  III
U||   When the stage drew up in front of the little hotel, it found Uncle
U||   Billy Tutt prepared for his revenge. In former days the stage had
U||   always stopped at the Tutt House for the noonday meal. Since the new
U||   railway was built through the adjoining county, however, the stage trip
U||   became a mere twelve-mile, cross-country transfer from one railroad to
U||   another, and the stage made a later trip, allowing the passengers
U||   plenty of time for “dinner” before they started. Day after day, as the
U||   coach flashed by with its money-laden passengers, Uncle Billy had hoped
U||   that it would break down. But this was better, much better. The coach
U||   might be quickly mended, but not the flood.
U||   “I’m a-goin’ t’ charge ’em till they squeal,” he declared to the
U||   timidly protesting Aunt Margaret, “an’ then I’m goin’ t’ charge ’em a
U||   least mite more, drat ’em!”
U||   He retreated behind the rough wooden counter that did duty as a desk,
U||   slammed open the flimsy, paper-bound “cash book” that served as a
U||   register, and planted his elbows uncompromisingly on either side of it.
U||   “Let ’em bring in their own traps,” he commented, and Aunt Margaret
U||   fled, ashamed and conscience-smitten, to the kitchen. It seemed awful.
U||   The first one out of the coach was the husband of the brunette matron,
U||   and, proceeding under instructions, he waited neither for luggage nor
U||   women folk, but hurried straight into the Tutt House. The other man
U||   would have been neck and neck with him in the race, if it had not been
U||   that he paused to seize two suitcases and had the misfortune to drop
U||   one, which burst open and scattered a choice assortment of lingerie
U||   from one end of the dingy coach to the other.
U||   In the confusion of rescuing the fluffery, the owner of the suitcase
U||   had to sacrifice her hauteur and help her husband and son block up the
U||   aisle, while the other matron had the ineffable satisfaction of being
U||   kept waiting, at last being enabled to say, sweetly and with the most
U||   polite consideration:
U||   “Will you kindly allow me to pass?”
U||   The blonde matron raised up and swept her skirts back perfectly flat.
U||   She was pale but collected. Her husband was pink but collected. Her son
U||   was crimson and uncollected. The brunette daughter could not have found
U||   an eye anywhere in his countenance as she rustled out after her mother.
U||   “I do hope that Belmont has been able to secure choice quarters,” the
U||   triumphing matron remarked as her daughter joined her on the ground.
U||   “This place looked so very small that there can scarcely be more than
U||   one comfortable suite in it.”
U||   It was a vital thrust. Only a splendidly cultivated self-control
U||   prevented the blonde matron from retaliating upon the unfortunate who
U||   had muddled things. Even so, her eyes spoke whole shelves of volumes.
U||   The man who first reached the register wrote, in a straight black
U||   scrawl, “J. Belmont Van Kamp, wife, and daughter.” There being no space
U||   left for his address, he put none down.
U||   “I want three adjoining rooms, en suite if possible,” he demanded.
U||   “Three!” exclaimed Uncle Billy, scratching his head. “Won’t two do ye?
U||   I ain’t got but six bedrooms in th’ house. Me an’ Marg’t sleeps in one,
U||   an’ we’re a-gittin’ too old fer a shake-down on th’ floor. I’ll have t’
U||   save one room fer th’ driver, an’ that leaves four. You take two now—-”
U||   Mr. Van Kamp cast a hasty glance out of the window, The other man was
U||   getting out of the coach. His own wife was stepping on the porch.
U||   “What do you ask for meals and lodging until this time to-morrow?” he
U||   interrupted.
U||   The decisive moment had arrived. Uncle Billy drew a deep breath.
U||   “Two dollars a head!” he defiantly announced. There! It was out! He
U||   wished Margaret had stayed to hear him say it.
U||   The guest did not seem to be seriously shocked, and Uncle Billy was
U||   beginning to be sorry he had not said three dollars, when Mr. Van Kamp
U||   stopped the landlord’s own breath.
U||   “I’ll give you fifteen dollars for the three best rooms in the house,”
U||   he calmly said, and Landlord Tutt gasped as the money fluttered down
U||   under his nose.
U||   “Jis’ take yore folks right on up, Mr. Kamp,” said Uncle Billy,
U||   pouncing on the money. “Th’ rooms is th’ three right along th’ hull
U||   front o’ th’ house. I’ll be up and make on a fire in a minute. Jis’
U||   take th’ Jonesville Banner an’ th’ Uticky Clarion along with ye.”
U||   As the swish of skirts marked the passage of the Van Kamps up the wide
U||   hall stairway, the other party swept into the room.
U||   The man wrote, in a round flourish, “Edward Eastman Ellsworth, wife,
U||   and son.”
U||   “I’d like three choice rooms, en suite,” he said.
U||   “Gosh!” said Uncle Billy, regretfully. “That’s what Mr. Kamp wanted,
U||   fust off, an’ he got it. They hain’t but th’ little room over th’
U||   kitchen left. I’ll have to put you an’ your wife in that, an’ let your
U||   boy sleep with th’ driver.”
U||   The consternation in the Ellsworth party was past calculating by any
U||   known standards of measurement. The thing was an outrage! It was not to
U||   be borne! They would not submit to it!
U||   Uncle Billy, however, secure in his mastery of the situation, calmly
U||   quartered them as he had said. “An’ let ’em splutter all they want to,”
U||   he commented comfortably to himself.
U||  IV
U||   The Ellsworths were holding a family indignation meeting on the broad
U||   porch when the Van Ramps came contentedly down for a walk, and brushed
U||   by them with unseeing eyes.
U||   “It makes a perfectly fascinating suite,” observed Mrs. Van Kamp, in a
U||   pleasantly conversational tone that could be easily overheard by anyone
U||   impolite enough to listen. “That delightful old-fashioned fireplace in
U||   the middle apartment makes it an ideal sitting-room, and the beds are
U||   so roomy and comfortable.”
U||   “I just knew it would be like this!” chirruped Miss Evelyn. “I remarked
U||   as we passed the place, if you will remember, how charming it would be
U||   to stop in this dear, quaint old inn over night. All my wishes seem to
U||   come true this year.”
U||   These simple and, of course, entirely unpremeditated remarks were as
U||   vinegar and wormwood to Mrs. Ellsworth, and she gazed after the
U||   retreating Van Kamps with a glint in her eye that would make one
U||   understand Lucretia Borgia at last.
U||   Her son also gazed after the retreating Van Kamp. She had an exquisite
U||   figure, and she carried herself with a most delectable grace. As the
U||   party drew away from the inn she dropped behind the elders and wandered
U||   off into a side path to gather autumn leaves.
U||   Ralph, too, started off for a walk, but naturally not in the same
U||   direction.
U||   “Edward!” suddenly said Mrs. Ellsworth. “I want you to turn those
U||   people out of that suite before night!”
U||   “Very well,” he replied with a sigh, and got up to do it. He had
U||   wrecked a railroad and made one, and had operated successful corners in
U||   nutmegs and chicory. No task seemed impossible. He walked in to see the
U||   landlord.
U||   “What are the Van Kamps paying you for those three rooms?” he asked.
U||   “Fifteen dollars,” Uncle Billy informed him, smoking one of Mr. Van
U||   Kamp’s good cigars and twiddling his thumbs in huge content.
U||   “I’ll give you thirty for them. Just set their baggage outside and tell
U||   them the rooms are occupied.”
U||   “No sir-ree!” rejoined Uncle Billy. “A bargain’s a bargain, an’ I allus
U||   stick to one I make.”
U||   Mr. Ellsworth withdrew, but not defeated. He had never supposed that
U||   such an absurd proposition would be accepted. It was only a feeler, and
U||   he had noticed a wince of regret in his landlord. He sat down on the
U||   porch and lit a strong cigar. His wife did not bother him. She gazed
U||   complacently at the flaming foliage opposite, and allowed him to think.
U||   Getting impossible things was his business in life, and she had
U||   confidence in him.
U||   “I want to rent your entire house for a week,” he announced to Uncle
U||   Billy a few minutes later. It had occurred to him that the flood might
U||   last longer than they anticipated.
U||   Uncle Billy’s eyes twinkled.
U||   “I reckon it kin be did,” he allowed. “I reckon a ho-tel man’s got a
U||   right to rent his hull house ary minute.”
U||   “Of course he has. How much do you want?”
U||   Uncle Billy had made one mistake in not asking this sort of folks
U||   enough, and he reflected in perplexity.
U||   “Make me a offer,” he proposed. “Ef it hain’t enough I’ll tell ye. You
U||   want to rent th’ hull place, back lot an’ all?”
U||   “No, just the mere house. That will be enough,” answered the other with
U||   a smile. He was on the point of offering a hundred dollars, when he saw
U||   the little wrinkles about Mr. Tutt’s eyes, and he said seventy-five.
U||   “Sho, ye’re jokin’!” retorted Uncle Billy. He had been considered a
U||   fine horse-trader in that part of the country. “Make it a hundred and
U||   twenty-five, an’ I’ll go ye.”
U||   Mr. Ellsworth counted out some bills.
U||   “Here’s a hundred,” he said. “That ought to be about right.”
U||   “Fifteen more,” insisted Uncle Billy.
U||   With a little frown of impatience the other counted off the extra money
U||   and handed it over. Uncle Billy gravely handed it back.
U||   “Them’s the fifteen dollars Mr. Kamp give me,” he explained. “You’ve
U||   got the hull house fer a week, an’ o’ course all th’ money that’s
U||   tooken in is your’n. You kin do as ye please about rentin’ out rooms to
U||   other folks, I reckon. A bargain’s a bargain, an’ I allus stick to one
U||   I make.”
U||  V
U||   Ralph Ellsworth stalked among the trees, feverishly searching for
U||   squirrels, scarlet leaves, and the glint of a brown walking-dress, this
U||   last not being so easy to locate in sunlit autumn woods. Time after
U||   time he quickened his pace, only to find that he had been fooled by a
U||   patch of dogwood, a clump of haw bushes or even a leaf-strewn knoll,
U||   but at last he unmistakably saw the dress, and then he slowed down to a
U||   careless saunter.
U||   She was reaching up for some brilliantly colored maple leaves, and was
U||   entirely unconscious of his presence, especially after she had seen
U||   him. Her pose showed her pretty figure to advantage, but, of course,
U||   she did not know that. How should she?
U||   Ralph admired the picture very much. The hat, the hair, the gown, the
U||   dainty shoes, even the narrow strip of silken hose that was revealed as
U||   she stood a-uptoe, were all of a deep, rich brown that proved an
U||   exquisite foil for the pink and cream of her cheeks. He remembered that
U||   her eyes were almost the same shade, and wondered how it was that
U||   women-folk happened on combinations in dress that so well set off their
U||   natural charms. The fool!
U||   He was about three trees away, now, and a panic akin to that which
U||   hunters describe as “buck ague” seized him. He decided that he really
U||   had no excuse for coming any nearer. It would not do, either, to be
U||   seen staring at her if she should happen to turn her head, so he veered
U||   off, intending to regain the road. It would be impossible to do this
U||   without passing directly in her range of vision, and he did not intend
U||   to try to avoid it. He had a fine, manly figure of his own.
U||   He had just passed the nearest radius to her circle and was proceeding
U||   along the tangent that he had laid out for himself, when the unwitting
U||   maid looked carefully down and saw a tangle of roots at her very feet.
U||   She was so unfortunate, a second later, as to slip her foot in this
U||   very tangle and give her ankle ever so slight a twist.
U||   “Oh!” cried Miss Van Kamp, and Ralph Ellsworth flew to the rescue. He
U||   had not been noticing her at all, and yet he had started to her side
U||   before she had even cried out, which was strange. She had a very
U||   attractive voice.
U||   “May I be of assistance?” he anxiously inquired.
U||   “I think not, thank you,” she replied, compressing her lips to keep
U||   back the intolerable pain, and half-closing her eyes to show the fine
U||   lashes. Declining the proffered help, she extricated her foot, picked
U||   up her autumn branches, and turned away. She was intensely averse to
U||   anything that could be construed as a flirtation, even of the mildest,
U||   he could certainly see that. She took a step, swayed slightly, dropped
U||   the leaves, and clutched out her hand to him.
U||   “It is nothing,” she assured him in a moment, withdrawing the hand
U||   after he had held it quite long enough. “Nothing whatever. I gave my
U||   foot a slight wrench, and turned the least bit faint for a moment.”
U||   “You must permit me to walk back, at least to the road, with you,” he
U||   insisted, gathering up her armload of branches. “I couldn’t think of
U||   leaving you here alone.”
U||   As he stooped to raise the gay woodland treasures he smiled to himself,
U||   ever so slightly. This was not his first season out, either.
U||   “Delightful spot, isn’t it?” he observed as they regained the road and
U||   sauntered in the direction of the Tutt House.
U||   “Quite so,” she reservedly answered. She had noticed that smile as he
U||   stooped. He must be snubbed a little. It would be so good for him.
U||   “You don’t happen to know Billy Evans, of Boston, do you?” he asked.
U||   “I think not. I am but very little acquainted in Boston.”
U||   “Too bad,” he went on. “I was rather in hopes you knew Billy. All sorts
U||   of a splendid fellow, and knows everybody.”
U||   “Not quite, it seems,” she reminded him, and he winced at the error. In
U||   spite of the sly smile that he had permitted to himself, he was
U||   unusually interested.
U||   He tried the weather, the flood, the accident, golf, books and three
U||   good, substantial, warranted jokes, but the conversation lagged in
U||   spite of him. Miss Van Kamp would not for the world have it understood
U||   that this unconventional meeting, made allowable by her wrenched ankle,
U||   could possibly fulfill the functions of a formal introduction.
U||   “What a ripping, queer old building that is!” he exclaimed, making one
U||   more brave effort as they came in sight of the hotel.
U||   “It is, rather,” she assented. “The rooms in it are as quaint and
U||   delightful as the exterior, too.”
