U||   more attempt to establish at least a proxy acquaintance.
U||   “You don’t happen to know Peyson Kingsley, of Philadelphia, do you?”
U||   “I’m afraid I don’t,” she replied. “I know so few Philadelphia people,
U||   you see.” She was rather regretful about it this time. He really was a
U||   clever sort of a fellow, in spite of that smile.
U||   The center window in the second floor of the Tutt House swung open, its
U||   little squares of glass flashing jubilantly in the sunlight. Mrs.
U||   Ellsworth leaned out over the sill, from the quaint old sitting-room of
U||   the Van Kamp apartments!
U||   “Oh, Ralph!” she called in her most dulcet tones. “Kindly excuse
U||   yourself and come right on up to our suite for a few moments!”
U||  VI
U||   It is not nearly so easy to take a practical joke as to perpetrate one.
U||   Evelyn was sitting thoughtfully on the porch when her father and mother
U||   returned. Mrs. Ellsworth was sitting at the center window above,
U||   placidly looking out. Her eyes swept carelessly over the Van Kamps, and
U||   unconcernedly passed on to the rest of the landscape.
U||   Mrs. Van Kamp gasped and clutched the arm of her husband. There was no
U||   need. He, too, had seen the apparition. Evelyn now, for the first time,
U||   saw the real humor of the situation. She smiled as she thought of
U||   Ralph. She owed him one, but she never worried about her debts. She
U||   always managed to get them paid, principal and interest.
U||   Mr. Van Kamp suddenly glowered and strode into the Tutt House. Uncle
U||   Billy met him at the door, reflectively chewing a straw, and handed him
U||   an envelope. Mr. Van Kamp tore it open and drew out a note. Three
U||   five-dollar bills came out with it and fluttered to the porch floor.
U||   This missive confronted him:
U||   Mr. J. Belmont Van Kamp,
U||   Dear Sir: This is to notify you that I have rented the entire Tutt
U||   House for the ensuing week, and am compelled to assume possession of
U||   the three second-floor front rooms. Herewith I am enclosing the fifteen
U||   dollars you paid to secure the suite. You are quite welcome to make
