U||   “Th’ hull house,” replied Billy, and then he somewhat sternly added:
U||   “Paid me spot cash fer it, too.”
U||   Mr. Van Kamp took a wad of loose bills from his trousers pocket,
U||   straightened them out leisurely, and placed them in his bill book,
U||   along with some smooth yellowbacks of eye-bulging denominations. Uncle
U||   Billy sat up and stopped twiddling his thumbs.
U||   “Nothing was said about the furniture, was there?” suavely inquired Van
U||   Kamp.
U||   Uncle Billy leaned blankly back in his chair. Little by little the
U||   light dawned on the ex-horse-trader. The crow’s feet reappeared about
U||   his eyes, his mouth twitched, he smiled, he grinned, then he slapped
U||   his thigh and haw-hawed.
U||   “No!” roared Uncle Billy. “No, there wasn’t, by gum!”
U||   “Nothing but the house?”
U||   “His very own words!” chuckled Uncle Billy. “‘‘Jis’ th’ mere house,’
U||   says he, an’ he gits it. A bargain’s a bargain, an’ I allus stick to
U||   one I make.”
U||   “How much for the furniture for the week?”
U||   “Fifty dollars!” Mr. Tutt knew how to do business with this kind of
U||   people now, you bet.
U||   Mr. Van Kamp promptly counted out the money.
U||   “Drat it!” commented Uncle Billy to himself. “I could ’a’ got more!”
U||   “Now where can we make ourselves comfortable with this furniture?”
U||   Uncle Billy chirked up. All was not yet lost.
U||   “Waal,” he reflectively drawled, “there’s th’ new barn. It hain’t been
U||   used for nothin’ yit, senct I built it two years ago. I jis’ hadn’t th’
U||   heart t’ put th’ critters in it as long as th’ ole one stood up.”
U||   The other smiled at this flashlight on Uncle Billy’s character, and
U||   they went out to look at the barn.
U||  VII
U||   Uncle Billy came back from the “Tutt House Annex,” as Mr. Van Kamp
U||   dubbed the barn, with enough more money to make him love all the world
U||   until he got used to having it. Uncle Billy belongs to a large family.
U||   Mr. Van Kamp joined the women on the porch, and explained the
U||   attractively novel situation to them. They were chatting gaily when the
U||   Ellsworths came down the stairs. Mr. Ellsworth paused for a moment to
U||   exchange a word with Uncle Billy.
U||   “Mr. Tutt,” said he, laughing, “if we go for a bit of exercise will you
U||   guarantee us the possession of our rooms when we come back?”
U||   “Yes sir-ree!” Uncle Billy assured him. “They shan’t nobody take them
U||   rooms away from you fer money, marbles, ner chalk. A bargain’s a
U||   bargain, an’ I allus stick to one I make,” and he virtuously took a
U||   chew of tobacco while he inspected the afternoon sky with a clear
U||   conscience.
U||   “I want to get some of those splendid autumn leaves to decorate our
U||   cozy apartments,” Mrs. Ellsworth told her husband as they passed in
U||   hearing of the Van Kamps. “Do you know those old-time rag rugs are the
U||   most oddly decorative effects that I have ever seen. They are so rich
U||   in color and so exquisitely blended.”
U||   There were reasons why this poisoned arrow failed to rankle, but the
U||   Van Kamps did not trouble to explain. They were waiting for Ralph to
U||   come out and join his parents. Ralph, it seemed, however, had decided
U||   not to take a walk. He had already fatigued himself, he had explained,
U||   and his mother had favored him with a significant look. She could
U||   readily believe him, she had assured him, and had then left him in
U||   scorn.
U||   The Van Kamps went out to consider the arrangement of the barn. Evelyn
U||   returned first and came out on the porch to find a handkerchief. It was
U||   not there, but Ralph was. She was very much surprised to see him, and
U||   she intimated as much.
U||   “It’s dreadfully damp in the woods,” he explained. “By the way, you
U||   don’t happen to know the Whitleys, of Washington, do you? Most
U||   excellent people.”
U||   “I’m quite sorry that I do not,” she replied. “But you will have to
U||   excuse me. We shall be kept very busy with arranging our apartments.”
U||   Ralph sprang to his feet with a ludicrous expression.
U||   “Not the second floor front suite!” he exclaimed.
U||   “Oh, no! Not at all,” she reassured him.
U||   He laughed lightly.
U||   “Honors are about even in that game,” he said.
U||   “Evelyn,” called her mother from the hall. “Please come and take those
U||   front suite curtains down to the barn.”
U||   “Pardon me while we take the next trick,” remarked Evelyn with a laugh
U||   quite as light and gleeful as his own, and disappeared into the hall.
U||   He followed her slowly, and was met at the door by her father.
U||   “You are the younger Mr. Ellsworth, I believe,” politely said Mr. Van
U||   Kamp.
U||   “Ralph Ellsworth. Yes, sir.”
U||   “Here is a note for your father. It is unsealed. You are quite at
U||   liberty to read it.”
U||   Mr. Van Kamp bowed himself away, and Ralph opened the note, which read:
U||   Edward Eastman Ellsworth, Esq.,
U||   Dear Sir: This is to notify you that I have rented the entire furniture
U||   of the Tutt House for the ensuing week, and am compelled to assume
U||   possession of that in the three second floor front rooms, as well as
U||   all the balance not in actual use by Mr. and Mrs. Tutt and the driver
U||   of the stage. You are quite welcome, however, to make use of the
U||   furnishings in the small room over the kitchen. Your luggage you will
U||   find undisturbed. Regretting any inconvenience that this transaction
U||   may cause you, I remain,
U||   Yours respectfully,
U||   J. Belmont Van Kamp.
U||   Ralph scratched his head in amused perplexity. It devolved upon him to
U||   even up the affair a little before his mother came back. He must
U||   support the family reputation for resourcefulness, but it took quite a
U||   bit of scalp irritation before he aggravated the right idea into being.
U||   As soon as the idea came, he went in and made a hide-bound bargain with
U||   Uncle Billy, then he went out into the hall and waited until Evelyn
U||   came down with a huge armload of window curtains.
U||   “Honors are still even,” he remarked. “I have just bought all the
U||   edibles about the place, whether in the cellar, the house or any of the
U||   surrounding structures, in the ground, above the ground, dead or alive,
U||   and a bargain’s a bargain as between man and man.”
U||   “Clever of you, I’m sure,” commented Miss Van Kamp, reflectively.
U||   Suddenly her lips parted with a smile that revealed a double row of
U||   most beautiful teeth. He meditatively watched the curve of her lips.
U||   “Isn’t that rather a heavy load?” he suggested. “I’d be delighted to
U||   help you move the things, don’t you know.”
U||   “It is quite kind of you, and what the men would call ‘‘game,’ I
U||   believe, under the circumstances,” she answered, “but really it will
U||   not be necessary. We have hired Mr. Tutt and the driver to do the
U||   heavier part of the work, and the rest of it will be really a pleasant
U||   diversion.”
U||   “No doubt,” agreed Ralph, with an appreciative grin. “By the way, you
U||   don’t happen to know Maud and Dorothy Partridge, of Baltimore, do you?
U||   Stunning pretty girls, both of them, and no end of swells.”
U||   “I know so very few people in Baltimore,” she murmured, and tripped on
U||   down to the barn.
U||   Ralph went out on the porch and smoked. There was nothing else that he
U||   could do.
U||  VIII
U||   It was growing dusk when the elder Ellsworths returned, almost hidden
U||   by great masses of autumn boughs.
U||   “You should have been with us, Ralph,” enthusiastically said his
U||   mother. “I never saw such gorgeous tints in all my life. We have
U||   brought nearly the entire woods with us.”
U||   “It was a good idea,” said Ralph. “A stunning good idea. They may come
U||   in handy to sleep on.”
U||   Mrs. Ellsworth turned cold.
U||   “What do you mean?” she gasped.
U||   “Ralph,” sternly demanded his father, “you don’t mean to tell us that
U||   you let the Van Kamps jockey us out of those rooms after all?”
U||   “Indeed, no,” he airily responded. “Just come right on up and see.”
U||   He led the way into the suite and struck a match. One solitary candle
U||   had been left upon the mantel shelf. Ralph thought that this had been
U||   overlooked, but his mother afterwards set him right about that. Mrs.
U||   Van Kamp had cleverly left it so that the Ellsworths could see how
U||   dreadfully bare the place was. One candle in three rooms is drearier
U||   than darkness anyhow.
U||   Mrs. Ellsworth took in all the desolation, the dismal expanse of the
U||   now enormous apartments, the shabby walls, the hideous bright spots
U||   where pictures had hung, the splintered flooring, the great, gaunt
U||   windows—and she gave in. She had met with snub after snub, and cut
U||   after cut, in her social climb, she had had the cook quit in the middle
U||   of an important dinner, she had had every disconcerting thing possible
U||   happen to her, but this—this was the last bale of straw. She sat down
U||   on a suitcase, in the middle of the biggest room, and cried!
U||   Ralph, having waited for this, now told about the food transaction, and
U||   she hastily pushed the last-coming tear back into her eye.
U||   “Good!” she cried. “They will be up here soon. They will be compelled
U||   to compromise, and they must not find me with red eyes.”
U||   She cast a hasty glance around the room, then, in a sudden panic,
U||   seized the candle and explored the other two. She went wildly out into
U||   the hall, back into the little room over the kitchen, downstairs,
U||   everywhere, and returned in consternation.
U||   “There’s not a single mirror left in the house!” she moaned.
U||   Ralph heartlessly grinned. He could appreciate that this was a
U||   characteristic woman trick, and wondered admiringly whether Evelyn or
U||   her mother had thought of it. However, this was a time for action.
U||   “I’ll get you some water to bathe your eyes,” he offered, and ran into
U||   the little room over the kitchen to get a pitcher. A cracked
U||   shaving-mug was the only vessel that had been left, but he hurried down
U||   into the yard with it. This was no time for fastidiousness.
U||   He had barely creaked the pump handle when Mr. Van Kamp hurried up from
U||   the barn.
U||   “I beg your pardon, sir,” said Mr. Van Kamp, “but this water belongs to
U||   us. My daughter bought it, all that is in the ground, above the ground,
U||   or that may fall from the sky upon these premises.”
U||  IX
U||   The mutual siege lasted until after seven o’clock, but it was rather
U||   one-sided. The Van Kamps could drink all the water they liked, it made
U||   them no hungrier. If the Ellsworths ate anything, however, they grew
U||   thirstier, and, moreover, water was necessary if anything worth while
U||   was to be cooked. They knew all this, and resisted until Mrs. Ellsworth
U||   was tempted and fell. She ate a sandwich and choked. It was
U||   heartbreaking, but Ralph had to be sent down with a plate of sandwiches
U||   and an offer to trade them for water.
U||   Halfway between the pump and the house he met Evelyn coming with a
U||   small pail of the precious fluid. They both stopped stock still; then,
U||   seeing that it was too late to retreat, both laughed and advanced.
U||   “Who wins now?” bantered Ralph as they made the exchange.
U||   “It looks to me like a misdeal,” she gaily replied, and was moving away
U||   when he called her back.
U||   “You don’t happen to know the Gately’s, of New York, do you?” he was
U||   quite anxious to know.
U||   “I am truly sorry, but I am acquainted with so few people in New York.
U||   We are from Chicago, you know.”
U||   “Oh,” said he blankly, and took the water up to the Ellsworth suite.
U||   Mrs. Ellsworth cheered up considerably when she heard that Ralph had
U||   been met half-way, but her eyes snapped when he confessed that it was
U||   Miss Van Kamp who had met him.
U||   “I hope you are not going to carry on a flirtation with that
U||   overdressed creature,” she blazed.
U||   “Why mother,” exclaimed Ralph, shocked beyond measure. “What right have
U||   you to accuse either this young lady or myself of flirting? Flirting!”
U||   Mrs. Ellsworth suddenly attacked the fire with quite unnecessary
U||   energy.
U||  X
U||   Down at the barn, the wide threshing floor had been covered with gay
U||   rag-rugs, and strewn with tables, couches, and chairs in picturesque
U||   profusion. Roomy box-stalls had been carpeted deep with clean straw,
U||   curtained off with gaudy bed-quilts, and converted into cozy sleeping
U||   apartments. The mow and the stalls had been screened off with lace
U||   curtains and blazing counterpanes, and the whole effect was one of
U||   Oriental luxury and splendor. Alas, it was only an “effect”! The
U||   red-hot parlor stove smoked abominably, the pipe carried other smoke
U||   out through the hawmow window, only to let it blow back again. Chill
U||   cross-draughts whistled in from cracks too numerous to be stopped up,
U||   and the miserable Van Kamps could only cough and shiver, and envy the
U||   Tutts and the driver, non-combatants who had been fed two hours before.
U||   Up in the second floor suite there was a roaring fire in the big
U||   fireplace, but there was a chill in the room that no mere fire could
U||   drive away—the chill of absolute emptiness.
U||   A man can outlive hardships that would kill a woman, but a woman can
U||   endure discomforts that would drive a man crazy.
U||   Mr. Ellsworth went out to hunt up Uncle Billy, with an especial solace
U||   in mind. The landlord was not in the house, but the yellow gleam of a
U||   lantern revealed his presence in the woodshed, and Mr. Ellsworth
U||   stepped in upon him just as he was pouring something yellow and clear
U||   into a tumbler from a big jug that he had just taken from under the
U||   flooring.
U||   “How much do you want for that jug and its contents?” he asked, with a
U||   sigh of gratitude that this supply had been overlooked.
U||   Before Mr. Tutt could answer, Mr. Van Kamp hurried in at the door.
U||   “Wait a moment!” he cried. “I want to bid on that!”
U||   “This here jug hain’t fer sale at no price,” Uncle Billy emphatically
U||   announced, nipping all negotiations right in the bud. “It’s too pesky
U||   hard to sneak this here licker in past Marge’t, but I reckon it’s my
U||   treat, gents. Ye kin have all ye want.”
U||   One minute later Mr. Van Kamp and Mr. Ellsworth were seated, one on a
U||   sawbuck and the other on a nail-keg, comfortably eyeing each other
U||   across the work bench, and each was holding up a tumbler one-third
U||   filled with the golden yellow liquid.
U||   “Your health, sir,” courteously proposed Mr. Ellsworth.
U||   “And to you, sir,” gravely replied Mr. Van Kamp.
U||  XI
U||   Ralph and Evelyn happened to meet at the pump, quite accidentally,
U||   after the former had made half a dozen five-minute-apart trips for a
U||   drink. It was Miss Van Kamp, this time, who had been studying on the
U||   mutual acquaintance problem.
U||   “You don’t happen to know the Tylers, of Parkersburg, do you?” she
U||   asked.
U||   “The Tylers! I should say I do!” was the unexpected and enthusiastic
U||   reply. “Why, we are on our way now to Miss Georgiana Tyler’s wedding to
U||   my friend Jimmy Carston. I’m to be best man.”
U||   “How delightful!” she exclaimed. “We are on the way there, too.
U||   Georgiana was my dearest chum at school, and I am to be her ‘‘best
U||   girl.’”
U||   “Let’s go around on the porch and sit down,” said Ralph.
U||  XII
U||   Mr. Van Kamp, back in the woodshed, looked about him with an eye of
U||   content.
U||   “Rather cozy for a woodshed,” he observed. “I wonder if we couldn’t
U||   scare up a little session of dollar limit?”
U||   Both Uncle Billy and Mr. Ellsworth were willing. Death and poker level
U||   all Americans. A fourth hand was needed, however. The stage driver was
U||   in bed and asleep, and Mr. Ellsworth volunteered to find the extra
U||   player.
U||   “I’ll get Ralph,” he said. “He plays a fairly stiff game.” He finally
U||   found his son on the porch, apparently alone, and stated his errand.
U||   “Thank you, but I don’t believe I care to play this evening,” was the
U||   astounding reply, and Mr. Ellsworth looked closer. He made out, then, a
U||   dim figure on the other side of Ralph.
U||   “Oh! Of course not!” he blundered, and went back to the woodshed.
U||   Three-handed poker is a miserable game, and it seldom lasts long. It
U||   did not in this case. After Uncle Billy had won the only jack-pot
U||   deserving of the name, he was allowed to go blissfully to sleep with
U||   his hand on the handle of the big jug.
U||   After poker there is only one other always available amusement for men,
U||   and that is business. The two travelers were quite well acquainted when
U||   Ralph put his head in at the door.
U||   “Thought I’d find you here,” he explained. “It just occurred to me to
U||   wonder whether you gentlemen had discovered, as yet, that we are all to
U||   be house guests at the Carston-Tyler wedding.”
U||   “Why, no!” exclaimed his father in pleased surprise. “It is a most
U||   agreeable coincidence. Mr. Van Kamp, allow me to introduce my son,
U||   Ralph. Mr. Van Kamp and myself, Ralph, have found out that we shall be
U||   considerably thrown together in a business way from now on. He has just
U||   purchased control of the Metropolitan and Western string of
U||   interurbans.”
U||   “Delighted, I’m sure,” murmured Ralph, shaking hands, and then he
U||   slipped out as quickly as possible. Some one seemed to be waiting for
U||   him.
U||   Perhaps another twenty minutes had passed, when one of the men had an
U||   illuminating idea that resulted, later on, in pleasant relations for
U||   all of them. It was about time, for Mrs. Ellsworth, up in the bare
U||   suite, and Mrs. Van Kamp, down in the draughty barn, both wrapped up to
U||   the chin and both still chilly, had about reached the limit of patience
U||   and endurance.
U||   “Why can’t we make things a little more comfortable for all concerned?”
U||   suggested Mr. Van Kamp. “Suppose, as a starter, that we have Mrs. Van
U||   Kamp give a shiver party down in the barn?”
U||   “Good idea,” agreed Mr. Ellsworth. “A little diplomacy will do it. Each
U||   one of us will have to tell his wife that the other fellow made the
U||   first abject overtures.”
U||   Mr. Van Kamp grinned understandingly, and agreed to the infamous ruse.
U||   “By the way,” continued Mr. Ellsworth, with a still happier thought,
U||   “you must allow Mrs. Ellsworth to furnish the dinner for Mrs. Van
U||   Kamp’s shiver party.”
U||   “Dinner!” gasped Mr. Van Kamp. “By all means!”
U||   Both men felt an anxious yawning in the region of the appetite, and a
U||   yearning moisture wetted their tongues. They looked at the slumbering
U||   Uncle Billy and decided to see Mrs. Tutt themselves about a good, hot
U||   dinner for six.
U||   “Law me!” exclaimed Aunt Margaret when they appeared at the kitchen
U||   door. “I swan I thought you folks ’u’d never come to yore senses. Here
U||   I’ve had a big pot o’ stewed chicken ready on the stove fer two mortal
U||   hours. I kin give ye that, an’ smashed taters an’ chicken gravy, an’
U||   dried corn, an’ hot corn-pone, an’ currant jell, an’ strawberry
U||   preserves, an’ my own cannin’ o’ peaches, an’ pumpkin-pie an’ coffee.
U||   Will that do ye?” Would it do! Would it do!!
U||   As Aunt Margaret talked, the kitchen door swung wide, and the two men
U||   were stricken speechless with astonishment. There, across from each
U||   other at the kitchen table, sat the utterly selfish and traitorous
U||   younger members of the rival houses of Ellsworth and Van Kamp, deep in
U||   the joys of chicken, and mashed potatoes, and gravy, and hot corn-pone,
U||   and all the other “fixings,” laughing and chatting gaily like chums of
U||   years’ standing. They had seemingly just come to an agreement about
U||   something or other, for Evelyn, waving the shorter end of a broken
U||   wishbone, was vivaciously saying to Ralph:
U||   “A bargain’s a bargain, and I always stick to one I make.”
