U||A CALL[71][26]
U||   By Grace MacGowan Cooke (1863- )
U||   A boy in an unnaturally clean, country-laundered collar walked down a
U||   long white road. He scuffed the dust up wantonly, for he wished to veil
U||   the all-too-brilliant polish of his cowhide shoes. Also the memory of
U||   the whiteness and slipperiness of his collar oppressed him. He was fain
U||   to look like one accustomed to social diversions, a man hurried from
U||   hall to hall of pleasure, without time between to change collar or
U||   polish boot. He stooped and rubbed a crumb of earth on his overfresh
U||   neck-linen.
U||   This did not long sustain his drooping spirit. He was mentally adrift
U||   upon the Hints and Helps to Young Men in Business and Social Relations,
U||   which had suggested to him his present enterprise, when the appearance
U||   of a second youth, taller and broader than himself, with a shock of
U||   light curling hair and a crop of freckles that advertised a rich soil
U||   threw him a lifeline. He put his thumbs to his lips and whistled in a
U||   peculiarly ear-splitting way. The two boys had sat on the same bench at
U||   Sunday-school not three hours before; yet what a change had come over
U||   the world for one of them since then!
U||   “Hello! Where you goin’, Ab?” asked the newcomer, gruffly.
U||   “Callin’,” replied the boy in the collar, laconically, but with
U||   carefully averted gaze.
U||   “On the girls?” inquired the other, awestruck. In Mount Pisgah you saw
U||   the girls home from night church, socials, or parties; you could hang
U||   over the gate; and you might walk with a girl in the cemetery of a
U||   Sunday afternoon; but to ring a front-door bell and ask for Miss
U||   Heart’s Desire one must have been in long trousers at least three
U||   years—and the two boys confronted in the dusty road had worn these
U||   dignifying garments barely six months.
U||   “Girls,” said Abner, loftily; “I don’t know about girls—I’m just going
U||   to call on one girl—Champe Claiborne.” He marched on as though the
U||   conversation was at an end; but Ross hung upon his flank. Ross and
U||   Champe were neighbors, comrades in all sorts of mischief; he was in
U||   doubt whether to halt Abner and pummel him, or propose to enlist under
U||   his banner.
U||   “Do you reckon you could?” he debated, trotting along by the
U||   irresponsive Jilton boy.
U||   “Run home to your mother,” growled the originator of the plan,
U||   savagely. “You ain’t old enough to call on girls; anybody can see that;
U||   but I am, and I’m going to call on Champe Claiborne.”
U||   Again the name acted as a spur on Ross. “With your collar and boots all
U||   dirty?” he jeered. “They won’t know you’re callin’.”
U||   The boy in the road stopped short in his dusty tracks. He was an
U||   intense creature, and he whitened at the tragic insinuation, longing
U||   for the wholesome stay and companionship of freckle-faced Ross. “I put
U||   the dirt on o’ purpose so’s to look kind of careless,” he half
U||   whispered, in an agony of doubt. “S’pose I’d better go into your house
U||   and try to wash it off? Reckon your mother would let me?”
U||   “I’ve got two clean collars,” announced the other boy, proudly
U||   generous. “I’ll lend you one. You can put it on while I’m getting
U||   ready. I’ll tell mother that we’re just stepping out to do a little
U||   calling on the girls.”
U||   Here was an ally worthy of the cause. Abner welcomed him, in spite of
U||   certain jealous twinges. He reflected with satisfaction that there were
U||   two Claiborne girls, and though Alicia was so stiff and prim that no
U||   boy would ever think of calling on her, there was still the hope that
U||   she might draw Ross’s fire, and leave him, Abner, to make the numerous
U||   remarks he had stored up in his mind from Hints and Helps to Young Men
U||   in Social and Business Relations to Champe alone.
U||   Mrs. Pryor received them with the easy-going kindness of the mother of
U||   one son. She followed them into the dining-room to kiss and feed him,
U||   with an absent “Howdy, Abner; how’s your mother?”
U||   Abner, big with the importance of their mutual intention, inclined his
U||   head stiffly and looked toward Ross for explanation. He trembled a
U||   little, but it was with delight, as he anticipated the effect of the
U||   speech Ross had outlined. But it did not come.
U||   “I’m not hungry, mother,” was the revised edition which the
U||   freckle-faced boy offered to the maternal ear. “I—we are going over to
U||   Mr. Claiborne’s—on—er—on an errand for Abner’s father.”
U||   The black-eyed boy looked reproach as they clattered up the stairs to
U||   Ross’s room, where the clean collar was produced and a small stock of
U||   ties.
U||   “You’d wear a necktie—wouldn’t you?” Ross asked, spreading them upon
U||   the bureau-top.
U||   “Yes. But make it fall carelessly over your shirt-front,” advised the
U||   student of Hints and Helps. “Your collar is miles too big for me. Say!
U||   I’ve got a wad of white chewing-gum; would you flat it out and stick it
U||   over the collar button? Maybe that would fill up some. You kick my foot
U||   if you see me turning my head so’s to knock it off.”
U||   “Better button up your vest,” cautioned Ross, laboring with the
U||   “careless” fall of his tie.
U||   “Huh-uh! I want ‘‘that easy air which presupposes familiarity with
U||   society’—that’s what it says in my book,” objected Abner.
U||   “Sure!” Ross returned to his more familiar jeering attitude. “Loosen up
U||   all your clothes, then. Why don’t you untie your shoes? Flop a sock
U||   down over one of ’em—that looks ‘‘easy’ all right.”
U||   Abner buttoned his vest. “It gives a man lots of confidence to know
U||   he’s good-looking,” he remarked, taking all the room in front of the
U||   mirror.
U||   Ross, at the wash-stand soaking his hair to get the curl out of it,
U||   grumbled some unintelligible response. The two boys went down the
U||   stairs with tremulous hearts.
U||   “Why, you’ve put on another clean shirt, Rossie!” Mrs. Pryor called
U||   from her chair—mothers’ eyes can see so far! “Well—don’t get into any
U||   dirty play and soil it.” The boys walked in silence—but it was a
U||   pregnant silence; for as the roof of the Claiborne house began to peer
U||   above the crest of the hill, Ross plumped down on a stone and
U||   announced, “I ain’t goin’.”
U||   “Come on,” urged the black-eyed boy. “It’ll be fun—and everybody will
U||   respect us more. Champe won’t throw rocks at us in recess-time, after
U||   we’ve called on her. She couldn’t.”
U||   “Called!” grunted Ross. “I couldn’t make a call any more than a cow.
U||   What’d I say? What’d I do? I can behave all right when you just go to
U||   people’s houses—but a call!”
U||   Abner hesitated. Should he give away his brilliant inside information,
U||   drawn from the Hints and Helps book, and be rivalled in the glory of
U||   his manners and bearing? Why should he not pass on alone, perfectly
U||   composed, and reap the field of glory unsupported? His knees gave way
U||   and he sat down without intending it.
U||   “Don’t you tell anybody and I’ll put you on to exactly what grown-up
U||   gentlemen say and do when they go calling on the girls,” he began.
U||   “Fire away,” retorted Ross, gloomily. “Nobody will find out from me.
U||   Dead men tell no tales. If I’m fool enough to go, I don’t expect to
U||   come out of it alive.”
U||   Abner rose, white and shaking, and thrusting three fingers into the
U||   buttoning of his vest, extending the other hand like an orator,
U||   proceeded to instruct the freckled, perspiring disciple at his feet.
U||   “‘Hang your hat on the rack, or give it to a servant.’” Ross nodded
U||   intelligently. He could do that.
U||   “‘Let your legs be gracefully disposed, one hand on the knee, the
U||   other—’”
U||   Abner came to an unhappy pause. “I forget what a fellow does with the
U||   other hand. Might stick it in your pocket, loudly, or expectorate on
U||   the carpet. Indulge in little frivolity. Let a rich stream of
U||   conversation flow.’”
U||   Ross mentally dug within himself for sources of rich streams of
U||   conversation. He found a dry soil. “What you goin’ to talk about?” he
U||   demanded, fretfully. “I won’t go a step farther till I know what I’m
U||   goin’ to say when I get there.”
U||   Abner began to repeat paragraphs from Hints and Helps. “‘‘It is best to
U||   remark,’” he opened, in an unnatural voice, “‘‘How well you are
U||   looking!’ although fulsome compliments should be avoided. When seated
U||   ask the young lady who her favorite composer is.’”
U||   “What’s a composer?” inquired Ross, with visions of soothing-syrup in
U||   his mind.
U||   “A man that makes up music. Don’t butt in that way; you put me all
U||   out—‘‘composer is. Name yours. Ask her what piece of music she likes
U||   best. Name yours. If the lady is musical, here ask her to play or
U||   sing.’”
U||   This chanted recitation seemed to have a hypnotic effect on the
U||   freckled boy; his big pupils contracted each time Abner came to the
U||   repetend, “Name yours.”
U||   “I’m tired already,” he grumbled; but some spell made him rise and fare
U||   farther.
U||   When they had entered the Claiborne gate, they leaned toward each other
U||   like young saplings weakened at the root and locking branches to keep
U||   what shallow foothold on earth remained.
U||   “You’re goin’ in first,” asserted Ross, but without conviction. It was
U||   his custom to tear up to this house a dozen times a week, on his
U||   father’s old horse or afoot; he was wont to yell for Champe as he
U||   approached, and quarrel joyously with her while he performed such
U||   errand as he had come upon; but he was gagged and hamstrung now by the
U||   hypnotism of Abner’s scheme.
U||   “‘‘Walk quietly up the steps; ring the bell and lay your card on the
U||   servant,’” quoted Abner, who had never heard of a server.
U||   “‘‘Lay your card on the servant!’” echoed Ross. “Cady’d dodge. There’s
U||   a porch to cross after you go up the steps—does it say anything about
U||   that?”
U||   “It says that the card should be placed on the servant,” Abner
U||   reiterated, doggedly. “If Cady dodges, it ain’t any business of mine.
U||   There are no porches in my book. Just walk across it like anybody.
U||   We’ll ask for Miss Champe Claiborne.”
U||   “We haven’t got any cards,” discovered Ross, with hope.
U||   “I have,” announced Abner, pompously. “I had some struck off in
U||   Chicago. I ordered ’em by mail. They got my name Pillow, but there’s a
U||   scalloped gilt border around it. You can write your name on my card.
U||   Got a pencil?”
U||   He produced the bit of cardboard; Ross fished up a chewed stump of lead
U||   pencil, took it in cold, stiff fingers, and disfigured the square with
U||   eccentric scribblings.
U||   “They’ll know who it’s meant for,” he said, apologetically, “because
U||   I’m here. What’s likely to happen after we get rid of the card?”
U||   “I told you about hanging your hat on the rack and disposing your
U||   legs.”
U||   “I remember now,” sighed Ross. They had been going slower and slower.
U||   The angle of inclination toward each other became more and more
U||   pronounced.
U||   “We must stand by each other,” whispered Abner.
U||   “I will—if I can stand at all,” murmured the other boy, huskily.
U||   “Oh, Lord!” They had rounded the big clump of evergreens and found Aunt
U||   Missouri Claiborne placidly rocking on the front porch! Directed to
U||   mount steps and ring bell, to lay cards upon the servant, how should
U||   one deal with a rosy-faced, plump lady of uncertain years in a
U||   rocking-chair. What should a caller lay upon her? A lion in the way
U||   could not have been more terrifying. Even retreat was cut off. Aunt
U||   Missouri had seen them. “Howdy, boys; how are you?” she said, rocking
U||   peacefully. The two stood before her like detected criminals.
U||   Then, to Ross’s dismay, Abner sank down on the lowest step of the
U||   porch, the westering sun full in his hopeless eyes. He sat on his cap.
U||   It was characteristic that the freckled boy remained standing. He would
U||   walk up those steps according to plan and agreement, if at all. He
U||   accepted no compromise. Folding his straw hat into a battered cone, he
U||   watched anxiously for the delivery of the card. He was not sure what
U||   Aunt Missouri’s attitude might be if it were laid on her. He bent down
U||   to his companion. “Go ahead,” he whispered. “Lay the card.”
U||   Abner raised appealing eyes. “In a minute. Give me time,” he pleaded.
U||   “Mars’ Ross—Mars’ Ross! Head ’em off!” sounded a yell, and Babe, the
U||   house-boy, came around the porch in pursuit of two half-grown chickens.
U||   “Help him, Rossie,” prompted Aunt Missouri, sharply. “You boys can stay
U||   to supper and have some of the chicken if you help catch them.”
U||   Had Ross taken time to think, he might have reflected that gentlemen
U||   making formal calls seldom join in a chase after the main dish of the
U||   family supper. But the needs of Babe were instant. The lad flung
U||   himself sidewise, caught one chicken in his hat, while Babe fell upon
U||   the other in the manner of a football player. Ross handed the pullet to
U||   the house-boy, fearing that he had done something very much out of
U||   character, then pulled the reluctant negro toward to the steps.
U||   “Babe’s a servant,” he whispered to Abner, who had sat rigid through
U||   the entire performance. “I helped him with the chickens, and he’s got
U||   to stand gentle while you lay the card on.”
U||   Confronted by the act itself, Abner was suddenly aware that he knew not
U||   how to begin. He took refuge in dissimulation.
U||   “Hush!” he whispered back. “Don’t you see Mr. Claiborne’s come
U||   out?—He’s going to read something to us.”
U||   Ross plumped down beside him. “Never mind the card; tell ’em,” he
U||   urged.
U||   “Tell ’em yourself.”
U||   “No—let’s cut and run.”
U||   “I—I think the worst of it is over. When Champe sees us she’ll—”
U||   Mention of Champe stiffened Ross’s spine. If it had been glorious to
U||   call upon her, how very terrible she would make it should they attempt
U||   calling, fail, and the failure come to her knowledge! Some things were
U||   easier to endure than others; he resolved to stay till the call was
U||   made.
U||   For half an hour the boys sat with drooping heads, and the old
U||   gentleman read aloud, presumably to Aunt Missouri and themselves.
U||   Finally their restless eyes discerned the two Claiborne girls walking
U||   serene in Sunday trim under the trees at the edge of the lawn. Arms
U||   entwined, they were whispering together and giggling a little. A
U||   caller, Ross dared not use his voice to shout nor his legs to run
U||   toward them.
U||   “Why don’t you go and talk to the girls, Rossie?” Aunt Missouri asked,
U||   in the kindness of her heart. “Don’t be noisy—it’s Sunday, you know—and
U||   don’t get to playing anything that’ll dirty up your good clothes.”
U||   Ross pressed his lips hard together; his heart swelled with the rage of
U||   the misunderstood. Had the card been in his possession, he would, at
U||   that instant, have laid it on Aunt Missouri without a qualm.
U||   “What is it?” demanded the old gentleman, a bit testily.
U||   “The girls want to hear you read, father,” said Aunt Missouri,
U||   shrewdly; and she got up and trotted on short, fat ankles to the girls
U||   in the arbor. The three returned together, Alicia casting curious
U||   glances at the uncomfortable youths, Champe threatening to burst into
U||   giggles with every breath.
U||   Abner sat hard on his cap and blushed silently. Ross twisted his hat
U||   into a three-cornered wreck.
U||   The two girls settled themselves noisily on the upper step. The old man
U||   read on and on. The sun sank lower. The hills were red in the west as
U||   though a brush fire flamed behind their crests. Abner stole a furtive
U||   glance at his companion in misery, and the dolor of Ross’s countenance
U||   somewhat assuaged his anguish. The freckle-faced boy was thinking of
U||   the village over the hill, a certain pleasant white house set back in a
U||   green yard, past whose gate, the two-plank sidewalk ran. He knew lamps
U||   were beginning to wink in the windows of the neighbors about, as though
U||   the houses said, “Our boys are all at home—but Ross Pryor’s out trying
U||   to call on the girls, and can’t get anybody to understand it.” Oh, that
U||   he were walking down those two planks, drawing a stick across the
U||   pickets, lifting high happy feet which could turn in at that gate! He
U||   wouldn’t care what the lamps said then. He wouldn’t even mind if the
U||   whole Claiborne family died laughing at him—if only some power would
U||   raise him up from this paralyzing spot and put him behind the safe
U||   barriers of his own home!
U||   The old man’s voice lapsed into silence; the light was becoming too dim
U||   for his reading. Aunt Missouri turned and called over her shoulder into
U||   the shadows of the big hall: “You Babe! Go put two extra plates on the
U||   supper-table.”
U||   The boys grew red from the tips of their ears, and as far as any one
U||   could see under their wilting collars. Abner felt the lump of gum come
U||   loose and slip down a cold spine. Had their intentions but been known,
U||   this inferential invitation would have been most welcome. It was but to
U||   rise up and thunder out, “We came to call on the young ladies.”
U||   They did not rise. They did not thunder out anything. Babe brought a
U||   lamp and set it inside the window, and Mr. Claiborne resumed his
U||   reading. Champe giggled and said that Alicia made her. Alcia drew her
U||   skirts about her, sniffed, and looked virtuous, and said she didn’t see
U||   anything funny to laugh at. The supper-bell rang. The family, evidently
U||   taking it for granted that the boys would follow, went in.
U||   Alone for the first time, Abner gave up. “This ain’t any use,” he
U||   complained. “We ain’t calling on anybody.”
U||   “Why didn’t you lay on the card?” demanded Ross, fiercely. “Why didn’t
U||   you say: ‘‘We’ve-just-dropped-into-call-on-Miss-Champe. It’s-a
U||   -pleasant-evening. We-feel-we-must-be-going,’ like you said you would?
U||   Then we could have lifted our hats and got away decently.”
U||   Abner showed no resentment.
U||   “Oh, if it’s so easy, why didn’t you do it yourself?” he groaned.
U||   “Somebody’s coming,” Ross muttered, hoarsely. “Say it now. Say it
U||   quick.”
U||   The somebody proved to be Aunt Missouri, who advanced only as far as
U||   the end of the hall and shouted cheerfully: “The idea of a growing boy
U||   not coming to meals when the bell rings! I thought you two would be in
U||   there ahead of us. Come on.” And clinging to their head-coverings as
U||   though these contained some charm whereby the owners might be rescued,
U||   the unhappy callers were herded into the dining-room. There were many
U||   things on the table that boys like. Both were becoming fairly cheerful,
U||   when Aunt Missouri checked the biscuit-plate with: “I treat my
U||   neighbors’ children just like I’d want children of my own treated. If
U||   your mothers let you eat all you want, say so, and I don’t care; but if
U||   either of them is a little bit particular, why, I’d stop at six!”
U||   Still reeling from this blow, the boys finally rose from the table and
U||   passed out with the family, their hats clutched to their bosoms, and
U||   clinging together for mutual aid and comfort. During the usual
U||   Sunday-evening singing Champe laughed till Aunt Missouri threatened to
U||   send her to bed. Abner’s card slipped from his hand and dropped face up
U||   on the floor. He fell upon it and tore it into infinitesimal pieces.
U||   “That must have been a love-letter,” said Aunt Missouri, in a pause of
U||   the music. “You boys are getting ‘‘most old enough to think about
U||   beginning to call on the girls.” Her eyes twinkled.
U||   Ross growled like a stoned cur. Abner took a sudden dive into Hints and
U||   Helps, and came up with, “You flatter us, Miss Claiborne,” whereat Ross
U||   snickered out like a human boy. They all stared at him.
U||   “It sounds so funny to call Aunt Missouri ‘‘Mis’ Claiborne,’” the lad
U||   of the freckles explained.
U||   “Funny?” Aunt Missouri reddened. “I don’t see any particular joke in my
U||   having my maiden name.”
U||   Abner, who instantly guessed at what was in Ross’s mind, turned white
U||   at the thought of what they had escaped. Suppose he had laid on the
U||   card and asked for Miss Claiborne!
U||   “What’s the matter, Champe?” inquired Ross, in a fairly natural tone.
U||   The air he had drawn into his lungs when he laughed at Abner seemed to
U||   relieve him from the numbing gentility which had bound his powers since
U||   he joined Abner’s ranks.
U||   “Nothing. I laughed because you laughed,” said the girl.
U||   The singing went forward fitfully. Servants traipsed through the
U||   darkened yard, going home for Sunday night. Aunt Missouri went out and
U||   held some low-toned parley with them. Champe yawned with insulting
U||   enthusiasm. Presently both girls quietly disappeared. Aunt Missouri
U||   never returned to the parlor—evidently thinking that the girls would
U||   attend to the final amenities with their callers. They were left alone
U||   with old Mr. Claiborne. They sat as though bound in their chairs, while
U||   the old man read in silence for a while. Finally he closed his book,
U||   glanced about him, and observed absently:
U||   “So you boys were to spend the night?” Then, as he looked at their
U||   startled faces: “I’m right, am I not? You are to spent the night?”
U||   Oh, for courage to say: “Thank you, no. We’ll be going now. We just
U||   came over to call on Miss Champe.” But thought of how this would sound
U||   in face of the facts, the painful realization that they dared not say
U||   it because they had not said it, locked their lips. Their feet were
U||   lead; their tongues stiff and too large for their mouths. Like
U||   creatures in a nightmare, they moved stiffly, one might have said
U||   creakingly, up the stairs and received each—a bedroom candle!
U||   “Good night, children,” said the absent-minded old man. The two gurgled
U||   out some sounds which were intended for words and doged behind the
U||   bedroom door.
U||   “They’ve put us to bed!” Abner’s black eyes flashed fire. His nervous
U||   hands clutched at the collar Ross had lent him. “That’s what I get for
U||   coming here with you, Ross Pryor!” And tears of humiliation stood in
U||   his eyes.
U||   In his turn Ross showed no resentment. “What I’m worried about is my
U||   mother,” he confessed. “She’s so sharp about finding out things. She
U||   wouldn’t tease me—she’d just be sorry for me. But she’ll think I went
U||   home with you.”
U||   “I’d like to see my mother make a fuss about my calling on the girls!”
U||   growled Abner, glad to let his rage take a safe direction.
U||   “Calling on the girls! Have we called on any girls?” demanded
U||   clear-headed, honest Ross.
U||   “Not exactly—yet,” admitted Abner, reluctantly. “Come on—let’s go to
U||   bed. Mr. Claiborne asked us, and he’s the head of this household. It
U||   isn’t anybody’s business what we came for.”
U||   “I’ll slip off my shoes and lie down till Babe ties up the dog in the
U||   morning,” said Ross. “Then we can get away before any of the family is
U||   up.”
U||   Oh, youth—youth—youth, with its rash promises! Worn out with misery the
U||   boys slept heavily. The first sound that either heard in the morning
U||   was Babe hammering upon their bedroom door. They crouched guiltily and
U||   looked into each other’s eyes. “Let pretend we ain’t here and he’ll go
U||   away,” breathed Abner.
U||   But Babe was made of sterner stuff. He rattled the knob. He turned it.
U||   He put in a black face with a grin which divided it from ear to ear.
U||   “Cady say I mus’ call dem fool boys to breakfus’,” he announced. “I
U||   never named you-all dat. Cady, she say dat.”
U||   “Breakfast!” echoed Ross, in a daze.
U||   “Yessuh, breakfus’,” reasserted Babe, coming entirely into the room and
U||   looking curiously about him. “Ain’t you-all done been to bed at all?”
U||   wrapping his arms about his shoulders and shaking with silent ecstasies
U||   of mirth. The boys threw themselves upon him and ejected him.
U||   “Sent up a servant to call us to breakfast,” snarled Abner. “If they’d
U||   only sent their old servant to the door in the first place, all this
U||   wouldn’t ’a’ happened. I’m just that way when I get thrown off the
U||   track. You know how it was when I tried to repeat those things to you—I
U||   had to go clear back to the beginning when I got interrupted.”
U||   “Does that mean that you’re still hanging around here to begin over and
U||   make a call?” asked Ross, darkly. “I won’t go down to breakfast if you
U||   are.”
U||   Abner brightened a little as he saw Ross becoming wordy in his rage. “I
U||   dare you to walk downstairs and say,
U||   ‘‘We-just-dropped-in-to-call-on-Miss-Champe’!” he said.
U||   “I—oh—I—darn it all! there goes the second bell. We may as well trot
U||   down.”
U||   “Don’t leave me, Ross,” pleaded the Jilton boy. “I can’t stay here—and
U||   I can’t go down.”
U||   The tone was hysterical. The boy with freckles took his companion by
U||   the arm without another word and marched him down the stairs. “We may
U||   get a chance yet to call on Champe all by herself out on the porch or
U||   in the arbor before she goes to school,” he suggested, by way of
U||   putting some spine into the black-eyed boy.
U||   An emphatic bell rang when they were half-way down the stairs.
U||   Clutching their hats, they slunk into the dining-room. Even Mr.
U||   Claiborne seemed to notice something unusual in their bearing as they
U||   settled into the chairs assigned to them, and asked them kindly if they
U||   had slept well.
U||   It was plain that Aunt Missouri had been posting him as to her
U||   understanding of the intentions of these young men. The state of
U||   affairs gave an electric hilarity to the atmosphere. Babe travelled
U||   from the sideboard to the table, trembling like chocolate pudding. Cady
U||   insisted on bringing in the cakes herself, and grinned as she whisked
U||   her starched blue skirts in and out of the dining-room. A dimple even
U||   showed itself at the corners of pretty Alicia’s prim little mouth.
U||   Champe giggled, till Ross heard Cady whisper:
U||   “Now you got one dem snickerin’ spells agin. You gwine bust yo’ dress
U||   buttons off in the back ef you don’t mind.”
U||   As the spirits of those about them mounted, the hearts of the two
U||   youths sank—if it was like this among the Claibornes, what would it be
U||   at school and in the world at large when their failure to connect
U||   intention with result became village talk? Ross bit fiercely upon an
U||   unoffending batter-cake, and resolved to make a call single-handed
U||   before he left the house.
U||   They went out of the dining-room, their hats as ever pressed to their
U||   breasts. With no volition of their own, their uncertain young legs
U||   carried them to the porch. The Claiborne family and household followed
U||   like small boys after a circus procession. When the two turned, at bay,
U||   yet with nothing between them and liberty but a hypnotism of their own
U||   suggestion, they saw the black faces of the servants peering over the
U||   family shoulders.
U||   Ross was the boy to have drawn courage from the desperation of their
U||   case, and made some decent if not glorious ending. But at the
U||   psychological moment there came around the corner of the house that
U||   most contemptible figure known to the Southern plantation, a
U||   shirt-boy—a creature who may be described, for the benefit of those not
U||   informed, as a pickaninny clad only in a long, coarse cotton shirt.
U||   While all eyes were fastened upon him this inglorious ambassador bolted
U||   forth his message:
U||   “Yo’ ma say”—his eyes were fixed upon Abner—“ef yo’ don’ come home, she
U||   gwine come after yo’—an’ cut yo’ into inch pieces wid a rawhide when
U||   she git yo’. Dat jest what Miss Hortense say.”
U||   As though such a book as Hints and Helps had never existed, Abner shot
U||   for the gate—he was but a hobbledehoy fascinated with the idea of
U||   playing gentleman. But in Ross there were the makings of a man. For a
U||   few half-hearted paces, under the first impulse of horror, he followed
U||   his deserting chief, the laughter of the family, the unrestrainable
U||   guffaws of the negroes, sounding in the rear. But when Champe’s high,
U||   offensive giggle, topping all the others, insulted his ears, he stopped
U||   dead, wheeled, and ran to the porch faster than he had fled from it.
U||   White as paper, shaking with inexpressible rage, he caught and kissed
U||   the tittering girl, violently, noisily, before them all.
U||   The negroes fled—they dared not trust their feelings; even Alicia
U||   sniggered unobtrusively; Grandfather Claiborne chuckled, and Aunt
U||   Missouri frankly collapsed into her rocking-chair, bubbling with mirth,
U||   crying out:
U||   “Good for you, Ross! Seems you did know how to call on the girls, after
U||   all.”
U||   But Ross, paying no attention, walked swiftly toward the gate. He had
U||   served his novitiate. He would never be afraid again. With cheerful
U||   alacrity he dodged the stones flung after him with friendly, erratic
U||   aim by the girl upon whom, yesterday afternoon, he had come to make a
U||   social call.
