U||HOW THE WIDOW WON THE DEACON[73][27]
U||   By William James Lampton ( -1917)
U||   Of course the Widow Stimson never tried to win Deacon Hawkins, nor any
U||   other man, for that matter. A widow doesn’t have to try to win a man;
U||   she wins without trying. Still, the Widow Stimson sometimes wondered
U||   why the deacon was so blind as not to see how her fine farm adjoining
U||   his equally fine place on the outskirts of the town might not be
U||   brought under one management with mutual benefit to both parties at
U||   interest. Which one that management might become was a matter of future
U||   detail. The widow knew how to run a farm successfully, and a large farm
U||   is not much more difficult to run than one of half the size. She had
U||   also had one husband, and knew something more than running a farm
U||   successfully. Of all of which the deacon was perfectly well aware, and
U||   still he had not been moved by the merging spirit of the age to propose
U||   consolidation.
U||   This interesting situation was up for discussion at the Wednesday
U||   afternoon meeting of the Sisters’ Sewing Society.
U||   “For my part,” Sister Susan Spicer, wife of the Methodist minister,
U||   remarked as she took another tuck in a fourteen-year-old girl’s skirt
U||   for a ten-year-old—“for my part, I can’t see why Deacon Hawkins and
U||   Kate Stimson don’t see the error of their ways and depart from them.”
U||   “I rather guess she has,” smiled Sister Poteet, the grocer’s better
U||   half, who had taken an afternoon off from the store in order to be
U||   present.
U||   “Or is willing to,” added Sister Maria Cartridge, a spinster still
U||   possessing faith, hope, and charity, notwithstanding she had been on
U||   the waiting list a long time.
U||   “Really, now,” exclaimed little Sister Green, the doctor’s wife, “do
U||   you think it is the deacon who needs urging?”
U||   “It looks that way to me,” Sister Poteet did not hesitate to affirm.
U||   “Well, I heard Sister Clark say that she had heard him call her ‘Kitty’
U||   one night when they were eating ice-cream at the Mite Society,” Sister
U||   Candish, the druggist’s wife, added to the fund of reliable information
U||   on hand.
U||   “‘Kitty,’ indeed!” protested Sister Spicer. “The idea of anybody
U||   calling Kate Stimson ‘Kitty’! The deacon will talk that way to ’most
U||   any woman, but if she let him say it to her more than once, she must be
U||   getting mighty anxious, I think.”
U||   “Oh,” Sister Candish hastened to explain, “Sister Clark didn’t say she
U||   had heard him say it twice.’”
U||   “Well, I don’t think she heard him say it once,” Sister Spicer asserted
U||   with confidence.
U||   “I don’t know about that,” Sister Poteet argued. “From all I can see
U||   and hear I think Kate Stimson wouldn’t object to ’most anything the
U||   deacon would say to her, knowing as she does that he ain’t going to say
U||   anything he shouldn’t say.”
U||   “And isn’t saying what he should,” added Sister Green, with a sly
U||   snicker, which went around the room softly.
U||   “But as I was saying—” Sister Spicer began, when Sister Poteet, whose
U||   rocker, near the window, commanded a view of the front gate,
U||   interrupted with a warning, “’Sh-’sh.”
U||   “Why shouldn’t I say what I wanted to when—” Sister Spicer began.
U||   “There she comes now,” explained Sister Poteet, “and as I live the
U||   deacon drove her here in his sleigh, and he’s waiting while she comes
U||   in. I wonder what next,” and Sister Poteet, in conjunction with the
U||   entire society, gasped and held their eager breaths, awaiting the
U||   entrance of the subject of conversation.
U||   Sister Spicer went to the front door to let her in, and she was greeted
U||   with the greatest cordiality by everybody.
U||   “We were just talking about you and wondering why you were so late
U||   coming,” cried Sister Poteet. “Now take off your things and make up for
U||   lost time. There’s a pair of pants over there to be cut down to fit
U||   that poor little Snithers boy.”
U||   The excitement and curiosity of the society were almost more than could
U||   be borne, but never a sister let on that she knew the deacon was at the
U||   gate waiting. Indeed, as far as the widow could discover, there was not
U||   the slightest indication that anybody had ever heard there was such a
U||   person as the deacon in existence.
U||   “Oh,” she chirruped, in the liveliest of humors, “you will have to
U||   excuse me for to-day. Deacon Hawkins overtook me on the way here, and
U||   here said I had simply got to go sleigh-riding with him. He’s waiting
U||   out at the gate now.”
U||   “Is that so?” exclaimed the society unanimously, and rushed to the
U||   window to see if it were really true.
U||   “Well, did you ever?” commented Sister Poteet, generally.
U||   “Hardly ever,” laughed the widow, good-naturedly, “and I don’t want to
U||   lose the chance. You know Deacon Hawkins isn’t asking somebody every
U||   day to go sleighing with him. I told him I’d go if he would bring me
U||   around here to let you know what had become of me, and so he did. Now,
U||   good-by, and I’ll be sure to be present at the next meeting. I have to
U||   hurry because he’ll get fidgety.”
U||   The widow ran away like a lively schoolgirl. All the sisters watched
U||   her get into the sleigh with the deacon, and resumed the previous
U||   discussion with greatly increased interest.
U||   But little recked the widow and less recked the deacon. He had bought a
U||   new horse and he wanted the widow’s opinion of it, for the Widow
U||   Stimson was a competent judge of fine horseflesh. If Deacon Hawkins had
U||   one insatiable ambition it was to own a horse which could fling its
U||   heels in the face of the best that Squire Hopkins drove. In his early
U||   manhood the deacon was no deacon by a great deal. But as the years
U||   gathered in behind him he put off most of the frivolities of youth and
U||   held now only to the one of driving a fast horse. No other man in the
U||   county drove anything faster except Squire Hopkins, and him the deacon
U||   had not been able to throw the dust over. The deacon would get good
U||   ones, but somehow never could he find one that the squire didn’t get a
U||   better. The squire had also in the early days beaten the deacon in the
U||   race for a certain pretty girl he dreamed about. But the girl and the
U||   squire had lived happily ever after and the deacon, being a
U||   philosopher, might have forgotten the squire’s superiority had it been
U||   manifested in this one regard only. But in horses, too—that graveled
U||   the deacon.
U||   “How much did you give for him?” was the widow’s first query, after
U||   they had reached a stretch of road that was good going and the deacon
U||   had let him out for a length or two.
U||   “Well, what do you suppose? You’re a judge.”
U||   “More than I would give, I’ll bet a cookie.”
U||   “Not if you was as anxious as I am to show Hopkins that he can’t drive
U||   by everything on the pike.”
U||   “I thought you loved a good horse because he was a good horse,” said
U||   the widow, rather disapprovingly.
U||   “I do, but I could love him a good deal harder if he would stay in
U||   front of Hopkins’s best.”
U||   “Does he know you’ve got this one?”
U||   “Yes, and he’s been blowing round town that he is waiting to pick me up
U||   on the road some day and make my five hundred dollars look like a
U||   pewter quarter.”
U||   “So you gave five hundred dollars for him, did you?” laughed the widow.
U||   “Is it too much?”
U||   “Um-er,” hesitated the widow, glancing along the graceful lines of the
U||   powerful trotter, “I suppose not if you can beat the squire.”
U||   “Right you are,” crowed the deacon, “and I’ll show him a thing or two
U||   in getting over the ground,” he added with swelling pride.
U||   “Well, I hope he won’t be out looking for you to-day, with me in your
U||   sleigh,” said the widow, almost apprehensively, “because, you know,
U||   deacon, I have always wanted you to beat Squire Hopkins.”
U||   The deacon looked at her sharply. There was a softness in her tones
U||   that appealed to him, even if she had not expressed such agreeable
U||   sentiments. Just what the deacon might have said or done after the
U||   impulse had been set going must remain unknown, for at the crucial
U||   moment a sound of militant bells, bells of defiance, jangled up behind
U||   them, disturbing their personal absorption, and they looked around
U||   simultaneously. Behind the bells was the squire in his sleigh drawn by
U||   his fastest stepper, and he was alone, as the deacon was not. The widow
U||   weighed one hundred and sixty pounds, net—which is weighting a horse in
U||   a race rather more than the law allows.
U||   But the deacon never thought of that. Forgetting everything except his
U||   cherished ambition, he braced himself for the contest, took a twist
U||   hold on the lines, sent a sharp, quick call to his horse, and let him
U||   out for all that was in him. The squire followed suit and the deacon.
U||   The road was wide and the snow was worn down smooth. The track couldn’t
U||   have been in better condition. The Hopkins colors were not five rods
U||   behind the Hawkins colors as they got away. For half a mile it was nip
U||   and tuck, the deacon encouraging his horse and the widow encouraging
U||   the deacon, and then the squire began creeping up. The deacon’s horse
U||   was a good one, but he was not accustomed to hauling freight in a race.
U||   A half-mile of it was as much as he could stand, and he weakened under
U||   the strain.
U||   Not handicapped, the squire’s horse forged ahead, and as his nose
U||   pushed up to the dashboard of the deacon’s sleigh, that good man
U||   groaned in agonized disappointment and bitterness of spirit. The widow
U||   was mad all over that Squire Hopkins should take such a mean advantage
U||   of his rival. Why didn’t he wait till another time when the deacon was
U||   alone, as he was? If she had her way she never would, speak to Squire
U||   Hopkins again, nor to his wife, either. But her resentment was not
U||   helping the deacon’s horse to win.
U||   Slowly the squire pulled closer to the front; the deacon’s horse,
U||   realizing what it meant to his master and to him, spurted bravely, but,
U||   struggle as gamely as he might, the odds were too many for him, and he
U||   dropped to the rear. The squire shouted in triumph as he drew past the
U||   deacon, and the dejected Hawkins shrivelled into a heap on the seat,
U||   with only his hands sufficiently alive to hold the lines. He had been
U||   beaten again, humiliated before a woman, and that, too, with the best
U||   horse that he could hope to put against the ever-conquering squire.
U||   Here sank his fondest hopes, here ended his ambition. From this on he
U||   would drive a mule or an automobile. The fruit of his desire had turned
U||   to ashes in his mouth.
U||   But no. What of the widow? She realized, if the deacon did not, that
U||   she, not the squire’s horse, had beaten the deacon’s, and she was ready
U||   to make what atonement she could. As the squire passed ahead of the
U||   deacon she was stirred by a noble resolve. A deep bed of drifted snow
U||   lay close by the side of the road not far in front. It was soft and
U||   safe and she smiled as she looked at it as though waiting for her.
U||   Without a hint of her purpose, or a sign to disturb the deacon in his
U||   final throes, she rose as the sleigh ran near its edge, and with a
U||   spring which had many a time sent her lightly from the ground to the
U||   bare back of a horse in the meadow, she cleared the robes and lit plump
U||   in the drift. The deacon’s horse knew before the deacon did that
U||   something had happened in his favor, and was quick to respond. With his
U||   first jump of relief the deacon suddenly revived, his hopes came fast
U||   again, his blood retingled, he gathered himself, and, cracking his
U||   lines, he shot forward, and three minutes later he had passed the
U||   squire as though he were hitched to the fence. For a quarter of a mile
U||   the squire made heroic efforts to recover his vanished prestige, but
U||   effort was useless, and finally concluding that he was practically left
U||   standing, he veered off from the main road down a farm lane to find
U||   some spot in which to hide the humiliation of his defeat. The deacon,
U||   still going at a clipping gait, had one eye over his shoulder as wary
U||   drivers always have on such occasions, and when he saw the squire was
U||   off the track he slowed down and jogged along with the apparent
U||   intention of continuing indefinitely. Presently an idea struck him, and
U||   he looked around for the widow. She was not where he had seen her last.
U||   Where was she? In the enthusiasm of victory he had forgotten her. He
U||   was so dejected at the moment she had leaped that he did not realize
U||   what she had done, and two minutes later he was so elated that, shame
U||   on him! he did not care. With her, all was lost; without her, all was
U||   won, and the deacon’s greatest ambition was to win. But now, with
U||   victory perched on his horse-collar, success his at last, he thought of
U||   the widow, and he did care. He cared so much that he almost threw his
U||   horse off his feet by the abrupt turn he gave him, and back down the
U||   pike he flew as if a legion of squires were after him.
U||   He did not know what injury she might have sustained; She might have
U||   been seriously hurt, if not actually killed. And why? Simply to make it
U||   possible for him to win. The deacon shivered as he thought of it, and
U||   urged his horse to greater speed. The squire, down the lane, saw him
U||   whizzing along and accepted it profanely as an exhibition for his
U||   especial benefit. The deacon now had forgotten the squire as he had
U||   only so shortly before forgotten the widow. Two hundred yards from the
U||   drift into which she had jumped there was a turn in the road, where
U||   some trees shut off the sight, and the deacon’s anxiety increased
U||   momentarily until he reached this point. From here he could see ahead,
U||   and down there in the middle of the road stood the widow waving her
U||   shawl as a banner of triumph, though she could only guess at results.
U||   The deacon came on with a rush, and pulled up alongside of her in a
U||   condition of nervousness he didn’t think possible to him.
U||   “Hooray! hooray!” shouted the widow, tossing her shawl into the air.
U||   “You beat him. I know you did. Didn’t you? I saw you pulling ahead at
U||   the turn yonder. Where is he and his old plug?”
U||   “Oh, bother take him and his horse and the race and everything. Are you
U||   hurt?” gasped the deacon, jumping out, but mindful to keep the lines in
U||   his hand. “Are you hurt?” he repeated, anxiously, though she looked
U||   anything but a hurt woman.
U||   “If I am,” she chirped, cheerily, “I’m not hurt half as bad as I would
U||   have been if the squire had beat you, deacon. Now don’t you worry about
U||   me. Let’s hurry back to town so the squire won’t get another chance,
U||   with no place for me to jump.”
U||   And the deacon? Well, well, with the lines in the crook of his elbow
U||   the deacon held out his arms to the widow and——. The sisters at the
U||   next meeting of the Sewing Society were unanimously of the opinion that
U||   any woman who would risk her life like that for a husband was mighty
U||   anxious.
