U||GIDEON[75][28]
U||   By Wells Hastings (1878- )
U||   “An’ de next’ frawg dat houn’ pup seen, he pass him by wide.”
U||   The house, which had hung upon every word, roared with laughter, and
U||   shook with a storming volley of applause. Gideon bowed to right and to
U||   left, low, grinning, assured comedy obeisances; but as the laughter and
U||   applause grew he shook his head, and signaled quietly for the drop. He
U||   had answered many encores, and he was an instinctive artist. It was
U||   part of the fuel of his vanity that his audience had never yet had
U||   enough of him. Dramatic judgment, as well as dramatic sense of
U||   delivery, was native to him, qualities which the shrewd Felix Stuhk,
U||   his manager and exultant discoverer, recognized and wisely trusted in.
U||   Off stage Gideon was watched over like a child and a delicate
U||   investment, but once behind the footlights he was allowed to go his own
U||   triumphant gait.
U||   It was small wonder that Stuhk deemed himself one of the cleverest
U||   managers in the business; that his narrow, blue-shaven face was
U||   continually chiseled in smiles of complacent self-congratulation. He
U||   was rapidly becoming rich, and there were bright prospects of even
U||   greater triumphs, with proportionately greater reward. He had made
U||   Gideon a national character, a headliner, a star of the first magnitude
U||   in the firmament of the vaudeville theater, and all in six short
U||   months. Or, at any rate, he had helped to make him all this; he had
U||   booked him well and given him his opportunity. To be sure, Gideon had
U||   done the rest; Stuhk was as ready as any one to do credit to Gideon’s
U||   ability. Still, after all, he, Stuhk, was the discoverer, the
U||   theatrical Columbus who had had the courage and the vision.
U||   A now-hallowed attack of tonsilitis had driven him to Florida, where
U||   presently Gideon had been employed to beguile his convalescence, and
U||   guide him over the intricate shallows of that long lagoon known as the
U||   Indian River in search of various fish. On days when fish had been
U||   reluctant Gideon had been lured into conversation, and gradually into
U||   narrative and the relation of what had appeared to Gideon as humorous
U||   and entertaining; and finally Felix, the vague idea growing big within
U||   him, had one day persuaded his boatman to dance upon the boards of a
U||   long pier where they had made fast for lunch. There, with all the
U||   sudden glory of crystallization, the vague idea took definite form and
U||   became the great inspiration of Stuhk’s career.
U||   Gideon had grown to be to vaudeville much what Uncle Remus is to
U||   literature: there was virtue in his very simplicity. His artistry
U||   itself was native and natural. He loved a good story, and he told it
U||   from his own sense of the gleeful morsel upon his tongue as no training
U||   could have made him. He always enjoyed his story and himself in the
U||   telling. Tales never lost their savor, no matter how often repeated;
U||   age was powerless to dim the humor of the thing, and as he had shouted
U||   and gurgled and laughed over the fun of things when all alone, or
U||   holding forth among the men and women and little children of his color,
U||   so he shouted and gurgled and broke from sonorous chuckles to musical,
U||   falsetto mirth when he fronted the sweeping tiers of faces across the
U||   intoxicating glare of the footlights. He had that rare power of
U||   transmitting something of his own enjoyments. When Gideon was on the
U||   stage, Stuhk used to enjoy peeping out at the intent, smiling faces of
U||   the audience, where men and women and children, hardened theater-goers
U||   and folk fresh from the country, sat with moving lips and faces lit
U||   with an eager interest and sympathy for the black man strutting in
U||   loose-footed vivacity before them.
U||   “He’s simply unique,” he boasted to wondering local managers—“unique,
U||   and it took me to find him. There he was, a little black gold-mine, and
U||   all of ’em passed him by until I came. Some eye? What? I guess you’ll
U||   admit you have to hand it some to your Uncle Felix. If that coon’s
U||   health holds out, we’ll have all the money there is in the mint.”
U||   That was Felix’s real anxiety—“If his health holds out.” Gideon’s
U||   health was watched over as if he had been an ailing prince. His
U||   bubbling vivacity was the foundation upon which his charm and his
U||   success were built. Stuhk became a sort of vicarious neurotic,
U||   eternally searching for symptoms in his protégé; Gideon’s tongue,
U||   Gideon’s liver, Gideon’s heart were matters to him of an unfailing and
U||   anxious interest. And of late—of course it might be imagination —Gideon
U||   had shown a little physical falling off. He ate a bit less, he had
U||   begun to move in a restless way, and, worst of all, he laughed less
U||   frequently.
U||   As a matter of fact, there was ground for Stuhk’s apprehension. It was
U||   not all a matter of managerial imagination: Gideon was less himself.
U||   Physically there was nothing the matter with him; he could have passed
U||   his rigid insurance scrutiny as easily as he had done months before,
U||   when his life and health had been insured for a sum that made good copy
U||   for his press-agent. He was sound in every organ, but there was
U||   something lacking in general tone. Gideon felt it himself, and was
U||   certain that a “misery,” that embracing indisposition of his race, was
U||   creeping upon him. He had been fed well, too well; he was growing rich,
U||   too rich; he had all the praise, all the flattery that his enormous
U||   appetite for approval desired, and too much of it. White men sought him
U||   out and made much of him; white women talked to him about his career;
U||   and wherever he went, women of color—black girls, brown girls, yellow
U||   girls—wrote him of their admiration, whispered, when he would listen,
U||   of their passion and hero-worship. “City niggers” bowed down before
U||   him; the high gallery was always packed with them. Musk-scented notes
U||   scrawled upon barbaric, “high-toned” stationery poured in upon him.
U||   Even a few white women, to his horror and embarrassment, had written
U||   him of love, letters which he straightway destroyed. His sense of his
U||   position was strong in him; he was proud of it. There might be “folks
U||   outer their haids,” but he had the sense to remember. For months he had
U||   lived in a heaven of gratified vanity, but at last his appetite had
U||   begun to falter. He was sated; his soul longed to wipe a spiritual
U||   mouth on the back of a spiritual hand, and have done. His face, now
U||   that the curtain was down and he was leaving the stage, was doleful,
U||   almost sullen.
U||   Stuhk met him anxiously in the wings, and walked with him to his
U||   dressing-room. He felt suddenly very weary of Stuhk.
U||   “Nothing the matter, Gideon, is there? Not feeling sick or anything?”
U||   “No, Misteh Stuhk; no, seh. Jes don’ feel extry pert, that’s all.”
U||   “But what is it—anything bothering you?”
U||   Gideon sat gloomily before his mirror.
U||   “Misteh Stuhk,” he said at last, “I been steddyin’ it oveh, and I about
U||   come to the delusion that I needs a good po’k-chop. Seems foolish, I
U||   know, but it do’ seem as if a good po’k-chop, fried jes right, would
U||   he’p consid’able to disumpate this misery feelin’ that’s crawlin’ and
U||   creepin’ round my sperit.”
U||   Stuhk laughed.
U||   “Pork-chop, eh? Is that the best you can think of? I know what you
U||   mean, though. I’ve thought for some time that you were getting a little
U||   overtrained. What you need is—let me see—yes, a nice bottle of wine.
U||   That’s the ticket; it will ease things up and won’t do you any harm.
U||   I’ll go, with you. Ever had any champagne, Gideon?”
U||   Gideon struggled for politeness.
U||   “Yes, seh, I’s had champagne, and it’s a nice kind of lickeh sho
U||   enough; but, Misteh Stuhk, seh, I don’ want any of them high-tone
U||   drinks to-night, an’ ef yo’ don’ mind, I’d rather amble off ’lone, or
U||   mebbe eat that po’k-chop with some otheh cullud man, ef I kin fin’ one
U||   that ain’ one of them no-’count Carolina niggers. Do you s’pose yo’
U||   could let me have a little money to-night, Misteh Stuhk?”
U||   Stuhk thought rapidly. Gideon had certainly worked hard, and he was not
U||   dissipated. If he wanted to roam the town by himself, there was no harm
U||   in it. The sullenness still showed in the black face; Heaven knew what
U||   he might do if he suddenly began to balk. Stuhk thought it wise to
U||   consent gracefully.
U||   “Good!” he said. “Fly to it. How much do you want? A hundred?”
U||   “How much is coming to me?”
U||   “About a thousand, Gideon.”
U||   “Well, I’d moughty like five hun’red of it, ef that’s ’greeable to
U||   yo’.”
U||   Felix whistled.
U||   “Five hundred? Pork-chops must be coming high. You don’t want to carry
U||   all that money around, do you?”
U||   Gideon did not answer; he looked very gloomy.
U||   Stuhk hastened to cheer him.
U||   “Of course you can have anything you want. Wait a minute, and I will
U||   get it for you.
U||   “I’ll bet that coon’s going to buy himself a ring or something,” he
U||   reflected as he went in search of the local manager and Gideon’s money.
U||   But Stuhk was wrong. Gideon had no intention of buying himself a ring.
U||   For the matter of that, he had several that were amply satisfactory.
U||   They had size and sparkle and luster, all the diamond brilliance that
U||   rings need to have; and for none of them had he paid much over five
U||   dollars. He was amply supplied with jewelry in which he felt perfect
U||   satisfaction. His present want was positive, if nebulous; he desired a
U||   fortune in his pocket, bulky, tangible evidence of his miraculous
U||   success. Ever since Stuhk had found him, life had had an unreal quality
U||   for him. His Monte Cristo wealth was too much like a fabulous,
U||   dream-found treasure, money that could not be spent without danger of
U||   awakening. And he had dropped into the habit of storing it about him,
U||   so that in any pocket into which he plunged his hand he might find a
U||   roll of crisp evidence of reality. He liked his bills to be of all
U||   denominations, and some so large as exquisitely to stagger imagination,
U||   others charming by their number and crispness—the dignified, orange
U||   paper of a man of assured position and wealth-crackling greenbacks the
U||   design of which tinged the whole with actuality. He was specially
U||   partial to engravings of President Lincoln, the particular savior and
U||   patron of his race. This five hundred dollars he was adding to an
U||   unreckoned sum of about two thousand, merely as extra fortification
U||   against a growing sense of gloom. He wished to brace his flagging
U||   spirits with the gay wine of possession, and he was glad, when the
U||   money came, that it was in an elastic-bound roll, so bulky that it was
U||   pleasantly uncomfortable in his pocket as he left his manager.
U||   As he turned into the brilliantly lighted street from the somber
U||   alleyway of the stage entrance, he paused for a moment to glance at his
U||   own name, in three-foot letters of red, before the doors of the
U||   theater. He could read, and the large block type always pleased him.
U||   “THIS WEEK: GIDEON.” That was all. None of the fulsome praise, the
U||   superlative, necessary definition given to lesser performers. He had
U||   been, he remembered, “GIDEON, America’s Foremost Native Comedian,” a
U||   title that was at once boast and challenge. That necessity was now
U||   past, for he was a national character; any explanatory qualification
U||   would have been an insult to the public intelligence. To the world he
U||   was just “Gideon”; that was enough. It gave him pleasure, as he
U||   sauntered along, to see the announcement repeated on window cards and
U||   hoardings.
U||   Presently he came to a window before which he paused in delighted
U||   wonder. It was not a large window; to the casual eye of the passer-by
U||   there was little to draw attention. By day it lighted the fractional
U||   floor space of a little stationer, who supplemented a slim business by
U||   a sub-agency for railroad and steamship lines; but to-night this window
U||   seemed the framework of a marvel of coincidence. On the broad, dusty
U||   sill inside were propped two cards: the one on the left was his own
U||   red-lettered announcement for the week; the one at the right—oh, world
U||   of wonders!—was a photogravure of that exact stretch of the inner coast
U||   of Florida which Gideon knew best, which was home.
U||   There it was, the Indian River, rippling idly in full sunlight,
U||   palmettos leaning over the water, palmettos standing as irregular
U||   sentries along the low, reeflike island which stretched away out of the
U||   picture. There was the gigantic, lonely pine he knew well, and, yes—he
U||   could just make it out—there was his own ramshackle little pier, which
U||   stretched in undulating fashion, like a long-legged, wading
U||   caterpillar, from the abrupt shore-line of eroded coquina into deep
U||   water.
U||   He thought at first that this picture of his home was some new and
U||   delicate device put forth by his press-agent. His name on one side of a
U||   window, his birthplace upon the other—what could be more tastefully
U||   appropriate? Therefore, as he spelled out the reading-matter beneath
U||   the photogravure, he was sharply disappointed. It read:
U||   Spend this winter in balmy Florida.
U||   Come to the Land of Perpetual Sunshine.
U||   Golf, tennis, driving, shooting, boating, fishing, all of the best.
U||   There was more, but he had no heart for it; he was disappointed and
U||   puzzled. This picture had, after all, nothing to do with him. It was a
U||   chance, and yet, what a strange chance! It troubled and upset him. His
U||   black, round-featured face took on deep wrinkles of perplexity. The
